<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS GET GOING WITH A MOVING VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This old house still had all the comforts of
home Monday night. Playing their first game at Foxboro Stadium
since owner Robert Kraft announced he was moving the team to
Hartford in 2001, the Patriots survived for at least one more night
by pulling out a last-minute 26-23 win over the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking off the effects of a sore right hand, Drew Bledsoe
marched the Patriots 80 yards, hitting Shawn Jefferson with a
25-yard touchdown pass with 34 seconds left to send the old fans
into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who completed 28 of 54 passes for 423 yards, with two
interceptions and two touchdowns, converted two third-down plays
and two fourth-down plays along the way.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the drive, his right hand was hit by Shane
Burton as he released the ball. Bledsoe had to take warmup tosses
on the sideline and at one point Scott Zolak was helmeted and ready
to enter.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson caught six passes for a career-high 131 yards. In
addition to the TD, he had a 14-yard reception on fourth and 10 to
the Miami 40 and an 11-yarder on fourth and 6 to the 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins got the ball back with 29 seconds left and
completed a 46-yard Hail Mary pass. With 5 seconds left and the
ball at midfield, Dan Marino completed another pass, but time
expired before Miami could call a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   The win left the Patriots at 6-5, within a game of the Dolphins,
Jets, and Bills in the AFC East. Some of the sellout crowd may have
been upset with Kraft, but overall the fans seemed well-behaved,
only once booing the Patriots when they couldn't move the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As they promised, the Patriots did open up their offense, using
several fakes and play-action passes. In the first half, Bledsoe
threw the ball downfield to Jefferson for two 30-yard-plus plays
and even ran a keeper up the middle for 11 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not good enough to gain a lead in the first 30
minutes, as the Patriots trailed at halftime, 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots seemed buoyed by the return of Terry Glenn, which
seemed to spread out the defense and create more downfield
opportunities for Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Jimmy Johnson must have sensed the potential
volatility of the crowd, knowing that he could tap into it by
scoring first. So, in the first quarter, on fourth and 10 at the
Patriots' 35, Johnson elected not to attempt a long field goal in a
swirling wind. And he elected not to punt. What he elected to do
was to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Marino showed he can still drill it when he needs
to, hitting Oronde Gadsden on the fly at the 17. A diving attempt
to break up the pass by Ty Law failed, and Gadsden ran in for a
touchdown with 8:17 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   There was silence.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins started the drive at their 28 and took a much
different approach than what the Patriots expected: They came out
throwing. Marino found tight end Troy Drayton for a 26-yard gain
that got the Dolphins into Patriot territory at the 47. After an
8-yard toss to Stanley Pritchard got it to the 35, the Patriots'
defense got stingy, creating the fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   The Gadsden score marked the first time this season _ and second
time in his career _ that Law has been beaten for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were not deterred. On the first play of a drive
that began at the 31, Bledsoe threw deep to Jefferson, who got
behind coverage for a 38-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried to run but again found it a futile exercise
as Robert Edwards found no room. So Bledsoe went with something
more familiar: passes to Ben Coates. The big tight end caught a
14-yard pass that got the ball to the 8. Two plays later, Coates
got away with murder when he knocked down strong safety Calvin
Jackson before Bledsoe delivered the ball for a free catch in the
end zone and the tying score.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were stopping the run in the first half, and Steve
Israel picked off a Marino pass _ Marino's 12th interception in his
last seven games against the Patriots. But the New England offense
couldn't capitalize. The Patriots pulled a Miami and went for it on
fourth and 3 from the Dolphins' 38. Bledsoe found Jefferson over
the middle, but the veteran receiver dropped the ball.
</P>
<P>
   While Marino's interception wasn't costly to his team, Bledsoe's
was.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was trying to lead rookie receiver Tony Simmons down the
left sideline but underthrew the ball and it was intercepted by Sam
Madison, who returned it to the Patriots' 37.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-yard face-mask penalty on Ted Johnson put the Dolphins in
business at the 14, and two plays later Gadsden got behind Chris
Canty on a slant and caught an 11-yard pea from Marino to give the
Dolphins a 14-7 lead with seven minutes remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots weren't done.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Bledsoe went deep to Jefferson for 33 yards to the
Miami 47. Terry Glenn, who had missed four games with a hamstring
pull, caught an 8-yard pass to the 36 on third and 7.
</P>
<P>
   But the drive stalled when Coates, who was held the entire way
to the end zone by Zach Thomas, couldn't come up with Bledsoe's
toss. The quarterback and the tight end argued the call, but the
Patriots had to settle for a 26-yard field goal by Adam Vinatieri
with 1:08 remaining that made it a 14-10 game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots played a little backward ball before pulling within
1 point, 14-13, in the third quarter. They got as far as the 17
when Calvin Jackson was called for a face-mask penalty on Glenn
following an 8-yard reception. But the Patriots lost ground from
there, as Bledsoe was sacked for a 10-yard loss after Lovett
Purnell was called for holding.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was livid at Purnell, and chewed out the backup tight
end out as he came off the field. The Patriots settled for a
44-yard Vinatieri field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins drove 71 yards to answer, taking a 17-13 lead on a
21-yard Olindo Mare field goal with 4:40 remaining in the third
quarter. Costly penalties _ a face mask on Chris Slade and an
interference call on Lawyer Milloy _ helped the Dolphins march down
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots made it 17-16 on Vinatieri's 45-yard boot with 31
seconds remaining in the third quarter, as the Patriots abandoned
the run and went to a no-huddle. Three passes _ two to Coates and
one to Glenn _ got the Patriots into field goal range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
