<SLUG> BC-NY-UNION-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION'S PROBLEMS DON'T TAINT THE MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With NY-UNION-FRAUD)  (nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was that campaign television commercial in 1997
that depicted a prominent member of District Council 37 embracing
the candidate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. There was the endorsement of
Giuliani's re-election that same year by the council's top
official. Above all, there was the council's ratification of a city
contract with a two-year pay freeze in 1996 that turned out to be a
mayoral coup.
</P>
<P>
   For several years now, Giuliani has enjoyed the perception that
he had forged close ties to the leadership of District Council 37,
the city's largest municipal union with 120,000 members. That
impression served him on several levels, including its
counterintuitive nature: a Republican Mayor being lauded as a
friend of labor by the officials of a traditionally Democratic
union.
</P>
<P>
   But now District Council 37 is reeling from criminal and
internal investigations into widespread corruption. The latest blow
came Monday, when two top officials resigned amid allegations that
ballot fraud had tainted the contract vote in 1996. A natural
question then arises: What does all this union turbulence mean for
Giuliani?
</P>
<P>
   At first blush it might appear that the corruption allegations
could taint a public official who earned his reputation as a
corruption-fighting federal prosecutor. In truth, it probably will
have no impact at all, say his aides and labor analysts, with the
outside chance that it might resurface if he seeks higher office.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year contract stands and probably will not be reopened,
they say. When does it expire, at the end of 2000, this
term-limited mayor will either already be gone _ depending on his
political aspirations _ or approaching his last months in office.
Finally, as Deputy Mayor Randy Levine says, it is not the mayor's
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything having to do with vote tampering and election fraud
is outrageous, despicable and has to be condemned,'' Levine said.
``But this has nothing to do with Rudy Giuliani. This is an
internal union matter. It is unfortunate that this union doesn't
seem to have adequate controls, but the mayor's role is
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, after a contentious battle, the union approved
a five-year contract with the city with no raises the first two
years and a combined 13 percent pay increase for the final three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The contract allowed the mayor to hold down spending at a time
of fiscal crisis and to keep the peace with the union that
represents more than half the city's workers. It also permitted him
to continue reducing the size of city government, because no job
security had been promised to union members working as aides in
municipal hospitals. And it established a pattern in municipal
contracts that was soon followed by other unions.
</P>
<P>
   The contract had its critics. Many within the union leveled
accusations of ballot fraud. Good-government groups complained that
the back-loaded structure of the contract, with a 6 percent pay
increase in the last year, would cause fiscal havoc in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said Giuliani is fair but tough; so tough, in fact, that
so far no municipal union has sought to negotiate new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little early,'' Levine said. ``But what they tell me is
that it may be easier negotiating with the next mayor, whoever that
may be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
