<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-BUYBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLSOUTH BUYBACK, OTHER MOVES BOOST STRATEGIC VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street has been waiting months for BellSouth Corp. to do
something dramatic in response to the consolidation that is
happening among phone companies all around it. So far, BellSouth
has not obliged.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday BellSouth showed that it was determined to lay up
supplies, in the form of value in its stock, in preparation for the
next round of financial battles. The company said it would split
its stock, raise its dividend and buy back up to $3 billion worth
of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements added momentum to a stock-promotion campaign
that BellSouth's executives have appeared to be waging since early
this fall. BellSouth recently encouraged some analysts to raise
their predictions for the company's financial performance and
touted the stock's performance with reporters. Monday, the shares
rose $2.125, to $83.50, on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, BellSouth has had reason to boast. From the
beginning of 1997 through the end of last week, BellSouth's stock
had gained 98.5 percent. That beat the gains of each of the other
five big regional phone companies _ Ameritech, Bell Atlantic, GTE,
SBC Communications and U S West _ by at least 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth says it has not changed the way it discusses its
stock. But naturally, the perception of a stock-promotion campaign
has raised the question of whether BellSouth is seeking a more
valuable currency in its stock with the idea of pursuing a large
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one were focused on some of the transforming events, the
mergers, those are generally based on stock and the better your
stock is doing, the better positioned you are for those deals,''
said Ronald M. Dykes, BellSouth's chief financial officer, adding
that the primary reason for Monday's moves was to return cash to
shareholders. ``No matter how the industry shapes up, it helps to
have a strong currency.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth said its stock would split next month and that the
dividend-increase and stock buyback would start next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
