<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-STOCKS-NYT &LR;      11-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RATIONALE EXPLANATION FOR THIS TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does the stock market know something the rest of us do not about
the terms of America Online's proposed purchase of Netscape
Communications?
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the kind of unusual trading in Netscape's stock
that took place Monday would have been seen as an indication that
another buyer was going to emerge to bid up Netscape's price. But
with all the irrationally exuberant trading in Internet companies,
it was difficult to read such reasoning _ or any rationale at all _
into the stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   After reports of the proposed deal appeared in Monday morning's
newspapers, Netscape released a statement confirming negotiations
but indicating that a final agreement had not been reached. It said
that the proposed transaction would involve an exchange of 0.45
share of America Online for each share of Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for much of Monday Netscape traded at a value equal to 0.47
times the value of America Online's shares, sometimes more. That
was exactly the opposite of the normal trading pattern, in which
the stock of takeover targets trades at a discount to the stated
purchase price, typically an acknowledgment that the deal might be
called off.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely explanation for Monday's pricing, several
analysts said, was not that some investors knew too much but that
many knew too little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that retail investors have gotten enthusiastic and
haven't quite figured out what is going on here and done the
math,'' said Daniel Rimer, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   As with much of the trading in Internet stocks, a great deal of
activity consisted of small trades by individuals rather than the
larger blocks by institutional investors that dominate trading in
most other industries. The average trade in Netscape's stock
yesterday was 615 shares, far smaller than for a typical industrial
company.
</P>
<P>
   Even smaller was the trade size in the typical Internet darling
stocks, and that may explain why their share prices surged on news
of a deal that would do nothing but make competition tougher.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Yahoo, the leading Internet portal, whose business
is the main target of the America Online-Netscape deal, jumped
$30.4375, to $221.4375, propelled by trades averaging just 458
shares each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo's stock did not react rationally today,'' said Derek
Brown, an analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan. ``The potential move of
AOL more aggressively into the Web business heightens the level of
competition long-term for Yahoo and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other Internet stocks that jumped were Amazon.com,
which rose $37.375, to $218, and Lycos, another portal service, up
$4.3125, to $65.0625.
</P>
<P>
   In that environment, shares in America Online reacted relatively
modestly, increasing $4.75, to $89.625; Netscape gained $2.75, to
$41.9375.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in many ways it has been the 376 percent run-up in
the price of America Online's stock in the last year or so that
made a Netscape deal possible. America Online is now worth $41
billion, a multiple of 368 times earnings. With its shares valued
at such an unheard of price-earnings ratio, America Online can
afford to make acquisitions by trading its stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all funny money when you think about it,'' said Shaun
Andrikopoulos, an analyst with BT Alex. Brown. He figured that the
deal would probably add to America Online's earnings in a year,
though key details were still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest uncertainty is what happens to Netscape's business
of selling World Wide Web servers and other industrial-strength
software to corporate users. Despite the rapid growth of its
Netcenter Web portal site, this software business will still
account for three-quarters of Netscape's revenue in 1999, Brown of
Volpe Brown estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the surging value of the other Internet
leaders made more big acquisitions all the more likely. Yahoo, for
example, now has a market value of some $21 billion, slightly more
than the value of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   And while CBS shareholders would no doubt be wary of exchanging
shares in the TV network for the supremely volatile Yahoo shares,
Yahoo is nonetheless in a position to buy all manner of Internet
and related companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
