r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-L     11-24 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES ARE A HOWLING SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As recently as the end of last season, when the
Phoenix Coyotes were eliminated from the playoffs in the first
round by the Detroit Red Wings, they were viewed as a talented team
with poor chemistry that probably would never develop into one of
the top contenders in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   But more than six weeks into the Coyotes' third season since
departing Winnipeg for the desert, Phoenix has risen to the top of
the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   With an 11-2-2 record, the Coyotes _ who visit the Kings on
Saturday night _ have been the NHL's biggest and best surprise.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Coyotes long been known for such big-name
offensive players as Keith Tkachuk and Jeremy Roenick, the most
important factor in their success has been their defense.
</P>
<P>
   In their last 11 games, the Coyotes are 9-0-2, and they have not
allowed more than two goals in any of their last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning because we've got all the guys on the same
page,'' Tkachuk said. ``The problem we had last year was guys were
taking too many nights off. This year, everybody's playing solid
every night. But one or two guys can't carry this team. The NHL is
too good. Obviously, our goaltending (Nikolai Khabibulin and Jimmy
Waite) has definitely helped. The goaltending has been absolutely
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Tkachuk, the Coyotes' strong start appears to have helped
him get beyond the bad feelings Phoenix fans had for him after his
preseason holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I have to prove is to win,'' Tkachuk said.
``That's the bottom line. You're measured on winning _ team
success, not individual stats. I've scored 50 before. That's fine.
I don't have to prove I can score 50. I've got to prove I can lead
this team and do the right things so we're there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey city: Teams change their uniforms for a variety of
reasons, not the least of which is to entice fans to reach into
their wallets to restock their clothing supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Kings, who changed their uniforms this
season, the strategy appears to be working.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lloyd Haymes of the NHL, the Kings ranked 20th of
27 NHL teams in jersey sales in 1997. This year, the Kings have
moved up to 14th, and their new jerseys weren't introduced until
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kings director of merchandise Mark Moehlenkamp,
through this season's first eight home games, sales of Kings
merchandise were up 169 percent over the first eight home games of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moehlenkamp said that aside from a desire to increase
merchandise revenue, the Kings changed their uniforms for several
reasons: to have a new look when they move into the Staples Center
next year, to have a more traditional look by reintroducing the
crown in their logo that was on their original uniforms when the
team entered the NHL in 1967, and to try to rid themselves of the
unwanted identification with street gangs that their old
silver-and-black uniforms had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really more a case of hopefully they won't,'' Moehlenkamp
said when asked if the Kings felt confident their new look would
not be adopted by gangs. ``But there are no assurances, quite
frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Roamin' Vopat: One month ago, the Kings traded center Roman
Vopat to Colorado for Eric Lacroix. Since then, Colorado has traded
Vopat to Chicago, which then traded the 22-year-old Czech to
Philadelphia. Vopat originally came to the Kings in the 1996 deal
that briefly sent Wayne Gretzky to the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Of his recent and involuntary nomadic ways, Vopat said: ``It was
unbelievable. I can't say how I felt. I was 19 (when acquired by
the Kings) and I thought I was going to stay in L.A. But I got
traded after two years. Soon as you get traded, you get traded
again? Three times in three weeks? That hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first game for the Flyers, Vopat had one shift and used
the opportunity to check Pittsburgh defenseman Victor Ignatjev (a
former Long Beach Ice Dog) into the boards. Ignatjev suffered a
shoulder injury on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Vopat's travels may be over. Flyers general manager Bob Clarke
has never made a secret of his admiration for players capable of a
little of the old ultraviolence, and he thinks Vopat is just such a
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good fighter,'' Clarke said. ``Not really his forte,
but he can take care of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragic predicament: Dallas' Mike Modano recently attributed his
slow start to the distraction of having to manage the money from
the six-year, $43.5-million contract he signed last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of wore on me and I was tired a lot,'' Modano said.
``You try as much as you can not to bring that to the rink. But
it's tough when it weighs on you the 22 hours you're not at the
rink. Then, the other two, you try to focus on hockey.`
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he spent the Stars' five-day break between games in
October working on his investments. When the break ended, he went
nine games without a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I didn't want it to creep into my game, it did,''
he said. ``I hate to use it as an excuse; I felt I could handle it
and concentrate on hockey. But it kind of caught up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Get out your crying towels. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
