<HEADLINE>
USC'S WIN OVER UNLV WAS SIGNIFICANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's not a nonconference schedule, it's a
nonschedule.
</P>
<P>
   That might be a cynical way of looking at USC's first nine games
of the season, but it also demonstrates why last Friday's 71-68
victory over Nevada-Las Vegas could be extremely important to the
Trojans' postseason plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans should go no worse than 8-1 in the preseason
following their upset of the Rebels. USC plays Long Beach State,
St. Bonaventure, UC Santa Barbara and Loyola Marymount before its
Dec. 12 game against No.8 Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Trojans lose at Kansas, they should finish up with
victories over American University and Arkansas State before
starting Pacific-10 Conference play.
</P>
<P>
   That means anyone evaluating USC, like perhaps the NCAA
Tournament selection committee, will look closely at the UNLV
result.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby said he wasn't concerned about the way the
Trojans' victory over UNLV will be interpreted in power rankings or
national polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are playing one game at a time,'' Bibby said. ``My
assistants are more concerned about that than me. My concern is to
make sure we're growing as a basketball team. Not power ratings.
Not where we are in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A big and small impact: Two games into the season, no one is
making a bigger impact than sophomore Brian Scalabrine and freshman
Brandon Granville, two players who were not on the team a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-9 Scalabrine leads USC in scoring (14.5 points) and
rebounding (9.0) and is shooting 67 percent from field.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Scalabrine) makes the difference. In the ratings we have,
he's been in the top two or three in all the practices,'' Bibby
said.
</P>
<P>
   Granville, who is just 5-9, has been the surprise of the team so
far, calmly directing the offense in the first two games even
though he was not expected to start this soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandon Granville has a lot of heart,'' Bibby said. ``He's a
smart guard. He's not a super quick guard. He's not a great
ballhandler or defensive player, but he plays with the air of a
winning player. It says a lot about the way he played against UNLV
and those hostile fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Granville had 15 points, seven assists and six rebounds against
the Rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back slowly: Point guard Kevin Augustine, who started 10
games last season, is still trying to work his way back into the
playing rotation. Augustine went just five minutes against UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the third guard behind Brandon and Quincy (Wilder),''
Bibby said. ``He'll get his chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's OK: Bibby said Jarvis Turner has not been bothered
recently by the back spasms that he has experienced since the start
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was OK (Sunday). I don't think it's a factor,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Doubting Thomas? Bibby said he doesn't know if freshman
quarterback Jason Thomas will play basketball this season. Thomas
has recovered from ankle surgery and is practicing with the
football team. Since USC is going to a bowl game, Thomas probably
could not join the basketball team before January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' Bibby said. ``We haven't talked since the
football season started. It's up to Jason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
