<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING UP ON FRIENDSHIP FOR FOUR DECADES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dennis McCarthy is a columnist with the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a cozy Thanksgiving dinner the Comstocks and the Kirbys
sat down to that first time in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight kids, four adults and one 12-pound turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, they're up to 54 people, two 20-pound turkeys
and a ham.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it rains, the kids are going to have to eat in the
garage,'' Irma is telling Kay on Monday, as the two matriarchs map
out the logistics of their families sharing their 40th consecutive
Thanksgiving dinner together.
</P>
<P>
   It began as one young family reaching out to another that found
itself alone on Thanksgiving after moving from Canada to the Los
Angeles suburb of Reseda in 1958. Since then, it has evolved into a
holiday saga of friendship and love -- not to mention a heck of a
lot of tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children grew up, babies followed marriages and death came
by,'' Irma Comstock Ajhar says, putting her arm around Kay Kirby.
``We've cried and we've laughed together.''
</P>
<P>
   All because a week before Thanksgiving in 1958, one woman looks
across the room at a church social and recognizes the face of
another woman she had seen at her children's school open house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out we were both new to the (San Fernando) Valley,
so we decided to have Thanksgiving together because the Kirbys
didn't know anyone and had no plans to celebrate it,'' Irma says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Canada, Thanksgiving was in October and not a big deal,''
Kay adds. ``But here, we really got into the warm, family feeling
of it. I told Irma that the next year, we'd have it at my house.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what the Comstocks and Kirbys have been doing ever
since -- trading off Thanksgivings at each other's homes, with the
host family cooking the turkey and hot dishes, and the guest family
bringing all the deserts and chips.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the tables get a little longer, the turkeys a little
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The Comstocks -- Irma and Richard -- had nine children together
before Richard died of a heart attack in 1987. Irma later
remarried, and she and her new husband have carried on the
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The Kirbys -- Kay and Peter -- have six children of their own.
</P>
<P>
   These kids, in turn, now have their own children and everyone
looks forward to this day when the two clans come from all over the
country and state to reunite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids were always great friends growing up and this gives
them a chance to catch up on each other's lives at least once a
year,'' Kay says. ``Plus, we all get to see and play with the new
babies in the families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful. I don't know what Thanksgiving would be
without this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, hosting 54 people for dinner in a 2,400-square-foot house
might sound like a logistical nightmare to some, but the way Irma
and Kay see it, the more the better.
</P>
<P>
   Both women scoff at the idea of catering the dinner, or worse,
going out somewhere. It wouldn't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never crowded when it's family,'' Kay says. ``Besides,
everybody is always too busy laughing to notice there's no place to
sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   There will come a time this Thanksgiving when the matriarchs
will sit their grandchildren down and tell them the story of how
this friendship began 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tell them how it is that two families have come together to
become one every Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's important for the children to know how lucky
they are to have family and friends like this,'' Kay says. ``When
you get good friends, you keep good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Irma smiles and looks out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure it's not going to rain Thursday?'' she asks her
friend, before they both burst out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It would certainly be a first, the kids having to eat
Thanksgiving dinner out in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 0054EST &QL; 
