<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS THROW DASH OF `SPICE' ON STALE DISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jon Kitna: Spice Boy.
</P>
<P>
   No, you won't find him singing on a hot CD. You'll find him
quarterbacking on a cold DOA team.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawk coach Dennis Erickson, rolling back the position's
odometer almost two decades, said Monday his new starting
quarterback would add ``some spice'' to the Seahawk offense, which,
as you may have tasted, has been as flavorful as Sam Adams' laundry
hamper.
</P>
<P>
   How much a third-stringer can contribute after 11 weeks running
the scout-team offense in practice is highly suspect. Then again,
the Seahawks rank 29th in the 30-team NFL in third-down
conversions, so it would be hard for any of the Spice Girls to do
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon does not bear exclusive responsibility for the
failure. His is simply the easiest position to alter with the most
potential for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   But Moon has, in a single season, slid from extraordinary to
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna is perhaps the one guy on the roster who cannot do that,
only because Kitna is not likely to be extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, unlike Moon, he can only improve. Also unlike Moon, he
can move a little bit and take a hit.
</P>
<P>
   While the Seahawks offense has taken numerous hits, it is better
if the hits are administered four yards downfield instead of in the
pocket. Kitna is not likely to explode on the Houston/Tennessee
Oilers/
</P>
<P>
   Titans (the first sports team ever to be mistaken for an e-mail
address) Sunday in the Kingdome in the fashion of Steve Young. But
at least he is a mobile mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Moon has become predictable. Not only is he locking on to his
primary receivers too frequently, he's zero threat to run away. He
can still roll out some, but when a quarterback's subconscious
knows the next hit may be the career finale, it's not hard to
communicate that through some mending ribs straight to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was distinct in Sunday's defeat in Dallas.
Impressive as was Cowboy quarterback Troy Aikman's passing,
particularly under heavy Seahawk pressure, he did a simpler thing
that made him even more effective.
</P>
<P>
   He ran the ball. Sure, it was only five times for 14 yards. But
one was a 10-yard scramble from the pocket for a first down at the
Seahawk 34 on the last play of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The play will be little noted nor long remembered, except by
football fans who haven't seen it in a while, such as all those in
Seattle. Aikman made a play where there was none, and sustained a
drive that became a Dallas touchdown and a 23-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how much the Seahawks would give for a third-down play
like that? In the five games since their mid-October bye, the
Seahawks have made just nine third downs in 55 attempts, yet have
won two and lost relatively closely the other three.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the mistakes that will cost Erickson and most of his
staff their jobs this offseason, perhaps a third-down play a game
that leads to a touchdown drive would have been enough to have made
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That's how close it is in the great middle of the NFL. Any extra
weapon is a big advantage. The trendy weapon of this season is
quarterback mobility.
</P>
<P>
   QBs such as Young, Aikman, Randall Cunningham, Jake Plummer and
Kordell Stewart force defenses to curtail the emphasis on extra
pass-cover guys. ESPN came up with a stat Sunday night that said in
the category of career scoring runs of 20 or more yards, Young was
second-highest in NFL history. Denver's John Elway was long the
master, but no longer needs to rely on his legs with such a
superlative cast around him.
</P>
<P>
   The linebacker or safety who drops into coverage against Moon's
throws might have to freeze a moment against a footloose QB. A
moment can make all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Moon was intimate with the virtue for years. In his last season
in the CFL with Edmonton in 1983, he rushed for 527 yards in 85
carries, a 6.2 average. In his heyday in Houston with the
run-and-shoot offense, his occasional forays were daggers in
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   But the last three seasons, age has caught up. It's not so much
a matter of lost quickness as it is slower recovery from the hits.
Moon doesn't want to risk a clobbering in the open field, or
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to quantify the cumulative toll taken by 20 years of
weekly poundings, but suffice to say it is beyond the comprehension
of the average mortal. There's a reason most NFL running backs
don't last much longer than five years before they drift toward the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Moon's increasing immobility could be indulged when he passed as
accurately as he did most of last season. But this year, at 42 with
a mistake-riddled offense hampered by a mediocre line, Moon's
descent into ordinariness and predictability made the Seahawks even
more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the quarterback switch now, of course, is that
the horse is so far beyond the barn door that it can only be found
by satellite. But team and league politics dictate a player of
Moon's distinction isn't benched until the evidence is irrefutable.
</P>
<P>
   Six losses in eight games makes the verdict easy.
</P>
<P>
   Old Spice makes a nice after-shave, but it's not much against a
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
