<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOON LOSES STARTING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Warren Moon came to work Monday with a hunch
that he might be replaced as the Seahawks' starting quarterback.
Before the day was over, it had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kitna will make his second NFL start in Sunday's game
against the Tennessee Oilers at the Kingdome. Moon will be the
backup and John Friesz the inactive third quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I totally agree with, but I accept it,''
Moon said. ``I have to accept that. If it will make our team
better, I definitely will accept it. That's what I'm hoping. That
it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before meeting with coach Dennis Erickson, Moon dropped a
couple of hints in the locker room that he could be out. It was one
of Moon's better reads of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is a one-game switch or the first step toward
replacing Moon for the final five games of this disappointing
season, and beyond, will depend on how well Kitna performs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope I would have a few weeks, and hopefully it will
be a deal where I could finish out the season,'' said Kitna, a
real-life local-boy-makes-good story waiting to happen. He played
at Central Washington University and Tacoma's Lincoln High School
before signing with the Seahawks as a free agent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   With the Seahawks at 5-6 and realistically _ if not
mathematically _ eliminated from the playoffs, Erickson made the
move many feel is too late in coming. Even if the Seahawks were to
win their final five games, it is not likely they would earn a
playoff berth for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the situation that I would have hoped for,'' Kitna
said. ``I knew coming into the season that the only way I was going
to play was either by injury or by us not playing well. ... So on
one hand, it's excitement. But on the other hand, there's still a
little bit of a downer on it because of the situation we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson is hoping Kitna can do what Moon has been unable to:
jump-start an offense that has slumped to 27th in the NFL. The
Seahawks' offense hasn't ranked this low since the 2-14 season of
1992, when it was dead last in the then 28-team league.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have lost six of their past eight games, and the
offense has scored only seven touchdowns in the six losses. They
have converted only nine third-down situations in their past five
games, dropping their third-down conversion percentage to .252
after 11 games, which ranks 29th in the league (Minnesota being No.
1 at .531; the New York Giants No. 30 at .240).
</P>
<P>
   After calculating all these numbers, Erickson came up with No. 7
(Kitna), not No. 1 (Moon).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're stagnant, like we are right now, you need to get
some kind of a spark,'' Erickson said. ``Obviously that's a
position that can give you a spark, and Jon is a guy who moves
around and does different things. So we're going to give him the
opportunity to see what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we're making the change is because we feel he can
be successful, not just to make the change,'' said Erickson, who
discovered Kitna at Central Washington and has dubbed him ``the
quarterback of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon has been benched briefly for ineffectiveness two other
times, both while playing with the Houston Oilers: once in 1985,
when he was replaced by Oliver Luck; and again in 1992, when Cody
Carlson took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt my ego and psyche a little bit that I
wasn't able to get it done,'' Moon said. ``But the bottom line is,
let's get it done as a Seahawks football team. Hopefully, this will
enable us to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Moon, who is in his 21st professional season, Kitna has
played very little in his first three years in the NFL. He got his
first start against the Raiders last year and rallied the Seahawks
to victory in the second half. He threw 12 passes in a mop-up role
during the Week 4 loss at Kansas City this season. Other than that,
he has played in preseason games and spent the regular season
working as the scout-team quarterback in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna said the move surprised him, especially because he first
heard about it from Moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little uncomfortable when Warren came and told me,
just because I don't feel like he was the problem,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   Is this move rooted in panic? Or with an eye to the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should be classified as either right now,''
said Moon, who turned 42 last week. ``I don't think we're looking
to the future yet. I think it's too early to give up on this
season. And I don't think we're panicking. I think Dennis has
probably gone about as long as he feels he can with what's been
going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
