<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' JOHNSON SUSPENDED FOR 12 GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kings enforcer Matt Johnson received a
birthday present from the NHL office Monday, though it would more
appropriately be termed a booby prize.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who turned 23 on Monday, was suspended without pay for
12 games by NHL vice president Colin Campbell for his actions in a
5-1 loss Thursday to the New York Rangers. Campbell said he
suspended Johnson because of a league-wide crackdown on deliberate
blows to the head and because of Johnson's past record of
indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who served the first game of his sentence Saturday when
the Kings beat Chicago, was suspended for a blind-side hit that
briefly knocked Rangers defenseman Jeff Beukeboom unconscious.
Beukeboom suffered what is believed to be a mild concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his $650,000 salary, the suspension will cost Johnson
$95,121. He will be eligible to play again on Dec. 22 at
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very severe suspension, but it's something we have
to deal with and we will move on,'' said Kings general manager Dave
Taylor, who attended Monday's hourlong hearing in New York with
Johnson and agent Ron Salcer. ``The message is that players can't
take matters into their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the Kings will not appeal Johnson's sentence, the
longest in the NHL since then-King Tony Granato was suspended for
15 games in 1994 for slamming his stick over the head of
Pittsburgh's Neil Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation Beukeboom also might be suspended,
for kicking the feet out from under Glen Murray a few minutes
before Johnson's actions, which were believed to have been
retaliatory. But Beukeboom received no discipline beyond the minor
penalty he received Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
