</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-HUSKIES-WOMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW WOMEN'S BASKETBALL ATTENDANCE KEEPS DECLINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The golden era for women's basketball at the
University of Washington apparently is over, and school officials
are trying to identify the reasons and find solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite back-to-back winning seasons and NCAA postseason
tournament invitations both seasons under new coach June Daugherty,
fewer people are attending Husky home games. The decline has been
steady, from 4,579 a game in 1993-94 to 3,609 last season.
</P>
<P>
   A program that twice ranked fourth nationally in average home
attendance _ most recently in 1990-91 _ was 23rd last season. NCAA
champion Tennessee led the nation in attendance, averaging 14,969
fans in 16 home games.
</P>
<P>
   It must be pointed out that when the Huskies ranked fourth, they
averaged 4,053 fans per game. That same figure would have ranked
them 15th last season.
</P>
<P>
   But with women's basketball rising in popularity nationally, why
is attendance at UW games falling?
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably have been a number of factors, but there isn't
one we can point to,'' said Leslie Wurzberger, the UW marketing and
promotions director. ``We are spending a lot of time asking people
what they think is the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the potential factors:
</P>
<P>
   -- Coach Chris Gobrecht, who orchestrated the women's program
during a remarkably successful 11-year run beginning in 1985,
departed after the 1995-96 season with eight 20-plus win seasons,
two league championships, one co-championship and nine NCAA
tournament berths.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Huskies haven't contended for a Pac-10 title in three
seasons or advanced beyond the first round of the NCAA tourney
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   -- Competition for the entertainment dollar is tough in a
metropolitan area that has pro football, basketball and baseball.
Stanford (10th in attendance) is the only other school ranked ahead
of the Huskies in attendance that must compete with the pros.
</P>
<P>
   -- The professional Reign began playing in 1996, giving
Seattle-area fans of women's basketball another team to follow.
</P>
<P>
   -- The UW men's program was a shambles for most of the women's
boom period, until Bob Bender became the coach.
</P>
<P>
   -- A love affair burned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all new and exciting 10 years ago,'' said Kathy
Anderson, a former Gobrecht assistant and now an assistant to
athletic director Barbara Hedges. ``The newness wore off.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is a city of many bandwagons, and its sports fans
climbed aboard the Montlake Women's Express in the 1989-90 season.
The team averaged 4,053 fans a game, shattering the previous best
of 2,967 per game in 1987-88.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for me was how the community adopted the
program and the players,'' Anderson said. ``It was unbelievably
exciting to watch the community develop that relationship with the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Gobrecht, now at USC, was known almost as much for her
demonstrative courtside manner as her in-your-face defense.
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty's demeanor is calmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have a coaching change, that is going to bring
disruption in your season-ticket holders until they see what you're
going to do,'' Daugherty said. ``When I came here (from Boise
State), I knew I was following in the footsteps of someone who did
a great job for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come into a situation like this, it's doubly hard.
Ask Jim Lambright what it was like following Don James. You know
that coming in, but it's important to be yourself and mold a
program the way you want to mold it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely going in the right direction, and I hope the
fans recognize this and grow with us.''
</P>
<P>
   When the current senior Huskies _ Jamie Redd, Malinda Lynch,
Amber Hall and Molly Hills _ began their collegiate careers in
1994, fan interest in women's basketball at UW was at an all-time
high. The women's team consistently was among the most-watched
teams in the country and had outdrawn the UW men's team five
consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, from South Jordan, Utah, was familiar with the program
before she saw her first Husky home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was against Stanford and the place was packed,'' she said.
``It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been large crowds since. Just not as large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love our crowds, but I have seen them taper off a little and
that makes me sad,'' Lynch said. ``We are working as hard as ever
before and have a very exciting team.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows were raised Nov. 15 when only 1,963 fans attended the
women's regular-season opener vs. the Iowa Hawkeyes despite
extensive advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed in the crowd, but sports-wise, there was a
lot going on that weekend,'' Daugherty said.
</P>
<P>
   The Husky opener came the day after the UW football team played
host to then-No. 2 UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is an all-day event,'' Wurzberger said, ``and to give
up both days of your weekend is asking a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a coincidence _ or because the Huskies haven't had
a 20-win season, challenged for a Pac-10 title or advanced beyond
the first round of the NCAA tourney _ the drop in attendance
coincides with the Reign's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reign only brings more attention to our game,'' Daugherty
said, ``but a lot of our fans cross over and it's hard to go to
four or five games a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies indicate that some Husky season-ticket holders either
changed allegiance to the Reign or reduced the number of UW games
they attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feedback I've gotten the past few years is there are too
many (women's basketball) games,'' Wurzberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Reign and Huskies are working to help each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that having a pro team in Seattle would help
promote women's basketball overall,'' said Reign general manager
Karen Bryant, a UW alumna. ``We have a great working relationship
with the UW, and I would be surprised if we are having a negative
impact on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked really hard to make sure we don't have any
scheduling conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reign was one of the American Basketball League's weakest
teams in its first two seasons, but has started strong this year,
which might further diminish the Huskies' Pac-10 attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to get our biggest crowds during the conference,''
Hills said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent drop-off, the Huskies have been second or
third in league attendance for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   After the average home crowd slipped to a five-year low last
season, UW officials sent a survey to season-ticket holders looking
for reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed:
</P>
<P>
   -- Fifty-six percent attend all home games.
</P>
<P>
   -- Six percent do not attend non-conference games.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fifty-three percent bring families.
</P>
<P>
   -- Thirty percent have UW football season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fourteen percent have men's basketball season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sixty percent attend Reign games.
</P>
<P>
   School officials say the success of the men's team _ reaching
the NCAA Sweet 16 last season _ hasn't had a negative effect on the
women because only 14 percent of those polled buy tickets for both
teams.
</P>
<P>
   So the search for answers continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that we've had a decline in attendance,''
Wurzberger said, ``but I don't think we've had a decline in
enthusiasm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
