<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE (AND ROSE) REVERSAL  
 THIS TIME ASU COULD BE SPOILER 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-ARIZONA-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder insists he won't raise the issue with his team, but
rest assured, the players know:
</P>
<P>
   ASU could keep Arizona out of the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sound funny? There's a reason. The Sun Devils have never knocked
the Wildcats out of a trip to Pasadena. Twice Arizona has kept ASU
from making the trip. On Friday in Tucson, the Sun Devils hope to
return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't brought it up, and I don't think I will,'' ASU Coach
Snyder said. ``That's not the emphasis. What you want to do, in any
rival game, is beat the other team just because they're the other
team. Regardless of what the benefits or downside to what a win or
loss might be, it's the thrill of playing in the game and playing
well enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh huh.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, too, insists he hasn't uttered the
words ``Rose Bowl'' to his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure guys think about bowls and so on,'' he said. ``All I
know is I think we'll be in a good bowl. Beyond that, we really
have no control, other than the way we play against ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the most important game in our season left, so we just
have to focus on playing our best game of the year, because that's
what it will take to win.''
</P>
<P>
   (See previous ``uh huh.'')
</P>
<P>
   Three things must happen for Arizona to receive an invitation to
Pasadena:
</P>
<P>
   UCLA must finish first or second in the Bowl Championship Series
standings. The Bruins are currently second, with one game to play
at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats must beat the Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl must opt to pick a Pac-10 team over an at-large
team. It would not be obligated to do so, and many have speculated
that Notre Dame would get the nod.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue interests ASU most, for several reasons. One, a
Sun Devils victory would guarantee a winning season and a likely
bowl berth. Two, a victory would mean payback.
</P>
<P>
   The latter issue may mean more to longtime fans than current
players.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, ASU was 8-2 under first-year coach John
Cooper. Arizona, coached by Larry Smith, was 7-3 and headed for a
Sun Bowl meeting with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Just before kickoff in Tempe, Southern California knocked off
UCLA in Los Angeles, giving the Sun Devils an opportunity to secure
their first Rose Bowl berth with a victory or tie.
</P>
<P>
   With 5:29 left in the game, Arizona's Max Zendejas missed a
52-yard field goal try, but a procedure penalty against the
Wildcats gave him another shot. He made the 57-yard try to tie the
game at 13.
</P>
<P>
   ASU took the ensuing kickoff with a chance to run out the clock,
but Arizona's Stan Mataele sacked ASU's Jeff Van Raaphorst, caused
a fumbled and recovered it at the ASU 20. Zendejas kicked a 32-yard
field goal to secure a 16-13 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils had to settle for a Holiday Bowl meeting with
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Three years earlier, it was much the same.
</P>
<P>
   ASU got a chance for a Rose Bowl invitation after Washington
State knocked off Washington during ASU's bye week.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils came into Tucson with a 9-1 record. Arizona was
5-4-1 and confident.
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. The Wildcats led, 10-0, at the half and 26-0
after three quarters and were never really challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the (roles are reversed), I'm approaching it the
same way,'' Tomey said. ``I don't think in games like this it
matters which side you are on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know each other well. We know each other's players.
Coaching staffs have coached against each other. There are not many
secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had a few secrets up their sleeve last season. A
handful of trick plays contributed to Arizona's 28-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, ASU was favored. The Sun Devils were 8-2, No. 12 in
the nation and had a possible bowl championship series on the line.
The Wildcats were 5-5 and looking to become bowl eligible.
</P>
<P>
   They did with the win and earned a spot in the Insight.Com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This game has impacted both teams in a variety of ways over the
years, but for many fans, 1986 stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Wildcats were the spoilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils had already secured a Rose Bowl berth and needed
only a victory over Arizona to lock up an undefeated season. Sun
Devils quarterback Van Raaphorst passed for 437 yards and two
touchdowns but threw three interceptions, including one Chuck Cecil
ran back 106 yards in the game's defining moment. ASU was trailing
24-10 in the fourth quarter but driving for what it hoped would be
a game-turning score. The Sun Devils never recovered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
