<HEADER>
A6253 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-UA-DOHERTY-AZ     11-24 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-UA-DOHERTY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE HAD A FOOT IN BOTH CAMPS  
 DOHERTY COACHED AT ASU, UA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He showed Vince Lombardi the T-formation. He was one reason the
Arizona Interscholastic Association keeps teams off the field on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Ed Doherty, football pioneer, became the only man to
be a head football coach at both Arizona State and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, with the rivalry, nobody would ever consider that,''
said Pete Doherty, one of Ed's nine children, who played
quarterback for his father at St. Mary's High in 1965 and '66.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty's last two ASU teams beat UA in 1949 and 1950, laying
the foundation for a competitive rivalry instead of a UA-dominated
series.
</P>
<P>
   When Doherty moved to Tucson in 1957 to coach the UA for two
seasons, he was razzed by some of the ASU players who played for
him in the late '40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he was a traitor,'' said Wilford ``Whizzer'' White,
a dazzling back for Doherty in Tempe. ``We had fun with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, 79, whose health has been on the decline for years,
wasn't available to be interviewed. He lives in Tucson, where his
last coaching job was at Salpointe High in the late 1970s and early
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   But his college memories remain at ASU, where he had much more
success than he did in his two seasons at UA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he still relates more to ASU than he does to UA,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty was 25-17 from 1947 to '50 at ASU, then known as Arizona
State College. His last two teams went a combined 16-5 and played
in the Salad Bowl. At UA, he was 4-15-1.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, a quarterback at Boston College in the early 1940s,
arrived in Arizona as a nattily dressed man who loved to create
offensive plays on a whim during practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the more creative offensive coaches I've ever
seen,'' said Morrison Warren, who played fullback for Doherty at
ASU.
</P>
<P>
   The year before Doherty got to Tempe, UA had scored a 67-0
knockout over ASU. In Doherty's first season, ASU led UA in the
first half before falling, 26-13. His last two ASU teams beat UA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That started the respect,'' Warren said. ``Arizona didn't look
at us as a pushover anymore. That showed the respect for the
quality of his coaching ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty had a hard time staying put. Other coaching stops
included Rhode Island, Xavier, Holy Cross and a stint as an
assistant for the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   He told ``The Arizona Republic'' in 1991 that he left ASU
because he felt he would be pressured by some alums to violate NCAA
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never liked college very well,'' he said in '91. ``I wasn't
good at it. I couldn't recruit worth a damn. Unless you recruit,
you don't win in college. In high school, you take what shows up
and make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   After his playing days at Boston College, while stationed at a
Brooklyn Navy yard in the 1940s, Doherty would go to St. Cecilia's
High in New Jersey, where he helped out a guy named Lombardi. He
taught Lombardi the T-formation, said Bill Quinn, who played with
Doherty at BC and was one of his assistants at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know that and take umbrage to it, but I
know, because I was there,'' Quinn said. ``Lombardi was a good
student.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty returned to his first love, high school coaching, at St.
Mary's, where he started many traditions that remain today. He led
the Knights to 5A state titles in 1967 and '68 and to a state
runner-up finish in '69, when they lost their only game in the
final to Central.
</P>
<P>
   At Salpointe, he took the Lancers to a state runner-up finish in
'81.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lavin, now coach at Bourgade, was a 22-year-old assistant in
'67 for Doherty when he won his first title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had diarrhea for two weeks, I was so nervous,'' Lavin said.
``He was such a legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called him Ed the Head. He was a cerebral coach, very
analytical. It was amazing how he could pick apart defenses. He was
very innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite health problems, Doherty worked relentlessly. A high
school rule was imposed in the 1960s because of his work ethic, his
son believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the Doherty rules was, `No practices on Sundays,' ''
Pete Doherty said. ``He was non-stop in game preparation. In the
'60s, coaches never heard of working seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty has undergone countless surgeries. His left leg was
amputated. His arteries have been unclogged and rerouted. He's
battled ulcer and gall bladder problems and aneurysms.
</P>
<P>
   ``His medical history would defy Ripley,'' said Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn was amazed to see his friend show up to a Tempe restaurant
before last year's ASU-Arizona game to honor the '47 ASU team,
Doherty's first.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty isn't able to make the annual get-together this week
with his former players and assistants from ASU.
</P>
<P>
   But they remember fondly the way he got young, local talent to
blend with World War II veterans into an overachieving team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we were glorifying our own efforts,'' Quinn said. ``But
those four years were special. It was a short time, but Ed did some
great things with the talent he had. He didn't have the best
talent, but he got them to achieve to their fullest. I believe Ed
had something to do with the development of ASU football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
