r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_STREAK-AZ     11-24 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_STREAK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 REASONS TO CHEER COYOTES HAVEN'T LOST IN A MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been such a long time since the Coyotes lost a game, you'd
think they wouldn't remember it. It's been more than a month _ 34
days, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough enough trying to remember what you ate for dinner on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time, but we all remember that defeat,''
Coyotes forward Rick Tocchet said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Oct. 22. A Thursday. The Coyotes were in Dallas and lost
to the Stars, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were mad,'' Tocchet said. ``Shoney (Coach Jim Schoenfeld)
was mad. The whole team was mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like it was last year, where it was, `Oh, we played
well in Dallas.' No, we ``should'' have won the game. It's a whole
new different attitude around here this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Dallas, the Coyotes have peeled off a league-leading
11-game undefeated streak of nine wins, no losses and two ties.
Phoenix (11-2-2) can make it an even dozen _ one shy of tying the
franchise record _ by beating the visiting Chicago Blackhawks
(5-12-3) tonight at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Though not even close to the NHL's all-time record of 35
consecutive undefeated games, set by the Philadelphia Flyers in
1979-80, it's a significant streak nonetheless. With that in mind,
here are 11 reasons for the Coyotes' 11-game run:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Commitment to teamwork &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The team's star players got together at the beginning of the
season and decided to check their egos at the door. Left wing Keith
Tkachuk and center Jeremy Roenick are no longer consumed by who's
No. 1 or No. 1A. Together, with the help of right wing Rick Tocchet
and other veterans, they have vowed to embrace the team concept.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment quickly spread. Nobody's trying to do it all by
himself; the proof is that 14 players have scored goals. Also,
every player has been willing to pay the price defensively. They've
created turnovers with relentless pursuit, especially between the
blue lines, and they're each taking turns diving to the ice to
block shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league is so competitive and all the teams are pretty even
now, so you really have to be working together and be on the same
page,'' defenseman Jyrki Lumme said. ``Bottom line, that's been the
biggest thing for us as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Goals-against factor &QL;  No team since the 1958-59 Montreal
Canadiens has gone this long
without allowing more than two goals in a game. The Coyotes have
held opponents to two or fewer in 14 straight, a post-expansion
record. During that span, they have allowed two goals six times,
one goal six times and have posted two shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they have given up only 22 goals in 15 games _
seven fewer than the next-closest team (Buffalo) and 50 fewer than
the worst (Chicago). In the last nine games of the streak, they
also have allowed only two third-period goals by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Men behind the mask &QL;  Where would the Coyotes be without their
goalie tandem of
Nikolai Khabibulin and Jimmy Waite? Not at the top of the NHL
standings, where they were leading the league with 24 points
entering Monday's games.
</P>
<P>
   Waite (4-0-1) and Khabibulin (7-2-1) are ranked first and second
among all goalies with 0.98 and 1.67 goals-against average. Waite,
who recently started four straight games and went 3-0-1 to win
Player of the Week honors, also leads with a .962 save percentage.
Khabibulin (.933) is tied for fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy played great while I was out (because of a bruised
hand),'' said Khabibulin, who will make his third straight start
tonight. ``But it was important for my confidence, I think, that I
came back and played well when it was my turn to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roenick's revitalization &QL;  First, he made a commitment to his
loved ones to be a
better family man. Then he made a commitment to the Coyotes and
himself to be a better hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   On the ice, he's leading the club with 19 points (five goals, 14
assists), and he's done it despite altering his game from his
free-wheeling ways to a more fundamental north-south style of
skating. He's still an exciting player to watch, but it's more
accommodating for his linemate Tkachuk. And it's safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge commitment for the benefit of the team and for
the benefit of Jeremy Roenick,'' said former NHL player Charlie
Simmer, the team's television analyst. ``You play as reckless as he
does and the hits are pretty severe. I think it's great the way
he's changed it up, and I think he's probably liking it a little
more now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; De-fense, de-fense &QL;  This is the
strongest batch of blueliners the franchise has ever assembled.
Though not the biggest or most physical, the Coyotes' defensemen
are clearing the puck and moving it up crisply to the forwards
better than anyone in the game right now.
</P>
<P>
   They have great speed and mobility. Oleg Tverdovsky, free-agent
addition Lumme and the reliable Teppo Numminen aren't afraid to
join the rush and create almost man advantage-type situations
because of their offensive creativity. Stay-at-home types such as
Gerald Diduck and Keith Carney make it a complete group.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Penalty killers &QL;  It might be the
toughest job in hockey, and statistically, the Coyotes are the best
at it. They lead the NHL with the No. 1-ranked penalty-killing
unit. They have killed off 67 of 73 power plays (91.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Specialists such as Bob Corkum, Mike Stapleton and Juha Ylonen
have put a vice-like grip on opposing clubs. The Coyotes have
allowed only six power play goals; to put that in perspective, 17
teams have scored double that or more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Captain Coyote &QL;  His contract
fiasco behind him, his captaincy reconfirmed, Tkachuk is off to a
huge start with 10 goals _ a pace that would put him at 56. His 217
goals since the start of the 1993-94 season are the most of any
player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing great,'' Roenick said. ``And he's having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coaching stability &QL;  For the first
time in five .years, the team will have the same head coach for two
straight seasons. Schoenfeld has got the players to buy into his
team-first system, and they're seeing the rewards for it.
</P>
<P>
   Assistants John Tortorella and Gordie Roberts have taken on
added responsibilities this season and are future head-coaching
material. Goalie instructor Benoit Allaire has the greatest job in
hockey right now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Practice facilities &QL;  Having their
own practice facility in north Scottsdale, complete with two sheets
of quality ice, several locker rooms and meeting rooms, plus a
state-of-the-art weight and conditioning room, has been a huge
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Before their $10 million headquarters opened in March, the
Coyotes never were quite sure where they would practice from one
day to the next. The Ice Den is close to their homes, convenient
and comfortable, and a big reason why the players seem in better
condition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Schedule  &UR; makers &QL;  In the beginning, they hated the idea of
.playing one game every
four days, but a leisurely early season schedule has allowed the
Coyotes extra time for rest, detailed practices and film sessions.
It's probably also why they've managed to stay so healthy.
</P>
<P>
   It took 27 days before the team played nine games. A hectic
December awaits, however, with 10 of 14 games away from home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Real sport, real fans &QL;  According to Tkachuk and others, America
West Arena is a
building that opposing teams are starting to fear. The fans are
rabid and, even despite the occasional ``red out'' when Detroit
comes to town, are acting as a sixth man on the ice for the home
team, Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the greatest fans in the world,'' he said. ``They're
a big reason why we're winning.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
