r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLAYOFF     11-24 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1 WORD OFF LIMITS TO CARDS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For much of the year the ``P'' word has been avoided, purposely.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals' wild win over the Washington Redskins on
Sunday put the team not only in control of its own destiny, but in
the driver's seat for the third NFC wild-card playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-5, they have a one-game lead over New Orleans and a
two-game lead over several others. But they have a two-game edge
over the Saints in NFC play, which is a tiebreaker after
head-to-head result. They play the Saints in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals haven't been in this position since they were 7-4
in their first season in the Valley in 1988, when quarterback Neil
Lomax was sidelined because of an arthritic hip. Five losses
followed.
</P>
<P>
   So as they prepare for Sunday's game at Kansas City, AFC West
champion last year and now residing in the basement after losing
six straight, is it time to talk about the ``P'' word?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' receiver Rob Moore said, firmly.
</P>
<P>
   When will the time come?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get there,'' he said, more firmly. ``It's way too
early. It's a goal, but we're playing a good Kansas City team
that's coming off some tough losses. It's not going to be an easy
test.''
</P>
<P>
   Added defensive end Andre Wadsworth, ``The only time to talk
about playoffs is if you have nine or 10 wins. There's plenty of
football left to be played. We have to take games one game at a
time, one play at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we're reluctant to talk about it. Maybe if we
were a team that went to the playoffs every year, you would talk
about it, but we've gotta cross that bridge when we come to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Moore adds a good point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our offense and defense could put a complete game together,
we'd be all right. But that remains to be seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive unit carried a confused young offense during the
first part of the season; now a suddenly hot offense has had to
bail out a suddenly shell-shocked defense the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Quick factoids: The 45-42 win in Washington marks the first time
in recorded Cardinals history (since 1920) that they surrendered 40
points and won. What's more, the franchise has allowed 40 or more
points only 40 times in that 68-year stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' defense has fallen to next to last in points
allowed in the NFC and ranks 26th in the NFL, allowing 274.
Conversely, an offense that ranked 29th in the NFL in total offense
a month ago now ranks 16th and is climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how we win,'' linebacker Jamir Miller said.
``A win is a win. We have some things we need to get corrected.
We'll work on them on Wednesday and see if we can get them
corrected. Hey, we've got to go out on Sunday and play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a case of us playing a little softer more than
anything. Trent Green was putting the ball on the money, and we
weren't coming out of our zones as hard as we were earlier because
we had the big lead. It worked to their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin, however, said the Cardinals changed little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to slow them down,'' he said. ``We tried blitzes,
played man coverage, zone, zone blitzes, double coverage and
weren't successful in any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins attacked the Cardinals' corners, more notably their
right corner, with receivers using double moves and cuts. Right
cornerback Tommy Knight came up lame again with the same hamstring
problem, and replacements J.B. Brown and J.J. McCleskey were
schooled (and so was the normally reliable Aeneas Williams).
</P>
<P>
   ``The right side certainly was a problem in this game; they
worked that area and had success throwing to our right,'' Tobin
said. ``But they threw to the other side, too. And down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work on double moves and cuts this week. Those
things don't go away. If one team does it, other people look at
films, too. We have to figure ways to stop it. That, and on our
jams. You are allowed to jam within five yards, and we were doing
it at seven to eight yards. We have to tighten that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said it's unlikely the team will add another cornerback to
bolster the right side, citing a couple of reasons: Few, if any, of
the caliber needed are available; and with only five games left, it
would take an exceptional corner to play the system well so
quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
