<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS SHOW FINLEY AROUND BOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Bernie Williams and his agent talked with Boston Red Sox
officials on Monday, the Diamondbacks began to focus on another
center fielder _ Steve Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, a two-time Gold Glove winner who helped San Diego claim
the National League pennant, toured Bank One Ballpark with his
wife. Leading the way were Diamondbacks Managing General Partner
Jerry Colangelo, General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. and Manager Buck
Showalter and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which lasted approximately five hours, went well,
according to Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were very interested. There's a mutual interest
on both sides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola was due to have further discussion with Finley's
agent, Tommy Tanzer, late Monday night. Tanzer was not on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who turns 34 in March, has a career .275 average. He
made $3.4 million while having a slow year with the bat for the
Padres _ .249 with 14 home runs and 67 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He is said to be looking for at least a four-year deal. Even if
his salary were to rise a bit from 1998, it still would be much
less than that of Williams, who is seeking a seven-year contract at
close to $14 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks denied they made an offer to Williams. Baseball
sources said the team might be willing to pay more than $12 million
but less than $14 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said the team's interest in Finley doesn't mean the
door is closed on Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep a lot of baseballs in the air, because you
are never sure what people are going to do,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's signing of outfielder Brian Jordan on Monday could
trigger a domino effect. The New York Yankees, Williams' previous
team, are on the verge of signing Albert Belle, which could lead
the Red Sox to sign Williams. &QL;  &QL; 
Tall in Texas &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Randy Johnson, Arizona's primary target this winter,
visited with Texas Rangers officials in Arlington, Texas, on Monday
and got a tour of The Ballpark from Nolan Ryan, his longtime
confidant. Johnson visited the Anaheim Angels and the Los Angeles
Dodgers over the weekend and attended a Mighty Ducks hockey game
with Disney chairman Michael Eisner, whose company owns the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo met with Johnson's two agents in Phoenix on Sunday
night and spoke again with one of them by phone Monday afternoon.
Johnson may announce his decision by the end of this week. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
