<HEADLINE>
TOMEY: RIVALRY HARD TO CONTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Arizona Coach Dick Tomey is determined that there will
be no repeat Friday of the 1996 brawl with Arizona State, but the
potential is always there.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey was reminded of it Saturday while watching news footage of
a fight that broke out before Florida State's victory over Florida
at Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, rivals couldn't control their emotions during a
highly charged moment that turned ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey conceded that coaches have a tough job preparing young
players for a long-awaited confrontation with a long-time rival.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dilemma. Coaches want their players to be full of fight,
but they don't want punches thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fine line,'' said Tomey, whose team got into a brawl
during the third quarter of the 1996 game after Wildcats defensive
tackle Daniel Greer was hit from behind. ``You want to be more
intense, hit harder, run faster and care about this game more than
any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, you want them to walk that fine line of good judgment
when it comes to not hitting late and getting penalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe you can do it. But, yeah, it's difficult.'' &QL;  &QL; 
On second thought &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greer, now a senior, was asked repeatedly Monday to look back on
the 1996 incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll never be erased,'' he finally said.
</P>
<P>
   He also continued to dismiss praise for a season that has a
chance to be Arizona's best ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything yet,'' Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A smart number: Defensive end Eli Wnek, a redshirt freshman from
Glendale Ironwood High School, leads the Pac-10's All-Academic team
with a 3.75 grade-point average. He also is the youngest player to
make the 25-member team.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey likes to look people in the eye, and that might be a
reason Arizona recruited defensive lineman Keoni Fraser, a freshman
who had to stretch to reach his listed height of 6 feet. ``Nobody
recruited Keoni because he's short,'' Tomey said. ``But I like
short guys. I'm short.''
</P>
<P>
   Still on a record pace: With every catch Friday, receivers
Dennis Northcutt and Jeremy McDaniel can break Arizona's record for
combined receptions. By combining for 11 against California,
Northcutt and McDaniel pushed their season total to 116, which
broke a 24-year old mark held by Theopolis Bell and Scott Piper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
