<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWAITING BOWL BID, HUSKIES LOOK FORWARD AND BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On the 100th day since they began fall practice, they
rested. The Washington Huskies looked gratefully back at 11
football games, at an impending bowl trip to Hawaii and at their
weary bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body is beat up,'' sighed Mr. Multi-purpose, Joe Jarzynka.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Washington is to receive its official invitation to
either the Aloha or Oahu Bowl on Christmas Day. For most, it's a
thrill. For others, it's repetitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back is not as exciting for me, partly because I
expected more,'' Jarzynka said. ``It doesn't symbolize improvement.
... I had Rose Bowl visions, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies will try to realize those visions next year with a
new quarterback, probably Marques Tuiasosopo. At least UW coach Jim
Lambright didn't sound like a guy introducing a boffo competition
between Tuiasosopo and reserve J.K. Scott when he said of
Tuiasosopo, ``He's the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have clamored for Tuiasosopo in favor of Brock Huard
soon will get the full dose. Lambright says that will wait until
after the bowl game, although Washington will try to re-establish
the run game next year; Christmas Day will be intended as Brock
Huard's stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He carries this one out exactly as we have all season long,''
Lambright said. ``This is an accomplishment Brock got us to, so we
want to make sure this is also his bowl game.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as Huard's statistics declined this year, Tuiasosopo's also
felt the brunt of a lesser supporting cast. There was no Jerome
Pathon, for instance, to flag down passes off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Tuiasosopo completed 50.6 percent of his passes compared with
57.8 last year and had a touchdown-to-interception ratio of 2-5
compared with 3-1 in 1997. He did relieve an injured Huard for
victories against Utah State and Cal, while in '97, Washington was
upset by Oregon in Tuiasosopo's only starting appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``His feet are a great escape and a great tool for us to use,''
Lambright said. ``At this point, we have to work a lot more on his
passing. It's a combination of mechanics and just repetitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuiasosopo doesn't have a mega-arm, but the Huskies feel they
can win with it. He is a terrific leader, so the main question
surrounds how he handles the role of being an every-down
quarterback rather than a change-of-pace substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to gain more grasp of the overall quarterback
position,'' Jarzynka said. ``He's an outstanding option runner, he
moves real well, but he doesn't necessarily have that quarterback
mentality. He's more of a pure athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get out there and work a lot with his throwing,
balance up his throwing and running ability.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Scott, says Jarzynka: ``J.K. might have a better arm than
Brock. He has a little bit of a control problem, a little bit of an
accuracy problem. Control, as far as touch passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuiasosopo, 6-foot-2 and 210 pounds, will be a third-year junior
in 1999. Scott, 6-3 and 210, will be a redshirt sophomore. He
played only two years of high school football in Burbank, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Huard announced after Saturday's 16-9 Apple Cup victory over
Washington State that he was leaving early for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we worked for everything we got,'' Huard said
Monday. ``Nothing was given to the '98 Huskies. I think that's
going to make it more meaningful when we look back on it.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD: Washington's 1999 schedule has opening non-league
games with BYU, Air Force and Colorado, no bye week, and wicked
consecutive November road games with Arizona, the probable
preseason Pac-10 favorite, and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   With a late opener (Sept. 11), moving a November game up may
make sense, although Lambright said he knew of no proposed move of
a game. Usually those TV-inspired changes are made in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   TRACKING TOALEI: Asked what he would tell little-used JC
transfer defensive tackle Toalei Mulitauaopele for the offseason,
Lambright said, ``Run.'' And he repeated the word six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's improved,'' said fellow tackle Mac Tuiaea. ``It's just a
matter of him understanding what he needs in terms of adjusting to
the time commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   TWO-SPORT TUSSLE: Next fall, it will be a year from the 2000
Olympics, which take place during football season. Wide receiver
Ja'Warren Hooker, a super sprinter who had only nine catches this
year while fighting football injuries, might have to choose which
sport to play if he intends to make a run at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't think he'll have to make a decision until you get
right down to the year,'' Lambright said.
</P>
<P>
   IFS, ANDS, MUTTS: Lambright says the Huskies will leave for
Hawaii when final exams are completed, probably Dec. 17 or 18. ...
Lambright says the Huskies will try to recruit a scholarship
kicker. ``The good thing is, we got so much publicity about needing
a kicker,'' he said. ... FS Hakim Akbar broke a metacarpal (hand)
bone, but Lambright says it should mend in time for bowl practices.
... Lambright says he doesn't know of any UW assistant coaches
leaving the program. Given the squad's limitations, he said, ``I'm
not sure we've ever had a more productive (coaching) year.'' ... LB
Lester Towns likely needs a long rest for his injured foot.
``Hopefully, we can get him walking so it doesn't look like he's 90
years old,'' Lambright kidded. ... As for whether power has shifted
to the Oregon schools, which staged a memorable Civil War game,
Lambright said, ``There has been a shift of power from Washington
to everybody during the sanctions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
