<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCS-AZR &LR;      11-24 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE FOLKS IN PURPLE MAY SEE RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the current Bowl Championship Series standings remain
unchanged through Dec. 6, the folks in Manhattan, Kan., might turn
a deeper shade of purple.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State, undefeated and ranked third in the BCS standings
last week, had hoped to gain ground on No. 2 UCLA this week.
Instead, the Wildcats dropped a half point further behind the
Bruins, who gained ground in the computer rankings and strength of
schedule components of the formula.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, ranked No. 1 in the AP, stayed atop the BCS ranking,
but its lead over UCLA was cut by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS was formed to ensure that the top two teams in the
country meet in a bowl game _ this year it's the Fiesta Bowl _ but
it hasn't quieted the call for a playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   That cry probably will grow louder should the three top-ranked
teams remain undefeated entering the bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one of our better options,'' said Herman Frazier,
Fiesta Bowl president, ``but I'm not sure it's the worst-case
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   That scenario is why many people, including UCLA Coach Bob
Toledo, favor a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all three are undefeated . . . two people are going to be
happy and one is going to be very disappointed,'' he said. ``I
don't know how else to solve it. I just know it's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation last week that the Wildcats could
pass UCLA even if both teams finished undefeated. But the Wildcats
fell further behind, despite beating No. 19 Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, meanwhile, surged even though they won against an
unranked team, Southern California. They jumped from second to
first in the ``Seattle'' ``Times'' computer rankings and from fifth
to fourth in the ``New York Times'' rankings. Their strength of
schedule also improved from 12th in the country to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Playing USC helped, even though it is unranked, because the
Trojans have the third toughest schedule in the country, according
to the ``Seattle Times'' computer rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Angry Kansas State fans might want to direct their questions to
Coach Bill Snyder and his philosophy of scheduling easy
non-conference games. While UCLA scheduled Texas, Houston and
Miami, Kansas State faced Northern Illinois, Northeastern Louisiana
and Indiana State, which is in Division I-AA.
</P>
<P>
   The top three ranked teams have a total of four games remaining,
and if they all finish undefeated, criticism of the BCS formula is
sure to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee plays Vanderbilt on Saturday and then faces either
Arkansas or Mississippi State in the SEC title game on Dec. 5 in
Atlanta. UCLA plays at Miami on Dec. 5, and Kansas State has the
Big 12 title game remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is not assured of a spot in the Fiesta Bowl even if it
beats Miami and finishes 11-0. Kansas State could still pass the
Bruins if the Wildcats win the Big 12 title game.
</P>
<P>
   If all three of the top-ranked teams were to lose, that likely
would move Florida State into the Fiesta Bowl, where it could
possibly face Texas A&AMP;M or Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing has been interesting,'' Frazier said. ``I
still think it's working so far. I think there's always going to be
criticism of anything like this from people who want a true
national championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
