<HEADLINE>
SWANN'S RETURN DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Cardinals are going to win Sunday at Kansas City, they
will have to do it again without stellar defensive tackle Eric
Swann, who still isn't ready to play after undergoing arthroscopic
knee surgery four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with our medical people (Monday) and he won't be back
this week,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``We will increase his level
of activity this weekend, and if he responds, he'll be back for the
New York Giants game. If he doesn't, then we'll move it back a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Swann was initially projected to be back for this weekend's
game. &QL;  &QL; 
Wild-card race  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have the easiest road of the teams they're
competing with for the third wild-card spot, but Tobin is far from
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got five games left, and we're not going to get in the
playoffs by winning six games,'' Tobin said. ``However it shakes
out, we have to win some games. We're aware of our position. We're
not living in a cocoon, or in the stratosphere, or whatever that
thing is they live in _ Biosphere, I guess. Unless we win, it
doesn't matter.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Sidelines &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer's three rushing touchdowns in Washington marked the
first time a quarterback has turned the trick in the NFL since
Archie Manning did it in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The offense has scored 66 points in its last six quarters. The
31-point lead in Washington was the largest for the Cardinals in
165 games, and the 45 points are the most since the team beat New
Orleans, 49-31, in 1977, when the offense featured Jim Hart, J.V.
Cain, Terry Metcalf, Jim Otis, Conrad Dobler and Dan Dierdorf.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of cornerback Tommy Knight, who has a hamstring
injury, won't be determined until Wednesday. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
