<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH WHIPS SUN DEVILS IN HAWAII 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-UTAH-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHAINA, Hawaii _ Before playing Utah in the first game of the
Maui Invitational on Monday, Arizona State Coach Rob Evans was
worried because he had only two scorers, forward Bobby Lazor and
guard Eddie House.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had two players score in double figures against the Utes.
But Lazor wasn't one of them. In fact, he had just one field goal
as ASU lost, 65-48, at the Lahaina Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-9 Lazor, defended mainly by 6-9 Alex Jensen, made 1
of 11 shots. He didn't score a basket until 2:01 remained and the
game long since settled. Averaging 18 points a game coming in, he
had nine points. House and guard Jason Patton each had 12 for the
Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ASU (1-2) made the game close at halftime, ending the first half
with five straight field goals. But aside from that, the Sun Devils
made 8 of 47 shots and finished at 25 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Utah (2-1), ranked 18th nationally, got 24 points from Andre
Miller, its All-American point guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils fell to the losers' bracket and will play Kansas
State today at 2 p.m. The Wildcats squandered a huge lead in the
second half and lost to Indiana, 71-70, earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first defeat of the year for Kansas State, which has
beaten St. Mary's (Calif.), California State-Fullerton and Division
II Washburn. The Wildcats led by 17 points with 12:58 to go and had
a 12-point lead with 5:09 remaining before falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   Although Evans is a man-to-man kind of guy, the Sun Devils came
out in a zone defense and stayed there. Probably Utah's 4-for-35
shooting from three-point range in its first two games had
something to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for a while. Miller was kept from penetrating, the
inside game was non-existent and the Utes were cold. But then they
started to find the range, and a three-pointer by Jensen put Utah
up, 23-9, with 4:10 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ASU also was content to fire from outside, but the Sun Devils
were shooting blanks. Trailing by 14, they were 4 of 25 from the
field. And when freshman forward Chad Prewitt, starting for the
first time, stepped to the line with 3:29 left in the first half, a
fan yelled, ``Break 10 before the half!''
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt made both free throws and, with walk-on Ron DuBois
running the team from the point instead of Alton Mason, and Patton
also providing a spark, ASU got hot. They closed the half with four
straight three-pointers, two by DuBois, and trailed by just three,
28-25, at halftime. What made the comeback even more improbable was
that Lazor was scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Utah made 6 of 12 three-point attempts in the half, 3 of 9
inside the arc. ASU was 5 of 11 from three-point range before
halftime, but was just 4 of 20 on closer shots.
</P>
<P>
   Lazor finally scored with 15:37 left in the game two free throws
to make it 33-31 Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils came within one when Patton made a free throw.
But Jensen scored on a feed from Miller, and Miller drove to the
basket in front of a passel of NBA personnel to put the Utes up by
five with 11:44 to go. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
