<HEADER>
A6552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOY-DONATION25-COX     11-24 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-DONATION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youngster makes sacrifice, urges others to also donate to
victims
 &HT;    By Dale Huffman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Chris Anderson, 11, of Butler Twp. was watching
television one Sunday morning when the images of those victimized
and killed by Hurricane Mitch caught his eye and his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Chris had been saving $100 his grandmother gave him on his
birthday in August to purchase snowboarding equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chris saw those pictures from Central America, he came to
us and said he wanted to help,'' said Terry Anderson, his mother.
``He collected his birthday money and he didn't stop there.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother said she was asked to match the $100, which she did.
Then he asked his father and his grandparents to make a match also.
</P>
<P>
   When it was totaled, it meant one child in the Miami Valley had
sent $500 to the American Red Cross to help the survivors of the
hurricane-ravaged areas of Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing what this boy has done,'' said David Petreman,
who teaches Spanish at Wright State University and who has visited
Central America on several occasions. ``For someone his age to
think in terms of helping others, and making a personal sacrifice
says a lot about his character. It is a wonderful thing and is
heart-warming.''
</P>
<P>
   The donation from young Chris Anderson was channeled into a fund
for the Red Cross that Petreman had started on campus shortly after
the disaster. The boy's mother works as an associate director for
informational services in the university library and heard of
Petreman's fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students, faculty, so many have rallied to donate,'' Petreman
said. ``Money does not come easy for students. But I passed the hat
in my classes, and I was surprised how generous everyone was. But
the gesture from this 11-year-old is really what impressed us
most.''
</P>
<P>
   Petreman has turned over $1,600 to the Dayton chapter of the
American Red Cross. Chris, who is a fifth-grader at St. Rita's
School in Harrison Twp., said he was moved to donate his nest egg
after he saw ``this picture of some people on the ground. They were
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought that I really didn't need a snowboard that bad.
I would share my birthday money. You know, it makes you feel
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Huffman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
