u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shysters share shady trait with quick-to-sue folk: No ethics
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It was like a fast-forward of an old Burt
Reynolds road movie. ``Hold onto your backside!'' my son shouted as
he floored the accelerator and whipped us onto the shoulder of the
road. ``Oh ----, Mom!'' he cursed as he gaped into the rearview
mirror in disbelief. ``He's going to nail us!''
</P>
<P>
   Within a split second, there was a sickening jolt followed
immediately by the gut-wrenching sound of metal and fiberglass
locked in their death throes. My beloved old Bronco had been chewed
up and spit out by a Pepsi truck on a congested interstate just
outside of Columbus. In an instant, my four-wheeled friend had
become a highway statistic.
</P>
<P>
   Dumbfounded, my son and I stared at one another as the Bronco,
with us strapped into it like two testing ground dummies, careened
to a screeching halt alongside the jammed up highway. We sat there
mute, waiting for the dust to settle. ``I really thought we were
going upside down,'' he said in awe. ``You OK?''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded dumbly. ``How about you?'' He swiveled his head a
couple of times, tentatively, and declared himself fit to walk the
hundred or so yards up the side of the road to the next wreck (the
one that had bottled up traffic in the first place) to ask the
officers to lend a hand.
</P>
<P>
   While we waited, we made a few crummy jokes about whiplash,
invisible back injuries, and maybe even the possibility of
developing a nervous tic. We had a good chuckle and let it go,
savoring the fact that we were alive and unhurt and might still be
able to make it to the east side cigar store before the Cuban
</P>
<P>
   lady stopped handrolling the cigars my son wanted to buy for his
father's birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   That was Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon and a hundred miles to the north, an odd
scenario had begun to unfold. My front porch mail basket was
overflowing with letters whose return addresses read like a Who's
Who of Columbus law firms. Am I being sued, I wondered, for getting
in the way of a Pepsi truck?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. It didn't take a crate of pop to fall on me before I
realized that each of these impressive letterheads had a copy of my
accident report enclosed. I wondered: Does the term ``ambulance
chaser'' apply here?
</P>
<P>
   The first letter informed me that according to the Columbus
Police Department Accident Records, I had recently been involved in
an automobile accident. Hell, I already knew that and had the mess
in my garage to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   His firm, he wrote, offers ``FREE'' initial consultation to
discuss my rights and to handle my personal injury case on a
contingent fee basis, but added (in parentheses) that even if I
didn't get any money, I was still responsible for his expenses. Now
this kind of says to me that should my neck brace and pathetic limp
fail to soften up the judge, I still owe Perry Mason some bucks for
checking it out.
</P>
<P>
   Another legal beagle offered to talk to me for an hour, FREE, in
order to discuss my injuries and the money damages to which I might
be entitled: personal injury, pain, suffering, medical bills,
property damage, and lost wages to name a few. Now this kind of
confuses me because right there on the accident report attached to
the back of his letter, it clearly states that ``A'' (that's me)
and ``B'' (my son) were ``5'' (not injured) and ``1'' (apparently
normal).
</P>
<P>
   The report continues to explain that the occupants of the chewed
up Bronco were wearing seatbelts and were not suspected of being
under the influence of alcohol or any other funny stuff that might
have caused us to drive onto the interstate looking to turn
ourselves into roadkill.
</P>
<P>
   Cut and dried. There was an accident. No one was hurt. And as
long as Pepsi Cola fixes my Bronco, I'm happy. The last thing I'm
looking for is legal pettifoggery to muddy the waters.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I've developed a real attitude about folks who
sue other folks for everything including when the neighbor's dog
tips over their garbage can. I blame it on a lack of backbone and a
nonexistent code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Add shysters to the list.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
