A6557 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life should be a little more like mathematics: certain
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ How can 24 hours last a lifetime? It happens every
time you're waiting for medical test results.
</P>
<P>
   We've all been there. Unexpected symptoms. The call to the
doctor. The round of tests. The wait.
</P>
<P>
   Possibilities _ all dire _ race through our minds, doing laps
with our emotions.
</P>
<P>
   I spent just such a 24 hours recently. That morning, I had
called my doctor and begged the nurse to fit me into his busy day's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wait as long as it takes,'' I told her. And I did. It was
worth it. Better than sitting at home waiting with only my own
scary thoughts for company.
</P>
<P>
   This day turned out to be a good one for me. The doctor had
reassuring news. None of the dire possibilities I had been
imagining were going to come true, it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite our theology, I don't think any of us can help but feel
we've somehow dodged the bullet in these situations. This time,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the medical office and walking through the parking lot
toward my car in the gathering dusk, I looked down and saw a
child's math paper on the asphalt. Tire tread marks crisscrossed
it.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at those simple, neat rows of addition and subtraction
problems, I nearly burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how I longed at that moment to be 8 years old, when my
biggest concern was the sum of 27 and 14 _ to have the answers to
all my problems march in orderly rows across a white paper.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard it said that mathematicians, in the order and
certainty of their equations, can discover the beauty and truth of
life. In fact, there's a little-advertised movie out titled Pi that
addresses this issue.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't seen it, but I'm told it's an odd, disturbing film
with more deep meaning than I'll ever catch. One of the
protagonist's premises is this: All of life is reflected in
patterns that can be expressed in numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at that smudged sheet of elementary math problems, I
could almost relate to that. Don't we all long for a world where
two plus two always adds up to four? It doesn't. Not when one day
you're healthy as a horse and the next you're lying on an examining
table wearing a hankie-sized piece of cotton wondering if you'll
survive the chemotherapy. That doesn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   One of our sons is fascinated with math. One night he showed us
Sierpinski's Triangle, where addition creates patterns that form
never-ending triangles, into infinity. Another time, he pulled up
fractals on the computer screen to show us how the patterns repeat
themselves endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   I remember one day he came home from an English essay test
totally stressed out, even though he knew the subject well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter?'' I asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so open,'' he sighed heavily. ``The answer can be
anything or nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   I know the feeling. The answer to my medical test that day could
have been anything or nothing at all. I didn't like the odds. And,
like an essay answer, I had no control over the teacher's grading
process.
</P>
<P>
   I've never particularly appreciated math. Typically, I don't
like foregone conclusions. There's no fun in that to me. No
mystery. No adventure. If you know how to arrive at the answer, why
make the trip?
</P>
<P>
   But then, on days like this one, I look at a dirty math paper
and it reduces me to tears. Sometimes, you like for things to add
up right.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas. E-mail: VMKabat(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
