<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The other Tom Wolfe
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The watch is mercifully ended. Tom Wolfe has not just
left the building but skipped town. The Second Coming, if it comes,
will not be more celebrated than Wolfe's stay in Atlanta. He was
everywhere, and everywhere lionized. From the Piedmont Driving Club
to the Atlanta History Center, the author of ``A Man in Full'' was
the man of the moment, a Southerner who was more than another
swizzle stick in Manhattan's literary life.
</P>
<P>
   The South treats its native sons better these days. It has
always loved them like no one else, but an earlier Tom Wolfe knew
how it could also turn on them. Had there been a watch for that Tom
Wolfe, it would not have been to celebrate him. It's easy to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   In October of 1929, on the eve of the Great Crash, sons and
daughters of immigrants sat in a New York City college classroom.
They were waiting for their eccentric English instructor, who
everyone knew was writing a book. Momentarily, one of them recalled
years later, their disheveled 6-foot-6 teacher came ``busting into
class, clutching a smashed hat to one side of his bosom and a
brightly jacketed copy of his new book over his heaving heart.''
Thomas Wolfe had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look Homeward, Angel'' was published when he was not yet 30
years old. William Faulkner's ``The Sound and the Fury'' and Ernest
Hemingway's ``A Farewell to Arms'' were published in the same year,
but in the fall of 1929 Thomas Wolfe was bigger than either and
bigger than Tom Wolfe, too.
</P>
<P>
   But no parades awaited him in his hometown. A local librarian
refused to order Wolfe's novel for her library, her stand for
decency applauded by a citizen who wrote: ``Do not let any
influence persuade you to let his buckets of night soil sit on your
shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, I stopped in Asheville, N.C., and drove by the
Thomas Wolfe home, where I had made a pilgrimage years earlier. His
detractors thought him unreadable in his own day, and he is unread
in ours. But at least one of his biographers, David Herbert Donald
of Harvard University, found in Wolfe's fiction ``a remarkably full
social history of the United States during the first four decades
of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Many would make a similar claim for the contemporary Tom Wolfe,
a chronicler of our vanities and ambitions. No one would think to
compare the two beyond that, either as men or as writers. One is a
dapper darling of the modern media; the other was a brooding giant
of overreaching ambition, staggering vitality and an insatiable
lust for rich women. More than anything, he was a man isolated
within himself.
</P>
<P>
   The most one could say, now that today's Tom Wolfe has two
novels under his belt, is that they write very big books. In Thomas
Wolfe's case, they were so big that the endlessly patient Maxwell
Perkins said editing him was like holding on to the fin of a
plunging whale. When Perkins agreed to take him on, he had
scribbled a manuscript twice the length of ``War and Peace,'' and
still wasn't finished.
</P>
<P>
   In the life of that Thomas Wolfe, there was the pathos of a
tragic figure. ``You are one of the rocks to which my life is
anchored,'' Wolfe wrote Perkins once. True as it was, the
relationship would rupture in hurt feelings, like his affair with
Aline Bernstein, a married woman 18 years older. Together, they
were _ in Andrew Turnbull's words _ ``the twin engines that got
Wolfe's heavy plane off the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Both endured and forgave Wolfe's rages and furies, much as
Asheville would forgive him his heresies. In September of 1938,
nine years after it was ready to hang him, the town stood at
attention for the funeral of its prodigal son, dead at 38 from
tuberculosis. The First Presbyterian Church resounded with hymns,
and the Rev. R.F. Campbell read from Wolfe's ``Of Time and the
River.''
</P>
<P>
   Days earlier, Aline Bernstein had wanted to come when it became
apparent that Wolfe would not make it, the great vitality draining
rapidly away. Maxwell Perkins, fearing her appearance would upset
him, dissuaded her. Perkins _ ``the silent friend of Tom's
spirit,'' as Andrew Turnbull called him _ was an honorary
pallbearer but stayed in the background, as he always had. At the
graveside, he stood off by himself in a grove of maple and oak, a
line from ``King Lear'' running through his head: ``He hates them
that would upon the rack of this tough world stretch him out
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   This forgotten Thomas Wolfe was on the rack all his life,
Perkins believed, and, had he lived, ever would be.
</P>
<P>
   His last letter, written from the hospital, was to Perkins. All
his trust in his old friend was restored, and his affection with
it, and he thanked him ``1,000 times.'' Touched, Perkins showed the
letter to a few intimates. ``Max,'' one of them said, ``You and
Aline made Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Perkins said, ``Tom had the wit to find us.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes about books, culture and beer for The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
