<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARE25-C     11-24 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's all about O. Mare
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wander around the Miami Dolphins' locker
room asking about Olindo Mare and you will hear the same words over
and over.
</P>
<P>
   (ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   They are descriptions that are so simple, so seemingly obvious,
that their significance almost doesn't register.
</P>
<P>
   Then you remember that Mare is a placekicker. That the last time
the Dolphins met the Patriots he scored all his team's points. That
his 43-yard field goal in overtime gave Miami a 12-9 victory. And,
most of all, that his teammates put him on their shoulders and
carried him part of the way to the Pro Player Stadium locker room.
</P>
<P>
   With that image in mind, the meaning of his teammates are saying
becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   It's like John Bock, the offensive lineman who first lifted
Mare, explained: ``Some kickers have never really been football
players. They don't really fit in. That's not the case with Olindo.
... He has everybody's respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The stereotype of a placekicker is this: He seems to fit into an
NFL locker room like Kate Moss fits in a Weight Watchers meeting.
He is small. He can do little more than kick a ball a long way. He
can't tackle. He grew up thousands of miles away, not knowing the
difference between a touchback and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Beano Cook once said, ``The two most important jobs in America
are held by foreigners _ room service and field-goal kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mare, of course, proves this wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, at 5-foot-10 and 186 pounds, he is small compared not only
to the rest of the people in his locker room but also to the new
wave of bigger kickers in the league. But he hardly grew up a
thousand miles away. More like a few thousands yards.
</P>
<P>
   His father came from Italy. But he was born in Hollywood and
raised in Cooper City, where he spent his weekends cheering for the
Dolphins, never thinking that one day he would be dressing a couple
lockers away from Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   That mere homegrown touch, however, hardly explains how, midway
through his second NFL season, Mare has earned the respect of
Marino and the rest of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   To understand that, let's go to the obstacle course.
</P>
<P>
   To spice up the offseason training, special teams coach Mike
Westhoff had the players play a little game. They split into two
teams, everybody but offensive linemen involved, and one by one ran
an obstacle course. Then, the two teams picked three players to
represent them in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Mare was one of the players picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the linebackers and defensive backs are picking a kicker
to represent them, it tells you something,'' Westhoff said. ``He
competes.''
</P>
<P>
   And he often wins. Whether it's on the obstacle course or the
golf course _ where he shoots in the low '80s.
</P>
<P>
   His athletic ability has prompted to the Dolphins to change the
playbook, inserting an onside kick that has worked to perfection
and a trick play that has not. And although the kick fake _ Mare
takes the ball and runs _ failed miserably in the first try, an
extra point against the Jets, don't be surprised if it the Dolphins
try it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most athletic kicker I've ever been around,'' tight
end Troy Drayton said. ``Hell, he probably can outrun some of our
receivers. ... Plus, he's aggressive. He likes to get down and
dirty like the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans' lasting memories of Mare may be his game-tying or
game-winning kicks _ he had three his rookie season _ but his
teammates like to recall something that happened in the final
preseason game this year against Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins scored on the opening drive. Then, after making the
extra point, Mare booted the kickoff two yards into the end zone.
The Packers' Roell Preston, who has returned three kicks for
touchdowns, burst through a couple holes and began a sprint down
the sideline. He only had one more person to beat, the kicker. And
he was charging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farther back on the field you are the tougher it is to
make the tackle,'' Mare explains. ``Obviously the returners are
faster than me, so you have to run up and get the angle, try to cut
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, he did more than that. He cut off Preston, grabbed
a hold of his jersey, pushed him out of bounds and slung him to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Flags came flying.
</P>
<P>
   Unnecessary roughness. On a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me after the game and said, `Why'd you have to
do that to me?''' Mare said. ``You know he was hearing about it
from his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Mare. Linebacker O.J. Brigance, the Dolphins' special
team captain, grinned as he recalled the tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a linebacker's mentality,'' Brigance said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second tackle he made in the preseason. And although
Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson doesn't seeing like penalties or blown
kickoff coverages, this combination the two seemed to put a glint
of approval in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   His kicker was a football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes kickers are so isolated, and they have so
much time away from the rest of the team, that they get a little
off-base,'' Johnson said last week. ``But Olindo's a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Mare made the switch from his first love, soccer, to
football, eventually earning a scholarship to attend Syracuse for
his final two years of college, he has made a point to be a part of
the team. At Syracuse practices, he often could be seen running
pass routes or playing running back on the scout team _ although
some of that can be traced to being a native Floridian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would get cold and I'd ask to do something just to keep
moving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even in the Florida summer, Mare goes the same offseason
drills as everyone else on the team. He does it more to be in shape
than to earn respect, but he realized that is an added benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I'm not this kid who's just here to kick a few balls
and ride the bike for 10 minutes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before games, Mare is hardly a recluse. To the contrary, he can
be seen running around the field. Catching balls. Throwing balls.
And, yes, kicking balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has endless energy,'' punter Klaus Wilmsmeyer said, shaking
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the game, the part of his job where Mare is forced to
turn off the energy, to sit and wait, to isolate himself from his
teammates while he gets into his own little world.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this also is where he earns his teammates respect.
</P>
<P>
   He has made 13 of 15 field goals this season, making him _ at
least at this moment _ the most accurate kicker in Dolphins'
history (80.4 percent). His only misses are from more than 50
yards: a 51-yarder in the season opener at Indianapolis and a
54-yarder at Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's kicking from 50 yards, I can turn my back,'' Drayton
said. ``I have that much confidence it's going to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the history of the Dolphins-Patriots series _ each
of the last three meetings has been decided by three points or less
_ it wouldn't be surprising if tonight's game came down to a kick
by Mare.
</P>
<P>
   So while much of the attention for the past week has been on the
11 names on New England's injury report, maybe Miami fans shouldn't
have been celebrating. There, on the Dolphins' report, was this:
Mare (hip) probable.
</P>
<P>
   When approached for an interview Thursday, Mare grimaced as he
slipped on a pair of sweatpants, then explained he had to go get
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He later shrugged off the soreness, calling it ``normal at this
time of the year'' and recalling that two days before the last
meeting with New England he wasn't exactly emitting positive vibes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed four field goals in practice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When it counted, though, he made four, adding another chapter to
what he calls a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   The kid from Cooper City is a professional football player.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Woods writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
