<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH BRIEFS: Suckers not what some doctors ordered
 &HT;    (Eds: A compilation of health stories that moved in the past
week.)
 &HT;    Staff report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What looks like a lollipop, tastes like a cough drop and has
some doctors concerned? Answer: A new product called Cough Pops.
</P>
<P>
   This cough drop on a stick is aimed at children and adults who
need temporary relief from minor cold and sore throat discomfort.
However, a child health specialist thinks the warning on the label
isn't strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very bad idea,'' said Dr. Sara O'Heron,
maternal child health specialist at Atlanta's Emory University.
``You're giving the message that it's candy. How can you tell them,
`No, you can't have another one of those, but you can have three
suckers?' How are you going to childproof those?''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for CoughCo Inc. in Aurora, Ohio, the company
that makes Cough Pops, said they are safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids love them,'' said Lisa Dean. ``There isn't any medicine
that would hurt them in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Ward, chairman of the American Academy of Pediatrics'
Committee on Drugs, agrees. Because the throat lozenges are
basically just sugar and pectin, Ward doesn't think there's
anything harmful about manufacturing them in lollipop form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the important part of the regulation of medicines that
look like candy is that they be given in the correct dosage and
that parents be well aware of that dosage and not exceed it,'' Ward
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our instructions are not to promote it near candy,'' Dornbush
added. ``It's among the cough-cold products so the parent picking
it up would know.''
</P>
<P>
   Cough Pops, made with chelated zinc, come in menthol, cherry and
lemon flavors. A box of eight has a suggested retail price of $2.49
to $2.99. The Get Better Bear retails for $1.49 to $1.99 for a box
of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Study points up problems for elderly drivers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Testing older drivers for depth perception and
ability to see traffic signals would be a better test of skills
than judging them on night vision, University of Utah researchers
say.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing Utah traffic accident data from 1992 to 1995 involving
people age 70 and older, the study found no support of the common
perception that older drivers cannot see as well at night and,
therefore, cause crashes.
</P>
<P>
   That theory, as well as the belief that older drivers lose
control of motor vehicles at high speeds, has been floated in many
states as reasons for restricting senior citizens' driver's
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A difference in older drivers and younger drivers involved in
crashes at night did not pan out,'' said Larry Cook, a statistician
for the University of Utah team that presented its findings
recently at the annual American Public Health Association meeting.
``And the odds ratio for a serious crash at highway speed vs. other
speeds was no different for older drivers than younger drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger drivers for the study were defined as ages 30-39.
</P>
<P>
   Where older drivers are more likely to cause crashes is at
crowded intersections, making left-hand turns and failing to yield
the right of way. They are almost four times as likely as younger
drivers to cause a crash by failing to yield and 1.5 times more
likely to cause an accident by running a stop sign or red light,
the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests older drivers have trouble spotting traffic signs
and signals in a cluttered visual field at any time of day,'' Cook
said. ``Depth perception may also be a factor because we found many
T-bone-type collisions (crashes in which one car broadsides a
second car) caused by turning left and running into oncoming
traffic. These are usually caused when drivers fail to judge the
speed of oncoming traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines target smarter, healthier babies
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of recent research indicating the first three years
of life are critical ones in a child's brain development, the state
of Georgia has developed voluntary guidelines to help child care
providers nurture smarter and healthier babies.
</P>
<P>
   Although developed by the Department of Human Resources' Office
of Regulatory Services and Child Care Licensing Section, the
guidelines are not a part of the minimum requirements a child care
provider must meet to continue operating.
</P>
<P>
   The standards, discussed at a recent DHR board meeting, give
child care providers basic information about what infants and
toddlers are capable of doing at specific ages and what toys and
activities child care workers should make available to stimulate
intellectual development.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, regulatory services had not stressed the importance
of sensory stimulation or provided information about brain
development. Georgia's licensing requirements focus on safety and
nutrition issues such as adequate meals, adult supervision and fire
evacuation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
