<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERFAITH-MARRIAGE25     11-24 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERFAITH-MARRIAGE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conservative Jews who intermarry banned as leaders
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Susann Ferarra was not happy to learn
that the rabbinical powers that be have decreed her unfit to hold
her job as executive director of Temple Beth David in Palm Beach
Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   She is, after all, a committed Jew. She has dedicated her
professional life to the Jewish community and her personal life
raising two observant children.
</P>
<P>
   But she married a Catholic. And as far as the highest rabbinical
assembly in the Conservative movement is concerned, that means she
cannot be a positive role model.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling this spring by the Rabbinical Assembly's Committee
on Jewish Laws and Standards, Jews who intermarry were banned from
holding leadership positions such as teacher, rabbi, cantor or
youth worker in Conservative-affiliated institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Pope's official pronouncements, the committee's
opinion does not have the weight of religious law. Fortunately for
Ferarra, the rabbi at her temple, David Goldstein, is choosing to
ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the assembly's ruling counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're basically telling (intermarried employees) to go
away,'' he said. ``If I got fired after this, I'd probably go to
the courts. This is discrimination. It's not discrimination because
of who you are, it's because of who you married.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Elliot Dorff of Los Angeles, the committee's vice
chairman, said he's confident the ruling is legally sound.
</P>
<P>
   But it points to the intensifying struggle within the Jewish
community to come to grips with an increasing intermarriage rate.
</P>
<P>
   Is it appropriate, for instance, for a rabbi to send a letter of
congratulations to the parents of a child who marries outside the
faith? Or to officiate at the wedding of a congregant who is
marrying a non-Jew?
</P>
<P>
   ``These are major questions,'' said Rabbi Richard Yellin, who
supports the ruling and who recently moved from Israel to lead
Temple Emeth in Delray Beach. ``They are part of a larger issue:
how do you keep a congregation Jewish?''
</P>
<P>
   On one side are those who want to slow the rate of Jews marrying
outside their religion by marginalizing intermarried couples
through guidelines like this ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On the other are those who believe intermarriage is an immutable
fact of modern life and a more logical tact is to welcome
intermarried couples into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Along the fault lines lie plenty of unanswered questions and
potential pitfalls. To avoid those pitfalls, most of the
Conservative rabbis in Palm Beach County interviewed for this story
said they favored the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   They said it reflects their current practices. Now it lets them
keep the peace by citing the rule instead of their own authority.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Epstein, a New York rabbi who is executive vice president
of United Synagogue of Conservative Judaism and the author of the
ruling, said the interpretation was unanimously supported by
committee members because it's necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize intermarriage exists, but we would prefer people in
role model positions . . . also model the ideal Jewish family,''
Epstein said. ``This is absolutely not a rejection of anybody. This
does not say to an individual that we don't respect you; it says we
don't think that you may be the appropriate role model.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was first printed this spring in JTS Magazine: The
Journal of the Jewish Theological Seminary of America and is titled
``Employing an Intermarried Jew.'' In three pages it cites
historical injunctions against intermarriage from biblical times _
when sharing a cup of wine with a non-Jew was prohibited _ through
modern times, when it was decided Conservative intermarried Jews
would not receive the honor of being called to read from the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really more of a sharpening of our position (on
intermarriage) than a change,'' said Dorff. ``We don't do this out
of meanness or nastiness; we do this out of a real concern for the
continuity of Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate of intermarriage has increased dramatically, from about
10 percent in 1965 to between 38 percent and 52 percent today,
according to several surveys. The last decade has seen an enormous
push by Jewish institutions, from synagogues to retirement homes,
to promote marriages within the faith. Hence the growth of Jewish
singles clubs and dinners and Jewish dating services on the World
Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Many rabbis say whatever can be done to staunch assimilation is
a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism is not just a religion, we are a team,'' said Rabbi
Leonid Feldman of Temple Emanu-El in Palm Beach, a supporter of the
ruling. ``If a Jew marries a non-Jew that means we're not sure that
his children will be part of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
