<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAVY-PRIMER25-COX     11-24 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVY-PRIMER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's all gravy from here
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All it takes to make gravy is broth, flour and fat. Some salt
and pepper. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   So why all the fuss about gravy? Even some veteran cooks refuse
to make it, remembering the failures _ the lumps and the anemic
color, which is what you get if you do it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Making good gravy is all in the technique, a matter of blending
those three central ingredients in the right way, at the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   But given the evaluation of the available store-bought gravies
(see adjacent story), Thanksgiving is the time to master this skill
once and for all. Even if you make gravy only once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that gravy is one thing on the table that has to be
piping hot. Making it can be a last-minute whirlwind performance at
the stove _ done at about the same time the turkey is being sliced
and the potatoes are being mashed. Doing everything possible ahead
of time is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Because there's a 1-2-3 order to making gravy, here's a primer
to making it right and as easy as possible.
</P>
<P>
   THE STOCK: You need turkey broth to make gravy. While some
prebasted birds that have been injected with broth exude a lot of
liquid, you'll need about 4 cups for a batch of gravy. Make your
own ahead of time with the turkey neck and giblets. Simmer in water
with celery, carrots, onion, salt and pepper for an hour. This can
be done the night before. Reserve the neck and giblets, if you
like, and dice them for giblet gravy. Store the broth, covered, in
the refrigerator. If you want to use the liver as well as the heart
and gizzard, cook it in the stock just for the last five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE FAT: Once the turkey is out of the oven and resting on a
serving plate, pour the juices off, ideally into a quart glass
measuring pitcher. You can skim the fat from the top and use it.
(It helps to stick the container in the freezer for a few minutes
so the fat rises to the top more quickly). Figure on using 1/3 to
1/2 cup fat. Or you can substitute butter.
</P>
<P>
   THE FLOUR: A lot of homemade gravy is pale and tastes of raw
flour. That just means the flour and fat mixture wasn't cooked long
enough. It should bubble and color nicely before the liquid is
added. To avoid lumps, use a whisk to blend in the flour. If you
don`t have one, this is the time to buy one. They're cheap.
</P>
<P>
   THE PAN: The best gravy is made in the bottom of the roaster,
where you can stir up the caramelized bits that add flavor to the
finished product. However, cooks who scorn prebasted birds may find
that the bottom of the pan has scorched. The choice then is to
start with a clean saucepan, butter and homemade turkey stock.
</P>
<P>
   Once the gravy is browned and thickened it's OK to let it simmer
at a bare bubble in the roaster at the back of the stove, keeping
it warm for the turkey, dressing and mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   And, remember, if your efforts are lumpy, run the gravy quickly
through a food processor and no one will know.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY GRAVY
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 quart
</P>
<P>
   chilled turkey stock (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fat, either from the pan drippings or butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   cooked, diced giblets, if desired
</P>
<P>
   When turkey is removed from roaster and set aside to rest, pour
off and reserve any accumulated juices. Skim off and reserve fat
</P>
<P>
   Add enough turkey stock to the pan juices to make 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Add enough butter to reserved turkey fat to make 1/2 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the fat in either the roaster or a large, clean saucepan.
Over medium heat whisk in the flour and cook, stirring
occasionally, until bubbling and aromatic and the mixture begins to
color. Gradually whisk in 4 cups of the combined drippings and
broth. Scrape the bottom of the roaster with the whisk to loosen
the flavorful brown bits. Cook until thick. Season with salt and
pepper. Add the giblets if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Options: If the guests are adults, deglaze the pan with a half
cup of wine such as a nutty Madeira, and stir to loosen up the bits
and pieces stuck to the pan. Add that to the reserved pan juices to
be used in making the gravy.
</P>
<P>
   To get a head start on Thanksgiving, make turkey stock now. For
real turkey taste you want the native bird, not chicken, but turkey
parts can be hard to come by. Buy turkey wings, backs etc. at the
Bowman &AMP; Landes Turkey Farm, 6490 E. Ross Road, New Carlisle
(between Ohio 201 and 202, north of Ohio 40).
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY STOCK
</P>
<P>
   turkey neck, heart and gizzard
</P>
<P>
   1 rib celery (leaves included), cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, cut into quarters
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 grinds black pepper
</P>
<P>
   5 cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   salt
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in a medium saucepan with a lid. Bring to
a boil, skimming off froth if a clear stock is essential (it isn't
with gravy). Turn the heat down so that the broth just simmers.
Cook for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the turkey parts and let cool before dicing. Strain and
discard the solids.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate promptly. When chilled, remove and save any fat that
has accumulated on the refrigerated turkey broth. It can be used as
part of the fat in the gravy.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to add the liver, just add it to the broth and cook
for just five minutes or it will be overcooked. Or saute the liver
in a bit of butter and add to the cooked giblets.
</P>
<P>
   Options: For richer flavor and color, roast the turkey pieces
with the chunks of onion, celery and carrot in a 400-degree oven
until nicely browned. Then proceed with the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
