<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Nov. 24, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-NETSCAPE (San Francisco) _ America Online announced Tuesday
that it will buy Netscape Communications Inc. in a $4.21 billion
deal that affects a majority of U.S. Web users. Under the deal, AOL
is expected to operate Netscape as a separate division but the
4-year-old company whose software popularized the Internet _ and
whose dramatic debut on the stock market was among the most
successful ever _ would cease to exist as an independent entity. By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   JOB-INTERVIEWS (San Francisco) _ Dr. Pierre Mornell, a
psychiatrist and author of ``Hiring Smart,'' advises companies that
carefully interviewing job candidates can save money _ and
potential headaches _ in the long run. Among his tips: ``Pay
attention to what people do, not what they say.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   YOURMONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Turkey and fruitcake aren't the
only things you can expect at this time of the year. There are the
sales pitches on the radio and TV to invest in heating oil futures.
Don't be fooled. It's risky, and it's not for amateurs. By PAMEL
YIP.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN-SONDHEIM (Albany, N.Y.) _ Stephen Sondheim, the
celebrated Broadway lyricist and composer, in a rare public
appearance, talks about his lyrics, his grim diagnosis of Broadway,
his memories of Ethel Merman and the ups and downs of his own
formidable output. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENCHANTED-ROCK (Fredericksburg, Texas) _ Following a winding
road north of Fredericksburg, an unusual sight awaits the newcomer.
Its the Enchanted Rock, a bald dome of pink granite that looms high
like nothing else in the surrounding areas of Central Texas. This
state park is so popular that attendance is often limited on
weekends and holidays to protect the fragile plant life. By DAVID
HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   With: ENCHANTED-ROCK-INFO
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANDLE-SHADES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Candle shades, popular in the
19th century, offer a more formal and decorative look. Candle
shades offer a flattering light for the complexion, and they keep
the flame from reflecting in the eyes of dinner guests. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know if she can
use beans from her daughter's wisteria pod to grow her own
wisteria. A Q&AMP;A. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS (Undated) _ A survey by the 3M Corp. shows that 27
percent of Americans put stereos, TVs, computers and the like at
the top of their wish lists. Next in line are clothing (18
percent), books (14 percent) and jewelry (13 percent). By STEVE
BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Of all the aspects of
Thanksgiving that I adore, my favorite may be an activity that is
almost exclusive to newspaper columnists: Publicly listing many of
the things for which I am grateful. It's such a refreshing
departure from the journalistic commentarian's usual task: Find an
ax and grind it. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-FOOTBALL (San Francisco) _ People think I am a football
fan. Maybe it's because I look like a typical guy, or perhaps it's
my fading athletic build, or possibly it's just the color of my
hair. The funny thing is that I hate football and haven't actually
watched a game since college. By KEN GALLEGOS.
</P>
</TEXT>
