<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCHANTED-ROCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITORS TO TEXAS HILL COUNTRY FIND ENCHANTMENT IN THE ROCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With ENCHANTED-ROCK-INFO)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Texas _ Following the winding Ranch Road 965
north of Fredericksburg, an unusual sight awaits the newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   Turn a corner amid the farms in the Texas Hill Country and there
is Enchanted Rock, a bald dome of pink granite that looms high like
nothing else in the surrounding areas of Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Enchanted Rock State Natural Area, a spot so popular
that attendance is often limited on weekends and holidays to keep
the fragile plant life from being trampled.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the 1,643-acre park is the domelike peak that
rises 425 feet. It's surrounded by smaller granite hills that are
part of the same vast piece of granite. Like an iceberg, only the
top is exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The granite formation, partially uncovered by eons of erosion,
is 1 billion years old.
</P>
<P>
   The first human visitors, more than 10,000 years ago, were
hunters and gatherers. Later, tribes such as the Comamche, Apache
and Tonkawa used the rock as a base. The Tonkawa are believed to
have been descendants of the prehistoric tribes and were there when
Spanish explorers stumbled upon the outcropping in the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   One such explorer was captured by Indians but escaped using the
vast surface of the exposed granite. Thus the name: swallowed by
the rock, the man was believed by the natives to have joined the
spirits of the enchanted past.
</P>
<P>
   Another enchantment is the way the rock has been heard to creak,
crackle and groan, sounds attributed to the granite's expansion in
daytime heating and its contractions in nighttime cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at the park and after setting up camp or
establishing a picnic site, it's time to conquer the central dome
by taking the Summit Trail.
</P>
<P>
   From the parking lot to the top, the walk is fairly easy, about
six-tenths of a mile. The rock's slope invites visitors to sit and
rest in stages of the climb to take in the spreading Hill Country
views.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the exposed rock is dotted with islands of
vegetation called vernal pools. Ecologists study the grasses and
the small animals that live there.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, park officials must go to great lengths, with signs and
brochures, to keep visitors from using the pools as restrooms or
places for garbage. These ``weather pits'' are for looking, not
touching.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, a multicolored lizard with a bright orange
belly might scamper out of one of the soil islands and greet you
with its floppy tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Serious climbers seeking more challenging angles than the Summit
Trail should register at the entrance office and get details on
recommended climbs of varying difficulty and learn the park's
climbing rules.
</P>
<P>
   Hardier hikers are in for a treat with the four-mile Loop Trail,
a giant circle through the park that rings the huge dome. The trail
seems to pass through several ecospheres as the scenery evolves at
every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers going counterclockwise will come across Sandy Creek
during the first mile, a good place to see while-tail deer. The
trail then turns left in front of the hill called Buzzard's Roose.
The name is appropriate, for buzzards constantly circle the peak,
their wide-spread wings barely moving.
</P>
<P>
   The back stretch offers wonderful views of Enchanted Rock's
steep side. The trail then becomes flatter and more woodsy. A side
trail diverts to Moss Lake. Another spur leads hikers to a point
called Scenic Overlook.
</P>
<P>
   Near the trail's end is a spooky landscape with 40- to 50-foot
high granite formations in all possible shapes. Passing between
such rocks and encountering new scenes on the twisting trail is one
of the highlights of the hike.
</P>
<P>
   The state park has four camping areas, a large-tent area plus
three designated primitive camping sites reachable only by foot.
Those are near Buzzard's Roost, Moss Lake and below the Scenic
Overlook along Walnut Spring.
</P>
<P>
   Campers should make reservations ahead of their visits.
Picnickers and campers should bring their own firewood for grills
(ground fires are prohibited). The park sometimes has a small
supply of firewood for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten camping and picnic items may be purchased at the
Crabapple General Store 4 miles north of the park entrance on Ranch
Road 965. The store also has camping grounds in back. The charge is
$5 per night.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer the comforts of home to the hard earth,
more than 300 bed-and-breakfast inns operate nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
