<SLUG> BC-CANDLE-SHADES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A FORMAL LOOK, TOP OFF CANDLES WITH A SHADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Once used for lighting purposes only, candles
have lately become a common accessory in almost every room of the
house, from the bath and family room to the kitchen and dining
room.
</P>
<P>
   Candles also can be found for sale in almost any store, from the
supermarket to the card shop. They come in virtually every size,
shape and scent. But for a more formal and decorative look, place a
candle in a wood, metal or glass candlestick, place a metal candle
follower over the top of the candle and then top that with a
decorative candle shade to diffuse and soften the light of a
flickering flame.
</P>
<P>
   Candle shades offer a flattering light for the complexion, as
well as keeping the flame from reflecting in the eyes of dinner
guests.
</P>
<P>
   Candle shades were popular in the 19th century. Many of those
elegant, beaded, fringed, cut-out and hand-painted styles are being
re-created by hand today by cottage-industry individuals and are
sold through boutiques or other retail stores specializing in
decorative accessories for the home.
</P>
<P>
   Candle shades also come in silver plate or brass, with either a
cut-out design or solid, smooth surface. However, the solid metal
shades tend to hold the heat in, making the candle melt faster and
making the follower list as it melts down. Always use straight,
hard Colonial classic candles, which sell for approximately $2
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Never leave a lighted shade-covered candle unattended. Make sure
the candle is upright, and not tilted.
</P>
<P>
   Freezing the candle will help it last longer and burn
straighter. A felt holder at the base will help to keep it secure
in the candlestick.
</P>
<P>
   The metal follower may vary a bit in size, so it's wise to take
it along when choosing a new shade.
</P>
<P>
   You can find mass-produced candle shades and candlesticks as a
set starting at $15. Shades alone can cost $72 for a large handmade
shade. The silver plate follower costs approximately $20, and brass
followers cost approximately $10 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
