<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS ELECTRONICS TOP GIFT LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Phone number, Web address are CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the most popular holiday gift this year?
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by the industrial conglomerate 3M, 27
percent of Americans put stereos, TVs, computers and the like at
the top of their wish lists. Next in line are clothing (18
percent), books (14 percent) and jewelry (13 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Although Americans love their gadgets, the survey also revealed
electronics aren't big-ticket items for most people: A full 80
percent spent less than $500 last year on the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETING 101: For a lesson in how the chattering furball named
Furby became this season's Tickle Me Elmo, consider: Furby was
unveiled way back in the first quarter of the year, at a major toy
convention in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   There, the proto-Furby talked up a storm, won over toy buyers
and promptly disappeared. Magazine and newspaper editors began
hearing about Furby during the summer, even though the creature
wouldn't be on store shelves until almost November.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally arrived, we too rushed out to hear him chirp in
his own language, Furbish. Find the $30 critter, if you can, at
most toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPERAMENTAL TUTOR: Quite the opposite of friendly Furby is a
computerized chess game called Ivan ``The Terrible.'' In his
teaching mode, Ivan will offer suggestions and ask gentle
questions, to which you answer yes or no, and help you improve your
game.
</P>
<P>
   Turn him into an opponent, though, and avuncular Ivan becomes a
tormentor. In a voice that sounds like Sean Connery's, Ivan says
things such as, ``Is that the best you can do?'' and ``Want a hint?
I will give you a hint. Give up,'' and, after a lengthy ponder on
your part, ``Are you sleeping or are you playing chess?''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan features a vocabulary of 500 words, 100 levels of chess and
sound effects including horses galloping, bugles blowing and swords
clashing. Find the $150 Ivan in electronics stores or order
directly by calling 800-59-CHESS (800-592-4377); Web site:
www.excaliburelectronics.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
