<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6729 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-INTERVIEWS-HNS &LR;      11-24 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-INTERVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERVIEWING JOB CANDIDATES REQUIRES SOME FANCY FOOTWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dr. Pierre Mornell once asked dozens of his
executive clients to tell him two things about the worst person
they ever hired: How long it took to resolve the situation and how
much it cost.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mornell, a psychiatrist, had spent years counseling
businesses about hiring key people, their answers stunned him. They
estimated that the median cost for that one mistake was $300,000 _
and it took the company a year to resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the things that led him to write ``Hiring Smart,''
a book from Ten Speed Press in Berkeley that offers 45 tips for
bosses who want to choose the best employees and avoid the costly
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Mornell offered a few favorite tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pay attention to what people do, not what they say.''
Mornell suggests such things as taking candidates for a walk around
the office or plant to see how they interact with others, asking
their opinion about a proposal or assigning them to write a page or
two about what they see as the strengths and weaknesses of your
company's Web site or one of its stores or plants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit a candidate's first interview to 20 minutes. That lets
you see if the chemistry is there without wasting much time.
</P>
<P>
   _ In later interviews, ask all your initial questions at once,
then shut up and listen. Mornell believes interviewers often talk
too much, sometimes telegraphing what answers they expect or trying
to sell the company to the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   _ All careers have peaks and valleys. If you don't know where
your candidate's valleys are and what caused them, you're ignoring
future problems. ``It's not a question of if they're going to
occur,'' he says, ``it's what they're going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mornell says people often gain insight about what is important
in life when they go through a painful period, such as a serious
illness. In the same way, companies often don't gain insight about
dangerous flaws in their hiring process until they make a severe
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   You can take steps to avoid those mistakes long before your
candidates walk in the door. Even before the 20-minute interviews,
Mornell suggests that companies have their most intuitive person
call the prospects for a couple of minutes each, simply to find out
how easy or hard they are to reach and whether they have good phone
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fail in those two areas don't even get their 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   During interviews, Mornell suggests throwing applicants a few
curves, like asking what bumper stickers they have on their car. In
the book, he tells how Larry Stupski, vice chairman of Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co., would ask the sort of question that Peter Falk used
on ``Columbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he knew plenty about the Human Resources department,
he would often play dumb and ask candidates for the department what
exactly a human resource director does.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the candidate could explain the job in detail, clearly and
concisely, Larry went on to the next question,'' Mornell writes.
``If the candidate spoke in jargon and buzzwords, Larry nodded and
smiled, but he always thought, `Gotcha!'''
</P>
<P>
   Mornell suggests that when taking notes during an interview,
divide the page into two vertical columns. Use one column for notes
about what the candidate says, and the other for what you're
thinking: questions, missing pieces, feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes your best insights come not during the formal
interviews, but before or after them. He says one technique you can
use is to walk the candidates back to their cars _ what people
drive and how it looks can say a lot about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest surprise walking a candidate to his car was when I
discovered the candidate's wife sitting inside the automobile,
waiting for him,'' Mornell writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hours in a hot car on a warm August day said more about
the candidate and his relationship with his wife, and her
acceptance of that relationship, than any of my questions in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against my recommendation, the man was hired for an operation
in Arizona. Predictably, his relationship with female employees was
an unmitigated disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of interviews, Mornell often asks the applicant to
call him in a few days, then they work out a time and day for the
call. Surprisingly, though, 15 percent of finalists don't make the
call at the agreed upon time.
</P>
<P>
   A lot more people make another basic mistake. Even though career
book after career book tells job applicants to write thank you
notes to those who interview them, Mornell says it wouldn't take
him long to count up how many notes he has received in 16 years of
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember every person who sent a note,'' he says. Mornell
adds that e-mail is acceptable for sending the notes, but the note
in any format should be personal rather than reading like a form
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Mornell suggests companies check public records to find out what
they can about candidates; sometimes it helps interviewers check a
candidate's honesty by asking a question when they already know the
answer from those records. He also suggests asking candidates what
their references will tell you when they call, which gives them a
chance to address any awkward situations.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to check references, his favorite method is to
call at a time when you assume the references will be out of the
office. Leave a message naming the candidate and saying they were
listed as references, then say, ``Please call me back if the
candidate was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are both immediate and revealing,'' Mornell
writes. ``If the candidate is outstanding or excellent, I guarantee
that eight out of 10 people will respond quickly and want to
help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1218EST &QL; 
