<HEADLINE>
PLENTY TO BE GRATEFUL FOR THIS THANKSGIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Of all the aspects of Thanksgiving that I adore,
my favorite may be an activity that is almost exclusive to
newspaper columnists: Publicly listing many of the things for which
I am grateful.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a refreshing departure from the columnist's usual
task: Find an ax and grind it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, I am especially grateful for:
</P>
<P>
   _ The results of the recent elections. I still wonder, am I
dreaming? The Republican Party in awkward disarray. The Christian
Right finally slapped back a pace or two. A Democratic governor and
lieutenant governor for California with our two and only senators
remaining Democrats and women. What an embarrassment of riches.
</P>
<P>
   _ On a related note, the window display at Streetlights Records
in San Francisco's Noe Valley. It sports miniature black coffins
filled with skeletons that have Newt Gingrich's face pasted onto
the skulls. Newsweek's ``The Loser'' cover is the centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   _ A real crab season. Despite all the travesties we have visited
upon nature _ polluted water bodies, species driven to the edge of
extinction by condominium developments and shopping malls _
crabbers are still hauling up tons of the sweet-meat crustaceans.
This year, if crab folks, wholesalers and restaurateurs can come to
an agreement, the industrious among us will be able to buy crab
fresh off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Living beside the Pacific Ocean. No matter where you reside in
San Francisco, you can walk outside your house some nights and
smell the sea as if it were across the street. Miraculously, gulls
still scream above the traffic din of gridlocked downtown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Archbishop William Levada of San Francisco. Although it is
costing the Catholic diocese a fortune, Levada has made it easier
for beautiful old churches like Old St. Mary's, St. Paul's, St.
Patrick's and St. Boniface to scrape up the millions they need for
legally mandated earthquake retrofitting. The man seems to get that
these are not just ``buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rev. Glenda Hope and all the folks who do the heavy
spiritual lifting at San Francisco Network Ministries. These are
people who still mean it every day when they say, ``Give me your
tired, your poor.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
