<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A HARVEST WAS MORE THAN CORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently put out a call for answers to a puzzle: If the word
autumn didn't join the English language till the 1300s, and fall
came two centuries later, what was the Old English word for the
season? By the following morning, e-mails from two readers _ David
Formanek of Arlington, Mass. and Jan Ziolkowski, a Harvard
medievalist _ had supplied the answer: harvest, now pretty much
limited to crops and metaphors, was once the season's name as well.
</P>
<P>
   Haerfest, wrote Ziolkowski, also formed the root of such words
as haerfestlic (autumnal), haerfestmonath (harvest-month,
September), and haerfesttima (autumn, harvest-time). As both
writers noted, modern German still uses the cognate word Herbst,
autumn. In English, though, autumn and fall gradually appropriated
harvest's role as a name for the third season of the year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the British-American split _ they prefer autumn, we go
for fall _ Ziolkowski wondered whether New England's more sudden,
dramatic ``fall of the leaf'' might have made the word fall seem
more appropriate here than in Britain, where a gentle climate makes
for a more restrained autumn. ``Maybe the reactions to your column
(fall-out?) will lead to a definitive study,'' he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Several other readers pointed out that though there are only
five nouns for the seasons _ spring, summer, fall, autumn, winter _
other, Latinate seasonal words are still in everyday use as
adjectives or verbs. In describing the spring and fall equinoxes,
for example, ``the more common adjectival forms are autumnal and
vernal,'' writes planetary scientist Brian Marsden from Cambridge.
And though we rarely use the adjectives hibernal and estival,
``bears still hibernate and African toads estivate,'' notes Richard
Sachs of Chelmsford.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Germanic forms of those verbs, winter and summer,
are also still current. And while you may have doubts about the
sort of people who winter and summer, you can't blame the language:
These are not new ``verbifications'' but centuries-old verbs with
deep roots in the Germanic languages. Spring and fall, already
burdened with meanings, are not used this way, though there's
evidence of an effort to adopt spring in the sense of ``spend the
season'': The sole citation in the Oxford English Dictionary, dated
1835, is ``Every third man has wintered at Naples, springed at
Vienna.'' This coinage, however, was clearly a recipe for trouble _
``She springed at Vienna, summered in Norway, and falled at Rome''?
_ and it seems not to have survived many winters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
What kind of verb am I?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wording of my lexical plea in the same column _ that ``some
generous medievalist will e-mail with the answer'' _ brought a
query from Kristina Nilsson of Newton, Mass., wondering about the
with in that phrase. Wouldn't ``e-mail the answer'' be more
logical, she asked, since mail is the closest relative of e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   Interesting question: Is e-mail a version of the verb mail, or
is it more like write? I could have used Nilsson's short version,
or said e-mail me the answer, or even e-mail me with the answer,
though that seemed long. Perhaps it should have been write (to) me
with the answer, given that a medievalist might well prefer the
pen-and-parchment method. But write the answer &UR;  &LR; alone wouldn't
work; it's grammatical enough, but it doesn't, as it were, get the
answer to me. A number of similar formulations are available, each
with its own variations _ call with the answer, phone (me) with the
answer, supply (me) (with) the answer. Probably none of these would
bother the average native speaker; but e-mail is new to the
language, still trying out various idiomatic combinations, and
people have different feelings about which ones sound ``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the birth of e-mail provoked a momentary tizzy among
usagists who thought the word shouldn't be a verb; they wanted us
to say send an e-mail. Traces of the debate linger in the new
Dictionary of Modern American Usage from Oxford University Press,
where e-mail is treated as a noun that is ``coming to be used as a
verb.'' The usage example, coincidentally, addresses our question,
and Oxford chooses the long version: ``Please e-mail me with the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
