<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLAIR-LORDS-BOS &LR;      11-24 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-LORDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEREDITARY LORDS WON'T GO QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When the House of Lords thumbed its nose last week at
Prime Minister Tony Blair,, vetoing a government bill for the fifth
time, Blair comforted himself by noting that it would be the last
roar of those he and his advisers refer to derisively as dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   But if those who inherit their titles in the House of Lords are
dinosaurs, they are of the carnivorous kind found at Jurassic Park,
and they have vowed not to lumber quietly into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,164 Lords, or peers, as members of the upper house of
Parliament are known, 759 of them are so-called hereditary peers
who got their seats simply because they were born noblemen. The
rest are appointed as so-called life peers. For about 700 years,
hereditary peers have passed their seats down through the
generations, like their titles.
</P>
<P>
   Of European countries that have bicameral forms of government,
Britain is the only one whose upper house has seats that are
inherited exclusively by the rich and privileged.
</P>
<P>
   Blair sees the hereditary peers as not fitting in with his plan
to modernize British democracy and make it more like the rest of
Europe. Blair and his Labor Party see the hereditary peers as an
embarrassing leftover of the days when an aristocracy ruled
Britain, and they cringe at the thought that a group of effete
nobles can stymie the wishes of an elected government.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle that has become the hereditary peers' Waterloo
has allowed them to cast themselves as the noble defenders of
democracy in the face of an arrogant government that wants to
handpick its European parliamentarians and eliminate one of the few
checks on its power.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, this is a simple political fight. Blair wants the
European Parliament election system to be similar to that used in
most other European Union countries, in which parties put forward
candidates, and voters cast their ballot for the party, not
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the Lords say these so-called ``closed lists'' are
undemocratic, and have vetoed the bill five times. All the Lords
can do is postpone legislation from becoming law for a year. The
reality is, no matter how much the Lords put up a fuss, even if
they filibuster until next fall, the new European voting system
will become law. In fact, next fall is when the hereditary peers
are expected to lose their voting and speaking privileges in the
Lords under a bill introduced by the Blair government.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides say something much more important than how
European elections are held here is at stake. The government says
the hereditary peers are an example of outdated, undemocratic
elitism, men who came to their jobs by the accident of birth, who
because of their traditional ties to the Conservative Party give a
permanent, built-in advantage to one party.
</P>
<P>
   The peers and their supporters contend that it is the Blair
government that is undemocratic, wanting to expand its patronage
turf while neutering one of the few institutions here that can slow
down a government that has had the biggest majority in the House of
Commons for nearly two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Timothy Beaumont says that while both sides are trying to
portray themselves as principled, neither is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair is trying to create a system that is blatantly
undemocratic,'' Beaumont said. Yet Beaumont, a Liberal Democrat who
was made a life peer in 1968, suspects some of the hereditary peers
are not as concerned with democracy as they profess.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to be covered in glory in this one,'' said
Beaumont, describing the controversy as the most ignoble one he has
seen in his 30 years in the house.
</P>
<P>
   As Britain becomes a country less bound by tradition, the Lords
are something of an anachronism. There are fewer than 100 women
peers, and hardly any minorities. It is the quintessential rich
white guys' club.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Lords have been championing themselves as
champions of the people, they seem to have little in common with
the common people, and have historically curbed government attempts
to whittle away the vestiges of privilege. For example, while the
majority of British people have said they want an end to fox
hunting, the overwhelming choice of hereditary peers is not only to
support fox hunting, but to take part in it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in recent years the hereditary peers have been ``down''
with the people, voting against tuition fees for Scottish college
students and against a wildly unpopular government ban on T-bone
steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Britons have been debating whether and how to reform the Lords
for nearly a century. One of Blair's predecessors, David Lloyd
George, trimmed back the Lords' power after the upper house
rejected the Liberal government's attempt to raise taxes on the
rich in 1909. But Blair has the votes that Lloyd George never did.
</P>
<P>
   Lord James Mackay, who as Lord Chancellor from 1987 until last
year was Britain's highest legal authority, says he has no problem
with reforming the Lords, but says it is pointless unless there is
a set of guiding principles agreed to up front.
</P>
<P>
   Viscount Cranborne, the Tory leader in the Lords, echoes that
sentiment, saying, ``I will go quietly if a properly independent
chamber takes our place.''
</P>
<P>
   But like most Conservatives, Cranborne says he does not believe
Blair wants to make government more democratic, but simply wants to
emasculate one of the few checks on his power.
</P>
<P>
   The Blairites can barely hide their contempt for the hereditary
peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't said they're all hopeless, but quite a few of them
are,'' said Baroness Margaret Jay, the Labor leader in the Lords.
</P>
<P>
   But even Labor stalwarts are divided. Lord Robert Winston says
he was in favor of scrapping the hereditary peers when he entered
the upper house three years ago. But he said it took him just three
days ``to recognize my prejudice.'' He said contrary to the
upper-crust stereotypes that he and others had of hereditary peers,
he found it impossible to tell the difference between them and life
peers, saying there were good and bad, liberal and conservative,
with no discernible voting patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe the hereditary principle to be indefensible,''
Winston wrote recently. ``What concerns me is that I cannot think
of a more logical alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither, apparently, can the Blair administration, which is why
so many peers are suspicious of the government's rhetoric about
getting rid of them to make Britain more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   As Winston sees it, if the hereditary principle is wrong, then
the monarchy should be scrapped, too. Blair, however, wouldn't
touch that with a 10-foot scepter. Last year, Blair described Queen
Elizabeth as representing ``the best of British.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Queen spelled out the government's legislative
plans for the next year in her annual speech to Parliament. Topping
them is the elimination of the hereditary peers, a foregone
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Beaumont says that one of the few peers who can hold his
head up is Lord Peter Shore, who was a Labor government Cabinet
minister in the 1970s, but refuses to go along with his party on
the new election system. Beaumont said he has watched in admiration
as Shore has made a principled stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord Shore is a democrat,'' he said admiringly, as if there
were no higher praise for a nobleman _ or a commoner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
