<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-24 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE EFFORT WAS IN GOOD HANDS WITH BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There are two signature games in Drew
Bledsoe's career so far.
</P>
<P>
   The first was four years ago when he threw 70 passes against the
Minnesota Vikings to bring the Patriots back from a 20-0 deficit to
win in overtime, 26-20.
</P>
<P>
   That was the game that turned around the then-hapless franchise.
They won seven straight games and made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, he saved the Patriots' season from ending here
against the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Against Minnesota, Bledsoe was put in a shotgun formation and
stayed in it to complete 45 passes for three touchdowns and 426
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the circumstances, Monday night was better. With the
season on the line, once again he was placed in the shotgun and
asked to bring his team back.
</P>
<P>
   He did, completing 28 of 54 passes for 423 yards, including a
25-yarder to Shawn Jefferson for the winning touchdown with 29
seconds left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe and Jefferson were the show. In the end, they were the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson (six catches, 131 yards) took advantage of backup
safety Brian Walker, who simply couldn't cover him. In two
fourth-down situations on the final drive _ in which the Patriots
wiped out a 23-19 deficit _ Jefferson had Walker man-to-man and
beat him to make first-down catches.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with Miami playing a three-deep zone, Walker was in the
middle of the field when Jefferson, coming down the left seam, got
open to make the catch in the end zone. That should never happen.
But it did, and the Patriots are alive.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, this particular group of Patriots had Dan
Marino's number. In the last two years, the star Miami quarterback
had one touchdown pass and 12 interceptions against New England.
</P>
<P>
   But in this game, he was outstanding. Marino completed 24 of 38
passes for 289 yards, with two TDs and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   The game became a shootout between Marino and Bledsoe because
neither team could run the ball. The Dolphins had 33 yards rushing,
the Patriots 41.
</P>
<P>
   The game officials let most everything go. Both offensive lines
were holding all over the place and nothing was being called.
Receivers and defensive backs were banging each other around, and
they let it go.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the game, Bledsoe had only one reliable target, Ben
Coates, who caught nine balls for 78 yards. Marino, likewise,
focused on O.J. McDuffie, who caught eight for 86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   However, with time running out, and Bledsoe taking everything on
his shoulders, he had to switch to Jefferson, as Coates hurt his
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   On fourth and 7 at the Miami 37, with just 43 seconds to play,
coach Pete Carroll was calling for a timeout at the Patriots bench.
But Bledsoe shook him off, then drilled a first-down pass to
Jefferson on the right sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team could stop the pass. Miami gave up a whopping 18
first downs through the air. The Patriots, still the worst in the
league vs. the pass, gave up 13.
</P>
<P>
   But the key was the Patriots' pass protection. Bledsoe threw 54
times but was sacked just once, despite facing a multitude of
blitzes. He saved the day. And the season.
</P>
<P>
   (ill McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
