<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOT TV GAMES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Finneran's Folly II:
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the National Football League, with the help of
Bob Kraft, is developing a scorched earth policy for Greater
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, on the day he signed a memorandum of understanding
with the state of Connecticut to move the Patriots to Hartford,
Kraft said that commissioner Paul Tagliabue assured him no new team
would move into the ``region'' (a new word in the NFL lexicon all
of a sudden).
</P>
<P>
   Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that if someone such as Paul Fireman decides he
wants to build his own stadium, buy another NFL team _ say, the
Buffalo Bills _ and bring it to Boston, then the league is going to
say he can't?
</P>
<P>
   We asked the NFL for a clarification Monday, and this is what
league vice president Joe Browne had to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston already has a team. The New England Patriots. And the
fans in Boston will continue to see their Patriots games on
television just as they have the last 27 years while the team has
played in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, many of our teams don't think `Boston' when they
think of the New England Patriots. The visiting teams fly into
Providence, R.I., when they play in Foxborough. They stay in a
Providence hotel the night before the game. Even two years ago when
the Patriots hosted the AFC Championship game against Jacksonville,
we had the league media headquarters in Providence, not Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I say, nothing has changed since last Thursday's
announcement. If the Massachusetts political leaders want to lure
another team to Boston, the move would require a three-quarter vote
from the other teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, I have a hard time seeing another team going to
Boston in the foreseeable future. A team needs a state-of-the-art
stadium. If the city and state legislature were not even willing to
spend money on basic infrastructure for a privately built stadium
by one of their own citizens (Kraft), why would they spend hundreds
of millions of dollars to build a stadium for an outsider coming
into town for the first time?''
</P>
<P>
   The distance between Boston and Hartford is 99 miles. Three
years ago, the Cleveland Browns moved to Baltimore, which is within
50 miles of the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the Raiders left Oakland for Los Angeles, 50 miles away
from the Rams in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Then three years ago, the Rams left Anaheim for St. Louis,
moving into the same state, Missouri, as the Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, would the NFL assure Kraft that no one would move
into Boston, which is 99 miles away from Hartford and not even in
the same state?
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though someone wants to put the screws to local fans
who have supported the Patriots so well over the years but simply
do not want to follow them to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   This is reinforced by what seems to be a changing NFL policy on
TV blackouts. Last week, NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said the
Hartford games would have to be sellouts before they could be shown
on TV in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. The NFL blackout policy is supposed to cover
only 75 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they try to do that,'' says US Rep. Ed Markey (D-Mass.),
``that's a late hit on Eastern Massachusetts. There is no reason
for them to do something like that. When the Patriots were 1-15 and
not selling out, were the games blacked out in Hartford? I don't
think so. I think that is the parallel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the deal in Connecticut, it seems they expect
not to sell out there. Why else would they give them all the
guarantees to pay for empty seats? But as far as I am concerned,
Boston is beyond the blackout area and should be able to see
Patriot games.''
</P>
<P>
   Markey is the ranking Democrat on the House Telecommunications
Committee in Washington and represents the North Shore area, so he
is going to watch how this situation develops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope the NFL policy stays the way it is,'' says Ed
Godman, the general manager of Channel 4 (WBZ-TV), the local CBS
affiliate, which has the rights to AFC games. ``I think it would be
in the best interests of our station and CBS to have Patriot games
back here in the Boston market.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL policy is unclear. On one hand, Green Bay Packers home
games are not supposed to be fed to Milwaukee, which is about 110
miles away, unless they are sold out. But the games are always sold
out. Conversely, Cincinnati Bengals home games, when they are not
sold out, are still shown in Columbus, which is about 100 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   So, like many NFL rules, this one seems to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Is the NFL's threat to black out Patriots games an attempt to
force Massachusetts fans to go to Hartford?
</P>
<P>
   It sure seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   And if the NFL is able to bully Boston around, then we can once
again thank Tom Finneran for screwing so many people just to
satisfy his own ego.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran's sticking it to Kraft has nothing to do politics. This
is personal. He doesn't like Kraft. Kraft's wife, Myra, backed
Finneran's opponent, Richie Voke, for speaker. When Voke lost, so
did Kraft, and eventually Patriot fans and the state of
Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
