<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SEA-BOS &LR;      11-24 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SEA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES FROM THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.  R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Mass. _ Dan Finamore, curator of the department of
maritime art and history at the Peabody Essex Museum, is too
modest. ``Well, there was a gap in the schedule,'' he recalled,
``and I said, `Hey, why don't we do a photography show?''' What he
meant was ``Hey, we've got a million photographs in our
collections, and it's about time we let the public in on the
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a simple sample of the collection turned
into something that Finamore didn't expect _ a show of 130 images
that transcends any single organizing principle. The show is, and
is more than, a history of photographic technique and a collection
of images of the end of sail through the age of motorized vessels.
This is no mere record of interesting historical events captured in
black-and-white.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the show comes from its basic source: These are
photographs, with a handful of exceptions, taken from the mariner's
point of view. Even when taken by landlubbers (Shanghai portrait
photographers, itinerant daguerreotype makers, or war
correspondents), the results are not about the sea; they are of the
sea, sprung from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't claim we looked at all 1 million images,'' Finamore
allowed, ``but we looked at a great many, and I was frankly amazed
at what we had.'' What he had was infinite variety. There may be
hundreds of photographs of ships' crews, but not one that says more
about the US Navy at the turn of this century than a group
portrait, taken by a professional photographer, of the men of the
Isla de Cuba. The viewer's first reaction is likely to be a passing
glance, and then the question: ``Is that sailor really holding a
goat?'' The men of the Cuba (who have shaped their uniform caps
into all sorts of nonregulation shapes) have sneaked a whole
menagerie on board. This is not the Navy according to the Navy
Department, this is a photograph of the reality of shipboard life:
occasional obstreperous amusement as a safe harbor in a sea of
ennui, danger, disassociation, and exile. The picture may be posed,
but the monkeys, dogs, cats, parrots, and the goat are real.
</P>
<P>
   Other images, often printed from Box Brownie and similar
fixed-focus, fixed-aperture cameras, speak to the seaman's point of
view rather than his condition in life. There is a remarkable print
showing a dismasted fishing schooner, the stubs of the masts rising
not nearly as high as the waves that still threaten the ship. A
sailor stands on the broken stump of the forward mast, peering
seaward, looking for a rescuing vessel. It is not a pose. Beyond
him, slightly out of focus, a few men slump against the rails at
the bow. It is a terrifying picture, altogether different from
Homer's stylized dismasted ship in ``The Gulf Stream.'' There is no
artistic distance to mitigate or stimulate the horror. Beyond the
captured image, it asks a question posed by many of the photographs
on the wall: ``Who could think of going below and getting a camera
at a time like this?''
</P>
<P>
   One person who did think of such things was a passenger on a
cruise ship to Miami, who, no doubt over his wife's objections
(``Harold, you can't be serious!'' at the minimum), takes a little
Kodak out on the deck and captures, barely lit and almost focused,
what appears to be a large, white-topped black cloud towering over
the ship. It is a wave. It is the wave of your worst dreams, and it
is not a picture you wish you had taken.
</P>
<P>
   There are images that do not speak of much more than mere
history, but even they do what art is supposed to do: change your
perspective on the world. A dismasted ship that had been caught in
a typhoon appears in a daguerreotype. It is sitting in a serene
lagoon, the water not rippled even in the minutes-long exposure of
the medium. A building with an oddly shaped roof line sits just
above the ship's pier. It is a picture from the Philippines, taken
before the Civil War. Who had lugged a daguerreotype camera to the
Far East? Is this a photograph to document an insurance claim or a
record of a triumph against nature? Or is it just the beginning of
the modern world, when the images will be purely factual and the
imagination will shift from questions of when and what to the more
complicated issues of how and why?
</P>
<P>
   There is a tension between modernity and retrospection
throughout the exhibition. A number of images seem to have the
precise intent of recording something before it disappears, and
some of them are very specifically from the sailor's perspective. A
disorienting montage of three photographs of one of the last active
combat sailing ships in the US Navy _ the USS Portsmouth _ shows
the vessel under full sail, seen from the very tip of the bowsprit.
The horizon tilts at a slightly different angle in each exposure,
and it takes just a bit of imagination to feel the ship plunging
ahead, an arm clasped around a line, a finger on the shutter
release, a breath held, a hope that the image will even begin to
capture the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Professional photographers, too, succumbed to the power of ships
under way. Enrique Muller Jr. documented sea trials for the US Navy
and, while shooting the USS Connecticut steaming at flank speed,
managed to capsize his photo boat in the bow wave of the
battleship. For sheer potential lethality, his photograph of a
submarine's periscope cutting through a calm sea is as disturbing
as the shark's fin in ``Jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   True, a few of the images could be dismissed as mere curiosities
at first encounter. At the entrance to the show are three
unremarkable daguerreotypes, a man, a boy, a baby. The pictures
sit, casually, on a small portable desk. Then you read that this is
the actual desk from the real cabin of the captain of the Mary
Celeste, the merchantman found in 1872 under sail, completely empty
of all human beings. The man is the captain, the baby is the
youngest child whose impression still indented its bed when the
ship was boarded. The small boy is the only survivor of that
family; he was at boarding school when his world evaporated in the
middle of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   It is an exhibition that works on every level. There are dozens
of images for photographers to study, the curious to wonder at, the
sophisticated gallery-goer to admire. Remarkably, almost every one
of the 130 photographs appeals to all three audiences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
