u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIPWRECK-ANNIVERSARY     11-24 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPWRECK-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIARY TELLS BROTHER'S GRIEF AFTER STORM SANK SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. on Nov. 26 a century ago, the top-of-the line steamer
Portland sailed from India Wharf in Boston with an estimated 192
passengers and crew. Their destination was Portland, Maine, but
their destiny was death in a storm that ultimately would bear the
ship's name.
</P>
<P>
   One George Kenniston Jr., a 20-year old Bowdoin College student,
was aboard that night, returning home from a Thanksgiving meal at
his Aunt Mabel's home in Hyde Park. Waiting for Kenniston in Maine
was his brother William, a country doctor who was raised on Yankee
principles of restraint and moderation _ and who kept a journal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The journal, recently ``discovered'' by a grandson who lives
in Arlington, Mass., details how William got a lifetime lesson in
self-control as he waited in vain, first for his brother's ship to
come in, then for his brother's body to wash up with wreck debris
that would litter Cape Cod. No shipwreck has claimed more lives in
New England waters than that of the Portland, according to local
naval historians.
</P>
<P>
   A version of the Kenniston story was probably told by relatives
of the estimated 450 people who died in the Portland Storm. Some 36
hours long, the storm claimed at least 150 ships. Massachusetts'
South Shore was hardest hit, particularly Scituate, where waves
obliterated a beach and bumped the mouth of the North River some 3
miles north to where it's located today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Portland Storm became the measuring stick with which all
subsequent storms would be measured until the Blizzard of 1978,''
said Dave &UR;  &LR; Ball of the Scituate Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   At the Scituate Maritime &AMP; Irish Mossing Museum, hanging on a
wall, are a life jacket and a pair of cabin doors from the steamer
Portland, but the ship's story doesn't end there.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Hollis Blanchard's decision to cast off, while many
other captains heeded the storm warnings, remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never know the end of the story because we'll never know
just why the captain sailed that night,'' said Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Another question closer to being solved is where the shipwreck
lies. About midnight the next evening, the first of two-dozen
bodies washed up on the outer shore of Cape Cod. Wrist watches had
stopped for these victims either at 9 a.m. or 9 p.m., the time
difference key to where the ship foundered.
</P>
<P>
   If the watches stopped that morning, currents and an ensuing
northwest wind had many hours to carry the wreckage southeast. If
it was p.m. _ just a few hours before its discovery on the beach _
the wreck would have been nearby. The late maritime author, Edward
Rowe Snow of Boston, insists in his writings that the ship is off
the Cape. Arnold Carr and John Fish, shipwreck researchers and Cape
residents, insist that it is midway between Cape Cod and Cape Ann.
Moreover, they maintain that they have found the wreck using
underwater scanning equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But have we got the nameplate? No. Not yet,'' said Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately a wreck identification will determine, among other
aspects of the ship's last chapter, just how long passengers fought
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland was a 281-foot paddle-wheeler with luxury
accommodations and a cheap fare _ $1 _ because it was competing
with rail transport between Boston and Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also carried the heart and soul of the African-American
community in Portland,'' said Peter Bachelder, co-author of ``Four
Short Blasts.'' Published last summer, the book attempts to
identify all the victims, which the shipping agent at the time
could not do because the only passenger list went to the bottom
with the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Portland tragedy, copies of passenger lists
were ordered kept on shore, and paddle-wheels, which are
ineffective in heavy seas, gave way to the propeller.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard had adequate warning that a classic New England
northeaster was brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Historians like Snow &UR;  &LR; thought Blanchard probably believed he
could outrun a storm. The wind direction in Boston suggested that
the storm was passing to the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard had another reason to sail. He wanted to make his
teenage daughter's birthday party home in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   When the Portland sailed, skies were cloudy. But within an hour,
Blanchard found himself in the deep grasp of a blizzard.
</P>
<P>
   Observers reported spotting the steamer knifing into heavy seas
off Cape Ann about 8:30 p.m. After that the Portland was not
conclusively heard from again _ until late the following night,
when debris and bodies came ashore on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lived long and much,'' Dr. William Kenniston wrote in
his journal shortly after the tragedy. ``Life had been running on
smoothly and pleasantly and in a way that seemed likely to continue
... (but now) has been changed.''
</P>
<P>
   William was the grandfather of Christopher Cirker, a
photographic equipment salesman and technician who several years
ago was asked by an elder relative to make copy photographs from an
old journal. Cirker never really read the text, however, until a
month or two ago, when he realized he was holding a yarn in stoic
prose about pain, loss, and a long-forgotten storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose at the core of it all is a need to recognize these
people for what they went through,'' Cirker said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, his grandfather William, then unmarried, lived in
Boothbay: ``Sunday morning there was a blizzard raging when I awoke
and again I thought of George and expressed my slight anxiety,'' he
wrote. But as he had done the previous night, he convinced himself
the steamer would not have sailed from Boston because of the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the Portland Press Herald reported that the
ship had not sailed. ``This relieved me of all worriment and I took
the paper over to Mrs. Freeman,'' the wife of E. Dudley Freeman,
William's best friend and another ship passenger.
</P>
<P>
   But by Tuesday, he still had not heard from his brother or
friend. Then he got a telegram from family members in Boston saying
the steamer had sailed.
</P>
<P>
   By lunch he was getting word that debris from the ship was
washing ashore on the Cape. William and George had been the closest
of several siblings. But in his journal, he sticks to essentials
such as borrowing cash from friends for the train trip to Boston,
then to Cape Cod, hoping to claim his brother's remains. He located
the body of his friend Freeman, but not that of his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never shall I forget the scene of that awful day. We were not
alone in the search for our dead _ nor were we the only ones
unsuccessful ... nor shall I forget (at an undertaker's hut in
Orleans) the dim rays of the old undertaker's lantern in the cold
shed of its ghastly tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Dec. 5, Dr. William Kenniston returned to work ``to
take up the routine of my practice, though with little heart for
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1325EST &QL; 
