<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAVE-ARIZONA-AZR &LR;      11-24 1932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVE-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS FIND `GOOD VIBE' IN ALL-NIGHT RAVE PARTIES  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYE BEELER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - In a back alley off Main Street in Mesa, Ariz.,
hundreds of teenagers and young adults converge in a kaleidoscopic
tangle, dressed like sci-fi conventiongoers on their way to an
all-night slumber party.
</P>
<P>
   They're jittery with a can't-wait feeling, knowing they'll soon
be psychicly free-falling through a rave, a form of all-night,
semi-clandestine partying that has re-invented itself again and
again over the past 10 years. It has become more slick, commercial
and global in its reach.
</P>
<P>
   There's a rave every weekend in the Valley, drawing at least
1,000 young people, who find their way to the site by dialing up a
recorded message or clicking on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs are part of the scene to some degree. But more important
are the opportunities a rave offers for losing yourself in
pulsating music, escaping your frustrations, feeling free enough to
fly.
</P>
<P>
   In this crowd, faces and shoulders sparkle with glitter, bodies
flash with Day-Glo necklaces, bracelets and Magic Marker-size
decorative sticks. Feather boas and fairy wings sweep across barely
clothed torsos.
</P>
<P>
   Necks and arms drip with children's costume jewelry _ edible
candy, colorful beads, animal charms. Heads and faces peek from
under brightly colored hairpieces, Afro wigs and surgical masks.
Pacifiers and lollipops project from partiers' mouths.
</P>
<P>
   The outrageous get-ups sum up the essence of the rave scene, a
free-flowing experience driven by the throbbing, synthesized beat
of electro music, which is heavy on bass and light on lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Through the music, ravers are free to be who they want to be in
this place, on this night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``It's all about the vibe. This is a spiritual thing. I feel
like I get high just listening to the music,'' one girl says.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching their $20 admission, they back up against the
building, forming two loose lines.
</P>
<P>
   From the open doorway, the heat and music escape into the cool
evening, tantalizing the impatient revelers with their intensity
and the psychedelic possibilities waiting inside. They're just 20
bones away from The Funky (expletive) Happens Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Raves have been around since the early 1990s, but they have
taken on a new form. The scene is still untamed, propelled by wild
dancing, drugs and secrecy, but the parties are more commercial.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, rave organizers would find a dilapidated
warehouse and plug in a couple of turntables and speakers. The
scene was undercover and underground. The pumping music was
powerful and magnetic.
</P>
<P>
   Party promoters would print up a couple hundred fliers and
selectively distribute them. Admission was less than $5.
</P>
<P>
   Now raves generate crazy-new money. Promoters pack the house
with a couple thousand people at $20 a head. A good night at a
``dope'' rave can bring in $40,000 to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some ravers don't mind traveling to get their groove on. At
Phoenix area raves, people come from as far away as California,
Colorado, New Mexico and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters advertise on the Internet and distribute glossy fliers
publicizing the appearances of much-worshipped deejays.
</P>
<P>
   These fliers herald the name of the rave and a phone number.
When dialed, a recorded message provides directions to the rave.
</P>
<P>
   On the first Saturday in October, the message directed people to
the Nile, a renovated movie theater at 105 W. Main St. in Mesa, and
the Funky (expletive) Happens Tour _ a national show with an
internationally known deejay. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE FUNKY TOUR: OCT. 3, 1998 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Nile, ravers seem deliriously happy. In the cavernous
room, bodies work every available space. It's so crowded that it's
hard to get to the bathroom or the water stations, or even to find
room to dance. The room is dark except for the blinking of
high-tech laser lights and the sweeping movements of glow sticks
waved by dancers.
</P>
<P>
   The room is smoky and has an odd collection of smells:
marijuana, clove cigarettes and Vicks VapoRub, which some ravers
believe helps them breathe more easily in the polluted air.
</P>
<P>
   George Hudak, 18, nibbles on a Day-Glo alien doll attached to
his necklace as he cruises through a sequence of fluid movements.
He is wearing a skeletonlike glove that glows red when he activates
its controls.
</P>
<P>
   He's already handed out more than $200 worth of goodies to
people here, most of them ages 14 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought candy, glow sticks and teddy bears for everyone,''
he says. ``It's the way. Everyone is so supportive and nice to each
other. It's a good vibe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravers hug a lot. They will ask to drink from your bottled
water, offer you candy or admit they're on the hallucinogenic
designer drug Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   As the layers of music wash over their bodies, ravers take an
internal journey. They forget they are surrounded by four walls,
that other people are in the room, that the moon has said good
night.
</P>
<P>
   When ravers tire of dancing, they simply sit wherever they
happen to be standing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the kids give each other back rubs. Others post a
lookout as a youth licks a piece of paper no bigger than a postage
stamp, which suggests he's taking a hit of LSD.
</P>
<P>
   A few kids press their bodies and faces into the humongous
speakers, which are stacked to the ceiling. Others lie on the
floor, their bodies vibrating to bass strong enough to shake the
stalls in the bathroom. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EARTHDANCE 98: OCT. 10, 1998 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The party at the Falcon Field hangar in Mesa is the kind of
place where raves used to be held _ mysterious and edgy. The blue
lights of the runway give it a surreal backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Earthdance _ a global dance rave held in 52 locations
simultaneously _ is intended to raise money to help Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet tracks the rave scene, allowing such international
coordination. In Arizona, ravers frequent www.azraves.org, where
you can find calendar information, reviews, photographs and music
links.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hangar, a candlelight shrine to the Dalai Lama glows
red, green and blue against the far wall. A few kids circulate a
petition protesting the Chinese occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this for his holiness,'' says the promoter, Randy
Blankenship, a private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   But his holiness isn't going to get his tonight. At 1:40 a.m.,
Mesa police officers bust up the party. A police helicopter hovers
in the sky, shining a spotlight on the kids, who scream obscenities
and gesture with middle fingers extended.
</P>
<P>
   Officers say they shut down the party after receiving complaints
about the noise and people driving on runways. No arrests were made
and no report was filed.
</P>
<P>
   From California to Florida, police and city officials have shut
down raves, confiscated illegal drugs and rushed hallucinating kids
to hospitals. In Tampa, the city went so far as to outlaw raves.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Mike Torres, a spokesman for the Phoenix Police, says city
officials look askance at raves because of potential problems
including fire code violations, safety concerns, and the
consumption of drugs and liquor with little or no supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a problem with that type of dancing,'' Torres says.
``It becomes a free-for-all. In order to have that kind of fun, you
have to get into the right mind-set. The kids are conditioning
themselves prior to getting in. They are taking hallucinogens, such
as LSD.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that some kids at raves do drugs, including crystal
meth, Ecstasy and marijuana as well as LSD. Sometimes, drugs are
offered only a short distance from security guards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dusty Cagle, 17, a Greenway High School senior, admits drugs
are part of the scene but adds that drugs are elsewhere, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get offered drugs walking to school,'' she says. ``You got
to choose. You want to listen to the music, meditate, let yourself
go. Or you want to screw up your brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Cagle went to her first rave when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gets kids off the streets, gives them something to do,''
she says. ``You will never see any kids fighting or arguing. This
is a safe place. It's like a shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents agree.
</P>
<P>
   Lorena Izenberg of Mesa allows her 14-year-old son, Tyler
Woodruff, to attend raves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't sell alcohol,'' Izenberg says. ``They search the
kids before they go in. As long as he keeps his grades up, he can
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff, an eighth-grader at Stapley Junior High, says he is
there for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place to dance to get away from reality, to release
frustrations,'' he says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOONSHINE OVER AMERICA 98: OCT. 24, 1998 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Nile on Oct. 24, about 1,000 ravers come out,
waiting to hear DJ Keoki, the headliner. Keoki, 34, is near the end
of his rave career but still draws fans.
</P>
<P>
   At a Denver rave, Miah Lovato, 18, of Albuquerque, heard that
Keoki would spin in Phoenix. Lovato and his friends call themselves
the Confetti Crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're candy ravers,'' says Lovato, wearing layers of kiddie
jewelry and trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   Candy ravers tend to fixate on kiddie accessories. They wear
jewelry and clothes that grade-school children might wear. They
also pass out candy, such as Smarties, Jolly Ranchers and
Blow-Pops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a style of dressing _ it's an attitude,''
Lovato says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SKUL: NOV. 7, 1998 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first Saturday in November offers an extravagant event
produced by promoter Angel Lovado and his partner, Larenzo
Contriras.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many raves have become Kmart raves,'' Lovado says. ``People
think because they have $10,000 they can rent a warehouse and get
any old deejay. It's deeper than that.''
</P>
<P>
   At ``The Dome,'' a renovated warehouse under the Seventh Avenue
bridge, between Grant Avenue and Jefferson Street in Phoenix, the
promoters put on a $20,000 show.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters say these productions often take three to six months
to arrange. Permits must be secured, a site found, fliers printed,
deejays hired and flown in, equipment set up, portable toilets
rented.
</P>
<P>
   This event features Sugar Twist, an international club
performance group. The members _ from the U.S., Germany and
Amsterdam _ include fire-eaters, a contortionist, a stilt-walker,
two trapeze artists and dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Fire-eater Airick Heater, 32, has a techno-punk look going:
silver studs in his face, elephant tattoos on his forehead and
neck. The holes in his earlobes can stretch to fit a soda can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an apocalyptic sense of fashion. But I'm very
passive,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 5 a.m., the promoters end the party. Several
hundred kids hang around until the needle is lifted from the last
vinyl record.
</P>
<P>
   Lovado, the promoter, believes electro music is big and getting
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually it will get to a point that this music is on the
radio 24 hours a day. When these kids get older, they won't know
such artists as Mariah Carey.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Cohen, media director for Moonshine Records in Los
Angeles, believes the rave scene is flatlining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about as big as it's going to get,'' he says in a phone
interview from LA. ``It's not going to explode. The music doesn't
have heart and soul. It doesn't look at you. It's all
computer-generated. The human input is minimum. Nobody is
sweating.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the case for the deejays. But for the under-21 crowd
_ too young to get into most nightclubs and bars _ they sweat
through the night, dancing at the one place that will have them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaye Beeler can be reached at jaye.beeler(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
