<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH ROUTE SEEN FOR HUB SUIT VS. GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Mayor Thomas M. Menino stood in the rain last week
talking of his planned lawsuit against gun manufacturers to recoup
costs associated with handgun violence in the city, a small crowd
gathered under umbrellas straining to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made his remarks standing beside the Massachusetts
Turnpike, across from a new billboard urging gun owners to lock
their guns and prevent shooting accidents involving children. Cars
and trucks roared by, and Menino had to raise his voice above the
din.
</P>
<P>
   He may also have trouble being heard in court, legal specialists
say, where Menino faces steep challenges as he presses ahead with
the lawsuit. Specialists say that trying to extract millions from
gun makers for the cost of urban violence will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stretch,'' Kenneth Simons, a professor at Boston
University's law school and a specialist in liability, said of
lawsuits that seek damages from gun manufacturers, distributors,
and stores. Boston is preparing such a suit, following actions by
Chicago and New Orleans. ``It will definitely involve the extension
of existing legal principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a surge of excitement about the gun-industry
lawsuits being brought by municipalities _ spurred in part by the
successes of state lawsuits against the tobacco industry _ there is
also widespread recognition that the suits are by no means easy
wins.
</P>
<P>
   They will require some stretching of laws governing product
liability.
</P>
<P>
   And the gun industry stands at the ready with potent precedents
that manufacturers cannot be held responsible for shootings where
their product is involved. Should distillers be responsible for
alcoholics, industry attorneys ask, or cattle ranchers responsible
for clogged arteries due to the consumption of red meat?
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, city officials are scrambling to put together the
strongest possible case. The city attorney, Merita Hopkins, met
with John Auerbach, head of the Public Health Commission, and aides
to the mayor Tuesday to put together the framework for the lawsuit,
said Menino aide Peter Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate choices are whether to model the Boston suit after
the New Orleans lawsuit, which alleges that gun manufacturers make
an inherently defective _ that is, unsafe _ product; or the Chicago
lawsuit, which alleges that gun makers and distributors knowingly
violate public nuisance laws by flooding the market with guns
favored by gang members; or, most likely, a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of issues we're still wrestling with,''
Welsh said. ``Clearly we're going to move ahead with product
liability. We've begun to look at nuisance. We need to determine
the proper jurisdiction, state or federal. And then put a dollar
figure on damages.... You don't want to throw something together
that doesn't have a hope of success.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the lawsuits being brought by the cities is not
necessarily to prevail in a trial. Municipalities hope to settle
with the gun industry, thereby reaping the kind of big money that
cigarette makers are paying to states that brought lawsuits against
them. Gun-control advocates also hope the threat of lawsuits will
prompt gun makers to put better safety locks on guns or voluntarily
scale back certain marketing efforts around cities.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston's legal team will have to put in long hours to make
sure the city lawsuit packs enough punch to be taken seriously by
gun makers, specialists say. Some of the arguments are new and
untested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as easy as the claim in the tobacco case that they
are marketing it to innocent youths,'' said Simons, the BU law
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Courts may be concerned about the fairness of making
manufacturers responsible for the effects of their product when a
criminal uses a gun. The lawsuits could have a better chance if the
alleged liability were confined to shooting accidents, Simons
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless courts decide to change the law, it's a case that
probably won't survive a motion to dismiss,'' said David Kopel, a
law professor associated with the Independence Institute, a think
tank in Colorado supportive of the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kopel recalled that the city of Memphis tried to sue strip
clubs, alleging they created a public nuisance and attempting to
recover damages. ``The court said, `Hey, if you don't like strip
clubs, don't come to the courts, go to the Legislature.'''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, are more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun industry has public relations people calling for
reality checks and downplaying this, but they're overestimating if
they think these old arguments are going to hold up,'' said Kip
Reader, a Cleveland attorney and chairman of the Tort and Insurance
Practice Section for the American Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are reasonable claims. They will involve a lot of work,
and there may be some initial skepticism from some judges and
jurors. But that's just the kind of skepticism you saw initially
with tobacco,'' said Richard Daynard, head of the Tobacco Products
Liability Project at Northeastern University. ``As (the cities)
work on it, I think they'll find paydirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tribe, a professor at Harvard Law School, said the
Boston lawsuit could be promising, especially if there is ``smoking
gun'' evidence about gun manufacturers flooding the market with
guns around urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, he argued, it could inspire regulators to
take a fresh look at the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had more responsible and responsive legislatures that
took a more consistent overview of social problems, there would be
less impulse for courts to give this occasional prod,'' Tribe said.
``In fact, ... it takes a kind of dialogue among the branches of
government to get things going. It may look sloppy, but on balance,
it's a constructive interaction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
