<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPRECIATE-HAMPTON-BO     11-24 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-HAMPTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY HAMPTON: HIS VISION WAS INSPIRATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's difficult to overestimate the impressive legacy of Henry
Hampton, who died over the weekend at 58.
</P>
<P>
   The robust African-American brought energy and style, class and
accessibility, and intelligence and verve to a genre that often
suffers from the worst sin of all _ dullness.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's Blackside group produced ``Eyes on the Prize,'' the
definitive miniseries on the civil rights movement, which won
dozens of awards, including a Peabody and a DuPont. The
organization also made ``Eyes on the Prize II,'' a magnificent
sequel; ``The Great Depression''; and the five-hour series
``America's War on Poverty,'' a devastating, highly personal story
of how the United States failed its poor. In the latter, the
Hampton touch was particularly apparent. While not flinching from
the hollow-faced victims of orchestrated economic horror, Hampton
also gave them a dignity society seldom allows its lower classes.
Not since James Agee and Walker Evans collaborated on ``Let Us Now
Praise Famous Men'' has a document so elegantly captured the grim
face of hopelessness. And Hampton, through cool logic and artful
imagery, let the viewer know that it wasn't the victim's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ken Burns and other PBS documentarians who rely heavily
on talking heads and expert testimony, Hampton headed directly to
the sources. Whether it was a young girl whose life was forever
scarred by racism or a railroad worker stung by a strike, Hampton
never masked their pain through intellectual generalizations that
meekly try to explain away an American tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hampton had every right to be bitter. He scrambled to get
funding for ``Eyes on the Prize'' after many PBS sponsors turned
him down because of his ``inexperience.'' After that, he was
rejected because his films were ``too political'' at a time when
PBS was sensitive about funding films that might be seen as
critical of the Washington establishment, to whom the network
turned for money.
</P>
<P>
   But the films aren't Hampton's only significant contribution.
Hampton should be remembered not only for what he got done but how
he got it done.
</P>
<P>
   For those who had the pleasure of spending a few minutes in his
company, it was clear that ego had nothing to do with his
accomplishments. He never referred to the films as ``his,'' but as
``ours,'' acknowledging the contributions of everyone from
production assistants to producers Terry Kay Rockefeller, Callie
Crossley, and Orlando Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work as a team,'' he said a few years ago. ``Everyone makes
their own contribution _ none more significant than another.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton believed that teamwork was the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't accomplish anything by yourself,'' he said. ``Only a
fool believes that.'' Now that he's left us, we'll see what can be
accomplished without his unique, inspirational vision.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 Globe interview, Hampton reiterated his philosophy
about leadership. ``We hunger for someone who means what he says
and says what he means,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone like Henry Hampton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
