A6836 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      11-24 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF WOLVES AND MEN AND MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The government is going after the killer with a
vehemence every victim's family dreams about.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the president's Cabinet flew in to the area to draw
attention to the case. All the TV stations and newspapers showed up
to watch Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt talk about how it was
``incomprehensible'' that anyone ``would resort to this kind of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The story was on the evening news and in all the papers.
</P>
<P>
   But, as good as publicity and moral indignation might be, it's
not often enough to motivate someone into turning in a killer. For
that, authorities need a more persuasive, a more convincing, more
practical law enforcement tool _ cash.
</P>
<P>
   This case has it.
</P>
<P>
   A $30,000 reward is being offered for information leading to the
arrests of the killer or killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, that's a lot of money,'' said Ed Hutchinson, whose son
Ron was one of three people found shot to death in the Agua Fria
riverbed last Easter, a murder that's still unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 grand isn't for Ed's kid, however. It's for the wolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wolf is here to stay,'' a defiant Babbitt said earlier
this month. He was talking about the Mexican wolves being
reintroduced into Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Several have been killed during the past year. The government
offered a $10,000 reward. The environmental group Defender of
Wildlife added another $10,000. The Southwest Center for Biological
Diversity in Tucson added $5,000 more. And the author of ``Dances
With Wolves,'' Michael Blake, tossed in $5,000 more. &QL; 
An enviable effort &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hutchinson, without a son since April, envies the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The detectives told us nobody would come forward for less than
$5,000,'' he said. ``Well, with some work, we've got our reward up
to $11,000. But so far, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, 26-year-old Ron Hutchinson, along with Dewey Peters
IV, also 26, and 21-year-old Crystal Lynn Allison were found shot
to death. Ron had been at college, and hadn't been home long when
he ran into his old friend Dewey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Saturday night, Dewey invited him to go with him to the
river,'' Ed said. ``It's a gathering place for young people. They
party down there.''
</P>
<P>
   A kid in an off-road vehicle spotted the bodies Sunday morning.
Two were in the bed of a pickup truck. One was on the ground
nearby. Sheriff's deputies don't have many leads.
</P>
<P>
   No Cabinet member has taken up the cause. The reward money is
more than most murder cases draw, thanks to a couple of corporate
contributions, but it's still not as much as the wolves are
getting.
</P>
<P>
   It outdoes the $1,000 offered for average cases in the local
Silent Witness program, however. Cases like that of Kathy
Pinkerton, shot in the head, her body found on the outskirts of
Gilbert after she tried to walk home July 8 after having car
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And Louis Bustamente, who fell asleep in his truck outside a
friend's house July 26 and was found later, shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of them drew the interest of a Cabinet member, either.
And no news conferences were called, like the one Maricopa County
Sheriff Joe Arpaio held over recent cat killings in Ahwatukee. &QL; 
Worth of victims &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the human victims didn't draw a $4,200 reward like
the one the Arizona Humane Society put up for the arrest and
conviction of the cat murderers.
</P>
<P>
   It's comparing apples to oranges, some say.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so. About 20 years ago, I read a book called ``Of
Wolves and Men'' by Barry Lopez. You can't read this book and not
appreciate this magnificent animal. And want to protect it. And
study it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, humans aren't an endangered species, like wolves,
though we might be if we don't learn what wolves have to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons about loyalty and fidelity. About sticking together in a
pack. About, first and foremost, taking care of your own. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
