<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-ART-BOS &LR;      11-24 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALLY QUINN'S CAPITAL OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As both a sharp-elbowed Washington journalist and stunning
socialite, Sally Quinn, 57, has always had a knack for stirring the
pot. During her stints at The Washington Post, beginning almost 30
years ago, Quinn revolutionized her paper's Style pages with her
gossipy, gotcha coverage of the rich and famous. In his memoir, her
husband, former Post editor Ben Bradlee, wrote that Henry Kissinger
once said ``he felt like committing suicide after Sally Quinn wrote
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's Quinn who's being written about as the focal point
of a political, journalistic, and personal firestorm. In a Nov. 2
article marking her return to regular Post duty, she offered up a
Beltway-eye view of the infamous ``disconnect'' _ elite
Washington's preoccupation with the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal
despite the rest of the nation's bone-aching fatigue with it.
</P>
<P>
   Headlined ``Not in Their Backyard,'' her Post story quoted
several dozen Beltway poobahs _ from ABC's Cokie Roberts to the
Reagans' former social secretary Muffie Cabot _ explaining why they
took such umbrage at the president's philandering. Much of the
``Washington Establishment is outraged by the president's behavior
in the Monica Lewinsky scandal,'' Quinn wrote. ``They feel
Washington has been brought into disrepute by the actions of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   For her trouble, Quinn has run afoul of the political zeitgeist,
earning the scorn of New York Times columnist Frank Rich, and
finding herself answering questions about her own sex life. Her
biggest offense: shining a bright light on Washington's insular,
insider culture at a time when much of the country disdains it as
an irrelevant outpost of pomposity.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Quinn said in an interview that she was simply
trying to give voice to official Washington, to provide some
Beltway ``sociology and anthropology.'' But what makes this more
than just a tale of intra-media skirmishing is that Quinn's story
proved what voters revealed in the stunning midterm elections. The
public's distaste for Washington's permanent pundit-and-partying
class outstrips any antipathy toward the wayward renter in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Quinn's story appeared, the C-SPAN lines were on
fire. ``The prevailing mood about the story that day was basically
livid,' recalls C-SPAN spokesman Richard Fahle. In its Nov. 23
cover story headlined ``Impeach the Media,'' New York magazine
declared the Quinn article a classic example of despised
``Washington-think'' and quoted Washington Monthly editor Charlie
Peters trashing it. (``Sally's had a very interesting sex life of
her own,'' he declared.)
</P>
<P>
   But the fiercest counterattack came from Rich, the liberal Times
columnist. In slashing Nov. 7 and 18 op-ed columns, he mocked the
sensibilities of Quinn's ``righteous Washingtonians,'' repeated
Peters' dishy quote, and accused her of ``writing like Tom Wolfe
minus the irony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kill the messenger. But it seems so bizarre,'' says
Quinn of Rich. ``He's having a major tantrum, and nobody knows what
it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradlee has another thought as he muses on the reaction to what
his ex-employee and wife of 20 years has written. ``I think they
wish she would shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  Quinn and Post executive editor Leonard Downie Jr. say her story
germinated from a growing buzz from Washington insiders, one that
had been virtually ignored in all the stories about public reaction
to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had written about what people in Washington were
talking about,'' says Quinn. ``We all knew there was a disconnect.
I had no idea I was going to come up with that much intense
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   After conducting ``hundreds'' of interviews, Quinn laid out her
findings. ``If Washington is a tribe, then the president is the
tribal chief,'' she wrote. ``He cannot be seen to dishonor the
tribe.'' She included independent counsel Kenneth Starr as a member
of the tribe, writing that Starr ``Is a Washington insider'' with
``many friends in both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn says she's getting a very positive feedback and Downie
adds that if the rest of the country is appalled, so be it. ``You
can disagree with what we are reporting on,'' he says. ``I really
don't care if we're popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the fallout: Washington Monthly editor Peters said that
``the frightening thing'' is that the article reflected most of the
Washington establishment. ``Sally is a charming person and Sally
made a considerable contribution to Washington journalism in her
early years,'' he added in an interview. ``It's just that she's
gotten into this queen bee thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a column he characterizes as ``tough'' but not ``ad
hominem,'' Rich wrote: ``Luckily for the country, not all the press
lives in Georgetown.''
</P>
<P>
   But Quinn wonders about the motives of her attackers. &UR;  &LR; ``I knew
that there would be a reaction,'' she says. ``I didn't realize it
would be so personal.'' In a December 1997 New York profile of
Quinn that followed the release of her book, ``The Party: A Guide
to Adventurous Entertaining,'' Alex Witchell wrote that her expert
hostess declined to offer her an additional cup of tea and pointed
her in the direction of the nearest cab when the interview was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only I had offered Alex another cup of tea or called her a
cab, this wouldn't be going on,'' says Quinn tartly.
</P>
<P>
   During a difficult Nov. 6 appearance on C-SPAN, Quinn had to
endure a caller's suggestion that she was unfit to judge Clinton
because she had advanced her career by sleeping with Bradlee when
he was her Post boss. ``Take a look at your own life,'' the caller
demanded. ``A lot of people said you slept your way to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Flustered, Quinn responded that ``We didn't get together until I
left the Washington Post and went to CBS'' in 1973. Bradlee's
memoir concurs, but he does acknowledge that he got anonymous mash
notes from Quinn before she left for CBS. And when she returned to
the Post after CBS, he wrote that she was often described as
``Bradlee's live-in girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so ugly and poisonous of Charlie Peters to say that and
so ugly for Frank to repeat it,'' she says angrily.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One other theory has surfaced in the wake of Quinn's Nov. 2
article: that it is the work of an FOB (Foe of Bill.) There is
certainly some evidence to suggest that the Clintons were not
clicking with her Quinn and her crowd. In a 1997 Times profile,
Quinn described the First Family's diminishing interest in
socializing, saying, ``A lot of people have the sense they're
already out of here in some odd way.'' And she acknowledges that
``we see them (the Clintons) very rarely socially.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a belief in Washington circles that Hillary
Clinton was upset by something Quinn wrote years ago. Some say it
was an August 1992 Post story chronicling Mrs. Clinton's changing
public image. Quinn believes it was a December 1992 piece she did
for Newsweek advising Hillary on how to navigate the ``treacherous
terrain called Washington,`` telling her to get a job outside of
government and to stop attending her husband's meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard she was personally disappointed, and I didn't think it
was a hostile piece,'' says Quinn, who claims to have enjoyed a
``cordial'' relationship with Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those searching for a motive for her Nov. 2 story have
circulated a report from the pro-Clinton online magazine Salon
recalling Bradlee's gratitude to Ken Starr for a 1987 ruling that
helped the Post win an expensive libel suit.``He freed us,'' says
Bradlee of Starr. But ``the idea that I am, in any way, a
right-wing anti-Democrat _ that's the first time anyone's said that
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, though, Quinn's critics don't quarrel
with Quinn's reporting, just her subject matter. (Even Rich admits,
``it was an extremely candid and accurate piece.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a portrait of Washington as an elitist group,''
says media analyst and Beltway resident Bernard Kalb. ``This is an
invitation for coast-to-coast psychiatric evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   In her own way, Quinn admits the city needs a shrink. The
Clintons ``had the effect of polarizing so many people who have
been close friends,'' she says. ``The city has been ravaged in a
kind of emotional and psychological way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the New York magazine story, Clinton political operative
James Carville offers his own view of the mental state of Quinn and
her friends. ``I like the way she calls (Washington) a village,''
he said. ``Remember how you were taught in grade school about what
every village had? Idiots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
