<HEADLINE>
A LEAP INTO THE MARKET COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What bear market?
</P>
<P>
   While broad stock market measures eclipsed old records Monday,
scores of companies could boast about powerful rallies of their
own. And most of them have been sorely in need of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Project Software &AMP; Development Corp. performed just
like many other Massachusetts stocks this summer, slipping from a
springtime high and unable regain its footing before prices had
been cut in half in the early fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bedford, Mass. software company has also typified the
booming recovery in local stocks that began on Oct. 8 and stretched
through Monday's trading. Project Software shares have more than
doubled since then, climbing 114 percent on a pleasant
third-quarter earnings surprise.
</P>
<P>
   An amazing total of 77 stocks, all members of the Bloomberg
Massachusetts index, have appreciated by at least 50 percent in the
last six weeks. The index is made up of 337 issues.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the Bloomberg Massachusetts stocks are up at
least 25 percent during that period. Some are larger companies
battered in the summer stock market, including integrated circuit
maker Analog Devices Inc. (up 57.2 percent), retailer TJX Cos. (up
49.3 percent), computer storage king EMC Corp. (up 43.2 percent),
and BankBoston Corp. (up 42.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   But many of the soaring local stocks are small issues or even
smaller microcap companies, whose prices had bounced back so
dramatically for the very same reason they plunged in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Poor liquidity _ a very limited number of buyers or sellers of a
small stock at any given time _ tends to exaggerate the market's
reaction to good or bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that missed their forecast quarterly earnings often
lost 30 percent to 40 percent of market value in a single day this
summer. For now, companies like Project Software are getting the
same kind of super-ball bounce from performance that exceeds
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Project Software reported quarterly earnings that were 9 cents
per share better than consensus forecasts on Nov. 6, and its stock
bolted up by 8 1/8, gaining 46 percent that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about very small allocations of cash from some of
the large institutions into some of these very small names,'' said
Bernice Behar, manager of the John Hancock Emerging Growth fund.
``It doesn't take very much for these stocks to move very
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate earnings that propel stocks aren't always higher, just
better than expected. Combine the pleasant surprise with lower
interest rates, the lubricant that helps all stocks rise, and
investors are buying.
</P>
<P>
   Money does seem to be moving into companies, big or small, that
can demonstrate an improving profit picture. Defensive measure such
as a company's stock price to its book value was a helpful tool
until the market began its rally, according to Bart Geer, manager
of the State Street Research Alpha fund. Now, Geer said, data
tracking a stock's price in relation to forecasts for its future
profits is more relevant for tracking a more aggressive market.
</P>
<P>
   But earnings reports don't account for all of the stock rallies.
There are a handful of subplots that explain the bounce in these
Massachusetts stocks:
</P>
<P>
   _Internet mania. Locals Lycos Inc. of Waltham (up 139.9 percent)
and CMG Information Services Inc. of Andover (up 117.7 percent)
soared with the rest of the group.
</P>
<P>
   _The financial stock recovery. The Federal Reserve's interest
rate cuts have been good news for most banks. Fleet Financial Group
Inc., which had not fallen nearly so far as BankBoston during the
summer, has advanced 31.8 percent since Oct. 8. Shares of the
state's bigger local banks are mostly up 20 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _The semiconductor rally. Earnings at semiconductor companies _
which were hammered by the Asian contagion _ haven't bounced back
yet, but orders are improving and that's good news to the
businesses that serve them. Semiconductor equipment makers PRI
Automation Inc. of Billerica (up 138.8 percent) and Teradyne Inc.
of Boston (up 93.4 percent) lead the way.
</P>
<P>
   _Special situtations like Aware Inc., the best-performing local
stock with a market value of at least $250 million over the last
six weeks. Aware, up 279 percent during that period, soared when a
United Nations agency adopted an international Internet access
standard that uses Aware's technology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
