<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, Nov. 25, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-COOK (Undated) ``Seasons Readings,'' a roundup of cook and
food books. By Gregory Roberts. (story will move in the ``e''
category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BABE (Undated) This little piggy very nearly didn't make it
to market. As of last week, prints weren't ready and Universal was
telling the world the filmmakers were still synching in the animal
voices. However, the reality was quite different. The studio took
one look at director George Miller's dark vision in this sequel to
``Babe'' ordered him back in the editing room to cut away the
edginess until the film could garner a G, instead of PG, rating.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BUGS (Undated) It's bound to be compared to the recently
released ``Antz,'' but ``A Bug's Life'' is a very different movie
altogether. Its similarities end with the fact that it, too, is
clever, inventive and a lot of fun for the entire family.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HOME (Undated) Even though its release date has repeatedly
been pushed back, ``Home Fries'' has garnered good word-of-mouth on
the film festival circuit. Still, it's easy to see why this quirky,
odd little movie might be considered a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRUISE (Undated) ``The Cruise,'' which is shot in black and
white, makes New York City glisten.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WIND (Undated) Perhaps some institutions should just be
left alone. Certainly the beloved children's classic, ``The Wind In
The Willows,'' written by novelist Kenneth Grahame and published in
1908, is an example.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RING (Undated) A disclaimer in the credits states
``Ringmaster'' is not affiliated with Jerry Springer's successful
afternoon talk show. But ``Ringmaster,'' which is Springer's big
screen grab at bigger stardom, is about a TV host named Jerry
Farrelly, who invites ``ordinary Americans'' to come on ``The Jerry
Show,'' air their dirty family laundry, engage in brawls and sit
through penance as Jerry (who has no qualifications as a therapist)
analyzes their actions. Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BAD (Undated) The publicity materials say ``Very Bad
Things'' is a ``mad, crazed comic vision.'' It might be more
accurate to describe the film as Peter Berg's infantile hostility
fobbing itself off as ``art.''
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
