<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BUG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A BUG'S LIFE' IS AMBITIOUS _ AND IT SUCCEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's bound to be compared to the recently released ``Antz,'' but
``A Bug's Life'' is a very different movie altogether. Its
similarities end with the fact that it, too, is clever, inventive
and a lot of fun for the entire family.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, but it's already been three years since Disney
and Pixar Animation released the smash ``Toy Story.'' If you
thought computer animation and technology were pretty ingenious
then, you'll be amazed by the equally creative strides made in ``A
Bug's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Many major movie and TV talents have contributed their voices to
the film, including Dave Foley, Kevin Spacey, Julia Louis-Dreyfus,
Phyllis Diller, David Hyde Pierce, Denis Leary and Bonnie Hunt as
well as veteran actor Roddy McDowall, who recently passed away.
</P>
<P>
   The story is based upon Aesop's fable about an idle grasshopper,
who whiles away his time playing his fiddle, while a colony of ants
toils nearby. The grasshopper gets hungry and begs the little
workers for food. In ``A Bug's Life,'' the grasshoppers have been
enlarged and turned into villains, with their leader, Hopper
(Spacey), demanding the entire harvest _ or else.
</P>
<P>
   One small ant named Flik (Foley) stands up to Hopper and his
thugs. Despite warnings that it's a ``bug eat bug world out
there,'' Flik treks off toward the big bug city to find
``warriors'' to help his colony fight the enemy. By mistake, he
discovers a flea circus of washed up performers _ a pair of
Hungarian pillbugs, a kindly black widow, a male ladybug and a
praying mantis magician among them.
</P>
<P>
   He mistakes them for brave bugs after he glimpses them engaged
in a bar brawl. Flik and his newfound friends dream up a wild
scheme to rid the ants of their unwanted enemies _ and to help the
Queen Ant (Diller), Princess Atta (Louis-Dreyfus) and the little
princess, Dot _ keep the colony together and safe from harm.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the film, it's virtually impossible to tell if
scenes are computer generated or shot with a CinemaScope camera and
lens. The movie is ambitious in other ways as well. While ``Toy
Story'' focused on a small group of characters and used mostly
indoor sets, much of ``A Bug's Life'' takes place in wide open
spaces so the animation depicts huge vistas, diverse grades of
shade and light, pounding thunderstorms - and ``crowd scenes'' that
included up to 800 ants.
</P>
<P>
   The film's creators were concerned with what they called the
``ick'' factor, since many people loathe bugs and consider them
more than a little creepy. The technicians viewed National
Geographic specials, the documentary ``Microcosmos'' and consulted
entymologists from around the world, then went to work to make
insects appealing to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a quick-witted, fast-paced delight that works on
several levels. The script is elemental and simple so it will to
appeal to very young kids and the jokes are sophisticated enough to
keep adults glued to their seats. And even if the story doesn't
grab hard-hearts and cynics, the artistry is more than enough to
keep all ages rapt.
</P>
<P>
   A Bug's Life. Directed by John Lasseter. Written by Andrew
Stanton, Donald McEnery, Bob Shaw. With the voices of Kevin Spacey,
Dave Foley, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Phyllis Diller, David Hyde Pierce,
Denis Leary. Walt Disney Pictures. 97 minutes. Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
