<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DISPLAY HEART IN THE FACE OF HARTFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In the end, it was about Heart instead of
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   It was 20 minutes to midnight when the black cloud finally
lifted over the worst pro football stadium in America. For a few
joyous seconds, there was no thought about injuries, Jets, firings,
or relocations to other states.
</P>
<P>
   With their season about to go down the hopper, their coach about
to face a firing squad, and their owner prepared to join the
Witness Protection Program, the New England Patriots saved their
season and maybe their souls with a pulsating 26-23 victory over
the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Much-maligned Drew Bledsoe, quarterback of the future Hartford
Patriots, took the Patriots 80 yards in 15 plays, connecting with
Shawn Jefferson for a 25-yard touchdown pass with 29 seconds left
to give the Patriots a rare and badly needed ``Monday Night
Football'' win.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was just about football again. It was about Bledsoe
completing 28 of 54 passes for 423 yards (the second-best effort of
his career) and converting two third-down plays and two fourth-down
plays in the final drive. It was about Jefferson _ who botched a
play that could have won last week's game at Buffalo _ making a
Willie Mays over-the-shoulder catch to bring home the win.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the drama, Bledsoe broke his finger midway through the
drive and almost came out of the game. Bet he's glad he stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was any way I could stay in the game, I was going to
do it,'' Bledsoe said. ``I couldn't get a very good grip on the
ball. The ball was taking off on me a little bit. But I'd be damned
if I was going to let Zo (backup Scott Zolak) come in in that
situation. That's the situation you dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of stuff we're counting on and we're going to
need it,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``We like to win in
that kind of fashion. It was fun. We needed it. Obviously, we
desperately needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great time tonight and I hope you did, too. We won a
game in dramatic fashion and we needed it badly. We have to focus
on Buffalo (next week's opponent). We can't go too crazy on one
game because it is just one.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. If Bledsoe hadn't converted the fourth-down
plays, this season was over. The Patriots would have slumped to
5-6, three games behind the Dolphins with an 0-4 record against the
three teams ahead of them in their division.
</P>
<P>
   But the season is not over. There will be football talk for the
rest of this week and some of it will concern play on the gridiron
rather than play in the Connecticut legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's thriller was the first game since Bob ``I cried
when the Braves left town'' Kraft announced his intention to take
the team out of town for 350 million pieces of silver.
</P>
<P>
   In the time-honored tradition of nationally televised New
England football follies, there was a circuslike atmosphere around
Foxboro Stadium until the final drive of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Jilted fans toting signs that maligned Massachusetts Speaker of
the House Thomas Finneran and Kraft filled the parking lots, then
filed into the inadequate stadium to see the Patriots and Fish in
windswept, 52-degree temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   The players were armed with a checklist of handy-dandy excuses.
They've been ravaged by injury and this week had to perform under
the cloud of uncertainty that comes when your owner says he's
moving the team out of state for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   None of this made life any easier for Carroll and his staff. The
Patriots had lost four of their last five and faced the almost
certain prospect that a loss would put them out of the playoffs for
1998. This, in turn, almost certainly would assure that Carroll
would not be on the sideline for any games in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kraft was seen only briefly on the field before the
game. TV crews staked out all corners of the stadium, but the
once-ubiquitous owner was harder to find than Whitey Bulger. He did
give an interview to ABC's Lesley Visser, but on this night there
was no golf cart victory lap, no autograph session, no papal waving
from the owner's box.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's welfare son was on the minds of the fandom. A boy
and his dad carried a sign featuring a cartoon of Kraft toting a
briefcase full of dollars. The script read, ``He could go all the
way ... to Hartford?''
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, a man held a sign with photos of Finneran and
Montgomery Burns, the power plant owner on ``The Simpsons.'' The
sign read, ``Separated at birth.'' Another man held a ``Sack
Finneran'' placard.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of signage in the parking lot as well. A red
pickup featured a tailgate billboard that stated, ``Impeach Tom
Finneran's Dictorial Rule.'' ``Dictorial'' is not a word, but hey,
these are Patriot fans.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment stretched to Interstate 95, where a blue Chevy
Celebrity wagon rode south sporting plywood on both sides
exclaiming, ``Boycott Pats ... No team, no fans.''
</P>
<P>
   There was concern that the ever-exuberant Patriot fans,
fortified by hours of pregame antifreeze ingestion, might be a tad
rowdy given the recent play of the team, coupled with Kraft's
intent to blow town.
</P>
<P>
   But all that went away as the Dolphins and Patriots put on a
pretty fair display of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our fans, I want to say thanks for coming out and
supporting us the way they did,'' said Bledsoe. ``There was a lot
of controversy about the move and all.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was about Heart instead of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
