<HEADLINE>
`HOME FRIES' IS QUIRKY AND OFFBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though its release date has repeatedly been pushed back,
``Home Fries'' has garnered good word-of-mouth on the film festival
circuit. Still, it's easy to see why this quirky, odd little movie
might be considered a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   It has no real star power and boasts such an offbeat sense of
humor that it defies mainstream marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Fries'' is reminiscent of of a Beth Henley play (and who
went to see ``Miss Firecracker'' or ``Crimes of the Heart?'') and
Warner Bros. probably didn't know what to do with this gothic
comedy. Now they're pitching it as a ``romance,'' though its unwed
female heroine has been impregnated by her middle-aged married
lover.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore plays Sally Jackson, a young woman who loves
Dolly Parton and has to work the drive-up window at the local
Burger-Matic so customers can't see her ``condition.'' Her baby's
dad, Henry Lever, has a wife (Catherine O'Hara) and two grown
stepsons, Dorian (Luke Wilson) and Angus (Jake Busey) but
soft-hearted Sally's only just given him the boot because he didn't
tell her he had a wife until after she'd conceived.
</P>
<P>
   When Henry is found dead of unknown causes (he's literally
scared to death), life becomes crazily complicated. Henry's widow
wants to find the bimbo he was fooling around with. Her son Angus
goes on a rampage to rid his manipulative mother of the thorn in
her side _ Henry's unknown mistress.
</P>
<P>
   But Dorian falls in love with Sally. He has no idea she's his
stepdaddy's girlfriend. Sally doesn't know Dorian is Henry's
stepson. All hell breaks loose once Angus figures out who is who
and he goes totally nuts after mom reveals that Dorian was always
her favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The script for ``Home Fries'' was written in 1988 and was
discovered at a screenplay writing contest sponsored by the
governor of Virginia. Vince, its young writer, has gone on to
become a creative consultant for TV's ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, ``Home Fries' has loopy energy and off-kilter charm
that make it likable and even touching in spots. Most of the time
it works, though there are moments that try too hard and miss the
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore and Luke Wilson, who was the best thing in the indie
sleeper ``Bottle Rocket,'' have an easy-going chemistry that's
apparently filtered over into real life. It's Wilson who keeps the
``Home Fries'' burning. He has a neat screen presence that is
heightened by a sleepy sense of comic timing. When he's center
stage, the film cooks. As for the rest, it's an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   Home Fries. Directed by Dean Parisot. Written by Vince Gilligan.
Cast: Drew Barrymore, Luke Wilson, Catherine O'Hara, Jake Busey,
Shelley Duvall. Warner Bros. 92 minutes. Rated PG-13 for language,
sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
