</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRUISE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY SHINES IN `THE CRUISE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Welcome to New York City,'' says Gray Line tour guide Timothy
``Speed'' Levitch in greeting. ``To tell a literary history is to
tell the story of the world. Fasten your seat belts.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will need to fasten their seat belts as well during this
wild ride of a documentary about Levitch, who does the ``double
decker loop downtown'' and who entertains passengers with a
non-stop monologue that verges on a pathological obsession with the
historical and architectural origins of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Levitch attains a new level of poetry with his rambling musings
about everyone and everything that zips by. The Chrysler Building
is ``uninspired voluptuousness'' and Central Park was ``birthed by
Transcendentalists. No baseball or sweating were allowed.'' He
regales his fares with off-color stories about H.G. Wells, Jack
Reed, Dylan Thomas and Dorothy Parker. He seems to know everything
about the city and its ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bennett Miller's compulsively watchable documentary
progresses, the cracks in Levitch's veneer begin to show. By the
end, he's spewing venom over the fact that his grandparents think
he's a failure and we begin to wonder if this energized,
larger-than-life character isn't just a bit nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Miller cruises by every corner and landmark in New York on
virtually no budget. Yet ``The Cruise,'' which is shot in black and
white, makes the city glisten. It's an ``organic'' view that takes
us deep into the core of the Big Apple, as well as Levitch's brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cruise'' is ultimately about the inter-dependence between
Levitch and the 2{-mile wide, 13{ mile-long island. And though he
admits he has a love/hate relationship with the place, he couldn't
survive anywhere else. He needs the energy it provides to fuel his
crazy pace and with every run-on sentence he utters about New York,
he could just as easily be talking about himself.
</P>
<P>
   He's as much in a state of ``constant fluctuation'' as the city.
Consequently, Miller never has the opportunity to dig too deeply
into Levitch's psychological make-up. While Levitch seems eternally
on the edge of boiling over and spinning out of control, he emerges
as fascinating as the town he loves so much.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruise. Directed by Bennett Miller. Documentary. Artisan
Entertainment. 76 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
