<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WIND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WIND IN THE WILLOWS' IS A NOVEL BETTER LEFT UNTOUCHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK   The Wind In The Willows. Perhaps some
institutions should just be left alone. Certainly the beloved
children's classic, ``The Wind In The Willows,'' written by
novelist Kenneth Grahame and published in 1908, is an example.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or, at least, it could have been brought to the screen with less
adult sensibility. Monty Python is too coarse and lead-footed to
depict such a wistful tale.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Terry Jones' (who was a member of the British
comedy troupe) live action approach to Grahame's book is often
plodding and dull and he entirely misses the delicate innuendo in
the timeless tale of old friends Mole, Rat, Toad and Badger. That,
or he's forgotten what it's like to view the world from a less
grown-up point of view.
</P>
<P>
   One day Mole (Steve Coogan) suffers a terrible hardship. His
quiet home, situated in a peaceful meadow owned by Toad (Terry
Jones) has been destroyed by progress. Toad, in his extravagance
and constant need for cash, has sold the land to the greedy Weasel
leader (Antony Sher).
</P>
<P>
   Depressed, Mole consults his friend, Rat (Eric Idle), who just
wants to picnic on the river. But the nasty weasels have a plan to
make picnics illegal on the river. They want to buy all Toad's
property and his palatial Toad Hall and turn it into a dog food
factory. The timid Mole, friendly Rat, and silly Toad must find a
way to keep peace in rural England _ and drum the evil weasels out.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' adaptation also includes human rabbits making love by the
side of the road and weasels drinking and groping each other in
homoerotic glee while flags that strongly resemble Nazi banners
hang on the walls behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Jones defends his version by arguing the story is ``full of
descriptions of a bucolic England that's vanished'' or that it is
``firmly embedded in middle-class society at the turn of the
century, and it's hard to imagine children nowadays responding to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because obviously enough kids still do. But Jones can't find the
balance between Monty Python-esque humor and the childlike world
that ``The Wind In The Willows'' typlifies so well. He's made a
film for adults, not kids.
</P>
<P>
   The Wind In The Willows. Directed and written by Terry Jones.
Cast: Steve Coogan, Eric Idle, Terry Jones, Michael Palin, Antony
Sher, Nicol Williamson, John Cleese, Stephen Fry, Michael Palin,
Julia Sawalha. Guild Pathe. 88 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
