<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEST PROPOSAL FOR THE 1990S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call me savage, but news that Wall Street firms are laying off
workers has raised spittle to the corners of my mouth and sent me
racing for my carving knife. It is these financial institutions
that have dished up the promise over the years that if we only
followed their advice we'd gorge on a never-ending feast of stock
market riches.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what? Now average investors like me are beginning to
wonder whether they will be able to put food on the table in the
wake of the world's economic and stock market bedlam. Sure, stocks
have recovered, but don't be fooled. As the Wall Street layoffs
suggest, the waiter will soon arrive at your table with several
more courses guaranteed to produce indigestion and penury.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with rare belly-rubbing satisfaction that I see in
recent weeks that Merrill Lynch has cut 3,400 jobs. ING Barings has
shaved 1,200 workers. J.P. Morgan is lopping off 5 percent of its
work force, or about 740 people. BT Alex. Brown is reported to be
considering chopping 10 percent of its 18,000 staffers. Other cuts
are expected to follow this first wave.
</P>
<P>
   What a shock for this class of worker. For the past 15 years,
Wall Street employees have enjoyed the fruits of an unparalled rise
in stock prices, no doubt savoring the richest of cuisine and the
finest of liqueurs, and, as will happen, growing fat and succulent
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   With the overabundance of Wall Streeter flesh and the
simultaneous scarcity on the average investor's dinner table, I
feel compelled by fairness to present ``A Modest Proposal for
Preventing the Surplus Workers of the Financial Industry From Being
a Burden to Their Employers, and for Making Them Beneficial to the
Investing Public.''
</P>
<P>
   I humbly propose that in place of laying off these
chubby-cheeked outcasts, Wall Street firms can benefit not only
their own bottom line but also the dining public by slaughtering
the workers and offering them as free grub to the hungry hordes of
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, on the face of it my proposal may appear distasteful,
but its advantages are manifold. In the first place, the brokerage
firms will eliminate the costs of job reduction. Slaughtering a
worker obviates the need to pay that worker for graciously
departing from the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, for instance, had to earmark $430 million to do
away with its jobs. The common-sense approach would be a genuine
flesh-and-blood slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   As for cash-strapped investors, they will be pleased by the
aroma of roasting Wall Streeter wafting from their ovens. I would
encourage the financial firms to complete their carcass giveaway by
Thanksgiving, allowing investors to have a broker for dinner rather
than the traditional turkey. Imagine the jubilant face of the
investor as broker juice dribbles over his lips. It is a clinically
proven digestive fact that munching on the roasted meat of a broker
who has plunged you into poverty-stricken retirement reduces an
excess accumu-lation of bile.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope that the financial industry layoffs accelerate.
At the current level, the flow of carcasses will in no way meet the
soaring demand from kitchens across America. Many investors would
like their broker's head on a platter, but it is clear that it will
be some time before every table in our great country is so graced.
What's more, experience has shown that barely 15 percent of any
broker is edible, the rest being composed of little more than hot
air. Had there been more meat on the bone and less hokum on the
tongue from the start, these lamentable circumstances might never
have come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(at)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
