<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VERY BAD THINGS' IS, WELL, VERY BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publicity materials say ``Very Bad Things'' is a ``mad,
crazed comic vision.'' It might be more accurate to describe the
film as Peter Berg's infantile hostility fobbing itself off as
``art.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who is best known as a doctor on the TV series ``Chicago
Hope,'' actually had a moderately promising film career prior to
his moving to the small screen. ``Very Bad Things'' represents his
first effort as a director and writer and it's safe to say he
shouldn't give up his day job.
</P>
<P>
   Few filmmakers do pitch black comedy well. The Coen Brothers had
a success with ``Fargo'' and Scottish director Danny Boyle crossed
over in the United States with ``Shallow Grave.'' Neil LaBute made
waves with his scathing comedy ``In The Company of Men'' (and
recently ``Your Friends and Neighbors'') and Todd Solondz hit the
mark with ``Happiness'' and ``Welcome to the Dollhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Coens and Boyle have also had their share of failures
while working in the genre. Though Berg blatantly borrows from
these more accomplished and better films, he hasn't the skill or
depth to create either true satire or make a barbed statement on
the bleakness of the human condition with this lame effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hell; hell or prison, whichever comes first,''
laments Adam Berkow (Daniel Stern). In the midst of throwing a stag
party in a ritzy Las Vegas hotel suite for pal Kyle Fisher (Jon
Favreau), who is about to marry ``creature like no other'' Laura
Garrety (Cameron Diaz), the $900 a night live ``entertainment'' is
brutally impaled while having sex with Adam's crazy brother,
Michael (Jeremy Piven). Leave it to Boyd (Christian Slater), a
sociopath of the first order, to come up with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can call the police. Or we can dispose of the 105-pound
problem in the desert,'' says Boyd. First, however, all five
friends, including shy mechanic Moore (Leland Orser), must agree to
keep mum about their bad behavior. But like all ill-devised simple
plans, this one runs amok in unanticipated complications. Soon the
``boys'' are battling each other and the trail to hell gets
bloodier and bleaker than Kyle could have ever envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Cliched, badly structured and, by the end, relentlessly tiresome
in its unmitigated gratuitous violence, immaturity and lack of
redemption or purpose, Berg's film seems to be purging some
personal vendetta against humanity. There's no remorse or iota of
conscience in any of the characters; they're all selfish and,
worse, they're boring.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Very Bad Things'' is an indicator of what is passing for
entertainment these days, much less comedy, perhaps it's time we
humans quit thinking of ourselves as the most civilized rung of the
evolutionary ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Very Bad Things. Directed and written by Peter Berg. Cast:
Christian Slater, Cameron Diaz, Daniel Stern, Jon Favreau, Jeanne
Tripplehorn. Polygram Films. 100 minutes. Rated R for graphic
violence, nudity, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: F
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-24 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTCARDS FROM CLOUD-CUCKOO LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did the Democrats steal the 1996 election, selling out American
trade policy and defense secrets to China to finance a ``comeback
advertising blitz'' that saved Bill Clinton and Al Gore from defeat
at the hands of Bob Dole, Steve Forbes, and the rest of the GOP?
</P>
<P>
   That's what New York Times columnist William Safire believes.
This proposition is behind the faint, tinny drum-rattling on the
right that still can be heard, as the stalwarts seek to rally the
congressional Republicans to impeachment's froth-and-spittle
stained flag.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno must announce by today whether she
will appoint a special prosecutor to investigate Vice President
Gore. The issue is whether Gore told the truth when he said he did
not know that campaign contributions he solicited would be split
between ``hard'' money &UR;  &LR; (which could be spent on his reelection
campaign) and ``soft'' money (which could be spent only on
``issues'' advertising).
</P>
<P>
   He may have lied. Reno was badgered by the House Judiciary
Committee into launching a preliminary investigation of the matter,
after notes surfaced that suggested Gore may have been aware that
the distinction was being blurred. Nevertheless, the attorney
general is widely expected to say no to an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Certainly not to curry favor with the nation's
editorialists.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times editorialized incessantly about the 1996
election over the summer. ``Law School for Reno'' in July was
followed by ``The Firestorm Cometh,'' &UR;  &LR; ``The Prosecutor Who Spoke
Up,'' ``Giving Ms. Reno Time to Study,'' ``The Reno Watch,'' ``One
Tiny Step for Janet Reno,'' ``Another Itty Bitty Reno Step,''
``Janet Reno May Finally Get It,'' and finally, in September, ``The
Change in Ms. Reno's Course.'' (``The subterfuge fooled no one but
Reno and her advisers in the Justice Department's misnamed Public
Integrity section.'')
</P>
<P>
   So did The Wall Street Journal. (``We may still get to the
truth, but probably only after Janet Reno succeeds in first
discrediting her ability to handle it.'') Even The Boston Globe
twice joined in. (``For more than a year now, her failure to act
has created the appearance of partisan political tampering.'')
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of all these editorials is that they make no
mention of the storm of bitter controversy that has torn the nation
apart for the past year. The presence of Kenneth Starr on the
political and ethical landscape was of no concern as these writers
argued for a new round of investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nation's three leading newspapers, only The Washington
Post has supported the attorney general's cautious reading of the
election laws _ for the good if somewhat narrow reasons that she
herself has offered. The campaign finance laws are too porous to
convict anyone for much of anything, Reno has argued. The decision
of a federal judge last month to dismiss five of six charges
against Democratic Party fund-raiser Maria Hsia demonstrated that
the campaign finance laws themselves are riddled with loopholes;
not even a special prosecutor would stand much of a chance of
gaining convictions.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of things to wonder about in the 1996
presidential elections. Campaign finance was a mess on both sides.
Those presidential coffees and Lincoln bedroom overnights were
hardly high crimes and misdemeanors, however. Not even the
unprecedented probe of presidential financial defenses by Asian
donors was sufficient to warrant extending the four-year
inquisition of a politically appointed prosecutor unchecked by any
other agency of government _ not even by public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of reason to worry about the influence of big
money in politics. The independent counsel law is no way to deal
with the problem. No wonder then that the blue-ribbon committee of
the American Bar Association that helped write the independent
counsel law _ and that lobbied strongly for its reauthorization _
is on the verge of urging that it now be allowed to lapse.
</P>
<P>
   So let's hope it will be three cheers for Reno. Two more
decisions remain after today _ in the matters of former White House
chief of staff Harold Ickes and Clinton himself. Against the
withering scorn of the editorial writers, the attorney general
seems to be ready to maintain her independence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
