<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6859 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-COOK-SPI &LR;      11-24 2377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS FOR COOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY ROBERTS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each year, American book publishers pump out hundreds of
cookbooks: fat and thin, long and short, plain and fancy,
complicated and simple. Finding the wheat among all that chaff is
no easy task, on matter how vivid your culinary imagination.
</P>
<P>
   What can make it easier to sort through the deluge is to come up
with a strategy, a point of view, a hook _ what journalists call an
angle.
</P>
<P>
   Or in this case, several angles. And no angle is more hallowed,
more time-honored, more cherished than ...
</P>
<P>
   THE LOCAL ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   This category includes books either by Northwest authors or
about Northwest cooking . . . or both.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Caprial's Bistro-Style Cuisine,'' by Caprial Pence  &UR; cf58 &LR; (10
Speed Press, 196 pages, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Caprial Pence used to cook at Fullers in the Seattle Sheraton
Hotel and Towers, and while there, she won the 1991 James Beard
Award as Best Northwest Chef. Since then, she's moved to Portland,
Ore., where she opened Caprial's Bistro, and she hosts a TV cooking
show. In this, her third cookbook, she gives bistro fare a stylish
spin with such recipes as Pork Roast with Pecan Stuffing and Creamy
Mustard Sauce, or Sauted Salmon with Black Bean-Shrimp Salsa.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cooking with Artisan Bread: Using Rustic Loaves for Perfect
Crostini, Panini, Bruschetta, Flavorful Stuffings and Inventive
Main Courses,'' by Gwenyth Bassetti and Jean Galton (Sasquatch
Books, 127 pages, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   The title alone is a mouthful and covers much of the contents,
which include additional recipes for soups, spreads and even bread
ice cream. Although it opens with a three-day formula for a country
loaf, this is not a breadmaking book. Bassetti founded Seattle's
own Grand Central Bakery, and Galton is a local writer.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Kingston Hotel Cafe Cookbook: Free-spirited Recipes to Warm
the Soul,'' by Judith Weinstock (Sasquatch Books, 157 pages,
$18.95)
</P>
<P>
   Weinstock emphasizes fresh, organic, regional foods in the meals
she prepares at her cozy bistro in the 19th-century Kingston Hotel
on the Kitsap Peninsula, though she's not afraid to mix in Asian or
other ethnic accents. Her cookbook follows the seasons, from
spring's Potato, Sorrel and Nettle Soup to winter's Seared Pork
Tenderloin with Spicy Green Apple-Tequila Sauce. Weinstock is a
former co-owner of The Streamliner Diner on Bainbridge Island and
author of ``The Streamliner Diner Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Northwest Berry Cookbook: Finding, Growing and Cooking With
Berries Year-Round,'' by Kathleen Desmond Stang (Sasquatch Books,
144 pages, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   What could be more Northwest than berries? This little paperback
discusses characteristics, seasons, buying, picking and raising
blackberries and raspberries, blueberries and huckleberries,
gooseberries, lingonberries and more. The 40 recipes range from
Bob's Blueberry Blue Cornmeal-Buttermilk Pancakes to Pork Roast
with Blackberry-Pinot Noir Sauce. Stang is a Seattleite who
occasionally contributes to these pages.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Northwest Food &AMP; Wine: Great Food to Serve With the Wines of
Oregon and Washington,'' by Dan and Kathleen Taggart (Sasquatch
Books, 284 pages, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the book is 120 recipes, but wine provides the
organizing principle, with recipes grouped according to the
Northwest wine varieties they are designed to accompany. The
Taggarts, who live near Portland, Ore., also discuss those wines
and sprinkle the text with winemaker bios and other regional
tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   THE CELEBRITY ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   Star chefs, starred restaurants:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ducasse: Flavors of France,'' by Alain Ducasse with Linda
Dannenberg (Artisan, 264 pages, $50).
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse is the only chef in France ever to win six Michelin
stars in one year, which is quite an accomplishment, considering
the top restaurant rating is three stars. He did it with two
three-star restaurants _ one in Paris, the other in Monte Carlo.
This beautifully illustrated, oversized book aims to convey his
secrets to an American audience. It's not Sunday-night supper fare,
unless Bass Fillets Baked in Parchment with Fennel-Truffle Sauce is
your idea of something to munch on while catching the NFL wrapup on
the tube.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Jean-Georges: Cooking at Home with a Four-Star Chef,'' by
Jean-Georges Vongerichten and Mark Bittman (Broadway Books; 224
pages, $35)
</P>
<P>
   With a four-star review from the New York Times (for his newest
restaurant, Jean Georges) and two 1998 James Beard awards
(Outstanding Chef, Best New Restaurant), Vongerichten is the toast
of New York and of haute-cuisine America. He's French, and classic
technique informs his refined cooking. But his penchant for Asian
flavors is well-established and his preparations, judging by the
recipes in this book, are suprisingly simple.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``John Madden's Ultimate Tailgating,'' by John Madden with
Peter Kaminsky (Viking, 224 pages, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Madden isn't a celebrity chef. But he is a celebrity, a
star sportscaster who often leads TV crews into the parking lot to
check out the food action outside the football stadium. He's an
unabashed fan of what he calls ``sinkers'' _ heavy eats that plunge
to the bottom of your stomach, and this book is full of them. The
recipes, mostly collected from tailgaters he has met, are designed
for fixing outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Le Bernadin Cookbook: Four-Star Simplicity,'' by Maguy
LeCoze and Eric Ripert (Doubleday, 372 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   LeCoze and Ripert are the owner and chef, respectively, of Le
Bernardin, a swanky, four-star New York restaurant dedicated to the
perfection of seafood. Le Bernardin was named Outstanding
Restaurant at the 1998 James Beard Awards, Ripert the top chef in
New York City. Both are French, and their recipes are rather
high-end, even if the results achieve a certain understated
elegance.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG BOOK,
</P>
<P>
   PRETTY PICTURES
</P>
<P>
   ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic gift-book formula.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Saveur Cooks Authentic American,'' by the editors of Saveur
Magazine (Chronicle Books, 320 pages, $40).
</P>
<P>
   Saveur is a lavishly illustrated and artful food magazine, and
this book fits the same pattern. Each of the 175 recipes comes with
a bit of background reporting. Most detail such down-home dishes as
macaroni and cheese, baked beans, fried chicken or strawberry
shortcake, drawn from throughout the land.
</P>
<P>
   THE ITALIAN ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   The American love (or at least the love of American cookbook
publishers) for Italian food continues unabated. The best I could
do was narrow the field to four.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cucina Ebraica: Flavors of the Italian Jewish Kitchen,'' by
Joyce Goldstein Chronicle Books, 202 pages, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   A twofer: Italian food and Jewish food in one, presented in an
attractively designed book. Goldstein is a successful restaurateur
(formerly of San Franciso's Square One) and cookbook author who
interweaves her recipes with the history and culinary lore of
Italy's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Diary of a Tuscan Chef: Recipes and Memories of Good Times
and Great Food,'' by Cesare Casella and Eileen Daspin (Doubleday,
336 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Casella traces his roots in Italian cuisine, speculatively, to
his conception in some unknown Tuscan kitchen. His professional
career started at 13 in his family's restaurant in Italy and has
continued at first-class Italian restaurants in New York.
Recollections supplement the recipes, arranged in seasonal menus.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Flavors of Tuscany: Traditional Recipes from the Tuscan
Countryside,'' by Nancy Harmon Jenkins (Broadway Books, 282 pages,
$27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins isn't Italian, but she's the next best thing: an
American who spends much of the year in a old stone farmhouse she
owns in Italy. Her book focuses on the rustic, earthy cooking of
her home away from home, with concise recipes and lots of anecdotal
chatter.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Food and Memories of Abruzzo: Italy's Pastoral Land,'' by
Anna Teresa Callen (Macmillan, 459 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing fascination with Italian cooking has meant more
appreciation for its regional variations. Callen, who runs a
cooking school in New York, explores the traditions _ culinary and
otherwise _ of her native Abruzzo, a mountainous region in central
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   THE EXOTIC ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   Keeping on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Elephant Walk Cookbook: Cambodian Cuisine from the
Nationally Acclaimed Restaurant,'' by Longteine de Monteiro and
Katherine Neustadt (Houghton Mifflin, 324 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Chinese food is old hat, everybody eats Thai, and Vietnamese
cooking has lost its novelty. How about Cambodian? The press
release for this pretty book describes Cambodian food as ``delicate
and refined . . . less salty that Vietnamese and less sweet than
Thai.'' Be the first on your block to serve Somlah Machou Mouan
(Khmer Chicken Soup With Eggplant) or Hong Chrouk (Pork With
Peanuts and Lilies). De Monteiro, a refugee from the Khmer Rouge,
runs three Cambodian restaurants in greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   THE A-TO-Z ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to leave no stone (or course) uncovered. Here are
three cookbooks develoted to something other than entr &UR; gfacute &LR; ees.
Besides, what's a cookbook list without a dessert book?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hors d'Oeuvres: Simple, Stylish, Seasonal,'' by Gillian
Duffy (William Morrow, 131 pages, $23).
</P>
<P>
   I've got a weakness for the kind of cocktail-party nibbles
featured in this book (and for cocktail parties, for that matter).
Just looking at the full-color photographs of Colombian Sirloin
Empanadas with Aji Sauce, Chevre Tartlets with Provencal Peppers,
and Shrimp with Green Chili Pesto (not to mention Sausage Rolls)
makes my mouth water.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Soup: A Way of Life,'' by Barbara Kafka (Artisan, 464 pages,
$35).
</P>
<P>
   What better way to warm up a drizzly winter evening than with a
steaming bowlful of soup? (Don't answer that; this is a family
newspaper.) Here are recipes for 300 soups _ fast soups and slow
soups, meat soups and vegetarian soups, hot soups and cold soups _
from an esteemed cookbook author with decades of food-writing
experience.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Desserts by Pierre Herm &UR; gfacute &LR; e,'' by Dorie Greenspan
(Little, Brown, 287 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Lionized in his native France, pasty chef Herme shares his
secrets in English for the first time. In the elegant photographs,
the stuff looks almost too good to eat. Expert dessert-makers
should find plenty to engage them here.
</P>
<P>
   THE VEGETARIAN
</P>
<P>
   ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   It's a hardy perennial among cookbook subjects.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Vegetarian Compass: New Directions in Vegetarian
Cooking,'' by Karen Hubert Allison (Little, Brown, 383 pages,
$29.95).
</P>
<P>
   The almost funereal hues of gray, black and maroon are unusual
for the cover of a vegetarian cookbook, and this one seems cast in
a different mold than most of its ilk: more mannered, more
sophisticated. Allison, a former New York restaurateur who died
last year, applied the rigorous techniques of classic French
cuisine to cooking vegetables. But her recipes reflect multiethnic
influences in such preparations as Pumpkin Chile Roulade Filled
With Tomatillo Salsa, or Lima Beans, Chayote and Baby Bok Choy in
Lemongrass Ragout.
</P>
<P>
   THE TRACK-RECORD ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   Books from writers with reputations.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mediterranean Grains and Greens,'' by Paula Wolfert
(HarperCollins, 368 pages, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Mediterranean cooking maven Paula Wolfert (``Mediterranean
Cooking,'' ``The Cooking of the Eastern Mediterranean,'' ``The
Cooking of South-West France,'' ``Couscous and Other Good Food of
Morocco,'' ``Paula Wolfert's World of Food'') weighs in with what
sounds like a vegetarian cookbook, but isn't. Certainly, greens and
grains play a prominent role and many of the recipes are meat-free,
but there are beef, chicken, fish, pork and lamb dishes as well,
gathered from throughout the Mediterranean Rim.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Seductions of Rice,'' by Jeffrey Alford and Naomi Duguid
(Artisan, 454 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   The husband-and-wife team of Alford and Duguid hit it big with
their first culinary collaboration, ``Flatbreads and Flavors: A
Baker's Atlas,'' winning the 1995 James Beard award for Cookbook of
the Year. Now rice is their vehicle for blending cuisine and
cultural studies, in a part-cookbook, part-travelogue that includes
200 recipes for rice and rice-related dishes, from Risotto with
Salami to Thai Red Chicken Curry to Shrimp Gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vegetables: The Most Authoritative Guide to Buying,
Preparing, and Cooking, with More Than 300 Recipes,'' by James
Peterson (William Morrow, 429 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Like Alford and Duguid (but without their lyrical anthropology),
Peterson goes in for the comprehensive approach. And like them,
he's won a Beard cookbook-of-the-year award (for ``Sauces:
Classical and Contemporary Sauce Making,'' in 1991). What he did
for seafood in 1996 with his reference-shelf book ``Fish &AMP;
Shellfish,'' he now aims to do for veggies, although this work is
less scientific and emphasizes the cook's perspective. The recipes
include some where vegetables accompany dead animals.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKS-GOOD-TO-ME ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yellow Farmhouse Cookbook,'' by Christopher Kimball (Little,
Brown, 410 pages, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   Kimball's approach to cooking is very analytical and full of
curiosity. The editor of Cook's Illustrated magazine and author of
``The Cook's Bible,'' he tests and experiments with recipes and
techniques. Then he records the results, reporting, for example,
which brand of cornmeal makes the best muffins, or what happens to
a leg of lamb pot-roasted at different temperatures. The yellow
farmhouse of the title is in Vermont, and the recipes cover sturdy,
American country fare. The reassuring tone and attention to detail
would make this a good choice for anyone, from beginner to expert.
</P>
<P>
   THE COMIC-RELIEF
</P>
<P>
   ANGLE
</P>
<P>
   Amuse your friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Spam: The Cookbook,'' compiled by Linda Eggers (Longstreet,
84 pages, $5.95).
</P>
<P>
   A stocking-stuffer not much bigger than a can of Spam, this book
is ``dedicated to those who eat Spam luncheon meat simply because
it tastes good.'' Recipes, contributed by Spam-lovers across
America, include such temptations as Spam Noodle Casserole, Spam
Risotto, Spicy Spam Party Dip and . . . I'm not making this up ...
Spam Bread.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6860 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ABOLITION-ART-     11-24 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ABOLITION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S OTHER FREEDOM TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Civil War's battlefields are hundreds of miles from
Boston, but throughout the city are dozens of reminders that it was
the center of antislavery activity for 30 years before the outbreak
of that conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those sites are on the Black Heritage Trail, including
the African Meeting House on Beacon Hill, which is being restored
with $1.4 million in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also an unofficial abolitionist trail, traced by
Henry Mayer when he was researching ``All on Fire,'' his biography
of William Lloyd Garrison that was a finalist for the National Book
Awards announced last week. Garrison published the fiery
antislavery paper The Liberator in Boston every week from January
1831 until slavery was abolished with adoption of the 13th
Amendment in December 1865.
</P>
<P>
   There is some overlap between the two trails, just as there were
points of intersection between the city's mid-19th-century black
community and the mainly white abolitionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Major antislavery events also took place at, or just outside of,
well-known sites on the city's Freedom Trail, such as Faneuil Hall
and the Old State House. But Mayer notes ruefully that nothing
marks the later events.
</P>
<P>
   Saddest of all, Mayer says, the site of the office from which
Garrison published The Liberator &UR;  &LR; is buried under City Hall Plaza.
The building itself was destroyed in a suspicious fire in 1963 &UR;  &LR; as
efforts were underway to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison had been inspired to join the antislavery cause after
meeting a crusading Quaker editor. And he settled on Boston as the
place to launch his own paper because of the city's small but
active free black community. Many lived on the back slope of Beacon
Hill near the African Meeting House on Smith Court _ among them,
Lewis Hayden and John J. Smith, two black leaders in the
abolitionist movement. Garrison attended a freedom meeting at the
church in July 1829 that, Mayer says, convinced him a
``gradualist'' approach to ending slavery ``was not a viable
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the site of the Liberator office, all of Cornhill,
the crooked street where bookstores and printing shops jostled
along the southern edge of Scollay Square, lost out to urban
renewal in the early 1960s. An earlier office was in the long-gone
Merchants' Hall at the corner of Congress and Water streets. But
Mayer finds enough reminiscent of the area where Garrison worked in
the narrow streets just north of Dock Square.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who would like to follow the abolitionist trail
today, there are two good starting points, both little changed from
when Garrison settled in Boston, determined to launch his
antislavery revolution in the city that had fostered the revolution
against Colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Park Street Church and Faneuil Hall were sites for
abolitionist gatherings. Garrison gave the Fourth of July address
at the church in 1829, in which, Mayer says, he rewrote ``the
Declaration of Independence to include African-Americans and linked
the end of slavery and civil equality as twin goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The most tumultuous events in Boston's antislavery history
occurred in the streets around Court Square _ the square itself is
much as it was in the 1850s, although the porticoed 19th-century
courthouse was replaced with the present building (now the Boston
School Committee headquarters) in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Abolition was not an instantly popular cause in Boston, and when
the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society, one of several such groups
in the city, scheduled a meeting in October 1835 at the
Anti-Slavery Office at 46 Washington St. _ now the location of the
Washington Street Mall _ a crowd Mayer describes as ``sultry and
disagreeable'' filled the streets in protest and stormed the
meeting hall.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Theodore Lyman, who had been monitoring the unrest from
his office at City Hall (now known as the Old State House), forced
his way into the meeting, shouting, ``Go home, ladies, go home,''
which they did, after he promised to see them safely through the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison was holed up in a room off the meeting hall and escaped
out a second-floor window. He was spotted and was being hauled out
into the street when two muscular truckmen came to his aid and
propelled him down the street to City Hall, where Lyman gave him
refuge.
</P>
<P>
   But attitudes in the city were changing. Boston had long been a
haven for escaped slaves, and the city's abolitionists were openly
defiant of the nation's Fugitive Slave Law after it was passed in
1850.
</P>
<P>
   The defiance came to a head in May 1854 when federal marshals
arrested Anthony Burns, a slave from Virginia who had arrived in
Boston as a stowaway and had been hidden in the city for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Burns was jailed at the courthouse while federal troops were
sent to Boston to ensure his return to Virginia. But ``with the
streets jammed with angry protesters and Faneuil Hall rocking
nightly with indignant oratory,'' Mayer writes, ``Boston endured
the most dramatic and tumultuous week in its history'' since the
week of the Boston Tea Party in 1773.
</P>
<P>
   Legal maneuvering failed and Burns was ``marched down State
Street completely surrounded by US soldiers'' and transferred to a
revenue cutter anchored in the harbor, Mayer writes, while ``church
bells tolled (and) lampposts and windows were draped in black
mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   That one event, Mayer writes, woke Boston and the North ``to
Garrison's prophetic message'' and set in motion the events that
would lead to the Civil War seven years later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAYER ON GARRISON'S TRAIL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the trail of abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison, biographer
Henry Mayer tramped the back slope of Beacon Hill, where many
members of the city's black community lived before the Civil War,
and he made sketch maps of streets in the South End, where Garrison
lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked maps to give you context,'' Mayer said.
``It's the way you blow the dust off history.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunching at the Union Oyster House, which opened just north of
Dock Square in 1826, the same year that Garrison first came to
Boston looking for work as a printer, Mayer said it was one of a
number of eating places popular with workers from the nearby print
shops. ``It's just the kind of place where Garrison would have
eaten,'' Mayer said.
</P>
<P>
   The biography ``All on Fire,'' published last month by St.
Martin's Press, was a finalist for the National Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer, 57, grew up in North Carolina and attended the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill during the civil rights movement.
``I got involved in a little movement to desegregate the local
movie thea-ter,'' he said, ``and remember the flood of emotion that
came from picketing.''
</P>
<P>
   He taught briefly after graduate school at the University of
California at Berkeley, but a course he developed on the American
Revolution got him interested enough in Patrick Henry to write a
biography of that leader, whose remark ``Give me liberty or give me
death'' became a revolutionary rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, Betsy, is a physician,'' Mayer said, ``and she
supports my writing habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer is now at work on another proj-ect, a biography of the
Depression-era photographer Dorothea Lange, but there is still some
unfinished business from the Garrison book.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the sites associated with the Boston's abolitionist
movement are marked, Mayer said _ neither long-gone sites such as
the office where Garrison published his abolitionist newspaper, The
Liberator, nor still-standing buildings such as the Old State House
and Faneuil Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I'd like to see,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
