<SLUG> BC-FILM-BABE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEQUEL TO `BABE' NOT AS GOOD AS THE ORIGINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This little piggy very nearly didn't make it to market.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, prints weren't ready and Universal was telling
the world the filmmakers were still synching in the animal voices.
However, the reality was quite different. The studio took one look
at director George Miller's dark vision in this sequel to ``Babe''
ordered him back in the editing room to cut away the edginess until
the film could garner a G, instead of PG, rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe: Pig In the City'' still deserves a PG warning. It's
disturbing and it's doubtful small children will grasp its adult
themes _ and those that do are likely to be scared to death.
</P>
<P>
   One scene sadistically depicts a bull terrier hanging by a chain
with his head submerged in water and one character is a
sophisticated, pink-hued poodle who talks about her past as a
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   And Miller, who produced the original ``Babe,'' (it was directed
by Chris Noonan) can't seem to escape pulling from his violent,
cult ``Mad Max'' movies. ``Babe: Pig In the City'' is full of
references to the trilogy and, in the end, Mrs. Hoggett (Magda
Szubinski), is even flying around a hotel lobby in a scene that
strongly resembles the ``thunderdome'' gladiator games from ``Mad
Max Beyond Thunderdome.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Babe'' came to a close, the little ``sheep pig'' had just
won the sheepdog trials with Farmer Hoggett (James Cromwell). The
second film opens with a scary scene of Hoggett falling down a
well. He was to have taken our beloved Babe to the big city to make
a personal appearance and make some money to save the farm from
foreclosure. All the animals are begging Babe to help _ Ferdinand
the duck, the three singing mice, the sheep and sheepdogs Fly and
Rex urge him to find a way to let the humans keep their home safe
from harm.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hoggett steps in and agrees to accompany Babe to town. It's
an adventure that should be fun for Babe. But things don't quite go
as planned. ``More often than not, fortune favors the brave,'' says
the narrator. And Babe must prove his courage in the face of what
will become his darkest hour.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a room in a surreal hotel full of animals with very
few owners, Mrs. Hoggett is hauled away by the DEA because a
drug-sniffing dog has shown Babe how easy it is to get a human
arrested at the airport. Then the hotel is raided by an animal
enforcement agency. Babe's new acquaintances are taken away to
research labs and one is even run over by a van (he survives, but
it's very intense). Babe must muster his wits and save his friends,
find Mrs. Hoggett and keep his promise that the farm will stay
untouched by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The story lands in a lighter world by the end, but it's been a
weird, twisted trip full of mayhem and chaos till then. If audience
reaction is an indicator, most small children at the preview
screening didn't get it and adults, at best, laughed uncomfortably
at heavy political messages about the plight of animals in society.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the film is visually full of imagination and has
some inspired, clever moments. It also thankfully avoids the
scatology that seems to permeate every family film these days. But
it still looks dark, feels darker and is full of iffy bits that
border on questionable taste. Miller, who was a doctor prior to
becoming a director, seems to have little hope for humanity. That
may very well be the case, but he should save it for his next ``Mad
Max'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   Babe: Pig In the City. Directed by George Miller. Written by
Miller, Judy Morris, Mark Lamprell. Cast: Magda Szubinski, James
Cromwell, Mickey Rooney. Universal Pictures. 95 minutes. Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
