<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE SETS TRAP THAT LEADS TO DASH'S RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- No doubt, in time, Sam Dash will hit the law
school circuit.
</P>
<P>
   And when he does, there is also no doubt that the smartest kids
in the classes on hair-splitting will thrill to his dazzling
explanations of how the same conduct by Ken Starr he said was
``unlawful'' before the House Judiciary Committee last week was not
unlawful in Starr's written presentation to the House in September.
</P>
<P>
   Dash will also no doubt be brilliant as he explains his own role
in leaving poor chairman Henry Hyde with a case that can only be
made via the inferences of Starr, because the witnesses and the
evidence are at best ambivalent and often exculpatory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rest of us will wrestle with Dash's mixed-message
resignation _ not solely on ethics issues, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   One clue came within hours of Dash's public departure, when all
of Starr's deputies began doing one of the few things they do
consistently well _ leak like sieves.
</P>
<P>
   While the boss stayed on the high road, the Starr deputies
portrayed Dash's professed concerns about dispassionate neutrality
in total contrast to his behavior when the impeachment referral was
being prepared late last summer.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dash, the Starr deputies angrily leaked, who had insisted
on many of the escalations in rhetoric that characterized this
argumentative submission; and it was Dash, they also leaked, who
virtually alone came up with the silliest charges in the entire
document, that President Clinton abused his power by asserting
rights and priveliges in court.
</P>
<P>
   Good points, by the way, but they miss the largest point, that
Starr is making the errors of a passionate advocate of the
president's removal from office, whose constitutional sin is
designed to fill the huge void left by Hyde's misfeasance and
nonfeasance, and that of his inept impeachment director, Chicago
crony David Schippers.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it from Starr's point of view. He sends his referral to
Capitol Hill more than two months ago, and what happens? Nothing
but gutter politics.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter who we are eventually told pulled which string
_ Newt Gingrich or Hyde himself _ but all that happens is that the
argumentative, soft-core pornographic referral is made public just
as the congressional election campaign is heating up. The same
thing happens to all of Starr's backup material and grand jury
records, including the famous video of Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing else happens, except that Schippers plays with
Starr's language in a rewrite of Starr's rewrite of testimony he
never heard from witnesses he never met.
</P>
<P>
   When the public doesn't buy into the political strategy, when it
in fact backfires, Hyde switches gears while denying he is doing
so. Despite the fact that he has failed to take one step toward
developing the House's own factual record, despite his insistence
that the Judiciary Committee will look beyond the Monica Lewinsky
matter, he says the entire impeachment matter is nonetheless to be
wrapped up before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   To short-circuit the absence of effort to develop the House's
own evidentiary record, Hyde then sends the White House his list of
81 ``affirm or deny'' questions, seeking either a Clinton assent to
Starr's allegations or another presumably perjurious set of sworn
denials.
</P>
<P>
   And then, he calls Starr as (to date)the sole public hearing
witness. Hyde could say the Democrats had sought him, but they
sought him on the understandable assumption that Starr would appear
as one witness to answer questions about his investigation, while
other witnesses would deal directly with the factual issues in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde called him as if he were one of those fact witnesses.
But Starr had admitted to Clinton lawyer David Kendall that out of
the entire record he sent Congress _ 134 FBI interviews, 19
investigative depositions, and 115 grand jury sessions _ he had
participated in only one, the President's White House testimony on
Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did Hyde set the constitutional trap over which Dash
resigned, on the grounds that Starr usurped Congress's sole power
of impeachment by arguing the case for it.
</P>
<P>
   To be accurate, though, there was one part of the case Starr
didn't argue as he had in his referral, and which committee
Democrats didn't, either. This just happened to be the basis for
the allegation of perjury that dwarfs the others, and indeed from
which the entire case flows and on which it depends.
</P>
<P>
   This is the charge that Clinton committed perjury in his Paula
Jones deposition 10 months ago when he denied ``sex'' with
Lewinsky, and then compounded it in August when he denied to the
grand jury that he lied in that deposition.
</P>
<P>
   To prove it, Starr had to accept the absurd, convoluted, and
perverted definition of sex Jones's lawyers gave the president, and
then to show via Lewinsky's unchallenged testimony that certain
acts occurred as she alleged. Hence, the pornography and the
political problem.
</P>
<P>
   The same ridiculous burden was faced by the White House in
defense of Clinton, though he, in fact, denied the Lewinsky sex
narrative. Hence all the silliness about ``legally accurate'' false
testimony and the Democrats' plea to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains, however, that the impeachment case exists only
in Ken Starr's inferential conclusions, not in a record developed
by the House.
</P>
<P>
   It's in fine shape for a shouting match on cable TV, but not for
the second impeachment vote in American history. And that is as
much Henry Hyde's fault as it is Ken Starr's.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
