<SLUG> BC-AOL-NETSCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL COMPLETES DEAL TO BUY NETSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ America Online announced Tuesday that it would
buy Netscape Communications Inc. in a $4.21 billion deal that
affects a majority of American Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Netscape gives the combined companies new
muscle to combat rival Microsoft Corp. in the booming Internet
software market. The federal government is suing Microsoft on
antitrust charges that stem, in part, from its aggressive business
practices against Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Dulles, Va.-based AOL is expected to operate
Netscape as a separate division in Mountain View, Calif. But the
4-year-old Netscape, which produces the software that popularized
the Internet and whose dramatic debut on the stock market was among
the most successful ever, would cease to exist as an independent
entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exciting partnership enables us to deliver even better
and more complete products and services to both existing and new
customers,'' said James Barksdale, the Netscape chief executive who
will join AOL's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acquisition of Netscape is a big step forward for America
Online that will greatly accelerate our business momentum,'' AOL
Chairman Steve Case said.
</P>
<P>
   In a side agreement, AOL will license Netscape corporate
software to Sun Microsystems Inc. of Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is massive,'' said Ira Machefsky, a research partner at
the Palo Alto-based Odeon Capital venture company. ``What you're
witnessing is the birth of an NBC on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal merges the World Wide Web's largest network with the
company that makes a popular Web browsing software. According to
recent figures, there are 50 million Web users in the United
States. AOL accounts for 14 million of those, and Netscape's
Netcenter portal _ a Web page that provides links to other Internet
sites _ on any one day has 20 million users or more.
</P>
<P>
   The $4.21 billion deal, struck late Monday, calls for an
exchange of .45 shares of AOL stock for one share of Netscape
stock, which, at current market values, means Netscape shareholders
will get about $40 per share.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, AOL gets Netscape's browser, and its burgeoning
Netcenter Web portal.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-year deal, Sun Microsystems Inc. will distribute
Netscape's business-level ``server'' software, and AOL will use
Sun's Java programming technology to offer AOL services on what the
company called ``next-generation Internet devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Java lets programs run on a variety of computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Consumer Project on Technology, a
public-interest organization run by Ralph Nader, vowed to protest
any AOL-Netscape deal, contending that the market for Internet
software, now divided between Netscape and Microsoft, hampers
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the negotiations said that talks between
representatives of the companies were conducted in a setting of
video conferences, conference calls and endless electronic mail
between the chief executives of all three companies: Barksdale,
Case and Scott McNealy of Sun.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement, sources said, was supposed to be made Monday
before Wall Street opened, but bogged down over complex licensing
and ancillary rights among Sun, Netscape and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   A deal finally was struck via a conference call between the
three executives at about 4 p.m. Monday, the sources said. The pact
was announced to Barksdale by Case using AOL's on-line e-mail
notice, said a Netscape staffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve (Case) finally called Jim (Barksdale) and told him
`You've got mail,''' the staffer said. ``That let Jim know that
there was a done deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
