<HEADLINE>
THANKFUL . . . BUT NOT TRUTHFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big travel weekend is coming up as families flock together
to celebrate Thanksgiving much as the Pilgrims did. Or maybe not:
So many of our cherished myths about Thanksgiving are ... well ...
bunk. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   _The first settlers weren't called Pilgrims. Instead, they
modestly referred to themselves as Saints.
</P>
<P>
   _They didn't wear big hats with buckles, either. That was
something 19th-century artists dreamed up.
</P>
<P>
   _The first Thanksgiving was no solemn religious occasion.
Instead, it was a three-day festival that included drinking,
gambling, and target shooting.
</P>
<P>
   _It didn't take place in November but sometime between late
September and mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   _If the celebrants ate turkey at all, it was as a side dish.
Deer was the main course.
</P>
<P>
   _There's no evidence they celebrated the following year.
</P>
<P>
   (We thank Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass., who in turn thanks
``Uncle John's Bathroom Reader,'' which in turn thanks historian
Samuel Eliot Morison. This, after all, is a time for giving
thanks.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``As you exit the plane, please make sure to gather &UR;  &LR; all
of your belongings. Anything left behind will be
distributed &UR;  &LR; evenly among the flight attendants. Please do not
leave children &UR;  &LR; or spouses.'' _ anonymous airline crew
announcement, reported by NZ News &AMP; Features.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  We'll put another shrimp on the barbie if you can
tell us what Qantas _ the name of the Aussie airline _ stands for.
(Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  There is a restaurant in Georgetown, Colo., called the
Happy Cooker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a phrase: &LR;  We say, ``It's all Greek to me.'' In Greece, some
say, ``It's all Chinese to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie: &LR;  For an 88-page winter/holiday guide to Boston, complete
with a Family Value Pass offering more than 40 discounts for
shopping, eating, and museumgoing, call 888-SEE-BOSTON.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Fascinating fact: &LR;  The Cotopaxi volcano in Ecuador, at 19,475 feet,
is the world's highest active volcano. (With thanks to Ron Levy of
Winchester.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Moon over Snowville:  &LR; Clothing is optional (yes, optional) when you
go cross-country skiing at night as part of a Full Moon Package at
the Snowvillage Inn in Snowville, N.H. The package includes two
nights' lodging, a candlelight dinner, two country breakfasts, and
unlimited use of the cross-country trails on the premises.
Flashlights for skiing under the full moon will be provided, as
will tapes of ``Moon River'' and ``By the Light of the Silvery
Moon.'' The dates are Jan. 1-3, Jan. 29-31, March 2-3, March
31-April 1 and April 30-May 1. The cost ranges from $125 to $250
per person, double occupancy. For more information, call
800-447-4345. As innkeeper Kevin Flynn slyly notes, ``By offering
clothing-optional cross-country skiing, we can guarantee our guests
that they'l always see a full moon!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Arigato to JAL: &LR;  As of April 1, Japan Airlines will ban smoking on
all international flights, making the airline completely smoke
free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Seaport ``store'':  &LR; So you're in Boston and find you need, say,
another shirt or pair of pantyhose. But you're in a rush and
haven't time to head to a store. Well, Boston's new Seaport Hotel
will bring the store to you. A selection from Filene's Basement is
available to guests. All they need do is fill out the card that is
already in their room, and the items, which are in the hotel, will
be delivered to the room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Qantas stands for Queensland and Northern
Territory Aerial Services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
