<HEADLINE>
A GREAT SEASON FOR ART EXHIBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston has Monet, Washington has Van Gogh. While these are the
hottest tickets in the museum world now, they are not the only
great art shows available.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't seen the Monet exhibit at the Boston Museum of
Fine Arts (call 617-369-3449), plan on doing so by Dec. 27, when
the exhibit ends. Boston is the only North American site for this
showing of the Impressionist master's works, from his later years
to his death in 1926 at 86.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to catch this blockbuster is by buying a
weekend hotel package that includes tickets to the show good any
time during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Among area hotels with packages are the Hyatt Regency Cambridge
at $190 a night (617-492-1234); and the Seaport Hotel, the city's
newest hotel, beginning at $225 a night (617-385-4000). The
packages include accommodations, two tickets to the exhibit, and
extras. For other hotel packages, call the Boston Convention and
Visitors Bureau at 888-SEE BOSTON.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Gallery of Art in Washington, ``Van Gogh's Van
Goghs: Masterpieces from the Van Gogh Museum, Amsterdam,''
continues through Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The show is the largest collection of van Gogh's work to be seen
in the United States in 25 years. After Washington, the exhibit
will only be seen in Los Angeles before returning to Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   For the exhibit, the gallery has a new policy: Only four
same-day passes per person will be offered, and once the gallery
opens 600 passes will be distributed the first hour, with the
remaining 1,400 passes being distributed at half-hour intervals
from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission is free but passes are for
specific time periods only. For information, call 202-737-4215.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one of the nicest ways to catch the exhibit is with a
hotel package. One of the best is from the Hay-Adams Hotel,
directly across from the White House. The package, which starts at
$1,400 for two nights, includes breakfasts, afternoon tea, and a
Van Gogh keepsake (call 800-424-5054).
</P>
<P>
   Also at the National Gallery through Jan. 3 is ``Gifts to the
Nation from Mr. and Mrs. John Hay Whitney,'' which includes eight
masterworks bequeathed by philanthropist Betsey Cushing Whitney.
Among them are Vincent van Gogh's ``Self Portrait'' and James
McNeill Whistler's ``Wrapping.''
</P>
<P>
   The gallery is also featuring ``Edo: Art in Japan 1615-1868''
through Feb. 15. The performing arts festival features a variety of
Japanese art forms, from marionettes to acrobats.
</P>
<P>
   Works by Monet are included in ``Impressionists in Winter:
Effets de Neige'' at the Phillips Collection in Washington through
Jan. 3 (202-387-2151.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, the first of Impressionist winter landscape
paintings, includes ``A Cart on the Snowy Road at Honfleur'' (1865)
by Claude Monet, along with works by artists such as Pierre-August
Renoir and Palul Gauguin, whose ``Breton Village in the Snow'' was
found unfinished on his easel in Tahiti at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Also spanning the last years of an artist's life is ``Delacroix:
The Late Work'' at the Philadelphia Museum of Art through Jan. 3
(215-763-8100). The exhibit commemorates the 200th anniversary of
the birth of the French painter and is the only US exhibit of these
works.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Delacroix is considered the last Old Masters, and the
exhibit of 70 paintings and 40 works on paper spans the final years
of the artist's life _ 1798-1863.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hotel packages available for the showing, US
Airways, Amtrak, and National Car Rental are offering discounts on
travel to or in Philadelphia for the exhibition. For complete
information, call the Philadelphia Visitors Center at 800-752-8206.
</P>
<P>
   Also on view in Philadelphia is the new Canaan and Ancient
Israel gallery at the University of Pennsylvania Museum of
Archaelogy and Anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   This new permanent exhibition is the first in North America
dedicated to the archeology of ancient Israel and neighboring
lands.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the role that the Bible has had in shaping the
personal and cultural identities of people throughout the world,
the new exhibit digs deep into the past to consider the question,
``What shaped the identities of the Bible's people?'' Special
hotel-and-travel packages are also available; call 800-752-8206.
</P>
<P>
   ``Degas and the Little Dancer,'' at the Baltimore Museum of Art
through Jan. 3 (410-396-7100), focuses on the French
Impressionist's most significant theme, the little dancer, with 45
paintings, prints, and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, ``Jackson Pollock,'' the first US
retrospective since 1967 of the most influential American painter
of the 20th century, is on view through Feb. 2 at the Museum of
Modern Art (212-708-9400).
</P>
<P>
   ``The mythic image of Jackson Pollock as a troubled,
hard-drinking figure of rebellion has sometimes come to obscure the
work itself,'' said Kirk Varnedoe, the museum's chief curator.
``Pollock's astonishing range and the full richness of his
remarkable achievement can only truly be perceived first-hand.''
For information on hotel and Amtrak packages, call 212-708-9403.
</P>
<P>
   At the Studio Museum in Harlem (212-864-4500), ``Selections from
the Permanent Collection,'' showcasing the works of four major
American artists, will be on view through Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney Museum is showcasing the work of figurative
expressionist painter Bob Thompson through Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 paintings and drawings, many of which have never
before been seen by a large audience, will be on view.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings span the years 1959-'65, when Thompson's narrative
abstract expressionist compositions were celebrated for their
artistry and originality.
</P>
<P>
   The first major exhibition dedicated to the vibrant folk culture
of Spain and its pervasive influence of life and art in Latin
American and the United States, ``El Alma del Pueblo: Spanish Folk
Art and Its Transformation in the Americas'' is on view through
Dec. 31 at the Spanish Institute in New York City (212-628-0420).
More than 250 objects from 30 museums are included in the exhibit,
which will later be seen in Chicago, Sacramento, and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Picasso's experimentation with ceramics, which he began
late in his career, produced a series of expressive figures,
vessels, and tiles that have rarely been seen in public. The Tacoma
Art Museum is making 60 of these playful works accessible in the
only American showing of ``Ceramics from the Marina Picasso
Collection,'' through Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Museum (212-423-3271) is featuring ``Common Man,
Mythic Vision: The Painting of Ben Shahn,'' through March 7. The
exhibit, which features 52 of the finest paintings created by
Shahn, is the first major museum exhibition of his works in the
United States since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   At the Metropolitan Museum of Art, ``Van Eyck to Bruegel: Early
Netherlandish Paintings in the Metropolitan Museum of Art'' brings
together more than 100 works from the museum's collection,
illuminating a critical period in the history of Western art. The
exhibit continues through Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Also on view Dec. 15 through March 21 is ``Anselm Kiefer: Works
on Paper, 1969-1993,'' featuring 54 of the artist's unique works on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the fascinating aspects of Kiefer's works on paper is
the way he manipulates a variety of mark-making techniques or plays
with compositions to fortify the subject matter,'' said Nan
Rosenthal, curator of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   More art exhibits will be mentioned in future columns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
17th-century day
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 28, you can step back 300 years to the 17th century at
Historic Deerfield in Deerfield, Mass. Members of the Society of
the 17th Century will demonstrate the handicrafts necessary for
survival on the New England frontier _ and Deerfield was the
American frontier in those years.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned are concerts, hearth cooking demonstrations, and
tours of the newly opened Flynt Center of Early New England Life
and its exhibition on ``Pursuing Refinement in Rural New England:
1750-1850.'' For information, call 413-774-5581.
</P>
</TEXT>
