 Tuesday, Nov. 24, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-RESEARCHER (Washington) _ A decade ago Dr. Anthony Fauci,
one of the nation's top scientific warriors against AIDS, was
public enemy No. 1 to gay health groups. But now they're on his
side. How he turned around the irate activists and made them his
allies is a story of a man with infinite patience and consummate
political skills. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Photos available on the Wieck database. Story could be
used anytime over the holiday weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ A conservative group has mounted a
campaign to carve Ronald Reagan's face on Mount Rushmore and
plaster his name on roads, buildings and airports in all 50 states.
Isn't this a tad premature? Shouldn't we wait for history's verdict
on him? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CENSUS (Washington) _ In a case that could alter America's
political landscape and redirect billions of dollars in federal
money, the Supreme Court on Monday will examine whether a new
method to conduct the 2000 Census would be legal. By MARK HELM.
</P>
