 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FUNERAL (St. Petersburg) _ Russia's beleaguered democrats
bury an assassinated member of parliament. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   GAZA-AIRPORT (Gaza Strip) _ Palestinians celebrate their
feelings of statehood as they open their own airport. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments on arms inspections in
Iraq. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Iraq developments, including
possible Security Council response to the letter from Tariq Aziz;
action on an oil-for-food program. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Jakarta) _ A government commission is to
investigate a report of a new East Timor massacre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-GORE (Washington) _ Developments in Attorney General
Reno's decision on whether to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Vice President Gore. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments in the House impeachment
inquiry against President Clinton. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-REPUBS (Washington) _ Sen. Mitch McConnell, head of the
Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee, is challenged by Sen.
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska. Critics say McConnell cared more about
blocking changes in the campaign finance laws than about electing
Republicans. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LIBRARY-NET-FILTER (Undated) _ In a test case watched by public
libraries across the country, a federal judge in Virginia has ruled
unconstitutional the Loudoun County public library's use of an
internet filter on its public-access computers.
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPT-ORPHAN (Baltimore) _ A 10-year-old boy will ask a judge
to declare him bankrupt after both of his parents die and the
mortgage company is threatening to take his family home. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   THANKSGIVING-PARADE (New York) _ Central Park West prepares for
its biggest party of the year, the Thanksgiving parade. By N.R.
Kleinfield.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-TEACHERS-STRIKE (Jersey City, N.J.) _ Four days into the
teacher strike, how are parents coping? Only one-third of the
children are attending school, partly from fear that the riotous
first day will be repeated, but largely because careful schedules
of after-school day care have been disrupted. Other developments:
both sides in court today. By Maria Newman. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-NETSCAPE (Undated) _ America Online agrees to buy Netscape
for about $4.2 billion in stock. It will exchange 0.45 share for
each Netscape share, valuing Netscape at $40.16, a 47 percent
premium to its Nov. 13 close. Under the agreement, Sun Microsystems
will market and develop Netscape's electronic commerce software and
Internet devices. Netscape also says that earnings fell but revenue
rose in the third quarter. By Steve Lohr John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   AOL-E-COMMERCE (Undated) _ A look at electronic commerce, which
is driving the AOL-Netscape deal. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments at the Microsoft
trial. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS-TRUST-DEUTSCHE (New York) _ Developments regarding
Deutsche Bank and Bankers Trust. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The government revises upward its
calculation of economic growth in the third quarter but also
reports that corporate profits faltered. The Commerce Department
now says that gross domestic product expanded at a 3.9 percent
annual rate in the third quarter, up from the previous estimate of
3.3 percent. The third quarter's after-tax corporate profits,
reported for the first time today, decreased 1.8 percent from the
prior three months. Two other economic reports are issued, showing
that consumer confidence rose more than expected in November and
that orders for durable goods fell 1.7 percent in October. By
Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 12:45 p.m., the industrial average was
off 46 points. Elsewhere, prices rose 2.6 percent in Tokyo and 3.2
percent in Hong Kong. They fell 1 percent in Frankfurt, 0.6 percent
in London, 2.4 percent in Brazil and 0.2 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 18/32 point at midday,
with the yield at 5.22 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   BOXES (Undated) _ The companies that make boxes are suffering
from overcapacity, giving them two choices: take over competitors
or shut production lines. There are two developments today:
International Paper is buying Union Camp and Smurfit-Stone
Container, formed this week by Jefferson Smurfit's acquisition of
Stone Container, says it will will cut as many as 3,600 jobs, or 10
percent of its workers, and take a fourth-quarter charge of as much
as $350 million. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   INTUIT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Intuit will post earnings and is
expected to report a loss of 46 cents a share. By Lawrence M.
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   NOVELL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Novell will post earnings and is
expected to report a profit of 9 cents a share. By Lawrence M.
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN-OIL (Moscow) _ A group of governments and Western oil
companies led by Chevron approves plans to build a $2.3 billion
pipeline from Kazakhstan, the first major export line from the
Caspian Sea region. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA-MEXICO (Toronto) _ The Canadian government has accused
Mexico of not enforcing its own environmental and labor standards
in the workplace. This could lead to sanctions against Mexico under
NAFTA because the United States has already filed such complaints,
and two of the three NAFTA members must agree to move to sanctions
against the third member. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   HAWKE-BANKS (Undated) _ John D. Hawke looked like the perfect
candidate to become the nation's top banking regulator, but his
nomination as comptroller of the currency is hung up in the
cross-currents of politics, policy and personalities. So the
65-year-old Hawke is now in the awkward and embarrassing position
of being in a bureaucratic no-man's-land. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties'' and Frank Rich's ``Journal'';
details to come.
</P>
