<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, Nov. 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PECANS (Perry, Ga.) _ A fresh pecan is a revelation, a far
different thing from the brown, often wizened nut that you find in
bags on supermarket shelves. At its best, no more than a month off
the tree, a pecan is golden, plump and tender, with a mellow,
buttery flavor and hardly any of the bitter tannins found in the
walnut, a distant relative. By Florence Fabricant. (1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic map.
</P>
<P>
   PECAN-PIE (Undated) _ It's classic. It's irresistible. And it's
a killer. Two bites into the standard pecan pie, and even the most
dessert-toughened Yankees, veterans of chocolate decadence cake,
tiramisu and creme brulee, know that they're in deep trouble. Like
Rhine maidens draped seductively on jagged rocks, those luscious
pecans sit atop a thick, tremulous layer of filling so sweet that
it can make grown men cry. More than a century after the Civil War,
pecan pie remains the last holdout against Reconstruction, but wily
carpetbaggers, assisted by a few Southern scalawags, have been
tinkering with the pecan-pie formula and coming up with ways to
make it a little less sweet. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   THANKSGIVING (New York) _ In which our intrepid reporter
triumphs over adversity to produce roast turkey that tasted exactly
like her mother's. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The column: He was the Peter Pan and Ariel
of wine; a man who described one of his own commentaries as ``a
critique of pure riesling,'' and who advised on a label that ``this
wine will accommodate all manner of game and wild beasts, including
the sloth.'' No, Randall Grahm _ for who else could it be _ has not
left us. But he has gone, as they say in the land of carrot juice
and the flapping sandal, to another plane. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Paris) _ On the 1998 Beaujolais Nouveau.
</P>
<P>
   RICE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews ``Seductions
of Rice.''
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: On Thursday, with an
entire Thanksgiving meal marshaled and ready, countless cooks will
quake over the last detail: the gravy. When it's a once-a-year
thing, there are no guarantees that the gravy will come out
perfectly smooth, deeply flavored and nicely browned. There is an
alternative, though. And, unlike the various concoctions that come
out of a jar, it requires no apologies. It is a deglaze sauce, and
it is the most easy and malleable sauces a cook can make. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Cinnamon stars.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES (Undated) _ The column: Three sites that offer a
culinary tour of Asia; artisinal cheeses; etc.
</P>
<P>
   FATFREE-EATING-WELL (New York) _ Drew Nieporent's original
concept for the menu at the restaurant he is planning to open on
East 49th Street was true fat-free food. The chef he hired to
create the menu, Michel Nischan, tried to please. Eventually, he
conceded defeat. Thank goodness. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Food questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Living Section stories by early evening
with a ``d'' category code, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
