</P>
<P>
   My father's failure to predict the behavior of the market, or
even of a single stock, cannot be held against him, however I might
feel about now having to work for a living. Indeed, the question of
whether the prices of stocks, bonds and other financial commodities
can ever be predicted is one of the great scientific controversies
of our time.
</P>
<P>
   According to orthodox wisdom, financial markets go up and down
with no more predictability than a coin toss, and no amount of
historical knowledge, intuition, tips or analysis will tell you
with any certainty what will happen today, next month or next year.
</P>
<P>
   This paradigm goes by the name of the Efficient Market
Hypothesis (EMH) or the Random Walk Hypothesis, a name derived from
the suggestion that the price of a stock stumbles around a given
value like a drunk around a lamppost.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy rages because of the unavoidable implication of
the hypothesis: if it's true, then traders who make money
speculating in stock movements _ George Soros, for instance, or
Warren Buffett _ are neither brilliant nor intuitively gifted, but
only lucky.
</P>
<P>
   While researchers have collected scientific evidence supporting
the hypothesis, there is also copious evidence to the contrary _ in
particular, everyone who has ever made money in the market.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the last decade has seen a wave of scientists
migrating to Wall Street and applying powerful computers and
sophisticated mathematical tools to the stream of data pouring out
of the world's financial markets. And they have founded a handful
of companies _ Renaissance Technologies, for instance, run by
mathematician Jim Simons, or D. E. Shaw &AMP; Company, run by computer
scientist David Shaw _ that are doing remarkably well placing
wagers on the behavior of financial commodities.
</P>
<P>
   But why? According to the Efficient Market Hypothesis, the
activity of countless traders competing to buy and sell stocks at
what they think are their proper values forces the market to
instantaneously adjust the price of each stock to what it's really
worth.
</P>
<P>
   When the market moves in response to any relevant news or
information, so the theory goes, it will move so quickly that no
one will be able to make money reliably.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (the EMH) says is that the more people who try to
forecast markets, the less forecastable markets tend to be,''
explains Andrew Lo, a professor of finance at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But the Efficient Market Hypothesis, says Lo, comes with the
kind of paradox that offers scientists an opportunity to find a new
truth: If the market is truly efficient, then it leaves no
incentive for anyone to learn new information because they can't
possibly profit from it. But if no one is out there learning it,
then the information will never make it into the market to be
instantaneously absorbed. ``Clearly that's an absurd premise,''
says Lo.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, says Lo, is that the market is efficient, but not
instantaneously so. Small inefficiencies can exist long enough for
traders to take advantage of them, at which point they will be
competed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine out of ten times, the guy who says he can beat the market
is probably wrong, because he doesn't have anything new,'' Lo says.
``All he's observed is a statistical fluctuation, pure luck. But
every once in awhile somebody comes up with a genuinely new idea
for either forecasting the market or assessing information better,
or being able to put all the pieces together in a more
cost-efficient manner. He will make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Because every new technology also makes the market more
efficient, Lo explains, traders must continuously adapt to stay
ahead. They do it by developing or enlisting new technologies, most
of which come from various fields of scientific research: financial
engineering, mathematics, statistics, computer science.
</P>
<P>
   That's what David Shaw and Jim Simons have done. Both figured
out how to mathematically model the behavior of financial markets
so that a computer can predict the direction of stocks, currencies
or other financial commodities, at least for long enough that they
can bet on the knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But those predictions have to be thoroughly tested to make sure
they're based on reality and not luck. The advantage scientists
bring to the game, says Simons, is less their mathematical or
computational skills than their ability to think scientifically.
They are less likely to accept an apparent winning strategy that
might be a mere statistical fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just take a bunch of data and grind through it and
find patterns,'' Shaw says. ``Rather, we formulate hypotheses and
build up models of a lot of mechanisms that we believe are
operating out there. And then we validate those models in the same
way any scientist would. We will do experiments looking at
historical data, and in some cases we actually have to move large
amounts of money through the system and see what happens. In a
given experiment we might pump billions of dollars through the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   But this business of scientific trading, says Shaw, is not the
future of finance, because the efficient market will eventually
triumph. If everybody gets into the game, the game vanishes. Both
Shaw and Simons say that it's harder to find profitable
inefficiencies now than it was when they started.
</P>
<P>
   So when Shaw talks about the future of his business he sounds
less like a scientist and more like a Wall Street sage. The most
important people in finance are still those who make money the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people who can analyze companies,'' he says, ``who
understand what products the companies make: whether the chief
executive officer seems to be a good chief executive officer;
whether their business plan makes sense; whether it's a growth
industry or a shrinking industry; and so forth. Those are the kinds
of things we do not believe are amenable to mathematical or
computational analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Taubes, a contributing editor of Discover magazine, won
the 1997 Pan American Health Organization award for excellence in
international health reporting.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
