</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURING-HAWAII-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN HAWAII 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!''
PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES! Just
call (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796), and you'll automatically be
connected to a salesperson in your territory.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOCELYN FUJII &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When leaf-peeping northeasterners begin retiring their
binoculars for the year, Hawaii residents start dusting theirs off.
November opens the unofficial season of rubbernecking, a time when
migrating whales and big-wave riders turn the ocean into the site
of the islands' favorite spectator sports.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the economy and the weather, the humpback whales can be
counted on. They return in late November and stay until April or
May, breaching, spouting, mating and calving spectacularly in the
island waters that serve as their refuge from the icy ones they
have left behind in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   As for surfing, winter is its zenith, a time when ``pray for
surf'' is the prevailing mantra and waves aren't big unless they're
15 feet or higher. On the north shore of Oahu, the coastline
becomes theater: no wave is too large for the world's most daring
and accomplished surfers, who look like specks in the winter swell.
</P>
<P>
   These attractions are free, a considerable plus in a state
reeling with economic woes. The disappearance of Japanese
investment and the decline in tourism have come on the heels of
widespread plantation shutdowns, calling upon the adaptive spirit
of Hawaii's people.
</P>
<P>
   Attractive rates in hotel, air fare and travel packages can be
found in November and the first three weeks of December. In this
shoulder season (high season begins around Christmas and lasts
until mid-April), the islands are less crowded and the weather, as
in late spring, is at its best, averaging in the mid-70s _ although
several degrees warmer on the Kona-Kohala coast.
</P>
<P>
   With events from ``The Nutcracker'' to the Hawaii International
Film Festival, culture addicts, like surfers and luau aficionados,
have a full plate in the weeks to come.
 &UR; EVENTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Josef Albers, Sol Lewitt, Andy Warhol, Jasper Johns, Frank
Stella, Richard Diebenkorn, Roy Lichtenstein and Claes Oldenburg
are among the 40 artists represented in ``First Decade: Highlights
from the Contemporary Museum's Collection,'' which runs through
Jan. 3 at the Contemporary Museum, 2411 Makiki Heights Drive,
Honolulu. Robert Motherwell's ``Elegy With Rice Paper and Blue,''
from his series ``Elegies to the Spanish Republic,'' is among the
works not previously shown here.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is set in a garden in the hills overlooking the city.
Open Tuesday to Sunday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission: $5. (808)
526-0232.
</P>
<P>
   A storm in the Aleutians would be great news for big-wave riders
and spectators hoping for epic El Nino-generated surf at this
year's Vans G-Shock Triple Crown of Surfing Series, from Nov. 5
through Dec. 20 at Haleiwa Beach, Sunset, and Pipeline on Oahu's
North Shore. Top professional surfers will compete for $1 million
in men's and women's events. Free admission; (808) 637-6376 for
daily recorded information.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet Hawaii will present ``The Nutcracker'' Dec. 18 to 20 at
the Blaisdell Concert Hall, 777 Ward Ave., with guest artists from
the American Ballet Theater. Admission: $15 to $35; (808) 591-2211.
 &UR; SIGHTSEEING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good timing, powerful binoculars and quick reflexes (to pull
over if you're driving, or to drop whatever you're doing if you're
not) are useful when humpbacks appear, most reliably along the west
and south Maui shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Favorable vantage points along the west shore include Pap awai
Point, McGregor Point scenic overlook, Launiupoko State Wayside and
Wahikuli State Wayside; on the south shore, Wailea Beach Park and
the dining rooms of the deluxe Wailea resorts. On Oahu, Makapuu
Point, Waikiki and the Kaena Point Trail on the leeward coastline
can be center stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Whale Foundation, 101 North Kihei Road, supports its
research with daily whale-watching cruises beginning Dec. 1 on
Maui, $22 to $31; (800) 942-5311.
</P>
<P>
   At the Maui Ocean Center, a new five-acre marine park at 192
Maalaea Road, life-size whale models are part of the 60 exhibits.
Jaws drop during shark feeding and in the 54-foot walk-through
tunnel aquarium. Admission: $17.50, $12 for children; open daily 9
a.m. to 5 p.m., (808) 270-7000.
</P>
<P>
   Sections of a 22.5-mile network of ditches, flumes and tunnels
built in 1906 to irrigate sugar plantations have been transformed
into an easy, meandering waterway for kayaking.
</P>
<P>
   Guides with the Kohala Mountain Kayak Cruise explain the
region's history while gliding in the narrow outdoor flumes that
traverse rain forest and stands of wild ginger. Headquarters are in
Hawi, at the junction of Highways 270 and 250. Cost for the
75-minute paddle: $75, $55 ages 5 to 18; (808) 889-6922.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Lahaina Luau on Maui _ in moving to a larger oceanfront
site, 1251 Front St. in Lahaina six months ago _ has reinvented
itself authentically in a genre rife with cliche.
</P>
<P>
   At sunset, guests sit at tables or on lauhala fiber mats on the
ground in front of a grass-mound stage. The program offers
intelligent narration and excellent ancient hula (the absence of
fire dancing is noted but not lamented). There are no watered-down
mai tais and, like the atmosphere, the food is authentic Hawaiian,
and delicious. Admission: $65, $30 for children; (808) 667-1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Oahu, Pearl Harbor's newest resident, the 887-foot Missouri,
where Gen. Douglas MacArthur accepted Japan's surrender, is being
scrubbed, buffed and prepared for its opening in January as a
national memorial and museum. It is moored near the Arizona, sunk
during the Pearl Harbor attack. Guided tours will be $14; (808)
545-2263.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new Waimea Brewing Company, at Waimea Plantation Cottages,
9400 Kaumualii Highway, Waimea, may seem out of character in a
retro-historic plantation village, but in the dusty, dry plains of
this west Kauai town, there's something to be said for cold beer.
</P>
<P>
   The 48 authentic plantation cottages from the early 1900s were
moved from a nearby plantation and faithfully restored and equipped
with verandas and full kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   For those heading for the Waimea Canyon and Kokee State Park,
this is the last hostelry before the 4,000-foot ascent. Rates: $170
to $500; (808) 338-1625, fax (808) 338-2338.
</P>
<P>
   On the Hana coast in east Maui, a three-hour drive from Kahului
Airport, the once musty Heavenly Hana Inn, 4155 Hana Highway,
reopened in June behind its signature bamboo gate as a sleek,
stunning Japanese-style hostelry of three suites under one roof but
each with separate entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Lush gardens surround the studio and suites and the grand dining
room, featuring exotic woods and impressive craftsmanship. Rates:
$100 to $235; (808) 248-8442.
</P>
<P>
   Shipman House Bed and Breakfast Inn, 131 Kaiulani St., Hilo, on
the Big Island, won the 1998 Historic Preservation Award from the
Historic Hawaii Foundation. It recently completed the renovation of
its conservatory, which will serve as the meeting room in this
100-year-old Victorian mansion. Rates in the three rooms and a
guest cottage with two units are $130 to $150; (800) 627-8447, fax
(808) 934-8002.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Scarcely a year old, the Old Wailuku Inn at Ulupono,
2199 Kahookele Street, Wailuku, helps make central Maui a viable
destination on this shoreline-crazy island. Situated near Iao
Valley, the Hawaii Nature Center, a block of antiques shops, and
mom-and-pop restaurants, this two-story, seven-room inn, built in
1924, is filled with vintage Hawaiiana. Notable features include
the original ohia and eucalyptus floors. Rates: $120 to $180; (808)
244-5897, fax (808) 242-9600.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: With lava from an 1801 flow as its foundation, it was no
surprise that Hualalai Resort, Kaahumanu Highway, Kaupulehu, Kona,
on the Big Island, which contains the 243-room Four Seasons Resort
Hualalai, has added hot stone therapy to its spa offerings. Smooth
stream rocks are heated and placed on massage points.
</P>
<P>
   The low-rise, bungalow-style resort's educational programs for
guests, including celestial navigation, are firmly anchored in
Hawaiian culture. Room-car or room-breakfast packages are available
for $390 to $930; (808) 325-8000, fax (808) 325-8100.
</P>
<P>
   With all 191 guest rooms and three suites fully renovated last
fall, Kapalua Bay Hotel, 1 Bay Drive, Kapalua, Maui, has awakened
from a long slumber. Eco-tourists love the hiking and environmental
programs of the Kapalua Nature Society, based in this quietly
luxurious resort. Rates from $275; (800) 367-8000, fax (808)
669-4694.
 &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those expecting attitude at the newly opened Neiman Marcus
restaurant, Mariposa, 1450 Ala Moana Blvd., Honolulu, will be
pleasantly surprised _ efforts to integrate casualness with fine
dining have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Lanai seating offers great views of park and beach, and the
American and regional menu highlights local ingredients. The
excellent wine list (38 by the glass) has good prices. Dinner for
two with wine, about $80; (808) 951-3420.
</P>
<P>
   Hoku's at the Kahala Mandarin Oriental Hotel, 5000 Kahala Ave.,
Honolulu, has a new culinary team: executive chef Markus Greiner,
formerly of the Regent Hotel in Hong Kong, and executive sous-chef
Wayne Hirabayashi, formerly of the Halekulani Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   They have been luring new diners to the elegant ocean-view
dining room, and keeping the faithful, with favorites like grilled
misoyaki vegetables with taro gnocchi and deep-fried whole island
fish. Dinner for two with wine, $130; (808) 739-8777.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a stellar lobster season on the north shore of
Kauai, where Roadrunner Bakery and Cafe, 2430 Oka St., Kilauea,
also features organic local vegetables, 30 types of chilies, and
pork, fish and free-range chicken. Lobster fajitas ($16.95) and
tacos prove that lobsters can be fresh, good and cheap. Dinner for
two (bring your own wine) is about $35; (808) 828-8226.
</P>
<P>
   Sansei Seafood Restaurant and Sushi Bar, 115 Bay Drive, Kapalua,
Maui, has turned the formerly moribund Kapalua Shops into a
culinary hot spot. Dishes include Asian rock shrimp cake,
shrimp-nori ravioli and tradition-defying sushi with tangy sauces
and unorthodox pairings. Dinner for two with sake, about $50; (808)
669-6286.
</P>
<P>
   In whale-watching territory on the south shore, Nick's
Fishmarket Maui opened two months ago in the striking Kea Lani
Hotel, 4100 Wailea Alanui, Wailea. Fresh seafood includes succulent
Tristan lobster and elegant snapper in several preparations. Dinner
for two with wine, about $120; (808) 879-7224.
</P>
<P>
   (Jocelyn Fujii lives in Honolulu.)
 &UR; ---- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1998 Jocelyn Fujii &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
