fire dancing is noted but not lamented). There are no watered-down
mai tais and, like the atmosphere, the food is authentic Hawaiian,
and delicious. Admission: $65, $30 for children; (808) 667-1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Oahu, Pearl Harbor's newest resident, the 887-foot Missouri,
where Gen. Douglas MacArthur accepted Japan's surrender, is being
scrubbed, buffed and prepared for its opening in January as a
national memorial and museum. It is moored near the Arizona, sunk
during the Pearl Harbor attack. Guided tours will be $14; (808)
545-2263.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new Waimea Brewing Company, at Waimea Plantation Cottages,
9400 Kaumualii Highway, Waimea, may seem out of character in a
retro-historic plantation village, but in the dusty, dry plains of
this west Kauai town, there's something to be said for cold beer.
</P>
<P>
   The 48 authentic plantation cottages from the early 1900s were
moved from a nearby plantation and faithfully restored and equipped
with verandas and full kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   For those heading for the Waimea Canyon and Kokee State Park,
this is the last hostelry before the 4,000-foot ascent. Rates: $170
to $500; (808) 338-1625, fax (808) 338-2338.
</P>
<P>
   On the Hana coast in east Maui, a three-hour drive from Kahului
Airport, the once musty Heavenly Hana Inn, 4155 Hana Highway,
reopened in June behind its signature bamboo gate as a sleek,
stunning Japanese-style hostelry of three suites under one roof but
each with separate entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Lush gardens surround the studio and suites and the grand dining
room, featuring exotic woods and impressive craftsmanship. Rates:
$100 to $235; (808) 248-8442.
</P>
<P>
   Shipman House Bed and Breakfast Inn, 131 Kaiulani St., Hilo, on
the Big Island, won the 1998 Historic Preservation Award from the
Historic Hawaii Foundation. It recently completed the renovation of
its conservatory, which will serve as the meeting room in this
100-year-old Victorian mansion. Rates in the three rooms and a
guest cottage with two units are $130 to $150; (800) 627-8447, fax
(808) 934-8002.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Scarcely a year old, the Old Wailuku Inn at Ulupono,
2199 Kahookele Street, Wailuku, helps make central Maui a viable
destination on this shoreline-crazy island. Situated near Iao
Valley, the Hawaii Nature Center, a block of antiques shops, and
mom-and-pop restaurants, this two-story, seven-room inn, built in
1924, is filled with vintage Hawaiiana. Notable features include
the original ohia and eucalyptus floors. Rates: $120 to $180; (808)
244-5897, fax (808) 242-9600.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: With lava from an 1801 flow as its foundation, it was no
surprise that Hualalai Resort, Kaahumanu Highway, Kaupulehu, Kona,
on the Big Island, which contains the 243-room Four Seasons Resort
Hualalai, has added hot stone therapy to its spa offerings. Smooth
stream rocks are heated and placed on massage points.
</P>
<P>
   The low-rise, bungalow-style resort's educational programs for
guests, including celestial navigation, are firmly anchored in
Hawaiian culture. Room-car or room-breakfast packages are available
for $390 to $930; (808) 325-8000, fax (808) 325-8100.
</P>
<P>
   With all 191 guest rooms and three suites fully renovated last
fall, Kapalua Bay Hotel, 1 Bay Drive, Kapalua, Maui, has awakened
from a long slumber. Eco-tourists love the hiking and environmental
programs of the Kapalua Nature Society, based in this quietly
luxurious resort. Rates from $275; (800) 367-8000, fax (808)
669-4694.
 &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those expecting attitude at the newly opened Neiman Marcus
restaurant, Mariposa, 1450 Ala Moana Blvd., Honolulu, will be
pleasantly surprised _ efforts to integrate casualness with fine
dining have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Lanai seating offers great views of park and beach, and the
American and regional menu highlights local ingredients. The
excellent wine list (38 by the glass) has good prices. Dinner for
two with wine, about $80; (808) 951-3420.
</P>
<P>
   Hoku's at the Kahala Mandarin Oriental Hotel, 5000 Kahala Ave.,
Honolulu, has a new culinary team: executive chef Markus Greiner,
formerly of the Regent Hotel in Hong Kong, and executive sous-chef
Wayne Hirabayashi, formerly of the Halekulani Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   They have been luring new diners to the elegant ocean-view
dining room, and keeping the faithful, with favorites like grilled
misoyaki vegetables with taro gnocchi and deep-fried whole island
fish. Dinner for two with wine, $130; (808) 739-8777.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a stellar lobster season on the north shore of
Kauai, where Roadrunner Bakery and Cafe, 2430 Oka St., Kilauea,
also features organic local vegetables, 30 types of chilies, and
pork, fish and free-range chicken. Lobster fajitas ($16.95) and
tacos prove that lobsters can be fresh, good and cheap. Dinner for
two (bring your own wine) is about $35; (808) 828-8226.
</P>
<P>
   Sansei Seafood Restaurant and Sushi Bar, 115 Bay Drive, Kapalua,
Maui, has turned the formerly moribund Kapalua Shops into a
culinary hot spot. Dishes include Asian rock shrimp cake,
shrimp-nori ravioli and tradition-defying sushi with tangy sauces
and unorthodox pairings. Dinner for two with sake, about $50; (808)
669-6286.
</P>
<P>
   In whale-watching territory on the south shore, Nick's
Fishmarket Maui opened two months ago in the striking Kea Lani
Hotel, 4100 Wailea Alanui, Wailea. Fresh seafood includes succulent
Tristan lobster and elegant snapper in several preparations. Dinner
for two with wine, about $120; (808) 879-7224.
</P>
<P>
   (Jocelyn Fujii lives in Honolulu.)
 &UR; ---- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1998 Jocelyn Fujii &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
