</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAWL-SPACE VENTS MAY HAVE LOUVERS THAT CAN BE CLOSED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For Release Thursday, Nov. 26, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My newly-bought old summer house in the Berkshires has a 3
1/2-foot crawl space with a concrete-block foundation and three
vents. The vent closures are on the inside, and I am loathe to
crawl in there to close them. Can I cover them on the outside? They
seem to have several steel louvers behind the cast iron grille.
</P>
<P>
   KAY KILPATRICK, Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Look at those grilles a little more carefully; there should
be a handle at one side or the other or in the middle that you can
move to close the louvers. They may be rusted open, which will make
them virtually impossible to close. Actually, you should be able to
unscrew the grilles and pull the whole unit out in order to get the
louvers to move again. To do so, spray the louver connections and
all mechanical parts with WD40, then try to work them closed and
open.
</P>
<P>
   But you can also cover them from the outside: Tape a piece of
polyethylene plastic over them, or secure a pressure-treated board;
any thin board will do; an insulated cover is not necessary; the
cover is needed only to stop the flow of cold air through the
space. The vents should be covered in cold weather, say from
October to April.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I like the idea of using hard-faced ceiling tiles for my
bathroom; I can keep them clean and paint them when I feel like it.
But where can I find them? Home Depot was no help.
</P>
<P>
   C.T., Reading, mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I did mention such tiles, and had several inquiries from
callers who could not find them. I assumed they still existed
because I put them in my own bathroom several years ago. If the are
no longer made, it's a pity; they did yeoman service. So, your best
bet is to call Armstrong to determine if they exist and where you
can buy them. Call 717-397-0611.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The original white ceramic title in my 70-year old house is
in good shape, except it is crackled in the glaze. The crackle
lines are black, and no bleach or anything else will work for me. I
tried Tilex, straight bleach and acid, on separate occasions (I
never combnine these materials), all without success. What will
clean those crackle marks?
</P>
<P>
   JANE WEISS, Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Those crackle marks are called crazing, and you may have to
live with them. But as a final try, wash the floor with Soft Scrub
or Simple Green. Flow on either material and let it sit on the
floor for 15 minutes or even longer. Then scrub and rinse. If this
improves things, fine; if not, you can try KRC-7 Porcelain Cleaner,
sold in plumbing supply stores. Good for dirty grout, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. All my doors are flush and pretty plain. Where can I get
paneled doors?
</P>
<P>
   WALT ABRAMS, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Home Depot has a huge selection of all styles. So does
Brockway-Smith of Andover, Mass., a distributor of lots of wood
items. For the latter provider, you have to order them through a
lumber dealer. The lumber store will have a Brockway-Smith (Brosco)
catalog that will list dozens of styles.
</P>
<P>
   Paneled doors not only come in different styles, but different
construction. The popular and least expensive paneled door is a
formed hardboard that looks paneled. The real paneled door is a
solid frame with solid panels, and is more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something you might try without buying a new door,
and it will cost very little. Buy wood or plastic molding and mount
it on the face of the flush door in the shape of a penel. Molding
comes in many shapes and sizes; just make a choice. Such ``panels''
will be raised from the face of the door rather than indented as in
a regular paneled door, but they will add to the style of the door
and give the feeling of panels. You can make the panels any shape,
size or form; you are limited only by your imagination and the
shape of the molding. You can nail or glue the molding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My dining room ceiling is scrolled, and is peeling. I was
advised to apply a coat of BIN after scraping off the peeling
paint. But tht BIN is now peeling. What an I do to prevent peeling?
</P>
<P>
   ANNE HILTON, South Weymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. BIN is a good stain killer where needed but not much of
primer or sealer. Now you have to try to scrape and brush off the
peeling paint with a medium-stiff bristle brush. Those scrolled
ceilinsg are a pain when the paint peels because removing the paint
is difficult. With paint scraped, brushed or sanded off, wash the
ceiling with a strong solution of detergent and water, let dry.
</P>
<P>
   Apply a thin coat of a latex enamel undercoater; normally this
is not needed on plaster, but because of previous peeling, it is a
good idea, because such undercoaters stick to a lot of surfaces.
Then apply two thin coats of latex ceiling paint. Notice I suggest
thin coats; thick coats are much more likely to peel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
