<SLUG> BC-YOURMONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL FUTURES GAME ISN'T FOR AMATEURS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turkey and fruitcake aren't the only things you can expect at
this time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   There are the sales pitches on the radio and TV to invest in
heating oil futures. They go something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be long before cold weather is here. Heating oil
inventories are down and demand is up. There are warnings about
shortages already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the facts on how $5,000 properly positioned can return
$20,000 or more with just a 10-cent move in heating oil prices.''
</P>
<P>
   What you're hearing in the sales pitches is a deceptive
description of these risky markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that you can rush into the heating oil futures
market and make a fortune is a come-on,'' said Larry Norton,
associate enforcement director at the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, which regulates the trading of commodity futures and
options. ``Making a claim that you can profit based on well-known
events is fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WARM SPELL CAN COST YOU &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this pitch? Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   First off, the professionals trading futures contacts that
promise delivery of fuel oil during the coldest months of the year
know the price goes up. If the winter is warmer than expected,
you're going to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the ad makes profiting from futures contracts seem like
a sure thing. The reality is, the value of these contracts swings
wildly up and down, sometimes for reasons that seem to have little
to do with the real-world demand for the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   That matters a lot to an investor because the typical futures
contract allows the buyer to put down a relatively small amount of
money to buy a huge amount of fuel oil for future delivery. Every
penny change in fuel oil price has a much larger impact on the
value of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the pitches is that they suggest that the
person with the knowledge of the (oncoming) season has an
informational advantage over other people,'' said Dan Nathan,
deputy enforcement director at the CFTC. ``The problem is, we're
talking about instruments _ futures and options _ that are traded
in high volume on exchanges where everybody who trades them is
aware of the same information.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRADERS TRACK MARKET CLOSELY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the case of fuel oil, the futures markets are in New York and
London, but the players include experts from around the world,
including many oil company traders in Houston with the best
information on supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about professionals that basically follow the
commodities market, who play it daily,'' said Ray Seegmiller,
president and chief executive officer of Cabot Oil &AMP; Gas in
Houston. ``You have to know what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   They are all buying contracts giving them the right to buy or
sell a set amount during a certain time period. For instance, today
you could buy a contract giving you the right to buy 42,000 gallons
of fuel oil for around 35 cents a gallon. If the price rises, you
could profit from this trade by buying another contract to sell
42,000 gallons of fuel oil at a higher price. Your profit or loss
is the difference between the two prices, minus the commissions,
which can be steep.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are commissions and fees built into these
transactions,'' Nathan said. ``You start out with a little less
money upfront.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the risk of having the leverage of a futures
contract work against you. If the price of a commodity dips
sharply, you may be called on to put up more cash to comply with
rules that require people holding futures contracts to have cash
equal to a certain percentage of the value of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The sales pitch would make you think that a seasonal rise in
heating oil prices is a sure thing. The problem with that thinking
is that there's currently a huge glut of crude oil right now and
the price of fuel oil is depressed during a season where prices
normally are peaking.
</P>
<P>
   Profiting on a futures trade often means being able to follow
the market constantly because futures are about twice as volatile
as the benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index of large stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to beat the market, but for oil prices to run up
this year, it would likely need to be much colder than expected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
