<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-24 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISTERIA FROM SEED PROVES LENGTHY TASK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By Kathy Huber 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: On a trip to Dallas there were pods hanging all over my
daughter's beautiful wisteria. Inside the pods were beans, much
like pinto beans, only larger. I snapped some of the pods off the
plant and put them in the freezer several days later. Can I use
these beans to start a wisteria of my own?
</P>
<P>
   A: The problem is that wisteria grown from seed can take 10 to
15 years to bloom. You might try cuttings, instead, or propagation
by simple layering.
</P>
<P>
   To propagate by softwood cuttings: Cut 6-inch lengths from
young, green stems. Make the cuts just above leaf nodes. Remove the
leaves from the bottom portion of each cutting. Dip the bottoms
into rooting hormone, tap excess and insert each into a
well-draining soil mix. Moisten with a fine spray. Place the pots
with cuttings in clear plastic bags. Fill the bags with air so that
the sides don't touch the cuttings. You also can prop the plastic
with sticks. Keep a close eye on the soil moisture and keep the
cuttings in good light. The cuttings may root in one to two months.
</P>
<P>
   If you take cuttings in late spring, the cuttings may be ready
to plant in the fall. If you take them later, don't plant outside
until after the danger of frost.
</P>
<P>
   To propagate by layering: Choose a young, low-growing shoot on
the mother plant. Trim the leaves so that there is a good length of
stem without foliage behind the tip. Make an angled cut on the
underside of the shoot. Dust the cut with a rooting hormone. Peg
the shoot into the soil. Use a piece of wire or a stone. When roots
have formed, sever the layered shoot close to the mother plant.
Plant in a pot or permanent place.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have more than 50 amaryllis I planted from seeds. They are
2 years old and have outgrown their pots. Please tell me how to
transplant these.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can transplant each bulb to a slightly larger pot if you
wish to keep them as container plants. I don't know the size of
your plants, but it could be that a 2 or 3-inch clay or plastic pot
would be adequate. Plant high in a rich, well-draining potting
mixture with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. Protect against freezes.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Prasek, president of both local amaryllis societies,
says you also can transplant the amaryllis in the garden now,
preferrably to a sheltered area where the seedlings will receive
morning sun. Space the plants, Prasek again advises, about 4 inches
apart. You will need to space them further apart when the plants
are larger. A well-draining, sandy and slightly acidic soil is
best. Avoid a heavy soil. Mulch against freezes.
</P>
<P>
   Build garden seedlings, Prasek says, from below ground by using
a potassium product, preferrably one that is organic. Use one that
contains little or no nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Amaryllis grown from seed may bloom within three to four years.
Your new plants may not resemble parent plants if the latter are
hybrids, but it can be fun to just see what you get. Garden
amaryllis flower in the spring or early summer. Container amaryllis
can flower earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I planted spuria iris last fall, and this spring had lots of
green foliage but only one flower. They get identical culture as my
Louisiana iris (except they're in well-draining soil) _ and my
Louisianas are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Four o'clocks are beautiful in my neighborhood, and I would like
to transplant them into containers. Can I do it this fall, and can
I prune them without inflicting too much trauma?
</P>
<P>
   A: Give your spurias another spring or so to come around. I have
had to wait on various irises to flower. Spuria iris like sun, a
moist, neutral soil and excellent drainage. Fertilize in early fall
and again in late winter.
</P>
<P>
   Established four o'clocks (Mirabilis jalapa) can have huge
tuberous roots, so I'd look for smaller plants. Generally, these
plants are tough as stumps, and I wouldn't worry about trauma. I'd
think deep pots would be best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
