<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOOTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING THANKS FOR THE MEANING OF LIFE AND OTHER THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Thanksgiving is upon us.
</P>
<P>
   So Thursday, Americans will gather around their tables and
re-create the historic scene played out so many years ago between
pilgrims and Native Americans in Plymouth, Mass., when . . . or was
that a bunch of Englishmen along the shores of the James River in
Virginia? Or somebody in Florida? Texas? Maine, maybe?
</P>
<P>
   Depends upon whom you ask. According to a recent newspaper
story, the site of the first Thanksgiving is the subject of some
dispute, with several states vying for the honor. The competition
is so heated you'd think federal funds were involved.
</P>
<P>
   As a native Virginian, I'm of course tempted to go with that
state's claim. (Snooty Virginia joke: How many native Virginians
does it take to change a light bulb? One hundred. One to change it
and 99 to tell you how important the original, historic one was.)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the meaning of the holiday remains as strong
today as it did at the first Thanksgiving, lo those many years ago
back there in . . . wherever.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have much to be grateful for. So when you are
spilling cranberry sauce on the good tablecloth Thursday, don't
forget to give thanks for:
</P>
<P>
   - Time limits on congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   - College basketball.
</P>
<P>
   - Ahmad Rashad's forced vacation.
</P>
<P>
   - Snooze bars on alarm clocks. &QL; 
- The day in late September when the Arizona heat finally breaks
and the breeze blows and it doesn't feel like it's coming from an
oven. That sound you hear is an audible sigh of relief from the
entire Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   - The mute button on the TV remote during games called by Dick
Vitale, Matt Millen or Joe Thiesmann.
</P>
<P>
   - ``MASH'' reruns (Henry Blake episodes only).
</P>
<P>
   - ``Gadfly,'' ``Outside'' and ``Oxford American.''
</P>
<P>
   - The first five R.E.M. records.
</P>
<P>
   - Heartfelt compliments.
</P>
<P>
   - Allowing yourself to cry during ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   - A baby's first smile that isn't caused by gas pains.
</P>
<P>
   - Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   - Nike's NBA lock-out commercials.
</P>
<P>
   - Getting invited to Thanksgiving dinner at the home of someone
who can actually cook, saving you the depression of a fast-food
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   - Salt-and-vinegar potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   - Finding someone else who read and loved ``The Object of My
Affection.''
</P>
<P>
   - Homer J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   - A good, solid burp _ from your baby.
</P>
<P>
   - David Sedaris' ``Naked.'' &QL; 
- Watching the roof open on opening night at Bank One Ballpark in
Phoenix. Made everyone forget, for a moment, what all the fuss over
taxes was about. Very cool.
</P>
<P>
   - Epidurals.
</P>
<P>
   - No more campaign ads _ at least for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   - Episodes of the ``X-Files'' that make sense.
</P>
<P>
   - All-you-can-eat breakfast buffets.
</P>
<P>
   - Programming your CD player to play tracks 1, 10 and 3 _ in
that order _ from Crowded House's ``Temple of Low Men'' on a first
date.
</P>
<P>
   - The one decent golf shot in an afternoon of shanks that keeps
you coming back.
</P>
<P>
   - ``A Charlie Brown Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   - www.lileks.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Tom Wolfe's clothes. Wait, that's something (begin ital) not
(end ital) to be thankful for. Tom Wolfe's books, rather.
</P>
<P>
   - Guilty pleasures. (``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' is mine;
reflect upon your own.)
</P>
<P>
   - The moment of clarity achieved only at 3 a.m. when you are up
with your newborn and everyone else in the house _ heck, the
neighborhood, or maybe the entire city _ is asleep and the silence
is tactile and you suddenly realize just what your life is about.
You forget by morning, of course, but that doesn't matter. Be
thankful you at least knew once. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
