<SLUG> BC-FILM-RING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING REDEEMING IN SPRINGER'S FILM DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A disclaimer in the credits states ``Ringmaster'' is not
affiliated with Jerry Springer's successful afternoon talk show.
But ``Ringmaster,'' which is Springer's big screen grab at bigger
stardom, is about a TV host named Jerry Farrelly, who invites
``ordinary Americans'' to come on ``The Jerry Show,'' air their
dirty family laundry, engage in brawls and sit through penance as
Jerry (who has no qualifications as a therapist) analyzes their
actions. Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   It may not be affiliated, but it sure is based upon the
phenomenon that's recently challenged Oprah in the ratings. Jerry
is TV's new cultural wonder and now he's out to tackle the movies.
So what does that say about us?
</P>
<P>
   If ``Ringmaster'' is a marker, not much. This Jerry is a bland,
befuddled guy who is content to sit back and let things happen all
around him. He sits in on a lot of meetings, sleeps with an
unidentified babe with whom he's not in love (Rebecca Broussard),
and wanders through the station halls, seemingly in a stupor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his passiveness, Jerry moderates a major TV show. One
episode features 19-year-old sex bomb Angel (Jaime Pressly), her
mom Connie (Molly Hagan), stepdad Rusty (Michael Dudikoff), and
Angel's doormat of a fiance, Willie (Ashley Holbrook). Angel is
sleeping with Rusty, so Connie seduces Willie for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Other guests include Demond (Michael Jai White), his feisty
girlfriend Starletta (Wendy Raquel Robinson) and her two best
friends. It seems Demond has been sleeping with her pals and
Starletta wants to clear the air. When all parties meet in L.A. to
tape the show, Demond and Angel begin flirting. Rusty walks out and
Willie gets drunk. Secrets are revealed and sparks fly.
</P>
<P>
   It may momentarily (and guiltily) entertain as a curiosity
piece, but ``Ringmaster'' is a mess. When an audience member jumps
up and lambasts the lot for having trashy values, Jerry emerges
from his coma and springs to life. He defends his guests, calling
them ``great, decent, kind _ and poor.'' And suddenly
``Ringmaster'' becomes politically motivated, making a mission
statement about the show and its class appeal. But what it doesn't
say is though these folks believe they're finding their 15-minutes
of fame, they're really Jerry's pawns.
</P>
<P>
   The script makes stereotypes out of everyone it purports to
dignify and ultimately it reeks of double standards. Worse, it's
mean, sleazy and a self-promoting ego piece that only wants to fool
viewers into spending eight bucks at the box office. My advice is
save your dough and watch the TV show for free.
</P>
<P>
   Ringmaster. Directed by Neil Abramson. Written by Jon Bernstein.
Cast: Jerry Springer, Jamie Pressly, Molly Hagan, Michael Jai
White. Artisan Entertainment. 90 minutes. Rated R for language,
sexual content, nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: F
</P>
</TEXT>
