<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NewsQuestions26-COX-T     11-24 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NewsQuestions26-COX-TAKE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many people has Dr. Jack Kevorkian been accused of
assiting in their deaths?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kevorkian, back in the news after CBS' ``60 Minutes''
broadcast a videotape of a killing in which the famed
right-to-death advocate said he injected a terminally ill patient
with lethal drugs, has acknowledged helping about 120 people take
their own lives. Since 1990, when he began his assisted suicide
campaign, Kevorkian has been acquitted of assisted suicide charges
in three trials, and a fourth ended in a mistrial. The latest
incident, in which Kevorkian was shown apparently injecting former
accountant Thomas Youk, 52, on Sept. 17, differs from past cases
because Kevorkian had said before that his clients voluntarily
activated his homemade devices that delivered the carbon monoxide
or intravenous chemicals that caused their death. Michigan's new
assisted suicide law, which took effect Sept. 1, makes the practice
a felony subject to five years' imprisonment. Kevorkian said he
took the tape to ``60 Minutes'' so a national audience could see
it, and to challenge prosecutors to settle the debate over assisted
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was there a female pilot aboard the ValuJet plane that
crashed in the Everglades?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported after the May 11, 1996, crash of ValuJet Airlines
Flight 592, the aircraft was captained by Candalyn Kubeck and
co-piloted by Richard Hazen. Kubeck, who turned 35 the day before
the crash, was one of three female captains who flew for the young
airline. She had logged close to 9,000 hours of flight time,
including 2,073 hours with ValuJet. Friends said Kubeck, who was
born in California, developed her love of flying as a youngster.
All 110 people aboard died in the crash, which was caused by a fire
in the cargo hold that started when improperly stored oxygen
cannisters taken from another plane ignited. ValuJet shut down
after the crash, but later merged with Orlando-based AirTran to
form a new company operating under the AirTran name. Company
headquarters were moved from Atlanta to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the address for political strategist James Carville?
I want to write him.
</P>
<P>
   A: After the Democratic political guru helped organize Zell
Miller's successful bid for Georgia governor in 1989, Carville
moved on to the presidential campaign of Arkansas Gov. Bill
Clinton. Carville, who remains a chief defender of the president,
helped Democrats hone the issue of lotteries for education, which
Miller has used to gain national praise and two challengers used
Nov. 3 to unseat incumbent Republican governors in Alabama and
South Carolina. Carville runs his consulting business at 112 5th
Street S.E., Washington, D.C., 20003. The phone number there is
202-543-1196.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently watched ``Fatal Vision'' on TV, the story of Army
Capt. Jeffrey MacDonald, who was found guilty of murdering his
family. Whatever happened to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: MacDonald is still imprisoned in Oregon. He was found guilty
in 1979 and sentenced to three consecutive life terms for killing
his pregnant wife and two young daughters in 1970. Since his
conviction, the former Army surgeon has steadfastly maintained his
innocence, alleging that the murders in the family's Fort Bragg,
N.C., apartment were committed by a band of drugged-out intruders.
He was stationed at Bragg with a Green Beret unit. MacDonald was
convicted on the basis of a fiber-and-blood reconstruction of the
crime, because there were no witnesses and no definite motive could
be established. ``Fatal Vision'' was a best-selling book
subsequently dramatized on television. MacDonald has made three
bids for a new trial, but each has failed. At last report, his
attorneys were pursuing a new strategy, seeking government evidence
for DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the year 2000 considered a leap year? I've read that some
years divisible by four are leap years, but some are not.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, 2000 will be a leap year, and will have a Feb. 29. A
leap year occurs in every year that can be evenly divided by four,
except the years that mark the even hundreds, such as 1500. The
only century years that are leap years are those that can be
divided by 400, such as 1600 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A newspaper article said race car driver Jeff Gordon earned
$6.1 million in 1998. Is that for him individually, or for his
team?
</P>
<P>
   A: His team. What Gordon receives out of the $6.1 million
depends on the contracts between him and the owner of his car, a
NASCAR spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The recently reported discovery of evidence of a fish-eating
dinosaur, Suchomimus tenerensis, was exciting news. I know
tenerensis must pertain to the Tenere Desert in Niger, where the
fossil was found, but what does Suchomimus come from? Also, how is
it pronounced?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both words taken together mean ``crocodile mimic from the
Tenere'' region of Niger in West Africa. ``Sucho'' is Greek for
crocodile, said Mark Norell, dinosaur specialist at the American
Museum of Natural History in New York, and ``mimus'' is the Latin
root word for mimic. The word is pronounced sook-oh-my-mus.
</P>
<P>
   The crocodile aspect was particularly fascinating to the
international team digging in the remote part of the Sahara. ``It
was a dinosaur trying hard to be a crocodile,'' University of
Chicago paleontologist Paul Sereno, who led the expedition, told
The New York Times. The ``crocodile mimic'' reference comes from
the peculiar reptile's most distinctive characteristic: its
4-foot-long skull. The snout was particularly long and narrow, much
like a crocodile's.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists emphasized, however, that the appearance of the
Suchomimus snout shouldn't be interpreted as evidence of a close
evolutionary relationship between crocodiles and these dinosaurs.
University of Maryland paleontologist Thomas Holtz Jr. suggested in
the journal Science that the crocodilian aspects of the skull may
have arisen ``as adaptions'' toward a diet that included fish as
well as other animals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's reported that Britain has become the first European
Union country to ban the use of animals for testing in cosmetic
products. Is there a way for people in the United States to get a
list of all companies that use animals to test their cosmetics?
</P>
<P>
   A: The best source for such information is the organization
People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals. PETA's Susan Rayfield
says you can request a list of companies that say they don't test
on animals by writing to PETA, 501 Front St., Norfolk, VA 23510; or
calling 757-622-7382 and asking for the literature department,
which will mail a free guide. Internet users can check PETA's home
page _ http://www.peta-online.org _ and, under Action Alerts, click
on Consumer Products Companies That Do and Don't Test on Animals _
for additional information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of the B-2 bomber? It's never mentioned in
news reports about all the different types of armament used when
the U.S. military is deployed overseas, such as B-52 bombers and
Stealth fighters.
</P>
<P>
   A: Training missions for the B-2 Spirit were suspended
temporarily in August because of problems with the aircraft's crew
ejection system, but the planes now are ``combat ready, able and
willing'' to be deployed when required, Air Force spokesman Maj.
Tyrone Woodyard told Q&AMP;A. Although they're ``active'' at Whiteman
Air Force Base in Missouri, he said the bombers aren't involved in
combat operations at present ``because the United States hasn't had
a need for such combat operations since the Gulf War.'' The B-2
Spirits were deployed recently in Guam as part of a ``global power
mission,'' Woodyard added, to show their ability to deliver
long-range conventional bombs. Internet users can find current
information about B-2s at http://www.af.mil _ the Air Force's home
page.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have several questions relating to the NBA strike. What is
the average player salary? How does it compare with the average
salary 10 or 20 years ago? Do players get a fixed extra amount when
away from home for hotel accommodations and meals? In a nonstrike
year, how long is the season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Last season's average salary was $2.6 million. In 1977-78 it
was $139,000, according to the NBA, and in 1987-88 it was $510,000.
When they're traveling, the players receive a per-diem allowance
for meals and other expenses, with the amount varying from player
to player. An NBA spokesman said he had no information on specific
dollar amounts or averages. The players don't pay for their hotel
rooms, he added. The regular season usually begins in early
November and runs through mid-to-late April. The playoffs extend
into June.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
