<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NewsQuestions26-COX-T     11-24 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NewsQuestions26-COX-TAKE2 </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the plan for the stock market to switch
from fractions to decimals in price quotations?
</P>
<P>
   A: The New York Stock Exchange announced in June 1997 that it
planned to switch to decimal pricing as soon as the securities
industry was ready. According to a report released by the General
Accounting Office, the industry will be prepared in the year 2000.
The NYSE's operations advisory committee has recommended that the
conversion take place in September 2000, as have all national
securities markets and the Securities Industry Association. The
NYSE, meanwhile, says it has been preparing its systems for the
conversion and will be decimal-ready by the end of 1998. The reason
the industrywide switch is being delayed, according to the GAO, is
that most available information-technology resources are being
dedicated to the year 2000 problem and the switch to a single
European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Big Game advertisements indicate there are eight ways to win.
Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: A $1 play actually offers nine ways to win the Big Game, says
Parquita Nassau of the Georgia Lottery Corp.: (1) the
multimillion-dollar jackpot, for matching five of five white balls
and the Big Money ball; (2) $150,000, five white balls without the
Big Money ball; (3) $5,000, four white balls with the Big Money
ball; (4) $150, four white balls without the Big Money ball; (5)
$100, three white balls with the Big Money ball; (6) $5, three
white balls without the Big Money ball; (7) $5, two white balls
with the Big Money ball; (8) $2, one white ball with the Big Money
ball; and (9) $1, only the Big Money ball.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will Paula Jones have to pay tax on the $850,000 settlement
she is receiving from President Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A: The IRS declined to respond to this specific case, citing
instead its regulations governing court awards and damages in
general, and damages received for nonphysical injuries and
sickness. Taxable income would include, among other things, amounts
received as punitive damages; damages for nonphysical injuries or
sickness; and interest on any award. Compensatory damages not
considered taxable income would include, among other things, awards
for personal physical injury, alientation of affection and ``damage
to your character.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently watched several football games on TV sponsored by
the U.S. Postal Service. And now the new rate-increase stamps have
gone on sale. Is that sponsorship of sports events on TV what we're
paying for with the higher rates?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Postal Service defends its advertising during televised
football games and in various other events and media as a way to
keep customers informed about their choices in a highly competitive
business. Advertising is ``one of the techniques any business uses
to promote its products and to ensure the kind of volume we need to
be effective,'' said Postal Service spokesman Norman Scherstrom in
Washington. Advertising helps customers make the best buying
decisions possible, he added, saying that people wouldn't know all
the options available to them without it.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase, scheduled to take effect Jan. 10, is the
first in more than four years, Scherstrom emphasized, and
represents only a 2.9 percent increase during a period when
cumulative inflation has been more than 7 percent. He also pointed
out that advertising maximizes the use of the mail, and the more
volume there is, the lower the cost per item delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much does Earth weigh?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is one of those questions that physics experts and
mathematicians love to debate, because weight has an implied
meaning of pounds or tons with respect to Earth. Weight is related
to both mass and gravity. As a scientist explained, the ``weight''
of Earth with respect to Earth is zero, since the vector sums of
all the particles of Earth would cancel each other out. This
probably isn't what you mean, however. If you mean the Earth's
mass, it's 6 sextillion, 588 quintillion short tons (about 6
sextillion metric tons).
</P>
<P>
   Q: While vacationing in Orlando, I bought two Florida lottery
tickets. I tried calling 1-900-737-7777 to get the winning numbers,
but couldn't get through. Is there any other way to find out?
</P>
<P>
   A. The information is available online at the Florida Lottery's
home page
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.flalottery.com _ by clicking on Previous Winning
Numbers under the heading for each game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the last name of England's royal family?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was changed officially in 1917 from Saxe-Coburg Gotha to
Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it known how President Clinton is going to pay the
recently announced $850,000 settlement to Paula Jones, on top of
his other legal expenses?
</P>
<P>
   A: White House advisers said they hoped the $850,000 would be
covered by the president's personal insurance policies, according
to a report in The New York Times. But if the two companies that
have insured the president decline to pay, the money would come
from the president's legal defense fund. That fund reportedly has a
balance of more than $2 million. Hillary Rodham Clinton had been
worried that a settlement in the Jones case might make too big a
dent in the defense fund, according to the Times, but the Clintons'
fund-raisers assured her that they could easily replenish any money
used toward a Jones settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative watchdog organization Judicial Watch,
meanwhile, is challenging the legality of the Jones settlement,
saying it would be implemented using ``illegally obtained monies.''
According to Judicial Watch, it's illegal for any federal official
``to solicit, accept or benefit from monies from private
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When does the rate hike for postage stamps go into effect?
</P>
<P>
   A: The basic 32-cent rate goes up by a penny Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that President Clinton has again exercised his authority
in Iraq as commander in chief of the military, can't he be charged
with adultery under the Code of Military Justice?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. As previously reported, this issue was addressed in
September by Defense Secretary William Cohen, who said that even
though the president is commander in chief, he's a civilian, and
therefore doesn't have to follow military rules prohibiting
adultery. Cohen was explaining how the president's case differs
from that of Kelly Flinn, the nation's first female B-52 pilot and
a first lieutenant, who resigned from the Air Force last year
rather than face a court-martial on charges of adultery, lying and
disobeying an order. So the latest Iraq situation, or any future
one involving Clinton's role in the military, won't change that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Robert Novak's professional background?
</P>
<P>
   A: The newspaper columnist and TV commentator, who was born in
1931 in Joliet, Ill., worked first as a reporter for the Joliet
(Ill.) Herald-News between 1947 and 1951.
</P>
<P>
   After that, these have been his career moves: Champaign-Urbana
(Ill.) Courier, 1951-52; Associated Press, in Omaha and Lincoln,
Neb., Indianapolis, and Washington, 1954-58; Wall Street Journal,
Washington, 1958-63; syndicated columnist, New York Herald Tribune,
Washington, 1963-66; commentator, Corinthian Broadcasting,
Washington, 1963-65; Metromedia, Washington, 1966-76; RKO-Features,
Washington, 1976-78; syndicated columnist, Chicago Sun-Times,
Washington, 1966 to present; commentator, CNN, Washington, 1980 to
present; National Empowerment TV, 1993 to present; publisher,
Evans-Novak Political Report, Washington, 1967 to present,
Evans-Novak Tax Report, Washington, 1985-92, and Evans-Novak Japan
Report, Washington, 1989-92; and roving editor, Readers Digest,
1979 to present.
</P>
<P>
   Novak is the author (with Rowland Evans) of ``The Agony of the
GOP,'' 1965; ``Lyndon B. Johnson: The Exercise of Power,'' 1967;
``Nixon in the White House,'' 1971; and ``The Reagan Revolution,''
1981.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
