<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MAURICE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MAURICE, OR THE FISHER'S COT
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Mary Shelley.
</P>
<P>
   Edited, with an introduction, by Claire Tomalin.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 179 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $20.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; HAPPILY EVER AFTER? &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA WARNER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After Rousseau decreed in ``Emile'' that fantasy and fairy tales
were dangerous, pedagogic reformers and children's publishers tried
to provide, instead of ``bloods'' and ``romances,'' rational
instruction in history, nature and geography. Mary Shelley's
father, William Godwin, pioneered this gentling of traditional
material with his Juvenile Library, and her 1820 story, ``Maurice,
or The Fisher's Cot,'' resembles his progressive nursery fare: it's
a classic fairy tale about a foundling restored to family and high
social status. But in Godwinian mode, Shelley updates it to
contemporary England, adding reformist social color and improving
touches.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice hasn't been stolen from his cradle by fairies but has
been snatched from his nanny by a desperate woman whose husband
beat her for her childlessness. When Maurice, a beautiful, delicate
child in the image of the young Percy Bysshe Shelley, grows up
sickly and frail, he too falls victim to his usurping stepfather's
violence. No maltreatment damages his radiant nature, however. He
leaves home and is taken in by an upstanding, poverty-stricken
fisherman and his wife. The couple embody rustic virtue; she
teaches children to read from the Bible and refuses payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maurice'' was written for Laurette, a girl of 10, and the
story's way of telling reveals that Mary Shelley was aware that her
reader was an English child who had never been ``home'' and whose
natal tongue was Italian: it's plainly written, and contains scenes
of the southern English coast and customs and the kinds of lichen,
moss and damp-loving plants that grow there. But the success story
lacks energy, its impact dulled by the melancholy that, as Claire
Tomalin observes in her introduction, undoes its Panglossian
optimism. It opens with the fisherman's funeral and ``finishes with
the crumbling away'' of his seaside cottage (the ``cot''). In a
Wordsworthian mood, Shelley seems to be lamenting that this kind of
probity will not be seen in modern times again.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Maurice'' echoes Godwin's own genial pedantry, he
turned it down, writing that it was too short. This was probably
diplomatic on his part. Although interest in Mary Shelley warrants
publication, it's clear that when news came of a lost manuscript,
stored in the Tuscan house of direct descendants of a family with
close links to the Shelleys, something rather more was hoped for.
``Maurice'' is a slight piece; it contains little of the seething
originality, moral complexity or sinister Gothic speculativeness of
``Frankenstein,'' written only four years before, and Tomalin, as
if in tacit acknowledgment of the story's shortcomings, digs deep
into the social background, where many fascinating specters gather.
</P>
<P>
   Laurette was the illegitimate daughter of Margaret, Countess
Mountcashell, and an Anglo-Irish gentleman-adventurer, George
Tighe. This household of adulterous expatriates presented in many
ways a mirror image of the Shelleys: after the poet's first wife,
Harriet, killed herself, he was denied access to their two
children; Lady Mountcashell had also been parted from her eight
previous, legitimate offspring. Meanwhile, three of Mary's infants
had died. Against this terrible background of severance and loss,
Mary Shelley's optimistic story becomes much more than a family
romance; when she imagines a boy who resists illness, cruelty and
poverty so well that he actually succeeds in growing up, she may be
uttering a wistful charm against the fate that dogged her.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Tomalin, whose main interest here lies in the biographies
of the tangled background cast, has unearthed much new material
about Laurette, her sister, Nerina, and their mother, whose lives
offer a rich and unfamiliar tapestry of women's troubles and
achievements in the turbulence of 19th-century Italy. But she can't
quite conceal her disappointment that Laurette, later a
professional, much-published author, never wrote anything worth
reading.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 10, Mary Shelley had adapted a jaunty vaudeville
song into a children's rhyme, ``Mounseer Nongtongpaw,'' which makes
spirited fun of English bigotry and greed. Godwin published it, the
first work of his prodigious child. The patient, gloomy ``Maurice''
confirms that the visionary writer of ``Frankenstein,'' the
brilliant daughter and wife of notorious firebrands, dreamed of a
quiet and simple existence. Maurice's mysterious benefactor, who
turns out to be his long-lost father, holds out ``the pleasure of
living in the country, of seeing the pretty flowers grow in the
hedges . . . and in the evening to read entertaining books.'' Like
the monster who looks in the window of the blind man's cottage at
the ideal scene round a peaceful hearth, Mary Shelley in
``Maurice'' communicates how much she hankered after an ordinary
life in England, how her elopement sentenced her to a perpetual
homesickness.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Marina Warner's most recent book is ``From the Beast to the
Blonde: On Fairy Tales and Their Tellers.'' Her study of fear, ``No
Go the Bogeyman,'' will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
