<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     11-24 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FREEDOM TO DIE
</P>
<P>
   People, Politics and
</P>
<P>
   the Right-to-Die Movement.
</P>
<P>
   By Derek Humphry and Mary Clement.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's, $24.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, my friend Lynne chose to die. She was losing
her battle with Lou Gehrig's disease and did not want to spend what
was left of her life hooked up to a respirator. She told her family
and her doctors: ``I would rather have a gentle, dignified death
than this unbearable, humiliating life. I want you to help me
die.'' According to Derek Humphry, co-author with Mary Clement of
``Freedom to Die,'' polls show that 63 percent to 78 percent of
Americans share Lynne's sentiments -- that people who are
terminally ill, and experiencing unbearable pain and suffering,
should be permitted to end their lives with the help of their
physicians. However, physician-assisted suicide and voluntary
euthanasia are issues that force uneasy confrontation with
religious beliefs, ethics, economic realities and medical
responsibility. ``Freedom to Die'' chronicles the right-to-die
movement from the first, unsuccessful euthanasia bill drafted in
Ohio in 1906 to the first two people who received their physicians'
help to die in 1998 as a result of the Oregon Death With Dignity
Act. To their credit, the authors -- Humphry is the founder of the
Hemlock Society; Clement is president of something called Gentle
Closure, ``an organization that assists people in addressing all
end-of-life concerns'' -- reach for balance. They demonstrate
effectively, albeit with frustrating repetition, what happens when
the sentiments of the public collide with religious, medical or
governmental institutions. They present trenchant arguments on both
sides of the debate and examine the influence of Dr. Jack
Kevorkian, the pivotal role of Karen Ann Quinlan, the impact of
high-tech miracles of science that keep people alive but
nonfunctional and the fear that family members will not give their
dying relatives a ``duty-to-die'' message. This book challenges our
thinking about a subject that is far more complex than simply
granting someone his ``ultimate civil liberty.'' _ GLORIA HOCHMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF MARTIN LUTHER KING, JR.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Clayborne Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the tragedies of Martin Luther King Jr.'s life is that he
did not live to write an autobiography. That sad truth diminishes
the value of ``The Autobiography of Martin Luther King, Jr.,''
Clayborne Carson's mistitled but otherwise worthy compilation of
King's autobiographical writings and statements. Carson has done a
good job of selecting letters, news interviews, an ``Autobiography
of Religious Development'' in manuscript and other documents
scattered in various archives and in the 14 volumes of the Martin
Luther King Jr. Papers Project, which Carson directs. For example,
a chapter on King's arrest at an Atlanta lunch counter
demonstration during the 1960 Presidential campaign combines King's
taped interview for the John F. Kennedy Presidential Library with
his statement to a judge rejecting release on bail, a letter to his
wife, Coretta, describing his incarceration at Georgia's Reidsville
Prison and a three-paragraph box ``On Richard Nixon'' from a letter
written in 1958. Each chapter includes a helpful chronology of the
events covered, and an opening sentence or two of King's that
defines the principle or significance of what follows. What is
missing, of course, is the cohesive narrative and balanced
perspective of a true autobiography. But this book is a valuable
reminder that on those subjects and occasions when he could not
have borrowed his words, King was consistently eloquent and
polished, a master of word and effect, possessed of a voice that
was unmistakable and true. _ DAVID WALTON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMPTY WITHOUT YOU
</P>
<P>
   The Intimate Letters of
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Roosevelt and Lorena Hickok.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Rodger Streitmatter.
</P>
<P>
   Free Press, $25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Historians began debating Eleanor Roosevelt's sexual orientation
in 1978, 16 years after her death, when her husband's Presidential
library opened the correspondence deeded it by Lorena Hickok, Mrs.
Roosevelt's unofficial adviser, vacation companion and ``first
friend.'' The two women became close in 1932 when Hickok, a
reporter for The Associated Press, began covering Franklin D.
Roosevelt's Presidential campaign. Soon thereafter, the new First
Lady procured her a job as chief investigator of the nation's
relief programs. It was then, while Hickok traveled for months at a
time, that the women engaged in an intense correspondence that
continued for 29 years. In ``Empty Without You,'' Rodger
Streitmatter, a journalism professor at American University,
presents the first collection of that correspondence, reproducing
more than 300 of the 3,500 letters that were preserved. While many
of the selections describe each woman's physical and emotional
longing for the other, the reader expecting a titillating chronicle
of a forbidden lesbian love affair will be disappointed; what
evidence there is that one took place is relatively restrained in
tone. Streitmatter's frequent editorial comments are hit-or-miss:
those that highlight Hickok's critical role in encouraging the
reluctant Eleanor Roosevelt to use the press to advance her own
social and political agenda are well placed, while those that
merely highlight the sensual passages add little that cannot be
gleaned from the text. Although this collection does not
definitively answer the question of whether Roosevelt and Hickok
had an affair, it does document the American landscape as seen by
two intelligent, influential women who loved their country, and
each other, with a passion that is rare. _ JOHANNA BERKMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE LOVE OF THE GAME
</P>
<P>
   My Story.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Crown, $50. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, the ultimate corporate sports star, has taken a
page from Dennis Rodman, the ultimate renegade sports star. In his
lavish picture-book autobiography, Jordan borrows the visual tics
Rodman employed in his books: garish graphics, disconnected text
with POINTLESS CAPITALIZATIONS, narcissistic self-absorption
(though Jordan lacks Rodman's saving sense of self-mockery). In
``For the Love of the Game,'' Jordan settles scores with former
teammates, coaches and franchise officials of the Chicago Bulls,
and explains why the most transcendent presence ever to grace a
basketball court happened to have the initials M.J. His legions of
fans will doubtless be grateful for this chance to share in
Jordan's early Christmas present to himself. _ MICHAEL ANDERSON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EROTIC LIVES OF WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   By Linda Troeller and Marion Schneider
</P>
<P>
   Scalo, $45 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Female sexual passion is often portrayed as sophomoric romance
or as the ecstasy following a high-end shopping spree. The Erotic
Lives of Women is different, and should be honored as one of the
most gutsy and imaginative erotic books of the decade. Linda
Troeller, an American photographer, and Marion Schneider, a German
writer, photographed and interviewed 30 women from the Americas,
Europe, the Middle East and Northern Africa. They include a
Brazilian singer, a Japanese-American flower designer, a black
American legal secretary, Islamic housewives and Moroccan belly
dancers. None of these women are model look-alikes, but each is
irrefutably seductive in her story and image. The honesty in the
interviews is extraordinary. The kinds of excuses, politically
correct slogans and gauzy fuzz that frequently suffocate erotic
candor are simply not here. The women tell their stories straight
out, and leave it to you to be aroused, disturbed or enlightened.
The photographs and the interviews were done at the same time, to
create a match between image and text, and the experiment proves to
be unexpected and moving. One woman, Nadia, a 36-year-old cigarette
vendor in Morocco, answered: ``Living by myself, earning my own
money, that is most erotic for me. . . . Being able to smoke
cigarettes wherever I like to and to smoke hashish when I feel like
it gives me such a strong feeling.'' She is depicted spreading
apart her djellaba like a pair of wings. _ SUSIE BRIGHT
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
