<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7249 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     11-24 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
 BY SCOTT VEALE
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CALIFORNIA'S OVER
</P>
<P>
   By Louis B. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Contemporaries, $13. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In detailing the narcissistic foibles of a hippie family in the
1970s, this novel strives to capture the era's hypersincerity and
inflated sense of destiny. The result is ``a satirical elegy for
the age of dime-store Zen,'' Walter Kirn said here last year. ``The
book is as light and swirly and eccentric as its Marin County
setting.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY NAME ESCAPES ME:
</P>
<P>
   The Diary of a Retiring Actor
</P>
<P>
   By Alec Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, $12.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Judging from this lively journal undertaken at the age of 80,
the versatile and idiosyncratic actor still has plenty to say. He
holds forth in charming and humorous fashion on everything from the
English weather to politics to his warm friendships with pets and
humans, not to mention the performances of other actors. Through it
all, ``Guinness remains pungently human, warts and all,'' John
Simon wrote in the Book Review in 1997. ``Sir Alec is an
accomplished writer, both in extended passages and in finely
etched, memory-hugging one-liners.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOB THE GAMBLER
</P>
<P>
   By Frederick Barthelme.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This novel focuses on the effects of compulsive gambling on a
family that wagers its comfortable life style on a chance to escape
the banality of middle-class existence. ``It is Barthelme's
peculiar post-modern gift to be able to invert the easy ironies of
contemporary life and reveal the truths beneath them,'' A. O. Scott
said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN: A REINTERPRETATION
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage, $14. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A journalist punctures the postwar myth of a single-minded Japan
Inc., content with conformity and dependency on the West, and
instead finds a troubled society struggling to reinvent itself in
the absence of any meaningful democracy. Last year our reviewer,
Frank Gibney, called this ``a stimulating, provocative book.''
 &UR; GEISHA, by Liza Crihfield Dalby (University of California,
$17.95) &LR; , tells of an American doctoral candidate who traveled to
Japan in the mid-1970s to study the female entertainers known as
geisha and wound up working as one. Her account, which has been
reissued with a new preface, is marked by ``delicate observation
and subtle common sense,'' Donald Rich wrote here in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SKY, THE STARS, THE WILDERNESS
</P>
<P>
   By Rick Bass.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These three novellas cover a lot of ground -- from Canada to
Mississippi -- but they share a precise observation of nature that
is both unsentimental and ecstatic. ``Reading this book has made me
glad . . . that there are still writers who can bring the
wilderness back alive and pin it to the page,'' Michael Gorra said
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BOOK OF MEMORIES
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Nadas. Translated by Ivan Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, $14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This large, philosophically complex Hungarian novel transposes
two elaborately linked Proustian narratives of consciousness to the
universe of Communist East Berlin and Budapest. ``The terrain of
Eastern European experience . . . gains an amplitude and an
illumination from the painstaking attentiveness, the penetration
with which it is imagined and contemplated,'' Eva Hoffman wrote
here last year.  &UR; THE LAND OF GREEN PLUMS, by Herta Muller,
translated from the German by Michael Hofmann (Hydra
Books/Northwestern University, $14.95) &LR; , is a grim novel about a
group of young Romanians persecuted as dissidents during the
dictatorship of Nicolae Ceausescu. ``Muller's vision . . . reads
like a kind of fairy tale on the mingled evils of gluttony,
stupidity and brutality,'' Larry Wolff wrote here in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOO-DAH!
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Foster and the Rise of American Popular Culture
</P>
<P>
   By Ken Emerson. Da Capo, $16.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The creator of ``Oh! Susanna,'' ``Camptown Races'' and other
enduring tunes from the 1800s was the first American songwriter to
achieve artistic independence from Europe. This is ``a vigorous,
thoroughly researched, amiably chatty tour through his life and
times,'' Margo Jefferson wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   cThoreau and nine other writers, a humanities professor argues
that the best American writing reflects political values in line
with those of liberal democracy. ``Delbanco's essays are
effortlessly erudite and smoothly readable,'' Jonathan Rosen said
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PR! A SOCIAL HISTORY OF SPIN
</P>
<P>
   By Stuart Ewen.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Books, $17. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In tracing the evolution of public relations, the author shows
how the hype machine has persuaded Americans to buy everything from
new cars to new wars, and how it has undermined our political
discourse. Last year in these pages, Judith Newman called this an
``exhaustive and ambitious study.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WONDER WORKER
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Howatch.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett Columbine, $14. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A young woman's obsession with the charismatic leader of a
London parish sets off a chain of events that includes a possible
murder and a suicide. Last year our reviewer, Betsy Groban, said
that despite its implausible ending, this is ``an absorbing
novel.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
