</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BEACH-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 AMERICAN BEACH
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Saga of Race, Wealth, and Memory.
</P>
<P>
   By Russ Rymer.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 337 pp. New York: HarperCollins Publishers. $25. &QL; 
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; DISINTEGRATION &QL; 
 &UR; By EDDY L. HARRIS &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the day I picked up ``American Beach,'' I was
stopped by a policeman who had no better reason than the few miles
an hour -- I think six -- by which I was exceeding Rhode Island's
highway speed limit. He was within his rights of course to stop me,
but he also wanted to search my car for drugs, and when I refused
him permission to look inside my trunk, he threatened to detain me
at the side of the road for a couple of hours while he sent for the
drug-sniffing dogs. It was, after all, as he made clear, his
highway and he could do anything he damn well pleased.
</P>
<P>
   And if I'd had a chip on my shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   And if I had reacted with a misunderstood gesture instead of
with words.
</P>
<P>
   Or if I had tried to drive away.
</P>
<P>
   These things happen, and in his new book, ``American Beach,''
Russ Rymer tells the story -- among other stories involving race
and power and politics -- of just such an incident.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wilson, on the eve of his 33rd birthday, was stopped by
the police not far from American Beach, a resort town in northern
Florida. He had not been speeding. He had been driving slowly and
had pulled off the road in order to let the police car that had
been following him pass. A little later on, he caught up with that
same police car, which now had pulled over to let him pass. The
policemen followed Wilson, waited for him to make a turn, then
switched on the blue lights of the police cruiser and nabbed him
because the left turn had not been textbook proper.
</P>
<P>
   The police dispatcher told one of the officers that there was a
warrant out for Wilson on a charge of resisting arrest with
violence, a felony. In fact, Wilson had answered a warrant a week
earlier -- for resisting arrest without violence -- but a clerk had
incorrectly entered the information into the police computer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had had problems with local authorities before; he had an
arrest record, and he was known even to his friends as
``hair-triggered.'' He had once been beaten severely by police
officers, and had won a lawsuit against them, earning a reputation
in the county as an agitator. And this was a county not known for
its kind treatment of blacks. He may have smelled a setup, and he
started to drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was unarmed, and he had not acted in a threatening
manner, but he bumped one of the policemen with his fender as he
pulled away and he refused to stop the car. The two officers fired
several shots as he fled. A man riding in Wilson's car was wounded.
Wilson was killed.
</P>
<P>
   When you enter Russ Rymer's ``American Beach,'' almost
immediately you fall into a world crackling with similar
experiences, a world where these things have happened and continue
to happen, a world that many if not most black people in America
inhabit, where they are mostly voiceless and mostly powerless and
almost always under suspicion. In the case of too many people like
Dennis Wilson, who lived in a small house just up the road from
American Beach, that suspicion leads very often to inexcusable
violence and needless death at the hands of uniformed authority.
</P>
<P>
   But Rymer is also concerned with another kind of powerlessness
-- the kind that wears the face of cultural erosion, political
impotence and disappearing historical landmarks. In ``American
Beach'' he tells three basic stories -- about Dennis Wilson and the
circumstances surrounding his death, about MaVynee Betsch, the
great-granddaughter of the founder of American Beach, and about
Eatonville, Fla., the oldest black incorporated town in the United
States, threatened by a highway project that would divide the town
in two.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these places, issues that are larger than life are
brought down to human scale by centering our attention on a few
lives and a few stories, rendering personal the tragedy that is
American racial history. These stories strike at the core of who we
are as a nation, caught as we are in the vise grip of race, and
between development and progress and our traditions and past.
</P>
<P>
   American Beach is so small and seemingly insignificant that it
doesn't even warrant a dot on most maps. But during the long
nightmare of Jim Crow, it was one of the only black beach resorts
in the country. Money and ownership of the culture stayed within
the community. MaVynee Betsch, speaking of how self-contained the
black community was, says, ``You could go from sunup to sundown and
never bother with white people.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the end of segregation came the end of that kind of
self-sufficiency. Black communities dispersed as the restrictions
on housing at least nominally ended, and a kind of decay set in and
with it a new kind of isolation. To a woman like Betsch, who had
witnessed at first hand the vague fluctuations of fortune and
history, it was more than distressing. Her great-grandfather, A. L.
Lewis, had founded Florida's first life insurance company and was
one of Florida's first black millionaires. She had seen the history
unfold, and that history was suddenly hard to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russ,'' she asks the author, ``what went wrong?'' But Rymer
tells us, ``From her tone of aching lament I knew she was speaking
to herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Rymer is a seasoned journalist, precise, attentive,
thought-provoking. (His first book, ``Genie: A Scientific
Tragedy,'' was a nominee for the National Book Critics Circle
Award.) At the same time -- and this is not a complaint -- he gives
the lie to the myth of journalistic objectivity. He has a feeling
for the people he meets and tells about and for the lives they have
lived, and he nudges his reader to care for them too and to arrive
at his intended conclusions, which he does with great skill.
</P>
<P>
   All is not perfect, of course. The book drags in places and
could be shorter, as almost all books could be. There are numerous
places where Rymer repeats himself, sometimes idea for idea,
sometimes almost word for word -- though some of that fault lies
with his editors, and ought not to detract from the overall
sensation that this is a book well worth the time.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the individual stories that illuminate ``American
Beach,'' there is nothing here that hasn't been told again and
again. Rymer is clearly aware of this, and of the fact that it is
necessary that these stories and this history be told until we all
understand more than we do, until we all come to realize what
continues to go on in the shadowy reaches of this country where so
many are so badly perceived and treated, until we can honestly
attempt to answer MaVynee's lamenting question: What went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Eddy L. Harris is the author of ``Mississippi Solo,'' ``South of
Haunted Dreams'' and, most recently, ``Still Life in Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
