<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7254 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MOVIES-NYTSF     11-24 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MOVIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TOTALLY, TENDERLY, TRAGICALLY
<TEXT>
<P>
   Essays and Criticism From a Lifelong Love Affair With the
Movies.
</P>
<P>
   By Phillip Lopate.
</P>
<P>
   384 pp. New York: Anchor Books/Doubleday. Paper, $12.95.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; WAITING FOR GODARD &QL; 
 &UR; By DIANE JACOBS &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FALLING in love with movies has proved a fruitful occupation for
intellectuals who might feel silly going wild over paintings or
books. ``John Wayne rode through my childhood,'' Joan Didion
rhapsodized in her memorable ``John Wayne: A Love Song''; David
Thomson announced that he could not be objective about anything to
do with Angie Dickinson. Now Phillip Lopate entitles a collection
of his writing on cinema ``Totally, Tenderly, Tragically'' and
starts off by confessing, ``All my life I have been movie-mad.''
Lopate, who takes Montaigne as his mentor, is known for bold,
cosmopolitan, complaint-driven (but never whiny) essays gathered in
impressive collections like ``Bachelorhood'' (1981) and,
especially, ``Against Joie de Vivre'' (1989). ``Totally, Tenderly,
Tragically'' is something of a departure. For where topics in the
earlier books ranged widely, from the machinations of a Manhattan
dinner party to an examination of Lopate's own body, here he rivets
his attention on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Lopate considers himself ``both an outsider and an insider'' in
the movie world, since he never held a regular film beat or
professorship, but has spent four terms selecting entries for the
New York Film Festival, written lots of articles and ``put in my
50,000 hours in the dark.'' What's more, he was a precocious child
with plenty to escape from.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most movie-mad youngsters, Lopate discovered film through
literature (``I bought Arthur Knight's survey, 'The Liveliest Art,'
and went about in my thorough, solemn way trying to see every movie
listed in the index'') and merely endured genre directors like
Hawks and Hitchcock while embracing the masters of high art, like
Murnau, Kurosawa and Bresson. In his teens, Lopate pursued cinema
across the bridge from his working-class Brooklyn family -- in the
wobbly seats of the Thalia, at makeshift screenings in Chelsea
church basements and finally in college at Columbia, where he
discovered Andrew Sarris and the auteur theory and formed a movie
club of his own. In ``Anticipation of 'La Notte' '' (an essay also
included in ``Against Joie de Vivre''), we meet Lopate's fellow
film buffs -- the temperate humanist James Stoller, a lover of
Satyajit Ray and Jean Renoir, and the ``mischievous'' Nicholas
Zill, a psychology major, who relishes the beggars' orgy in
``Viridiana'' and cutting up rats in the lab. Both men greatly
influence Lopate, who -- ``unable to break through to women'' --
spends his free time browsing through movie magazines, savoring ``a
mood of sweet latency'' and dreaming of the films he will see.
</P>
<P>
   It was the early 1960's, a high point for the French New Wave.
``Our man was Godard,'' Lopate recalls, and proceeds to interweave
his highly charged reactions to films like ``Breathless'' with
cursory remarks about his virginity and other aspects of college
life off screen. Discussing his suicidal depression, for instance,
Lopate nonchalantly observes, ``Between screenings of Vigo's
'L'Atalante' and 'Zero de Conduite' at West 106th Street, I told my
older brother that I was thinking of killing myself.'' And two
weeks after he has vomited up the 20 sleeping pills he swallowed:
``My brother met me at the hospital and we went straight downtown
to see a double bill at the Bleecker Street Cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Totally, Tenderly, Tragically'' comprises 27 essays divided
into three sections: ``Memories,'' ``Films and Filmmakers'' and
``Can Movies Think?'' Roughly chronological, it jumps from short
reviews to leisurely career studies, film festival reports, close
considerations of individual movies (memorably, Bresson's ``Trial
of Joan of Arc'') and interviews with the likes of the critic
Pauline Kael. These pieces are culled from a variety of
publications; and while Lopate makes an effort to link them by
tacking on explanatory notes at the end of most articles, they
never do cohere. ``The First New York Film Festival -- 1963,''
written for The Columbia Daily Spectator, is predictably solemn and
erudite, while ``The Gallant Andrew Sarris,'' contributed to a book
honoring Sarris's 70th birthday, is chatty and wry. Still, Lopate's
language is consistently engaging, and the high points include a
deftly argued defense of Jerry Lewis's ``Three on a Couch,'' a
trenchant interview with the Iranian director Abbas Kiarostami and
a brief but moving rumination on Chris Marker's magisterial oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   Notable too are Lopate's profile of Luchino Visconti and his
long, informative homage to the Japanese director Mikio Naruse.
Less successful are the more ambitious, convoluted essays.
``Fassbinder's 'Despair,' '' for instance, sets out to merge
analysis of a failed movie with the story of Lopate's own botched
infatuation, but it does not build interest about either. And
Lopate's musings on the possibility of an essay in film (``In
Search of the Centaur: The Essay-Film'') prove pedantic, even
plodding at times, though he clearly intends to delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no faith that my discriminations in taste are anything
but the picky awareness of what will keep me stimulated, based on
the peculiar family and class circumstances that formed me. The
knowledge that my discriminations are skewed and not always
universally desirable doesn't stop me in the least from making
them,'' Lopate announced in ``Against Joie de Vivre.'' And a
swaggering individualism informs his film judgments, too. This can
be satisfying, as when Lopate nails ``Letter to Jane'' as ``a
closely reasoned, if nasty, provocation by two male-bonded
ingrates, Godard and Jean-Pierre Gorin, against the female movie
star who so generously collaborated with them on their otherwise
unbudgetable feature, 'Tout Va Bien.' '' At other times Lopate's
thrusts seem merely peevish -- when, during the 60's, for instance,
he deplores Ingmar Bergman as ``the darling of the suburbs,'' or in
the 90's damns Woody Allen's (sad and hilarious) ``Bullets Over
Broadway'' as ``impersonal,'' ``anti-intellectual'' and ``glib.''
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Totally, Tenderly, Tragically'' is an uneven volume,
never as fluent or strikingly original as ``Against Joie de
Vivre,'' it is always and unwaveringly intelligent. Fortunately,
its tendentious moments are outweighed by a wealth of thoughtful
analysis conveyed in lively, often eloquent prose. ``I approach
moviegoing seriously,'' Lopate announces in his introduction. And
serious he is. But he is also curious, wise and frequently amusing,
a sharp observer of his own quest for ``sublimity on screen.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Diane Jacobs is the author of ``Christmas in July: The Life and
Art of Preston Sturges.'' She is writing a biography of Mary
Wollstonecraft.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
