<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7257 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-EAST-1000&AMP;ADD     11-24 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EAST-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 EAST INTO UPPER EAST
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plain Tales From New York and New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth Prawer Jhabvala.
</P>
<P>
   314 pp. Washington: Counterpoint. $25.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; PASSAGE TO AMERICA &QL; 
 &UR; By DEBORAH MASON &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Should one want to try to become something other than what one
is?'' This is the question Ruth Prawer Jhabvala asked in the
introduction to her previous story collection, ``Out of India,'' in
which she reveals a deeply ambivalent love for her adopted country.
There she lives each day in the thick of its languid communality,
``a central European with an English education and a deplorable
tendency to constant self-analysis'' who is fated to feel like an
eternally displaced person.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is precisely this sense of dislocation that has provided
Jhabvala with the cross-cultural eye to create, over the past 40
years, the sumptuous emotional geography of her short stories, her
screenplays for Merchant-Ivory Productions and her dozen novels,
including the Booker Prize-winning ``Heat and Dust.'' Jhabvala is a
connoisseur of divided souls, conceiving characters whose inner
longings are at odds with their outer protective coloration --
Indians who covet and achieve more tidy, ``modernized'' existences,
then feel as if someone had stolen their life force; Westerners who
eagerly hand themselves over to India's chaotic bliss, then find it
too rigorous to endure.
</P>
<P>
   In her most recent works, Jhabvala's rich depictions of New York
City's extinguished lives -- melancholy German intellectuals
arguing in dusty West Side apartments, madmen pawing through trash
cans on Broadway -- have come to rival her signature descriptions
of India's intricate seductions. This new collection of stories,
``East Into Upper East: Plain Tales From New York and New Delhi,''
written over the last 20 years, reaffirms her as a spellbinding
urban fabulist.
</P>
<P>
   Set, for the most part, in the gilded co-ops of New York's Upper
East Side and the expensive villas of the ``new New Delhi,''
Jhabvala's stories lay open the rootless, chameleon existences that
thrive in habitats requiring no firm commitments, just a bundle of
money and a great address. Much further adrift than the dislocated
souls of her previous works, many of these characters have passed
over into permanent spiritual exile. Choked off from religious
moorings and family origins, they find their hungers resurfacing in
a desperate voraciousness. Sensuality is reduced to clownish sexual
preening, family loyalties to the language of real estate parcels
and advantageous marriages. These people can be unexpectedly
amusing -- or terrifying in their dumb soullessness. From time to
time, they manage to find salvation through the work of spiritual
shamans who may or may not be charlatans -- not that it matters.
Both the louts and the potentially redeemable are portrayed with
wry, bristling irony.
</P>
<P>
   Each story reveals Jhabvala's mastery of the form: the sleek
economy of words, free of heavy symbolism or easy judgments, that
allows her to home in on small, telling details. Often, a story
starts as if she were simply picking up a conversation in
midstream. ``Farid couldn't believe what he heard about Farida,''
one story begins. ``She was his wife, and he would have thought
that no one had known her more deeply, in every way, than he had.''
Jhabvala's plots unfold just as crisply, delivering sly humor and
sudden, startling turns into tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York stories, her characters routinely seal
themselves up in willed, anonymous isolation, as if warding off the
messy truths of the city might help them avoid unsettling changes
in their own lives. Behind their double-bolted doors, many are
locked into crushing emotional dependencies.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Fidelity,'' a middle-aged woman named Sophie spends most of
her time in her dark Park Avenue apartment, hiding behind her
family money and the constantly drawn drapes that prevent the sun
from fading her grandparents' Biedermeier furniture. Sophie's
ravenous wheeler-dealer husband, Dave, has left her yet again --
this time to live around the corner with a new young girlfriend who
``wasn't worth, he said, to kiss Sophie's shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   He still visits his wife regularly and just as regularly bursts
into tears over his infidelities, both romantic and financial --
tears so cleansing that they give him fresh strength to walk out on
her once again. ``Dave's relation to his wife was an affair of the
utmost delicacy to him,'' Jhabvala writes. ``He considered his love
for her as the only pure and selfless part of him, which he was
reluctant to tarnish with a request for money to keep him out of
jail.'' Sophie's accession to Dave turns out to be far more tragic:
she is so grateful for his visits that she will not interrupt his
monologues to tell him she is dying.
</P>
<P>
   Jhabvala's New Yorkers can be fiendish or funny, and they can
also can be pitiable -- like Pauline, the lonely real estate agent
in ``Great Expectations,'' who hands over her apartment and her
life to a parasitic family she has just met. The Indians in
Jhabvala's stories, on the other hand, seem somewhat wiser, less
cut off from their ancestral culture. But although they live in
daily intimacy with India's fervent spirituality, only a few
partake of it genuinely. The most haunting of these is Prakash in
``Husband and Son,'' a once amorous, Cambridge-educated Cabinet
minister who is now a toothless old holy man living on the roof of
his Delhi house, singing Vedic hymns to greet each dawn. Otherwise,
there are few saints among the Indian characters -- far from it.
</P>
<P>
   Farid and Farida, in the story of the same name, are a chic
young Delhi couple who move to London to hustle India's full line
of enchantments, from handcrafts to cocktail delicacies. When their
schemes collapse, so does their marriage. Twenty years later,
Farid, his waistline and his drinking problem increasing, tracks
down his wife to the Himalayas, only to find her sitting under a
banyan tree with her own fleet of handmaidens and a line of
pilgrims waiting to touch her feet: she has transformed herself
into an even more marketable product, a holy woman. ``Her skin was
clear,'' Farid notes, ``and shone with a radiance that could only
be the result of the best cosmetics, applied, he knew, with
consummate skill.'' He has arrived just in time to see her lose
what little remains of her soul.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-EAST-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: her soul.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Indian characters engage in the same social climbing and
power playing as the New Yorkers. Harry (born Hari), the
disaffected husband in ``Independence,'' amuses himself with
English detective novels, Urdu poetry and vodka. Meanwhile, his
wife, Sumitra, the Pamela Harriman of post-independence New Delhi,
is out every night ministering to the newly elected politicos
streaming in from the provinces -- teaching them to use the right
fork at the French Ambassador's dinner and sometimes romancing them
afterward. As Sumitra's career ascends, Harry reverts to wearing
Indian clothes and staging embarrassing scenes at his wife's
soirees. Gradually, he drinks himself into darkness, becoming a sad
relic of the graceful, old, outworn India.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ma in ``The Temptress,'' an ``ordinary Indian housewife
with extraordinary powers,'' who is the cheeky queen of this
collection. A fat, chatty sorceress in her 60's, Ma is imported to
New York by a wealthy collector of gurus, one of the many young
people in these stories starved for the spiritual grounding their
parents have discarded. But after sharing Ma with her friends, the
woman abruptly abandons her. Ma doesn't mind: she is a specialist
in self-renovation, having retooled herself into a glittering woman
of the world who shifts cities, countries, even New York apartments
with playful ease. Besides, ``Ma wasn't ready to go home. She felt
she was still needed here, also that she hadn't yet had her fill of
shopping and nice restaurants and all the lights coming on in the
theater district and the advertisements flashing and the many
different cable channels and flavors of ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma is also busy coaxing out of hiding the city's vast,
suppressed spiritual yearnings. Her tony neighbors unlatch their
doors and pour out their hearts to her; salesgirls from the local
discount store consult her between customers. Even doormen, that
most hardened of urban breeds, walk away from their jobs to join
her chanting, lentil-cooking commune. There Ma soothes them by
dealing ``with everyone in the manner of one used to hearing
strange and even terrible things without letting herself be
overwhelmed by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma comes the closest to sainthood of anyone in the book. She may
even be Jhabvala's earthy, late 90's incarnation of the Indian
Mother Goddess herself, who changes her own form at will, while
urging humankind to embrace -- not hide from -- the chaos,
contradiction and changeability of existence. Reconciling East and
West with one jingle of her bangle bracelets, Ma shows how a
benevolent acceptance of our frailties and longings can bind
disparate cultures -- and even a few divided souls.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Mason is a writer and critic who lives in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
