<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MARSHALL-1000     11-24 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MARSHALL-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THURGOOD MARSHALL: AMERICAN REVOLUTIONARY.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Juan Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 459 pp. New York: Times Books/Random House. $27.50.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; THE MARSHALL PLAN &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID K. SHIPLER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Reading a biography of the great civil rights lawyer Thurgood
Marshall (1908-93) is good treatment for the disease of complacency
about race relations. Progress does not look inevitable when you
watch the powerful resistance that confronted Marshall's every step
to gain rights for blacks. Nor do all the advances seem
irreversible when you witness the backsliding that embittered his
later years as the first black Justice on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his towering victories, he retired from the Court in
1991 not in a victorious spirit but in anguish over a task that
remained woefully incomplete. As an NAACP Legal Defense and
Educational Fund attorney, he had won landmark Supreme Court
decisions overturning segregation and discrimination in elections,
housing, transportation and education. Yet as a justice he saw his
influence wane as the Court swung to the right, leaving him
isolated and angry -- and unappreciated by a generation of blacks
no longer enamored of integration and too young to remember the
struggles he had waged since the 1930's. Some regard him as having
been a better lawyer than judge.
</P>
<P>
   The story of his extraordinary life contains a measure of our
history, so his exhilaration and melancholy reflect more than a
man's moods. They represent our national experience, which takes us
to the heights of decency one moment and to the depths of bigotry
the next. That larger landscape, illuminated as Marshall passes
through, is deftly sketched by Juan Williams in ``Thurgood
Marshall: American Revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   The term ``revolutionary'' might seem exaggerated for a man who
worked wholly within the judicial system, albeit using the
Constitution as a weapon of liberation. But on the first page
Williams labels Marshall ``one of America's leading radicals,''
places him in a triumvirate with Malcolm X and Martin Luther King
Jr. and argues that it was Thurgood Marshall who ``stood as the one
with the biggest impact on American race relations.'' The ranking
is debatable, but it would surely have pleased Marshall, who
detested the separatism of Malcolm X; ``I think we called each
other sons of bitches'' at a chance meeting on a Harlem street,
Marshall told Williams. In private, Marshall also disparaged King
and opposed most demonstrations -- even the Montgomery bus boycott
and the lunch counter sit-ins -- as senseless invitations to
violence. He initially resisted defending black students arrested
at a sit-in, because he thought they had violated private property
rights at a Woolworth's in Greensboro, N.C. He gives no sign, in
Williams's portrait, of recognizing how King's movement mobilized
the conscience of the country, creating the climate in which
courtroom triumphs could be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is an accomplished reporter with The Washington Post
who wrote ``Eyes on the Prize: America's Civil Rights Years,
1954-1965,'' the companion volume to the public television series.
His skills at digging out facts have been tested here, for although
he did a dozen interviews with Justice Marshall over six months in
1989, he was unable to gain access to the Legal Defense Fund's
files, and Marshall's children and second wife, Cissy, declined to
cooperate. Still, Williams interviewed widely, assembled accounts
of debates and maneuvers within the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People and obtained documents revealing
Marshall's sporadic cooperation with J. Edgar Hoover. The book is a
strong piece of journalism crammed with fascinating detail, done in
an unassuming style driven by the factual narrative.
</P>
<P>
   It portrays Marshall as a curious mixture of stubbornness and
accommodation, a gruff wit who chased women and drank heavily and a
dedicated lawyer who repeatedly ventured into the dangers of the
South to defend blacks being railroaded on murder, rape and other
charges. In 1946, he was nearly lynched with the help of the local
police in Columbia, Tenn., after he got an all-white jury to acquit
23 of 25 blacks charged in riots started by whites. ``One local
paper said the trial was packed with spectators who came to town to
see 'those niggers up there wearing coats and ties and talking back
to the judge just like they were white men,' '' Williams writes.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Baltimore, Marshall knew how to avoid provoking
whites' resentment over an ``uppity'' black, and so he adopted a
charming deference in his arguments before the Supreme Court. ``His
light humor made the young black lawyer a fast favorite among the
older white justices,'' Williams observes. ``Marshall always took a
moment to thank the justices, whisper some confidence and make each
of them feel as if he were relying on their superior knowledge to
help him through the maze of laws.'' Near the end of his Court
career 45 years later, though, he issued rare public criticisms of
his conservative colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter's book and not a legal history, this biography
offers little from Marshall's briefs, opinions and dissents --
perhaps a reasonable choice, since these documents are available
elsewhere. But we never quite see Marshall's legal mind at work.
Williams tells of his powerful orations, but rarely shows us more
than fragmentary quotations, even as Marshall argues the famous
school desegregation case, Brown v. Board of Education, before the
Supreme Court. A more serious flaw
</P>
<P>
   lies in Williams's uncritical use of McCarthy-era innuendo to
describe certain civil rights activists as ``Communist-backed'' or
having ``Communist ties.'' As a pre-emptive defense of the
N.A.A.C.P., Marshall exchanged information on such people and
groups with Hoover, who was obsessed by Communists, both actual and
phantom. But Williams treats the paranoia unquestioningly. His
reporting stops far short of defining the boundary between reality
and fantasy, leaving his readers unsure about Marshall's role in
this other crucial test of American democracy, which raised issues
of free speech and free association. It is the book's largest
defect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-MARSHALL-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: largest defect.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the book offers a valuable picture of the odd
Marshall-Hoover liaison. The F.B.I. Director placed Marshall under
surveillance and resented his complaints that F.B.I. agents were
covering up for white sheriffs' departments sympathetic to mob
violence against blacks. But when the two met in 1947, Marshall
``won Hoover over with his charming, good-ol'-boy, 'I'm a little
ol' Baltimore lawyer' persona,'' Williams writes. The Director
offered a collaborative relationship, and Marshall suggested that
the N.A.A.C.P. could defuse accusations of racism in the F.B.I. if
the F.B.I. would investigate attacks on blacks. Both men got a
little of what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   This volume captures the sweep of Marshall's impact beyond the
civil rights movement, for as lawyer and judge and justice, he
expanded the rights of all Americans. Williams shows him
influencing fellow justices in rulings that recognized the right to
abortions, indigent defendants' right to state-paid psychiatrists,
protections against double jeopardy in state courts and the right
of defendants not to have jurors excluded on racial grounds. He
helped shape the narrow decision to abolish the death penalty in
1972, but saw it reinstated by the Court several years later.
</P>
<P>
   The power of his presence was formidable. ``Marshall could be a
persuasive force by just sitting there,'' the conservative Justice
Antonin Scalia told Williams. ``Anyone who spoke in conference on
one of these race issues had to be looking at Thurgood. . . . He
wouldn't have had to open his mouth to affect the nature of the
conference and how seriously the conference would take matters of
race.'' The vacuum now is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David K. Shipler, a former correspondent for The Times, won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1987 for ``Arab and Jew: Wounded Spirits in a
Promised Land.'' His most recent book is ``A Country of Strangers:
Blacks and Whites in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
