<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM SAYS BYE-BYE LEFTOVERS, HELLO BAD MOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I found a bag of cookies in my kitchen today. Old, stale
cookies. They were in a lower cabinet, behind the crockpot I never
use. The bag was open, but only three of the chocolate chip treats
had been eaten.
</P>
<P>
   How did a bag of cookies live and die in a household with two
rapidly growing males and one snack-happy dad? Well, I ate the
three cookies and hid the bag from them, that's how. I just forgot
where I hid them until now. Wait, let me explain. I am not crazy.
</P>
<P>
   It all starts with that simple question, ``Are you going to eat
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, not often, but sometimes I only eat half of my
sandwich and then I gingerly wrap the other half in plastic wrap
intent on finishing it off at a later date. Or perhaps, I decide
that life will go on if I don't actually eat my way through the
entire pint of chocolate ice cream in one sitting. It might be any
morsel of food or drink left over from my meal. Invariably, before
it reaches the temperature of the refrigerator, one of the boys
wants to know if I'm going to eat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I say. ``Yes, I'm going to eat MY leftovers. It's good
food and I plan to finish it when I become hungry again. I don't
mean to be greedy but we each had an individual serving and you
have already eaten yours. This is mine. In the unlikely event that
I change my mind, you will have the right of first refusal.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I look in the refrigerator, my food is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who ate the biscuit and half of a cocktail wiener that I was
saving for lunch?'' I query.
</P>
<P>
   My husband responds, ``Oh, did you want that? It's been in there
forever. It was going to spoil like that turkey last
Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just ate breakfast an hour ago. I don't even think that
biscuits can spoil. Why did you eat my food without asking me
first?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that my soft drink next to you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It's flat anyway. Do you want it back?''
</P>
<P>
   Geez.
</P>
<P>
   Once, I bought these dried-out, awful-tasting, dehydrated banana
slices. I didn't even like them but I figured that no one else
would either, so at least when I got ready for a snack, they would
still be in the cabinet. Wrong. A week later, I went to grab a
handful and the bag was in the pantry completely empty.
</P>
<P>
   I was livid.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to my bananas!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Mom, those were awful. We ate them for you but we could
barely swallow them. We had to drink some of your diet tea to get
them down. Don't ever buy those again.''
</P>
<P>
   After I ranted and raved about that for a week, they devised
this method of making sure that I get a sample of everything. Last
week, they left me a slice of chocolate cake that was so thin I
could see through it. I didn't even have to chew it, I just mashed
it up a bit with my tongue and swallowed. I couldn't even taste it,
but at least they thought of me.
</P>
<P>
   So now if I get a really special treat, I hide it from them. The
only problem is sometimes I forget where I hid it and by the time I
find it, it really is spoiled. Then I have to throw it away.
</P>
<P>
   You know, that is a little loony isn't it? Oh well.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington wife, mother and
dentist. You can write her in care of the Star-Telegram at 1111 W.
Abram St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
