<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7269 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     11-24 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE TRUTH ABOUT DARYL HANNAH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I saw a special on Daryl Hannah that said something was wrong
with one of her hands. My husband swears otherwise. Who was right?
Say me, me, me. _ D.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Hannah has a shortened fingertip on one hand. Her publicist,
Alan Nierob, denied a recent report by Jeannette Walls of MSNBC
that the actress wears a prosthetic for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something you would notice,'' Nierob said. ``I think
that it's a congenital condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls reported on Nov. 9 that the prosthetic came off on the set
of the ABC movie ``Rear Window'' and production stopped until it
could be located.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah, who turns 38 on Dec. 3, is currently filming
``Diplomatic Siege'' in Romania with Peter Weller and director
Gustavo Graef Marino. Fans can write to her in care of Chuck
Binder, 1465 Linda Crest Drive, Beverly Hills, Calif. 90210.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was in the Navy with Lance LeGault. Lately he has been the
narrator of a few TNN productions and had roles on ``Magnum P.I.''
and ``The A-Team.'' How can I write to him? _ R.G., via the
Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to LeGault in care of the Tisherman Agency, 6767 Forest
Lawn Drive, Suite 101, Los Angeles, Calif. 90068.
</P>
<P>
   LeGault, a one-time movie stand-in for Elvis Presley, has
appeared in more than 50 films and TV shows. He most recently
portrayed ``Elder God of Fire'' in the film ``Mortal Kombat:
Annihilation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop the Movement,'' a collection of country songs by LeGault,
is available by mail order from Shock Records, 16105-8H Victory
Blvd., Suite 382, Van Nuys, Calif. 91406. The price is $10 plus $2
shipping and handling, and checks should be payable to ``Lance
LeGault Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the term ``hard-wired'' come into use? _ R.J.,
Houston
</P>
<P>
   A: The term was coined in the late 1960s, shortly after
``hardware'' and ``software'' were adopted as references to
computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware dates to the 16th century as a way to describe the
mechanical equipment required to perform an activity.
``Hard-wired'' originally referred to an element of an electronic
circuit that was determined by the wiring and could not be changed,
according to the Free On-Line Dictionary of Computing.
</P>
<P>
   It has been extended to refer to ``anything that is not
modifiable.'' The On-Line Dictionary is available on the World Wide
Web at nightflight.com/foldoc.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7271 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     11-24 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICE WHO? IT'S TIME WE ALL KNEW HER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Book Awards have a 60-year history without having
gained much attention. They were initiated as a reaction against
the literary Pulitzer Prizes, most pointedly the fiction award so
constrained by terms of Joseph Pulitzer's last will and testament.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzers remain America's literary awards of highest
visibility, but even the National Book Critics Circle's annual
awards _ dating only to 1975 _ had surpassed the National Book
Awards in general interest until ...
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, when Charles Frazier's ``Cold Mountain'' took
the fiction award in what was loudly reported as an upset, because
Don DeLillo's ``Underworld'' was the prefigured favorite. Yet I was
delighted, overjoyed that Frazier won for his very first novel.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's another upset.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1998 National Book Award winners were announced on
Wednesday, it seemed the whole world was anticipating victory for
Tom Wolfe, whose ``A Man in Full,'' published only this month,
approximates the most hyped literary event of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   I would have been disappointed if Wolfe had taken the prize. For
all its felicities, his corpulent novel has some liabilities that
are being articulated in a second wave of criticism after the
initial raves. I would not have been disappointed if the
also-nominated Robert Stone, a previous winner, had triumphed again
with ``Damascus Gate,'' a masterwork more seriously constituted
than Wolfe's opus.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't have known what to think if either of two other
fiction nominees had won the judges' endorsement _ Allegra Goodman
for ``Kaaterskill Falls,'' Gayl Jones for ``The Healing'' _ but I
certainly would have been surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning that the new ``upset'' winner is Alice McDermott
for ``Charming Billy,'' I was somewhat surprised but more elated. I
really wanted McDermott to win, for the needed recognition it can
bring her, and because ``Charming Billy'' is as strong in its own
way as the quite different ``Damascus Gate,'' if no higher on the
qualitative scale.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Frazier was a phenomenon from out of nowhere, but Alice
McDermott has been around. She is one of those authors deservedly
adored by critics, who compare her (favorably) with the great
William Trevor. But critics have not succeeded in winning for her
the constituency that still sniffs after great novels.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott isn't one to crank them out. She devotes several years
to each project; and her score, if I have it right, is four runs,
four hits, no errors. I missed her well-praised apprentice work,
``A Bigamist's Daughter'' (1982), but caught up with her next, the
beautifully crafted ``That Night'' (1987). Anyone mistaking
McDermott for a newcomer should be advised that she was a National
Book Award nominee 11 years ago, and a tattling juror revealed that
she almost won for ``That Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Her entry for 1992 _ ``At Weddings and Wakes,'' which I reviewed
_ is every bit as prize-worthy. And with that novel, it became
apparent that McDermott has her own literary preserve. She is the
prose poet of Irish-Americans living in and around New York but
still tied spiritually to the Auld Sod.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't have thought McDermott could improve either on ``That
Night'' or ``At Weddings and Wakes,'' but ``Charming Billy''
somehow transcends both. It is her richest work in character,
incident and action, and it emits an even stronger Irish aroma than
do its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Billy indeed is a charmer when sober, but that isn't often
enough, and thwarted love has knocked him off the wagon. It isn't
revealing too much that Billy has drunk himself to death, too
young, and that the fabric of the novel concerns the efforts of his
bereaved family and friends to come to terms with his tragic life.
Yet the novel itself is affirmative and triumphant in its loving
embrace of raffish humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, Alice McDermott. You're here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
