<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-THANKSGIVING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALED-DOWN HOLIDAY DINNER PROVIDES A HEARTY FEAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idealized image of Thanksgiving is of generations of family
crowded around an 18-foot-long table laden with the fruits of our
combined labor: Cousin Liz's sweet potatoes, Aunt Mary's Jell-O
salad and Grandma's rich pumpkin pies.
</P>
<P>
   But for many of us, the family is a close-knit group of three or
four, or even two. There's no need for us to cook enough food to
feed the Mormon Tabernacle Choir. And there, indeed, lies another
reason to be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   With just a couple of hours in the kitchen, a feast (with plenty
of leftovers for the mandatory post-ballgame sandwiches) can
beautifully grace your table. Thanksgiving becomes an intimate,
more thoughtful affair.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE, ONION AND ROSEMARY SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 navel oranges
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 small red onion
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon minced fresh rosemary or 1/2 teaspoon dried
rosemary, plus sprigs fresh rosemary for garnish
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Peel oranges and section them or slice them thinly. Peel onion
and slice thinly. Toss both with minced fresh or dried rosemary, a
small amount of salt and pepper and the olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   This can be served immediately or refrigerated for up to 2
hours. Bring to room temperature before serving and garnish with
rosemary sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 130 calories, 7 grams fat, 17
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium,
49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``How to Cook Everything,'' by Mark Bittman (Macmillan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY BREAST BAKED WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 boneless turkey breast half, skin on, about 11/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 medium sweet onions, such as Maui or Vidalia, peeled, cut in
half from end to end, sliced
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   _ Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ 3/4 cup reduced-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   _ Sauteed fresh mushrooms; see note, optional
</P>
<P>
   _ Mashed potatoes; see note, optional
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons chopped chives, optional for garnish
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: If desired, saute 8 ounces of sliced mushrooms (button,
shiitake or cremini) in 1 tablespoon butter and 1 teaspoon olive
oil on medium-high heat. Cook until mushrooms are softened and
lightly browned and liquid has evaporated. Season to taste with
garlic salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   This dish is great served on mashed potatoes. Make them your
favorite way, but use less butter. Instead, add some prepared
horseradish, about 2 teaspoons per 3 pounds of potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Dust turkey on both sides with flour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large, nonstick skillet on medium-high heat. Add
onions and brown, stirring occasionally, about 5-7 minutes. Add
thyme, Worcestershire sauce, balsamic vinegar and pepper. Stir to
combine. Place turkey, skin side up, in a 9-inch square baking pan.
Pour onion mixture on top, so that some stays on top of turkey and
some falls into the pan. Pour broth around turkey. Cover loosely
with aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 45 minutes. Remove foil and bake 30-45 more minutes, or
until an instant-read thermometer reads 170 degrees when inserted
into the thickest part of the turkey breast. Allow turkey to rest
10 minutes. Cut into slices.
</P>
<P>
   PRESENTATION: If using, spoon potatoes on platter. Place sliced
turkey on top, overlapping slightly like a fan. Spoon sauce on top.
If desired, top with sauteed mushrooms and sprinkle with chives.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 190 calories, 3 grams fat, 95
milligrams cholesterol, 103 milligrams sodium, 16 percent of
calories from fat. _ Orange County Register
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED ROOT VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil, butter or a mixture of
the two
</P>
<P>
   _ 11/2 to 2 pounds mixed root vegetables, such as carrots,
potatoes, sweet potatoes, parsnips, turnips, shallots (leave whole)
and onion, peeled and cut into 11/2- to 2-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   _ Several sprigs fresh thyme or about 1 tablespoon fresh
rosemary leaves, optional
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 head garlic, broken into cloves but not peeled
</P>
<P>
   _ Minced fresh parsley leaves, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place oil or butter in large
roasting pan on top of stove and turn heat to low When butter
melts or oil is hot, add all the vegetables (except garlic) along
with thyme or rosemary. Sprinkle with salt and pepper and cook them
briefly, shaking and stirring so everything is coated with oil or
butter. Place pan in oven.
</P>
<P>
   Cook for 30 minutes, opening oven and shaking pan once or twice
during period. Add garlic and stir vegetables; at this point they
should be starting to brown. If they're not, raise oven temperature
to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Continue to cook, stirring and shaking every 10 minutes or so,
until vegetables are tender and nicely browned, at least another
half-hour. If vegetables soften before they brown, run under
broiler for a minute or two. If they brown before they soften, add
a few tablespoons water to pan and turn heat down to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish and serve hot or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 182 calories, 8 grams fat, 27
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 28 milligrams
sodium, 39 percent of calories from fat. _ How to Cook Everything
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEFTOVER TURKEY AND MUSHROOM RISOTTO
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   _ 11/2 cups fat-free, low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup dry vermouth
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 ounces sliced portobello mushrooms (about 3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 medium onion, sliced (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup diced, drained pimento, optional
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 pound cooked or smoked turkey cut into 1/2-inch cubes (2
cups)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 cup uncooked orzo
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 cup chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   Toast pine nuts in a large nonstick saucepan on medium-high for
2 minutes, tossing constantly to prevent burning. Remove to a
plate. Add broth and vermouth to pan and bring to a boil on
medium-high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the sliced portobello mushrooms into small pieces. Add to
the broth with the onion, pimento, turkey and orzo. Lower heat to
medium and simmer 10 minutes, stirring several times. The liquid
will be absorbed and the orzo cooked through. If it becomes dry
before the orzo is cooked, add more broth.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat. Add salt and pepper to taste. Stir in the
Parmesan cheese. Sprinkle the basil and pine nuts on top.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 697 calories, 52 grams
protein, 46 grams carbohydrate, 19 grams fat, 99 milligrams
cholesterol, 853 milligrams sodium, 25 percent of calories from
fat. _ The Miami Herald
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
