<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-CORRUPTION-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BLACK AND BLUE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By JENNY ANDERSON 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Alfredo Aldaco is writing a novel that
he believes all of his native Argentina should read. But the book
by the former director of Argentina's Banco de la Nacion is not
about his country's bold experiment with a currency board or his
experience at the helm of the nation's largest and most powerful
bank. With the working title I am not Innocent, it is a tale about
a bank director who illegally accepts millions of dollars to
approve a major computer contract with a powerful U.S. company that
breaks the rules when doing business abroad. Set against a backdrop
of impunity and corruption at the highest levels of government and
business, the main character confesses, only to incite the wrath of
the country's leading spin-doctors and top political operatives.
 &HT;    What makes Aldaco's book a must-read is that it is based on a
true story. His story.
 &HT;    In real life it's called the ``IBM/Banco de la Nacion affair,''
in which IBM Argentina, a subsidiary of the U.S. computing giant,
allegedly funneled US$21 million dollars in kickbacks to secure a
$249 million contract to network the sprawling branch operations of
Banco de la Nacisn, Argentina's largest state-run bank. So far, 30
people have been indicted, including the former president and
former chief financial officer of IBM Argentina. Earlier this year,
Aldaco and one other bank director admitted to accepting bribes
totaling $4.5 million, while investigators have uncovered more than
half a dozen bank accounts suspected to hold illicit funds.
Prosecutors say they believe the money trail leads to IBM's U.S.
corporate headquarters and they have issued arrest warrants for two
current and two former officials from U.S.-based IBM Latin America.
For its part, IBM vehemently denies that regional executives had
any part in the affair. ``IBM does not participate in bribery of
local officials or do business with companies that do that,'' says
official IBM Latin America spokesman Fred McNeese.
 &HT;    The murky rivers of corruption run deep in Argentina. The media
makes a near-daily meal of the latest erupting scandal and foreign
executives working in the country say that the only change in the
environment is that would-be extortionists have become more
shameless. The question facing any firm that decides to do business
here is how to confront the kickback culture. A multinational like
IBM-bound by the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, its status as
a founding member of the anti-corruption business group
Transparency International and its own corporate ethics code-faces
a deeper challenge: how to ensure that the entire organization is
playing by rules set at the top.
 &HT;    Recently, that has been a challenge for Big Blue. Aside from the
Banco de la Nacisn case, other IBM contracts are also under review
by the Argentine Congress and prosecutors. In Mexico, IBM recently
paid $11.5 million to settle charges of fraud in a contract to
install a system for the Mexico City District Attorney's office.
And in another incident, IBM's Russian subsidiary pleaded guilty to
17 felony charges of violating U.S. export-control laws. In each
case, IBM headquarters admitted to no wrongdoing and no evidence
has been traced back to executives at corporate headquarters.
 &HT;    A look at the events in the IBM/Banco de la Nacion scandal
raises questions of whether IBM is doing enough to ensure that the
rules on the books are the rules in force.
 &HT;    The Banco de la Nacion affair started in January, 1991, when the
bank's board of directors hired Booz, Allen &AMP; Hamilton, the U.S.
consultants, to determine the best way to modernize the bank's
antiquated information systems. At the time, the bank had 500
branches, but only 50 were linked through a common computer
network. Another 150 had individual systems that forced each bank
to work as a separate entity, while 300 branches ran with manual
accounting systems. The bank was, and continues to be, Argentina's
largest.
 &HT;    By mid-1992, Booz, Allen produced a report that proposed to
overhaul communications by linking all branch offices on an
electronic network. U.S. accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche
supervised a public bidding for the mega-modernization plan, which
came to be known as the Century Project. Three firms submitted
proposals _ IBM Argentina, Impsat and TTI, all based in Argentina _
and, in February 1994, the project was awarded to IBM Argentina,
whose bid of $249 million included a central software system called
Hogan, named after a U.S. software developer, Hogan International.
 &HT;    In the months leading up to the bid, according to Aldaco, key
executives within Banco de la Nacion had engaged in a contentious
debate over whether the Hogan software system was the best for the
bank. At the beginning of 1993, bank officials visited foreign
banks in other countries, including Canada, Mexico, Portugal,
Spain, and the United States, to study various information systems.
Besides the Hogan solution championed by IBM, another option was on
the table. The alternative project called for separate bids for the
five major components of the system: central hardware, central
software, branch hardware, branch software and training. Based on
their findings, the board of directors agreed at a meeting held
June 11, 1993, that Hogan was not the system they wanted. Aldaco
now says he favored the alternative, which would have cost the bank
between $80-$90 million. He says the board rejected IBM's Hogan
system because some of the banks visited by directors had run into
serious complications with the installation and customization of
Hogan. Also, the directors had apparently not decided exactly how
they wanted to centralize the bank's data processing.
 &HT;    Then, according to Aldaco, less than a week after this decision,
Aldo Dadone, the president of the bank, called Aldaco into his
office and told him that Domingo Cavallo, then the powerful economy
minister and a close political ally to Dadone, had insisted that
the bank use the Hogan system. Dadone then sent Aldaco to Spain and
Portugal to reassess the use of Hogan in other banks. Aldaco
returned within a week, again with a negative report. Dadone
ignored the report, and a heated debate ensued between Carlos
Thomson, the head of systems, and Dadone, the bank president. The
Hogan system prevailed, and Thomson was transferred to another
section of the bank. ``We were told that we were showing a lack of
respect [toward Cavallo]. The reality was, if you didn't like
Cavallo's decision, you had to leave the bank,'' Aldaco says.
 &HT;    Cavallo vigorously denies Aldaco's version of the story [see
sidebar]. But in his book, El Peso de la Verdad (The Weight of the
Truth), Cavallo writes that he had seen the Hogan system in
operation at Canada's Bank of Nova Scotia and that he was
enthusiastic about the Century Project.
 &HT;    One month after IBM Argentina had been approved for the project,
another meeting took place, this time between Aldaco and Marcelo
Cattaneo, a ruling party insider and the president of Consad, an
Argentine information-technology consulting firm subcontracted by
IBM to provide components of the overall modernization project.
``[Cattaneo] said he knew I was bothered by the project and offered
me $3 million dollars, deposited directly into a Swiss bank account
to see that the project went smoothly,'' says Aldaco. ``And sadly,
I took the money.''
 &HT;    Apparently, Cattaneo was making the rounds. Genaro Contartese,
another former Banco de la Nacion director, also admitted to
receiving $1.5 million.
 &HT;    The directors' confessions came earlier this year, but the
entire case may have remained undiscovered had not a routine tax
audit revealed that an obscure local company called Capacitacion y
Computacion Rural (CCR) received $21 million dollars in checks from
IBM Argentina. CCR, in turn, had a dead man and a waitress on their
payroll. The revelation prompted an investigation.
 &HT;    CCR was a relatively new company on the Argentine technology
scene, spun off from Consad between 1992 and 1993. A year later
Consad sold CCR a management software program called SBL for $1
million, though at this point the company had no clients and no
work history.
 &HT;    Digging away at the relationship between IBM, Consad and CCR
became the main task of federal Judge Adolfo Bagnasco. The young,
loquacious, and, some charge, politically ambitious judge was
assigned to the case midway through 1994, one year after the $249
million contract was awarded to IBM Argentina.
 &HT;    He originally set out to discover how Banco de la Nacion and
Deloitte &AMP; Touche selected IBM's Hogan system. Two technical
experts were asked to evaluate the original contract; they
determined that it was overvalued by up to $100 million and that no
mention of CCR or installation of a backup computer system appeared
in the document.
 &HT;    However, further investigation showed that IBM's first
disbursement of funds, $21 million, went to CCR, supposedly to pay
for a backup computer system. ``When you purchase a car, you don't
first go purchase a backup car,'' says Aldaco. ``IBM did not buy
all the [principal] hardware and software first. The first payment
was for an alternative system. This was payment of the bribes.''
 &HT;    Indeed, the payment was the beginning of a financial labyrinth
for investigators, so complicated that the judge has to draw a flow
chart outlining a hazy web of offshore bank accounts and money
transfers. According to Bagnasco, IBM Argentina deposited two
checks, one for $8 million and one for $13 million, into CCR's
account at the Argentine branch of Banco General de Negocios. The
$8 million was paid in cash to CCR's suppliers. The other $13
million went to an offshore bank called Compania General de
Negocios. From those funds, CCR paid Consad $3 million, which,
according to Bagnasco, disappeared. The remaining $10 million went
to the United States, with $1 million being deposited in Citibank
and $9 million traveling on to Switzerland's Bruxelles Lambert.
Half the Swiss funds were split into four accounts. Two of these
accounts belong to Banco de la Nacion's Aldaco, one to Contartese
and the fourth, says Bagnasco, to a friend of Aldaco.
 &HT;    The other $4.5 million passed through Luxembourg, and then
dispersed into five accounts: two in Switzerland, one in Uruguay
and two in the United States. Bagnasco has asked Swiss authorities
to verify whether the accounts belongs to Mario Dadone, the brother
of Banco de la Nacion's ex-president, and Walter de Fortuna,
another close ally of Domingo Cavallo. Bagnasco says he believes
that the Uruguayan account will be tied to Contartese, while the
owners of the two U.S. accounts _ one in MTB New York and one in
Brown B. Harriman &AMP; Co. _ remain unknown.
 &HT;    The judge's report alleges that IBM Argentina's $21 million
payment to CCR for a backup software system was actually a cover
for funneling bribes. According to the indictment, CCR received
checks from IBM for services that were never rendered.
 &HT;    Based on his findings, Bagnasco won 30 indictments on a first
round of fraud charges in April, 1996. Cited were three former IBM
Argentina officials, the entire Banco de la Nacion board of
directors, including former president Aldo Dadone, and several
employees from the Argentine office of Deloitte and Touche.
Cattaneo was also indicted, but the charges were later dropped. A
year later, Bagnasco won 10 more indictments on charges of bribery,
but a federal appeals judge ruled that the accused were being
charged twice for the same crime and threw out the latter charges.
That decision is under appeal.
 &HT;    In June 1996, Banco de la Nacion cancelled the project and
demanded an $82 million refund from IBM. IBM Argentina filed a
breach-of-contract suit demanding payment and damages, while
claiming that Banco de la Nacion continually changed the technical
specifications of the job.
 &HT;    The confessions of former bank directors Aldaco and Contartese
to accepting a total of $4.5 million as a gratuity for approving
IBM for the project came earlier this year and they add weight to
the judge's accusations of bribery.
 &HT;    Also this year, Bagnasco issued arrest warrants for two current
and two former IBM executives that were based in the United States
at the time of the incident. Robeli de Librero was the former
general manager of the Latin America division. He retired in 1995
after 35 years with the company. Peter Rowley was in charge of
marketing for the region and now heads IBM's small business unit.
Steven Lew was IBM's technical advisor to the Banco de la Nacion
contract and still works for the company. Marcelo Kaiser left IBM
in 1995 and now works for U.S. database firm Oracle in Brazil.
Bagnasco says all four are formal suspects in the case and has
demanded under a bilateral treaty between the United States and
Argentina that they be sent to Buenos Aires for questioning. IBM,
which makes public statements for the four, says that they are
willing to meet with investigators on U.S. soil.
 &HT;    At the heart of Bagnasco's inquiry is whether top IBM officials
knew that CCR was receiving funds from IBM Argentina. And on that
count, IBM officials in the United States are adamant. ``It boils
down to the specific question of whether Latin America headquarters
knew any money was going to CCR,'' says IBM Latin America region
spokesman Fred McNeese. ``We have found no indication written, oral
or otherwise that anyone in the United States knew that money was
going to CCR. Regional headquarters was never told.''
 &HT;    McNeese says regional executives were aware of the Banco de la
Nacion project and had received a list of sub-contractors that had
been hired. He says Consad appeared on the list, but that CCR did
not, and that officials at IBM Argentina were primarily responsible
for the details. The company undertook its own investigation after
allegations became public and decided that IBM's internal policies
had not been properly followed. Argentine subsidiary general
manager Ricardo Martorana and the unit's CFO resigned, while
operations head Gustavo Soriani left the company in relation to the
incident. ``Internal business procedures were not followed. And the
three people responsible are no longer with the company,'' says
McNeese. But he adds: ``The procedures were adequate.''
 &HT;    Were they?
 &HT;    Observers scoff at the idea that regional executives would not
know where nearly a tenth of a $249 million contract was going. IBM
has repeatedly denied that any employee outside of IBM Argentina
knew of wrongdoing. No evidence has surfaced suggesting otherwise.
 &HT;    What else were IBM's regional executives unaware of? Other IBM
contracts in Argentina are being reviewed by officials, including
irregularities discovered in a $513 million contract awarded
without a public bidding to install a network to monitor tax
payments and pension-fund contributions. Other cases with state
banks in the provinces are pending and a Congressional Commission
established in 1996 to investigate the awarding of government
contracts to IBM is still at work.
 &HT;    IBM is a company that has long held a good reputation for
corporate ethics. Employees must sign on to the firm's code of
conduct each year. An internal department is currently responsible
for vetting employees and business partners, foreign companies,
usually technology service providers, that act as authorized
dealers for IBM products. The resumes of prospective hires are
verified, but the company does not have any additional procedures
for investigating executives that will hold top management posts or
be responsible for handling finances.
 &HT;    Business partners go through financial and technical qualifiers
to make sure they have the wherewithal to carry out contracts. IBM
also checks out the companies' reputations and ethical standards.
Business partners are subject to routine, regular checks of these
requirements.
 &HT;    According to McNeese, sub-contractors working on IBM projects
are not subject to the same extent of ethical background checks
before assisting on a project under IBM's supervision. Consad and
CCR were both sub-contractors working under IBM Argentina's
authority. McNeese defends that policy: ``Contractors are hired to
do a specific project. There is not a relationship.''
 &HT;    But more than legal wrangling is at stake when companies do
business overseas. Getting tangled in a scandal is time-consuming
and costly, even if corporate officers are judgd innocent. Security
experts say investing in preventive measures makes business sense.
As corporations do more and more business overseas, knowing exactly
who the company is doing business with and communicating ethics is
key to maintaining standards, especially in countries where
corruption has become endemic. The consultants recommend aggressive
ethics education and training for employees, coupled with
sufficient amounts of due diligence on companies that will be
working alongside multinationals. ``You have to manage the issue,''
says Bruce Goslin, managing director of Kroll Associates, a U.S.
corporate-security consultancy. ``You want to create the
environment where it is understood that illegal actions are not
tolerated.''
 &HT;    IBM has announced some changes in the way it bids for contracts,
forbidding subsidiaries from competing for work that is not open to
a competitive bid process. And in Argentina, government contracts
will not be sought by IBM's subsidiary, though McNeese says the
decision comes from the company's desire to concentrate its
resources on potential private-sector growth. The company refused
to comment on whether its own investigation of the Banco de la
Nacion contract lead to procedural changes at IBM.
 &HT;    Companies looking to learn from the Banco de la Nacion affair
will start by making sure that they have the checks and balances in
place to transmit corporate ethics to the farthest reaches of
business activity. To do otherwise is to risk legal snares and
publicity pitfalls. After all, reputations are much easier to
destroy than to rebuild. ``No one has to pay a bribe,'' says Luis
Moreno, the Argentine representative of Transparency International
and a former prosecutor. ``What we learn from the IBM case is that
to pay a bribe might mean winning business, but it is a dangerous
business.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
