<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD Q&AMP;A: FLOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flours: The Hard and the Soft
</P>
<P>
   Q: Often, recipes specify ``cake flour'' or ``bread flour.''
What are they? If I don't have them, can I substitute all-purpose
flour? And what is ``hard'' flour, which is called for in some
recipes? Is there such a thing as ``soft'' flour?
</P>
<P>
   A: For all intents and purposes, bread flour and hard flour are
the same thing. Ditto for cake flour and soft flour.
</P>
<P>
   Before all-purpose flour became ubiquitous, recipes for baked
goods often called for one specific type of flour, but that happens
only occasionally now.
</P>
<P>
   White wheat flours are categorized by their protein content.
Bread flour is ground from wheat that is especially high in
proteins, including those that make up gluten.
</P>
<P>
   When bread dough is kneaded, the gluten in the flour forms an
elastic network, or web, which traps the carbon dioxide gas given
off by the yeast. That is what causes the dough to rise. The more
gluten, the greater the bread dough's tendency to rise (provided
there is sufficient yeast activity), and the lighter the finished
loaf.
</P>
<P>
   Flour milled from low-protein strains of wheat has less gluten.
It is called soft flour, and is often marketed as ``cake'' or
``pastry'' flour, since it is perfect for mixing into tender,
delicate cake batter and pastry dough.
</P>
<P>
   All-purpose flour _ a mixture of hard and soft wheat flours _
has become a standard compromise in contemporary recipes. While it
can be used for most baked goods, it excels in none. However, when
a recipe calls for all-purpose flour, it means that the recipe has
been developed _ or at least tested _ using all-purpose flour, and
it is best to follow the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   But if a recipe calls for cake flour and all you have is
all-purpose, you can make a fine substitute by mixing \ cup
cornstarch with } cup all-purpose flour for each cup of cake flour.
</P>
<P>
   If a recipe calls for bread flour and you have only all-purpose,
adding a tablespoon of gluten powder for every cup will help the
dough rise; it will also make multigrain breads lighter. (Gluten
flour is available in health food stores.)
</P>
<P>
   Another tip: When a recipe calls for cake flour, don't use the
self-rising kind. The added salt and leavening will throw off the
proportions and bake up into a tough-crumb cake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
