<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7450 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUG-COX     11-24 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pixar's ants push limits of animation
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   See if this rings a bell: Here's a computer-animated movie about
an imperiled ant colony. Our hero is a worker ant who gets in
trouble for being a nonconformist. When his colony faces
annihilation, he braves the danger and wins the heart of the ant
princess in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, this sounds a lot like the fall's earlier release ``Antz.''
But there's a big difference. ``A Bug's Life'' is a visual wonder
that blows the DreamWorks release off the screen. Often as witty as
it is eye-popping, it recaptures some of the magic of the last
movie from Pixar Animation Studios, ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Flik (voiced by Dave Foley) is an inventor ant whose gadgets are
viewed with suspicion by his march-in-line colleagues, overseen by
the queen (Phyllis Diller) and her daughter Princess Atta (Julia
Louis-Dreyfus). It's Flik's indirect fault that his colony incurs
the wrath of a grasshopper gang led by Hopper (Kevin Spacey), who
extorts food from the ants in exchange for ``protection.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Flik's bright idea to search the countryside for some
``tough bugs'' who can fight the grasshoppers. Through a series of
misunderstandings, he thinks he's found them when he encounters a
flea circus. The troupe includes a genial black widow spider
(Bonnie Hunt), a gypsy moth (Madeline Kahn), a melodramatic
magician mantis (Jonathan Harris), a walking stick (David Hyde
Pierce) and a grumpy male ladybug named Francis (Denis Leary).
There are also a couple of language-challenged acrobatic pillbugs,
Tuck and Roll, who steal a bunch of scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Flik takes them all back to the anthill to wage war. The bugs
think it's just a new gig. Complications (and comedy) ensue.
</P>
<P>
   The circus bug setup provides a slew of show biz jokes adults
will appreciate. Kids will love the slapstick. Everyone will be
amazed by the animation.
</P>
<P>
   Presented in wide-screen ratio (compared to the boxier
proportions of ``Toy Story'') ``A Bug's Life'' is bursting with
extraordinary visual grace notes: Forests of clover. A dandelion
tuft used as a parachute. A rowdy grasshopper cantina hidden under
a sombrero. The flea circus alone is an eye-filling accumulation of
found objects, including a dog collar used as the main performance
ring and a Chinese takeout carton filling in as a magician's
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers' expertise doesn't end with the backgrounds. The
movie features action scenes that seem designed to test the limits
of computer animation, including a complex airborne chase through a
rainstorm. One sequence, involving the attack of a hungry bird, is
handled with spectacular skill and suspense. (A useful comparison
is to the shoelace rescue in ``Antz,'' which was slowed down until
it lost any sense of danger.)
</P>
<P>
   The script is full of quips almost as abundant as the movie's
eye candy. ``I only got 24 hours to live, and I ain't gonna waste
it here,'' grumbles one housefly, in the definitive put-down of the
flea circus. The film's version of a buggy big city includes a
homeless insect with the sign ``Kid Pulled My Wings Off'' and that
universal urban horror, a millipede mime. And thanks to Leary's
reliably grumpy vocals, the movie gets great mileage off Francis,
especially when the ladybug is adopted as ``den mother'' by Atta's
kid sister Dot and her fellow girl ants.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the film's riches tend to work against it. While
the characters of ``Toy Story'' were wittily well defined, the
large number of characters (and species) in ``Bug Life'' means that
we don't get to know all of them as well. Maybe that's what sequels
are made for. (``Toy Story 2'' hits theaters next year.)
</P>
<P>
   Parents, take note. The movie doesn't have explicit violence,
but Hopper attempts to squash an ant by stepping on his head, and
one bug gets eaten (offscreen). And remember: Stay for the credits,
which include some cleverly made ``outtakes'' from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of Dave Foley, Kevin Spacey, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus. Directed by John Lasseter and Andrew Stanton. Rated
G. 1 hour, 34 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A multi-legged wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
