<HEADER>
A7451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CRUISE-COX     11-24 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CRUISE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Cruise' is quite a trip as long as it doesn't stop
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bennett Miller's low-budget documentary ``The Cruise,'' filmed
in gritty black-and-white, is something of a stunt, but it's an
appealing one. Especially if you ever did time on Manhattan Island.
</P>
<P>
   Miller focuses on Timothy ``Speed'' Levitch, a loquaciously
eccentric tour guide who works for Manhattan's Gray Line bus
company. Surveying New York City from the top of a double-decker
bus, Levitch likes to point out the less ``touristy'' aspects of
the Big Apple. The streets where H.L. Mencken, D.H. Lawrence, Edith
Wharton and Mark Twain lived; the Village's White Horse Tavern,
where Dylan Thomas died (his last words, according to Levitch,
were: ``I just had my 16th martini'').
</P>
<P>
   Levitch is a font of factoids. The World Trade Center has its
own ZIP code. Eleven people survived their suicide jump from the
Brooklyn Bridge. Twenty-seven thousand trees were originally
planted in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   As neurotically self-absorbed as Woody Allen and as
transparently attention-craving as Richard Simmons (whose voice and
mannerisms he brings to mind), Levitch is a sort of quintessential
New Yorker with a quintessential love/hate relationship with the
city. ``I felt this winter we were getting a divorce, that the city
was angry with me,'' he confides to the camera. But over the
summer, he admits, ``a reconciliation'' has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Levitch is a lot more intriguing on the bus than off.
Unfortunately, the film gives him a lot of time at street level
where we're forced to listen to his metaphysical musings on ``the
cruise'' as a way of life or to such get-over-it poetic utterances
as ``The city is a streamlined mermaid who sings to me at night.''
In these scenes, he's just another sad, lonely, frustrated guy
whose verbal audacity merely masks his repetitious mantra, ``I am
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   But back on board his bus, mike in hand (``Can you hear me in
the back?''), Levitch is a kind of inspired performance artist. A
spiel about Manhattan and the end of civilization abruptly segues
into ``the new AnnTaylor store, on your left.'' And paeans to the
city don't get any better than his instructions to his captive
audience, ``The sun, ladies and gentlemen. Another great New York
landmark. Above you, to the left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cruise''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Timothy ``Speed'' Levitch. Directed by Bennett Miller.
Rated PG-13 for language.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Get on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
