<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7456 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BABE-COX     11-24 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BABE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Babe' sequel offers up little to squeal about
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This little piggy has a sequel. But while most of the main
players are reunited in ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' some of the
magic has worn off.
</P>
<P>
   ``City'' quickly welcomes us back to the world of Babe and his
farmyard friends. It starts with a parade celebrating the piglet's
sheep-herding triumph at the end of the 1995 best picture Oscar
nominee. The deadpan narration is again by Roscoe Lee Browne, the
main animal voices are the same, and the farming couple the
Hoggetts are portrayed once more by James Cromwell and Magda
Szubanski.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, those three mice are still singing malicious intros to
the movie's multiple chapters.
</P>
<P>
   But the sequel _ directed by ``Babe'' producer and co-writer
George Miller, instead of Chris Noonan _ gets off on the wrong hoof
(sorry) with its main plot device. Farmer Hoggett is confined to
bed by an accident, and it's up to Mrs. Hoggett to save the
indebted farm by taking Babe (voiced by E.G. Daily) to a lucrative
personal appearance at a county fair.
</P>
<P>
   This not only turns Oscar nominee Cromwell into a cameo, but
does the same to Babe's surrogate parents, the Border collies Fly
and Rex (voiced by Miriam Margolyes and Hugo Weaving). Even those
dumb, annoying sheep only have one scene, baaaaing, ``Save the
farm, Babe!''
</P>
<P>
   When the farmer's wife and Babe are stranded in the city (a
witty blend of Paris, New York, San Francisco, Sydney and just
about every other metropolis), the movie buzzes along for a while
on Roger Ford's whimsical production design. Mrs. Hoggett and Babe
find shelter in a turreted hotel run by a twitchy landlady (Mary
Stein), whose neighbors are anxious to bust her for harboring
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The inn is home to every kind of animal: tough dogs, a roomful
of cats who sing choral versions of ``Three Blind Mice,'' and a
couple of street-smart chimps (voices by Glenne Headly and Steven
Wright) who work for a clown named Fugly Floom (Mickey Rooney, in a
tiny role). Babe's rude awakening in the city includes getting
recruited into Floom's act, which ends in disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Around this point, ``Pig in the City'' starts to lose its shape.
The first film had the clean, even moving story of Babe struggling
to prove himself (and save his own life) by herding sheep. In the
sequel, nothing replaces the emotional connections between Babe,
Fly and Farmer Hoggett. It disintegrates into a series of chases.
Babe has to escape some angry dogs. Babe has to escape some animal
control officials, etc. And lots of things are constantly crashing
down around the piglet.
</P>
<P>
   While the first film wittily reinterpreted a recognizable
reality (farm life) through the animals' eyes, the sequel offers a
far-fetched city overrun by animals. Instead of the suspenseful,
quiet finale of original, we get the rotund Szubanski
bungee-jumping through a chic fund-raiser trying to rescue her pig.
Why? It's never really clear. In its last half-hour the movie opts
for slapstick instead of clarity. In the process, Babe gets lost;
he's an ensemble member more than a lead character.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, kids will probably love the animals and the seamless FX
that make them seem to speak. The film reportedly had to be
revamped to get a G rating instead of a PG. But remember, the first
movie was quite dark: The main point for Babe and Francis the duck
was to keep off the butcher block. In the new film, we get a sick
old man being carried to the hospital and the near deaths of two
dogs and a goldfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pig in the City'' has its charmed, offhand moments: A kitten
whimpering, ``My tummy hurts.'' The mice singing ``Non, Je Ne
Regrette Rien.'' The fierce loyalty of a crippled Jack Russell
terrier named Flealick (voiced by Adam Goldberg) who wears training
wheels on his rear legs. And a late-night parade of animals through
a children's hospital ward that recalls the hushed magic of ``101
Dalmatians'' (the book, not the movies).
</P>
<P>
   The animals are beautifully trained, and Szubanski is a game
performer, though her role is little more than a drawn-out sight
gag. But too often, the action-mad ``Mad Max'' side of director
Miller seems to come out. While the first ``Babe'' inspired wonder,
the new sequel makes you wonder why anyone would create a sequel
that ignores most of the things that made the first movie so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe: Pig in the City''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Magda Szubanski, James Cromwell, Mickey Rooney.
Directed by George Miller. Rated G. 1 hour, 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not as tasty as the first film.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
