<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-FRIES-COX     11-24 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FRIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Home Fries' a half-baked attempt at romantic comedy
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the big-budget blunders of ``The Avengers,'' ``The
Postman'' and ``Batman and Robin,'' Warner Bros. seems to be going
in the opposite direction. Its new ``Home Fries'' looks like the
kind of edgy, low-budget independent flick that usually emerges
from the Sundance Film Festival. But the resemblance is only
skin-deep. It's a dumb Hollywood romantic comedy in a small-town
disguise.
</P>
<P>
   It starts off appealingly weird, like a country cousin of ``The
X-Files.'' (The script is by Vince Gilligan, an executive producer
of that show.) While ultra-pregnant Sally (Drew Barrymore) takes
orders at the drive-through of the BurgerMatic, she hears
disembodied voices chattering on her headset.
</P>
<P>
   They belong to a couple of pilots in a military helicopter,
chasing a middle-aged man through the woods. The man's name is
Henry (Chris Lever); he's the father of Sally's unborn child. And
the next day, he's found dead.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Sally can't go to the funeral because Henry has a wife
(Catherine O'Hara) and two grown stepsons, Dorian (Luke Wilson) and
Angus (Jake Busey, typecast again as a lunatic). These two are the
guys who were flying the copter, scaring their stepdad for his
cheatin' ways. It was Mom's idea. Now, Mom wants to find the hussy
who was sleeping with Henry. And kill her.
</P>
<P>
   That's the convoluted setup that results in Dorian finding work
at the BurgerMatic and falling in love with Sally . . . even while
the murderous Angus redoubles his efforts to find her. This could
be fun, if the movie knew what tone to take. Instead, it tries to
mix farce with romance, and the blend never gels.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's idea of character development is to mention Sally's
obsession with Dolly Parton, a joke that's at least a decade old.
Barrymore's role is pretty much defined by her fake belly and
floppy Orphan Annie wig; she's a sweet blank. Maybe it's fitting
that Dorian falls for her. He's not all there, either. (Though
Barrymore and Wilson are linked in real life, they have zero
chemistry on-screen.)
</P>
<P>
   That leaves it up to O'Hara to walk away with the movie. The
brilliant ``SCTV'' alumna turns in a performance that's Lady
Macbeth by way of a Tupperware party. You keep waiting for her big
confrontation with Shelley Duvall (underused as Sally's mom), but
it never happens.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck between Hollywood blandness and backwoods condescension,
the movie unfolds against melancholy shots of grain silos, railroad
tracks and fields of graying baled hay. You can almost hear
director Parisot exulting about the ``realness'' of the shots. That
verisimilitude only makes the script seem sillier.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's heavy-hitter list of producers includes directors
Barry Levinson and Lawrence Kasdan. Maybe they're pining for the
freedom of their younger, independent days. Movies like this won't
bring those days back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Fries''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Drew Barrymore, Luke Wilson, Catherine O'Hara. Directed
by Dean Parisot. Rated PG-13. 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A small-town romantic comedy, scant on the romance,
and too broad on the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
