<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-SPRINGER-COX     11-24 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SPRINGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    lHeadline idea: `Ringmaster' as real as Springer's TV show
(wink, wink)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, first, Angel beats the crap out of Willie. Then Starletta
smacks around Angel. LeShawnette screams at Demond and Angel
screams at Connie. Then Angel attacks Demond, Starletta tries to
tear out Angel's hair and Angel returns to pounding on Willie.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, now . . . Is that everything? It wouldn't do to
overlook any part of the climactic scene in ``Ringmaster,'' not
with rabid fans of ``The Jerry Springer Show'' worrying that the
movie might be different somehow. You know, not as good.
</P>
<P>
   Good _ we'll get back to that later. For now, let's just say
that if ``Ringmaster'' was any more like the TV show, you'd mistake
your popcorn for the remote. A few things are different about the
films's look at a wildly popular TV talk program called ``The Jerry
Show'' _ most notably, we watch as two different equally
dysfunctional groups gradually realize their dreams of having lives
awful enough for ``Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet nearly everything else that's made the real (no cracks,
please) TV show such a hit is here:
</P>
<P>
   The whooping audience members. The hair-pulling, chair-throwing
``guests'' barely controlled by burly security guards. And of
course, Springer himself, marooned with his microphone somewhere in
the audience, looking shocked _ shocked! _ by everything
spontaneously (wink, wink) occurring all around him.
</P>
<P>
   It's his schtick and he's schticking to it. Or is that too harsh
an assessment? After all, ``Ringmaster'' would have us believe that
there's a real message to all this madness _ and it's certainlynot
that a particular large segment of America apparently can't get
enough of trash-talkin' people slapping each other upside the head.
On nationwide TV, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy, no. The real message here is that anybody who's not part
of that large segment is a snob. The kind of snob who looks down
his nose at real people's problems, who . . . Oh heck, why not let
the movie speak for itself?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you find poverty bleak and that depresses you, '' Mel
Riley (John Capodice), a high-level employee of ``The Jerry Show''
solemnly informs a downcast TV reporter who's spent a little too
much time on the set.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Jerry Farrelly (Springer)puts it in a ``closing thought''
, the Angels and Starlettas of the world may not be rich or ``speak
the King's English,'' but they have ``just as much right to be on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as long as they're sleeping with their stepdaddy, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Ringmaster''I's barely begun (in a rundown Florida
trailer park, natch) and one realizes there's only four things
``poor people'' do in Jerry's world: Drink, swear, beat each other
up and have constant, indiscriminate sex.
</P>
<P>
   OK, sometimes it's discriminate _ for instance, Connie purposely
sleeps with daughter Angel's fiance after Angel sleeps with
Connie's husband _ but that hardly lessens our not-so-sneaking
suspicion that Jerry doesn't think much more of these people than
do the so-called snobs he's purportedly puncturing.
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely none of which matters if you're a fan of Jerry
Springer. If you like his TV show (or if you claim not to like it,
even as you secretly watch those nightly reruns on Channel 5) then
doubtless you'll enjoy ``Ringmaster'' 's familiar
expletive-hurling, breast- baring tricks.
</P>
<P>
   If not, well, as Jerry snarls near the end, ``This is a slice of
real life. If you don't like it, bite something else!''
</P>
<P>
   Or in the King's English: Go see ``Babe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Springer: Ringmaster''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jerry Springer. Directed by Neil Abramson. Rated R. 1
hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A split decision. Either you'll love it _ or you'll
want to split mere minutes into it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
