<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-THINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dark comedy refuses to pull punches
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people may stumble out of ``Very Bad Things'' convinced
they've seen the best movie of the year. Others may feel they've
seen the very worst. The wild thing is, these polar responses
aren't incompatible. ``Very Bad Things'' is the kind of movie that
either works for you or doesn't. It's a nasty, mean-spirited, sick
piece of celluloid. If you consider that a recommendation, buy a
ticket. If not, steer clear.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Peter Berg, best known as an actor on
``Chicago Hope,'' ``Things'' takes a familiar situation (stag party
gone bad) and squeezes every possible drop of bile out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Slater, Daniel Stern, Jeremy Piven and Leland Orser
play buddies who take groom-to-be Jon Favreau away for one last
wild weekend. On their way out of town, the fellows fuss about cell
phones and foreign policy; they poke and prod each other like old
friends do.
</P>
<P>
   But once they've settled into their hotel, their party-hearty
blend of booze, drugs and a stripper results in an accidental
death, which leads to a second, which leads to . . . well, that
would be telling.
</P>
<P>
   The plot-driven flick plays on your fears of a split-second
accident that can ruin your life and destroy every personal
relationship you thought was indestructible. And it's played for
sick laughs. The movie gets its gags (pun intentional) with
excruciating, mundane detail. Example: If you need buckets,
shovels, suitcases and an electric saw to ditch a body, where do
you go? Answer: a 24-hour Target.
</P>
<P>
   The movie isn't as sharp as it could be, especially when it
comes to Slater's character. Taking on responsibility for the
cover-up of the killings, he becomes a dark prince of mayhem,
determined to keep the murders hidden at all costs. Even if that
means murdering more people. After a point, it's hard to believe
his pals would give him such power.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a shame that the women are so marginalized. As Stern's
wife, Jeanne Tripplehorn tries to inflate a negligible role.
Cameron Diaz as the bride-to-be spends most of the movie whining
about the wedding. But she delivers a sharp turn-around near the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath its tough-boy sneer, ``Very Bad Things'' is a
deceptively moral work. Unlike most movies, it insists that actions
have consequences. Not that it ever slows down to underscore such
an obvious message. It's too busy with its hit-and-runs, fatal
betrayals and geysers of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you like it or loathe it, ``Very Bad Things'' stays true
to itself. It maintains the courage of its pitch-black convictions
right to its final, cruel frame. Considering how most movies get
softened and compromised to appeal to the largest number of people,
that is a very good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very Bad Things''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Christian Slater, Jon Favreau, Cameron Diaz. Written
and directed by Peter Berg. Rated R for simulated sex, nudity,
language, violence, gore. 1 hour, 41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A black comedy you're likely to love or loathe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
