<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A personal visit with the history of Sweet Apple
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It can't happen to many people since so many people
live in new houses nowadays, but a perfectly wonderful occasion for
me was having the descendants of the builders of my cabin drop by
and talk about their ancestors who cut and raised the very logs
that surrounded us.
</P>
<P>
   Two great-great-granddaughters of James Adams, the American
Revolution veteran who came to Georgia with his son and helped him
settle at Sweet Apple, came armed with pictures and records of the
transactions in what was then Milton County in 1830-40. They are
Ann Adams Wilt, who now lives in Charlotte, and her sister, Alecia
Adams Jameson, who lives in Buford. Their husbands, who have long
endured the searches of people like me who are interested in their
ancestors, accompanied them.
</P>
<P>
   And other special guests were my former neighbors Ralph and
Mildred Dangar, their daughter, Judy Walker, and a niece who came
bringing unbelievably precious documents of that day. One, creased
and worn, is the original deed to Sweet Apple and the land
surrounding it. It needs to be restored and framed, as does a fine
little journal of expenditures my predecessors at Sweet Apple kept.
One list contained two pairs of shoes made for $1.50. (I was
fascinated by that, since I just bought a pair of plain, everyday
shoes for $49 _ and that was a marked-down price.)
</P>
<P>
   We sat by the fireplace, which the women knew about from their
antecedents, who had warmed by it and cooked on it, and we
carefully unfolded yellowed documents that told us a little bit
about the people who had lived and worked in that place. Ann Wilt
did a charming thing. She assembled in a loose-leaf folder pictures
of the Adams family, Sweet Apple cabin and their eventual home, a
pretty white frame house in Buckhead, where her grandfather Dr.
Charles Adams lived and practiced medicine for many years. He was
one of the many children who were born in my cabin, and he was
apparently greatly beloved by people he took care of all the way
from Buckhead to Roswell. Their house was a block west of Peachtree
on West Paces _ maybe the first victim of so-called progress, since
it was torn down to make way for commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilt and her husband, Frank, did a wonderful thing for the
likes of us who are curious about early settlers. They had the
diary of a couple of Ann's ancestors, and when she realized it was
100 years old, she decided to transcribe the faded, spidery writing
and bring me a typewritten copy of it. Mrs. Wilt wrote a prologue
describing the lean days at Sweet Apple when Charlie Adams' daddy
told him that the ``only way out of poverty is an education.'' He
added: ``The local school could teach you enough to read the Bible
and figure out taxes, but to really learn a trade or profession you
had to go to the city.'' Charlie Adams hitched up the wagon and
came to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their life,'' wrote Ann, ``was one of voluntary simplicity. .
. . Survival was hard, but families and friends were close and
loving. They worked and prayed for a place to call home _
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann and Alecia were interested in the changes we had wrought at
Sweet Apple. I was apologetic for having installed lights and water
and bathrooms. I didn't like to admit that, instead of a black iron
pot out by the well house, I had a washing machine and dryer. But
they took another tack. I had preserved their ancestors' first home
in what was then Milton County, and they were grateful to me.
Imagine, when the pride and pleasure are all mine!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
