<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD BITS AND BYTES: CULINARY-RELATED WEB SITES OF NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Noodle Theme Park and Bike Carts on Line
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw ``Tampopo,'' the offbeat 1986 movie directed by
Juzo Itami, knows about the Japanese passion for ramen, or noodles.
Those who would revisit the obsession or plunge in for the first
time can travel to the Shin-Yokohama Ramen Museum on the Tokyo Food
Page (www.twics.com/robbs/tokyofood.html), one of three stellar Web
sites that will take you on a culinary tour of Asia without
traveling farther than your mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the museum, which is part historical theme park and
part mall, click on the Culinary Explorer. Pictures and text cover
the history of ramen eating in Japan. At the museum itself, you can
see it all in dioramas and interactive video panels. There are
pictures of the museum's reproduction of a bustling working-class
neighborhood, circa 1958, a golden age for ramen. At the museum,
there are eight noodle shops, each cooking its own variety of
classic ramen. (Sorry, no tastes: this is a virtual tour.)
</P>
<P>
   The Culinary Explorer also offers pictures of Osaka's
spectacular restaurant signs, including a 12-foot mechanical crab,
and a Tokyo Food Photo Gallery (the open-air Ohmicho fish market is
worth seeing).
</P>
<P>
   The site's Eating and Drinking in Tokyo section is a guide to a
mere 1,000 restaurants; Japanese Specialty Cuisines gives, among
other things, a sushi glossary and an essay on okonomiyaki
(literally ``cook what you like''), a pancake that may be Japan's
answer to pizza. There's a recipe collection. And don't ignore the
Resources and Web Links, with 90 more sites a click away and a page
of books on Japanese cooking and culture, in English and
immediately available through amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop is China, with a photo-essay on farmers' markets by
Ditty Deamer (www.saturdaymarket.com/chinaveg). Ms. Deamer
describes herself as a consultant with a small San Francisco
company that helps establish large joint-venture factories in
China. ``My work takes me to China many times a year, but cooking
is my real passion,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Her tireless survey shows the changes in China since the
government dismantled people's communes and decontrolled the growth
and sale of fresh produce. Street markets are flourishing, and
farmers sell directly to consumers. Middle men have sprung up, too.
</P>
<P>
   The tour also visits outdoor wholesale markets, indoor markets,
both government-run and private, and roving markets. Ms. Deamer
delves into subjects like the difference in design of the
bicycle-driven carts of Beijing, Shanghai, Hangzhou and Mudanjiang.
In the capital, the carts have a single wheel forward, with the
driver pedaling a two-wheel-supported load, which converts into a
market stand. In the beefier carts of Mudanjiang, near the Siberian
border, the load is in front and the driver behind, to carry more
over longer distances.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers try to avoid paying market fees by selling directly
from their carts, which is easier to do on the wide boulevards of
Beijing than in the mazy streets of Shanghai. In the new China,
police tend to be tolerant of these offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The shoppers, many of whom lack refrigeration at home, go to
local markets every day and buy small quantities. Weighing is often
still done on balance scales.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, from June to September, watermelons are widely sold
at makeshift tent shops set up on street corners. Families of
growers camp out for the season in tents stacked four feet high
with watermelons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Deamer's tales and pictures of how China goes to market
throw open a window on a vast, changing society.
</P>
<P>
   The last stop on this Asian tour is Muoi Khuntilanont's Kitchen
in Thailand (http://news.vu-korat.ac.th/muoi/), a thorough primer
on Thai cooking, with recipes, glossary, description of ingredients
and suggestions for substitutions (like sour green cooking apples
for mangoes). ``A Letter From Khun Kasma Loha-unchit'' is a paean
to Thai food on the street and in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Favorite Food Stops on the World Wide Web
(www.outlawcook.com/Page06.html) for these three sites, with many
more there for the virtual traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Create a Cheese Board
</P>
<P>
   The French Web site that sells artisanal cheese made from
unpasteurized milk (www.fromages.com) has made it easier for buyers
to choose their own cheeses. Previously, it was necessary to select
from set packages _ for instance, Camembert, Selles-sur-Cher and
Comte. Now click on the Epicurean Cheese Shop, and you can pick
three or more cheeses to make up your own cheese board from 16
choices, including St.-Nectaire, Cantal, raw-milk Camembert,
Epoisses and St.-Marcellin.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations require that any cheese sold in this country
must be made from pasteurized milk unless it has been aged at least
60 days. This site's cheeses are allowed in because they are
shipped to individuals, and not for resale.
</P>
<P>
   A good selection of cheeses available in this country is at
www.idealcheese.com, the Web site of Ideal Cheese Shop in New York
on the Upper East Side. The shop sells a completely goat-milk
gjetost, the chocolaty cheese that most people love or hate;
orange-hued mimolette; medium-aged Cantal, Beaufort and a good many
others from Europe, the British Isles and North America. The Web
site is only a display case. Orders are placed by calling (800)
382-0109; the shop ships throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Antique Apples as Gifts
</P>
<P>
   Antique varieties of apples, like the Spitzenburgs that Thomas
Jefferson grew at Monticello, would make an unusual treat or gift
for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   A Web source for them is Kilcherman's Christmas Cove Farm in
Northport, Mich. (http://kermit.traverse.com/christmascove). Seeds
of Change of Santa Fe, N.M. (www.seedsofchange.com), sells
certified organic fresh fruit, including Oregon Anjou pears, free
of herbicides, pesticides and fungicides. Another fruit site worth
knowing is Cushman's in West Palm Beach, Fla., for honeybell
oranges (www.honeybell.com). Honeybells are supersweet Minneolas _
navel oranges (with outsy navels) that are seedless, with skins
that come away almost at a touch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
