<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ELEGANT TASTE OF PARIS IS COMING TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fauchon, the venerable food market and restaurant complex that
anchors one corner of the Place de la Madeleine in Paris, plans to
open its first United States store, in New York, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Adamowicz, 41, a former investment banker who bought
Fauchon in April, said he was negotiating for nearly 4,000 square
feet at the corner of Madison Avenue and 74th Street, but was
considering other Upper East Side sites. He has hired Michael
McGovern, a former manager of Dean &AMP; DeLuca, to manage the New York
Fauchon.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company, founded by August Fauchon in 1886 with a
cart of produce, has 750 stores in Europe, Asia and the Middle
East, those are franchises, and not company-owned, as the New York
store will be.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these plans, Adamowicz is spending $12 million to
revamp the Paris headquarters. The main store and Fauchon's
packaging are being redesigned in a more traditional style, dozens
of new products are being added and three of the six Fauchon
restaurants clustered around the Place de la Madeleine have been
closed, including an Italian trattoria.
</P>
<P>
   Adamowicz said that next year there would be a new Fauchon
tearoom decorated like one the company had 100 years ago, and a new
wine bar. ``First we are going back to our roots,'' Adamowicz said.
``Then New York will be our next step.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   A new apple, the Pink Lady, is now available in limited
quantities. And it's a winner. A medium-large, squarish variety
with a pink-red, almost Day-Glo skin, the Pink Lady is crisp and
refreshingly tart for fine eating and dense enough for baking and
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The apples, which originated in New Zealand, are grown in
California. Because they need a long growing season, some of the
finest come from the Cuyama Valley near Los Angeles. These are sold
only by mail from Loguluso Family Farms ($29.95, plus shipping, for
23, including a corer). To order: (877) 564-6587.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Harry Wils &AMP; Co., the butter-and-egg merchant, has left 182
Duane Street (Hudson Street) in TriBeCa, its home for more than 70
years. It has moved to Secaucus, N.J. The company, now owned by
Stephen Wils, a grandson of the founder, has expanded its line of
products to include cheeses, chocolates and other foods.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many small retailers who have been forced to close or
move by rising rents, Wils, who sells mainly wholesale and owns the
building on Duane Street, needed more space. The new premises, at
505 Jefferson Avenue, are eight times bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Call it the stout of hard ciders. Hard Core, the cider company
owned by Boston Beer, which makes the Samuel Adams line, has
introduced Hard Core Black Cider, a richly complex coffee-color
brew with 6 percent alcohol, is more dry than sweet and excellent
with hearty dishes like short ribs and game. It is even good for
cooking those meats.
</P>
<P>
   The cider, which gets its color from caramelized apple juice, is
$1.69 a bottle at Broadway Farm, Broadway and 85th Street; at
D'Agostino and Food Emporium supermarkets, and at the Thrifty
Beverage Centers in Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
