<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-SHOPPING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS ARE OPTIMISTIC AS SHOPPERS HIT THE STORES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHRYN HOPPER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a lot of shoppers, Lee Meaders and Charlotte Masters are
feeling comfortable about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Meaders, a mortgage company worker from North Richland Hills
near Fort Worth, Texas, and Masters, who was visiting from San
Antonio, said they plan to spend at least as much as last year on
holiday presents. Still, Meaders and Masters won't exactly be
shelling out as if they've hit the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be good and write down a list before I go out,''
said Meaders, who was lugging shopping bags through Fort Worth
Outlet Square this week. ``I don't want to do a lot of impulse
buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the tumult of the past year, retailers will likely settle
for a lot of shoppers like Meaders and Masters. People in the
industry are fairly optimistic as they head into the important
holiday shopping season, which accounts for the bulk of many
stores' sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Most predict respectable sales gains of 4 percent to 5 percent
in stores open at least a year. That's enough to make the season as
good as last year, when retailers enjoyed their best holiday in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears like a lot of things are going in our favor,'' said
Bruce Van Kleeck, vice president of member services at the National
Retail Federation. ``We didn't launch an attack against Iraq, we've
finally seen some cold weather and the stock market seems to have
rebounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Most shoppers say they plan on spending the same amount or
slightly more on presents this year. A survey by American Express
found that shoppers who responded plan to spend an average of 4
percent more on holiday gifts this year.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, retailers said they feared that the late summer
stock market slide would dampen shopping plans. Those fears faded
as the market rebounded and the Fed trimmed interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are generally upbeat,'' said David Edmondson, executive
vice president of Fort Worth-based Tandy Corp. and chief operating
officer of Radio Shack. ``Unemployment is low and interest rates
continue to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have tempered their optimism with a dose of reality.
Last year, many chains did not meet sales projections and were
forced to take margin-eating markdowns in late December.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avoid that fate this year, J.C. Penney decreased its
inventory levels by a half-percentage point going into November.
The Plano, Texas-based retailer said it plans to use its catalog
operations to replenish fashion items that catch shoppers' fancy.
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving Day, Penney's will roll out an advertising
campaign that spotlights specific gift items such as $49.99
televisions and $24.99 Pillow Pets _ pillows shaped like stuffed
animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing customers have told us is there's a sameness to
everything at retail,'' said John T. Cody, chief operating officer
at Penney's. ``We want to give them something unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders say this Christmas could be a tough one for
traditional department stores, as shoppers flock to discounters and
specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discounters' price advantage will help them, and specialty
stores have figured out what the customer wants,'' said John
Konarski, director of research at the International Council of
Shopping Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are also struggling to staff stores in a tight labor
market. George Gillen, a retail consultant at
PricewaterhouseCoopers in Dallas, said consumers will have to
endure longer lines and scant sales help as they make their
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may get frustrated, but you'll wait because you have to
buy gifts and you figure it's just as bad everywhere else,'' Gillen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some malls are extending their shopping hours and encouraging
shoppers to come early or late to avoid crowds.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, shoppers waited until the last few days before
Christmas to do most of their buying. Almost half of American
shoppers don't start their Christmas buying until mid-November, and
23 percent wait until December, according to the International Mass
Retailers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no big toy this year, no Cabbage Patch doll,'' said
Marvin Girouard, chief executive officer at Pier 1 Imports, a Fort
Worth-based decorative home furnishings retailer. ``So people might
wait and buy later, buying things on sale.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, many shoppers may put off holiday shopping until the
day after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Van Kleeck said he expects Dec. 26 to be the biggest shopping
day of the year as people flock to make returns, use their gift
certificates and take advantage of post-holiday markdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after will be a bonanza for retailers,'' Van Kleeck
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
