<HEADLINE>
DO YOU LIKE JERRY SPRINGER ENOUGH TO PART WITH $7.50?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Are the guests on ``The Jerry Springer Show''
stupid or moronic?
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``Ringmaster'' answers that burning question. The
answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   A fictionalized account of life (if you can call it that) behind
the scenes of a sleazy daytime chat show, ``Ringmaster'' stars
Springer as a bemused, country music-playin',
slightly-appalled-with-himself host named Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   His life of embarrassed celebrity is contrasted with those of
two typical guest units: a sexually uninhibited young woman (Jaime
Pressly), her mama (Molly Hagan) and the lovers they share; and the
hunky Demond (Michael Jai White) and the three best girlfriends
(Wendy Raquel Robinson, Tangie Ambrose, Nicki Micheaux) who've all
been his women.
</P>
<P>
   The level of humor here is, in a word, broad; the level of
conversation, loud. The combination makes for a few laughs,
markedly more groans and an overall feeling of time and effort
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Neil Abramson, makes a few 11th-hour stabs at
suggesting the freakish guests enjoy the same full range of human
characteristics as do those of us who snicker at Springer's show.
But it's not just too little, too late; their expressions of love
and reason are just as cartoonish as their displays of dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Springer himself comes off as an affable, self-deprecating type.
When he's not sporting a ``What have I done?'' grimace, he's
passionately arguing that his show is about people, not trash.
</P>
<P>
   It would be elitist to claim otherwise, about the TV show
anyway. But the made-up characters in ``Ringmaster'' register a few
rungs down on the evolutionary scale from the stars of ``Babe: Pig
in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't speak as well, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
