<SLUG> BC-STATION-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CENTRAL STATION' OFFERS SATISFYING TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That old foreign movie staple, adorable orphan kid
brings joy into crabby old person's life, gets a nice, tough
workout in the Brazilian film ``Central Station.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Walter Salles' often realistic, sometimes mildly
magical road movie has all the standard heart-tugging features as
well. There's an adorable, unkempt moppet (Vinicius de Oliveira)
who can shed tears on cue while maintaining a brave expression.
Then there's the series of unnervingly helpful strangers who, for
all their poverty and unrewarded hard work, happily reassure us
that most people are wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Having none of this, though _ and thereby saving the project
from terminal twinkliness _ is Fernanda Montenegro. The 67-year-old
actress, who you may recognize from the Brazilian features ``Hour
of the Star'' and ``They Don't Wear Black Tie,'' creates such a
genuinely, even gleefully, selfish sourpuss here that her eventual
redemption plays like a real victory of the human spirit rather
than just a manipulative cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's Dora is a retired, never-loved-nor-married
schoolteacher who supplements her pension by writing letters for
illiterates at Rio de Janeiro's main train station. At night, she
takes the letters home to her crummy apartment, shares them and
derisive laughs with her only friend (Marilia Pera) and shoves them
in a drawer, never to be mailed.
</P>
<P>
   De Oliveira's Josue is the son of one of Dora's hapless
customers, a young woman who's trying to contact the boy's no good
drunk of a father somewhere in the vast, northern interior. When
Josue's mother is hit by a bus, Dora learns she can make good bucks
by turning the 9-year-old over to a private adoption agency.
Informed that kids his age are only marketable for organ
transplants, Dora is uncharacteristically moved by conscience and
engineers an escape. With both of their lives at stake, it's time
to hit the road and hunt down Josue's father.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully shot against the semi-arid landscape of Brazil's
Bahia district, the trip naturally becomes a journey of discovery
for the unwanted boy and the bitter old woman. Setbacks abound, and
they keep running into Christians of wildly divergent stripes (for
all of that, Salles refrains from posing religion as the answer to
Dora and Josue's problems).
</P>
<P>
   While the inevitable tough love blooms between our reluctant
fellow travelers, the real emotional heart of ``Central Station''
belongs to Dora, as Montenegro gradually reveals the
disappointments that have made her what she is and the hopes that
keep her going. It's a world class performance that uplifts a
formula foreign film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
