<SLUG> BC-FRIES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOME FRIES' A BIT HALF-BAKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 { Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Home Fries'' tries hard to be quirky _ too hard,
in fact. The effort shows. Its dimwitted characters seem to have
come straight from an appearance on ``The Jerry Springer Show,''
only somewhere along the way they lost their low-life credibility.
That problem extends to the film itself, which is less a movie than
a series of interconnected sketches. Certainly there are some
amusing moments, but since you never believe in the characters, you
have a hard time becoming involved in their story.
</P>
<P>
   The social life of the Texas small town in ``Home Fries''
revolves around the greasy counter and plastic tables of the
Burger-Matic franchise. Sally (Drew Barrymore) mans the
drive-through counter, hiding her eight-month pregnancy beneath the
window. The father of her baby is an old lout named Henry (Chris
Ellis), who deceived the good-hearted Sally about his marital
status and now won't own up to either the relationship or the
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, Henry gets his comeuppance, courtesy of a couple of
weekend warriors piloting a military helicopter. They just mean to
scare the guy, but it goes much deeper than that. Much deeper. It
turns out that the two National Guard pilots (Luke Wilson, Jake
Busey) have ulterior motives for their domestic terrorism, as does
Henry's ``grieving'' widow (the marvelous Catherine O'Hara).
</P>
<P>
   Since everyone here seems to either be related to each other or
desirous of such a connection, it's no surprise that the film's one
romantic coupling (Barrymore and Wilson, a real-life pair as well)
employs a family tree more twisted than a cypress. Can a man be a
good father and a big brother, too? It's a quandary best left to
Solomon _ or Springer _ to sort out.
</P>
<P>
   The darkly comic script (written several years ago by Vince
Gilligan, currently the supervising producer of ``The X-Files'')
has a few inspired scenes, among them a foiled robbery at the
Burger-Matic and a charming Lamaze session between Wilson and
Barrymore. But despite the twists and turns, ``Home Fries'' has a
rather thin premise at its core and, ultimately, doesn't take you
any place too interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore, with a huge belly and curly hair straight out of
Little Orphan Annie, is largely wasted here. Barrymore certainly
can be quite fetching when she's sweet and smiling (see ``The
Wedding Singer''), but, if given the chance, she can do a whole lot
more, too. (See ``Ever After.'')
</P>
<P>
   The film's treasure is O'Hara as a widow and mother whose
passive-aggressive tendencies could fill a dozen psychological case
books. O'Hara takes the character to places you never would have
imagined. It's too bad the movie doesn't always have the courage _
or the inspiration _ to do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      11-24 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINNAMON STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 This is the seventh of eight columns by Francois Payard, the chef
and owner of Payard Patisserie and Bistro in Manhattan. Payard's
collaborator on these columns is Dorie Greenspan.  
 By FRANCOIS PAYARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I heard a story that may or may not be true, but it certainly
makes a point. After World War II, inspectors were going through
the food depots somewhere in France and discovered that most of the
supplies had been ravaged by rats.
</P>
<P>
   One observant inspector was supposed to have said: ``We can be
sure of only one thing _ the rats were French. The cinnamon is
untouched.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Americans love cinnamon, that's about how much we
French don't. Vanilla is the typical Frenchman's favorite flavor,
so you can imagine the adjustment I had to make when I came to work
in this country. Fortunately for me, I've come to like cinnamon _
as long as it's not overpowering. These puff-pastry cookies are
perfect for my taste: they sandwich just a dollop of
cinnamon-scented pastry cream.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for these festive cookies, great for the
holidays, came from a classic French petit four: the allumette, or
match, a thin rectangle of puff pastry topped with a baked-on
glaze.
</P>
<P>
   For my cookies, made with store-bought puff pastry, the pastry
is rolled paper thin and spread with royal icing, a blend of
confectioners' sugar and egg white. Then _ and here's a feature
that makes them right for the holidays _ the pastry can be frozen
for a month.
</P>
<P>
   When you want cookies, all you have to do is defrost, cut out (I
make these star-shaped) and bake in a double process: first you put
the cookies into a hot oven to set the icing, which pulls away from
the pastry, so that you can lift it off and keep it aside; next you
bake the bottoms until they're puffed and perfectly caramelized, a
trick to avoid the common problem of soggy half-done puff pastry.
Give the cookies their pastry cream filling, and you're set.
</P>
<P>
   You can add ground cinnamon to the icing if you want more of
that spice, or sprinkle the icing with colored sugar or even
sprinkles. You can vary the pastry cream, too. Make a plain pastry
cream and flavor it with orange zest, instant coffee or cocoa
powder; or, if you're French, go for vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   CINNAMON STARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes plus 4 hours chilling and drying
</P>
<P>
   { pound packaged all-butter puff pastry
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   3 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   5{ cups confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. On a sheet of parchment paper, roll out the puff pastry into
a paper-thin rectangle. Prick it deeply all over with the tines of
a fork. Slide the paper and pastry onto a baking sheet. Cover with
plastic wrap and chill for at least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare the pastry cream: In a medium saucepan, combine the
milk and cinnamon sticks. Place over high heat and bring to a boil,
then immediately remove from the heat. Cover and allow to sit for 5
minutes. Strain, and discard the cinnamon sticks. In a medium bowl,
combine the sugar, flour and cornstarch; whisk to blend. In another
bowl, whisk 4 eggs until frothy, then add them to the dry
ingredients. Whisk the mixture vigorously, and while whisking, pour
the hot milk into the bowl. Return the mixture to the saucepan, and
place over medium heat. Whisk without stopping until the pastry
cream comes to a boil; cook 1 minute longer. Pour the cream onto a
piece of plastic wrap laid on a baking sheet. Cover with plastic
wrap, and refrigerate at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare the royal icing: In a mixer with a paddle attachment,
or by hand with a whisk, beat the egg whites on low speed until
foamy. Gradually add the confectioners' sugar, and beat until the
icing is shiny and thick as taffy. Keep at room temperature until
needed.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove the puff pastry from the refrigerator. Using an offset
spatula, spread the royal icing evenly over the pastry. Set aside
at room temperature until the icing dries, 1 to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   5. To bake the cookies, preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Use a
star-shaped (or any other shape) cookie cutter to cut out the
cookies. Release the cookies from the cutter by blowing into the
cutter. Put the cookies on a baking sheet lined with parchment
paper, and place in the oven. Immediately turn the oven off and
bake until the icing tops separate from the puff pastry bottoms.
Remove from the oven, and return the oven to 400 degrees. Carefully
pull the icing tops off the pastry bottoms, and place the tops on a
large plate; set aside. Return the bottoms to the oven and bake
until the pastry is golden and caramelized, about 10 to 15 minutes.
Cool the cookies on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, whisk the chilled pastry cream to loosen it, and
put it in a pastry bag with a star tip. Pipe a little pastry cream
onto each pastry bottom (or put on a small dollop with a spoon).
Cap with a royal icing top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 60 cookies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
