A7560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      11-24 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: CLOSE RACE FOR TOP RATINGS; `RUGRATS' AND NICKELODEON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With only Wednesday night left in the November ratings sweep
period, the final standings are still very much in doubt; what is
not in doubt is that millions were spent to doctor some prime-time
schedules that will enter the holiday season still looking pale and
sickly.
</P>
<P>
   The headline that NBC has tried almost desperately to avoid may
still be written. For the first time, Fox may beat NBC in the only
race that both networks count: pre-eminence among the
18-to-49-year-old audience that advertisers most covet. As of
Monday night, the two networks were in a virtual dead heat; Fox
executives predicted Wednesday that the photo would show a
flat-footed tie.
</P>
<P>
   What is indisputable is Fox's growing ability to take young male
viewers away from NBC. Fox will beat NBC in every male category.
``I think whatever the results, we're coming out of November
sending the message that Fox is hip and cool again,'' said David
Hill, the chairman of Fox Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly close is the race to win among total viewers, where
CBS, thanks to its store of viewers over 50, has been pressing NBC.
</P>
<P>
   What a victory will mean is certainly debatable, especially for
NBC, which has seen its sweep dominance end, if not its four-year
sweep winning streak among those young adults. NBC pulled out
almost every stop over the last two weeks, tossing in theatrical
movies to supplant its gasping Monday night comedies, and using up
valuable original episodes of other series to fill holes left by
failed new shows.
</P>
<P>
   The price NBC paid to stave off defeat is eclipsed only by the
price Fox paid to try to steal a win. The network essentially
tossed out every weak show on its schedule, (much easier for Fox
because it programs only 15 hours to the other networks' 22)
filling in with video specials aimed at rubberneckers, featuring
attacks by alligators and endless car crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Fox may have paid as much as $80 million for bragging rights.
That was the cost of the film ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park,''
which Fox, in almost total disregard of its long-term value, tossed
into the sweep competition twice within 24 days.
</P>
<P>
   ABC did not have a great month, falling off about 9 percent
among young adult viewers. But at least some of ABC's new shows are
holding their own. ABC's problem is its abysmal showing on
Thursdays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ABC may also have to reconsider the financial wisdom of using
big movies for ratings: the network spent more than $20 million for
``Mission Impossible'' and got about 10 percent of the Thursday
audience for its money.
</P>
<P>
   As for CBS, it played this sweep more conservatively,
pre-empting the fewest hours of any network, hoping to build a
following for its regular series. That appears to be working in a
few places, notably Monday, when ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' is
emerging as a hit, and Tuesday when ``JAG'' has begun to draw a
large if not very young audience.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS still finds itself in the odd position of having the
most viewers, yet finishing fourth among both the
18-to-49-year-olds and the 25-to-54-year-olds that CBS always
argues are a better target for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the smaller networks, WB continues to make good progress
with its teen-heavy audience; while UPN has had disastrous falloffs
across the board.
</P>
<P>
   One note that every network, broadcast or cable, might start to
pay more attention to. Overall television use by those hotly sought
18-to-49-year-olds fell by 4 percent this month.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   First Lesson in Hype
</P>
<P>
   Even Nickelodeon, the cable network parents would least expect
to disappoint their children, could not resist a Hollywood-hype
gimmick last week that may have done exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugrats,'' one of the most popular children's shows in
history, normally appears weeknights at 7:30 p.m. But Nickelodeon
took it off the air from Tuesday through Friday last week to help
promote the movie based on the show, which opened Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At tune-in time for the television show, children were told,
``The Rugrats have gone to Hollywood, but they'll be back in their
normal time slot next Monday.'' Although the message was not overt
(``Go see the movie''), children naturally could be expected to ask
their parents what was meant by ``the Rugrats have gone to
Hollywood,'' and after hearing the explanation, their next question
would logically be, ``Can I go see the movie?''
</P>
<P>
   Albie Hecht, president of film and television entertainment at
Nickelodeon, said it was difficult for a family movie to get
attention today amid the clamor over ``the big blockbuster type
movies that compete with a G-rated or even a PG-rated family
movie'' for customers. ``We thought this would help generate
excitement for the movie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The move also gave ``Hey Arnold!,'' Nickelodeon's second most
popular show, also scheduled for a feature film _ extra exposure,
filling in for ``Rugrats'' at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugrats'' is not only the most popular children's show on
television but also normally the most-watched entertainment show on
cable aside from pro wrestling. That's a hefty audience to entice
to movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   If the television tease bothered some parents, it may have
helped the film. ``The Rugrats Movie'' had the fourth-best opening
weekend ($27.3 million gross) in animated-film history, behind
three Disney hits, ``The Lion King,'' ``Pocahontas'' and ``Toy
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
