<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER25-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nerds 2.0.1. zooms like MTV documentary but settles in to PBS
style
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nerds 2.0.1: A Brief History of the Internet'' (8 EST tonight
on WGTV) may be brief compared to the sprawling encyclopedia of Ken
Burns. But by the regular blinkety-blink standards of television,
it's practically an eternity: three full hours on, yes, the history
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, host Robert X. Cringley (PBS's online technology
columnist and host of the previous ``Triumph of the Nerds'') and
his producers try mightily to make their subject rock. The first 20
minutes zoom like an MTV documentary, flitting from subject to
subject (including a brief interview with an Internet ``sex
industry worker''). It's shallow and scattershot, and therefore
looks like much of the rest of TV instead of like PBS, as if your
English teacher stood outside the classroom before a lecture on
``Romeo and Juliet'' yelling ``Teenaged lust! Come and get it!''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Nerds'' finally settles down, though, it looks a lot like
PBS, and it tells an interesting story, although possibly at
greater length than most viewers will want to sit through. Cringley
takes us through his ``glossary of geek,'' explaining what
``digital'' means and how information is moved around on the Net in
``packets.''
</P>
<P>
   Cringley starts his tour with the launch of Sputnik in 1957 by
the Soviet Union, and the boost it gave to the U.S. space program.
It turns out that NASA gave us more than Tang and Walter Cronkite;
it also gave us Arpanet (for Advanced Research Projects Agency),
the forerunner of today's Internet, as the government and
universities began finding ways to share information among
computers. From that to Matt Drudge in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In additon to talking to big names like Bill Gates and Steven
Jobs, Cringely interviews lesser-knowns like Ray Tomlinson, the guy
who was fiddling around with the origins of e-mail, looked at his
typewriter keyboard and decided the ``(at)'' above the ``2'' key
had promise.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, though, the boys tinkering in their garages give
way to the venture capitalists, and the pioneering ``Soul of a New
Machine'' spirit starts being all about the money.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
