<SLUG> BC-TALKIN-RADIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. KABC GETS WAKE-UP CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Marc (Mr. KABC) Germain, new interim morning host
at talk station KABC-AM (790), says waking up early may be the
hardest part of going up against 85 competitors on the radio dial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting up that early _ it was a big struggle today,'' he said
Friday, his first day in the bleary-eyed airshift that begins at 5
a.m. ``But it's very exciting to host morning drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Germain segued from talker KFI-AM (640) to KABC almost two years
ago. He's doing the q&AMP;a segment familiar to fans of his Mr. KABC
alter-ego in the first hour of the new morning program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the show is talking about topical issues and the
news of the day,'' he explained, ``which is what KABC does
throughout the day.''
</P>
<P>
   With the end of KABC's previous morning team of Ken Minyard and
Peter Tilden last Thursday, general-interest talker Joe Crummey
moved into Germain's newly vacated 9 p.m. weekday slot. Crummey
will continue his weekend hosting duties.
</P>
<P>
   Minyard, who handled the KABC morning show for 26 years, has
hinted of debuting a new program with his son as co-host, possibly
at forthcoming talk outlet KRLA-AM (1110), which goes on the air
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK, NEW YORK: Longtime record spinners Scott Muni and Dave
Herman were fired recently from New York's WNEW-FM, which has been
trying to make a go of a ``classic rock and classic jocks'' format.
</P>
<P>
   Muni and Herman are New York rock radio veterans. Herman worked
at the old progressive-rock WABC-FM, moving to WNEW in 1972 as
morning host until switching to nights 10 years later. After a
stint at WXRK-FM _ known locally as K-Rock _ he returned to WNEW as
morning man in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Muni, known as ``The Professor,'' has worked in New York radio
for five decades, starting at the old WMCA-AM in 1959 when Top 40
radio was in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Muni moved to the legendary WABC-AM before signing on
at free-form rocker WOR-FM. In 1967, he joined WNEW, which had just
adopted a progressive-rock music mix.
</P>
<P>
   During his 31 years at WNEW, Muni served as program director,
operations manager and, for the most part, afternoon-drive host.
</P>
<P>
   HELLO AND GOODBYE: Ex-KHJ Boss Jock Charlie Tuna segues to
mornings Monday on adult-standards KLAC-AM (570), replacing Don
Imus who moves to KRLA. ... KLOS-FM (95.5) afternoon-drive host
Garth Kemp exits the station at the end of the year to focus on his
work as weatherman at KABC-TV (Channel 7).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
