<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7569 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-24 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One example of Susan's improved status is that this Thanksgiving
she'll have leftovers. When you're homeless you can usually find a
free turkey dinner, but leftovers are for people with kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Susan was the one-eyed red-haired woman with the dog
and the cardboard sign standing on the sidewalk outside a gourmet
market in Santa Rosa. Because of her looks or her dog or the fact
she was asking for money from people who'd come shopping for a
special on French Brie, it was Susan's lucky spot and often she got
enough for a $38 motel room for herself and her dog.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago Susan told me her story and said what she
wished for 1998 was a new eye and a job, because no one was going
to hire her looking like she did.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people decided to invest in Susan, helping her to
get an eye prosthesis, enroll in a computer class and put together
enough money to move into an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, six months after Susan got off the street and started
working, it looks like her benefactors were right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am finally back in the rat race and I love it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day we had coffee together, like any two people
before work, talking about mothers and kids, diets, even hot
flashes.
</P>
<P>
   Susan's mother died this summer. She knew Susan's luck was off
but never that she was as desperate as homeless. ``It was good,
though, before she died I could tell her that I had my eye, a place
to live, a job and a boyfriend. She knew I was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan told her two sons all the details, giving them the
newspaper stories about her to read. Her older son, a 29-year-old
social worker, was embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me, `How could you do that?' I told him it is just
something that happened. It's over. It's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan's gained a little weight and she's boxed up some of her
snugger clothes to give away. She's delivering them to a woman who
once gave her a box of hand-me-downs. ``Now she can give mine to
someone else who needs them.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan used to start her hustle early in the morning, but now she
works late hours. She misses the mornings, she says, and having her
dog, Rinky, accompany her everywhere, but the job dictates her
routine.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her relative prosperity, Susan has not become a
consumer. She doesn't have a phone because she doesn't want phone
bills. Some day, she says, she'll get a computer and talk to her
sons by e-mail. She frowns over the price of a scone and says she
can't believe what some people spend their money on. She doesn't
buy new clothes. This day she's wearing a purple top from Goodwill
but she has a new haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite possession is a blue bicycle that one of her
benefactors, whom she calls ``my angel,'' gave to her and which
gets her to work and across town.
</P>
<P>
   Her only consumer purchase is a remote control to go with the TV
that her boyfriend found beside a trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her what her luxuries are and she says dried cranberries
which she eats like candy and ginger-flavored granola. Her favorite
entertainment is ``going to garage sales and blowing a buck or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan works at a convenience store in the same neighborhood
where she used to panhandle. Some of the same clerks from the fancy
store come in and buy their morning coffee but she doubts many of
them recognize her behind the cash register. ``I have two eyes
now,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   One who did was an assistant manager who Susan remembered as
friendlier than most when she stood on his sidewalk. ``He came into
my store and said he was being transferred. I bought him a soda.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan used to spend her days worrying about where to spend the
night. I ask her what homeless people worry about when they finally
get their own place and she says ``keeping it.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds, ``I try not to think about what I don't have. I guess
I worry about not having enough money, but doesn't everybody worry
about having enough money?''
</P>
<P>
   It is a slow process, moving off the streets, and even though
Susan maintains that she never felt that alien from the people who
handed her dollars from their car windows she's clearly crossed
over into the workaday world.
</P>
<P>
   After work she watches TV and crochets a blanket. Last summer
she grew tomatoes and roses in her back yard.
</P>
<P>
   She says that when she and her boyfriend can afford to fix their
car she wants to drive to Jenner and spend the night in the car.
For nostalgia's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that sound stupid?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   As we leave the coffee house a young man approaches with a gas
can and asks, ``Do either of you ladies have a quarter so I can buy
some gas?''
</P>
<P>
   I give him some change and ask Susan how much gas you can get
for a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   She says, ``He probably doesn't even have a car.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
