<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      11-24 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURE CURE FOR THE GRAVY JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, with an entire Thanksgiving meal marshaled and ready,
countless cooks will quake over the last detail: the gravy. When
it's a once-a-year thing, there are no guarantees that the gravy
will come out perfectly smooth, deeply flavored and nicely browned.
There is an alternative, though. And, unlike the concoctions that
come out of jars, it requires no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   It is a reduction sauce, the easiest, most malleable sauce a
cook can make. In fact, it is a precursor to pan gravy, but because
it doesn't use flour, there's no chance of lumps or a starchy,
uncooked taste.
</P>
<P>
   When you roast meat or poultry at high heat, bits of skin, meat
and fat stick to the surface of the pan, becoming dark brown and
concentrated; meat juices and rendered fat also gather at the
bottom. If you remove the roast, add liquid to the pan and place it
over high heat while stirring, you incorporate these essences into
that liquid. At the same time, some of the liquid evaporates _
reduces _ thereby intensifying its own flavor and thickening
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not essential, most reduction sauces are finished
with a bit of butter, oil or cream to add smoothness and even more
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of ways to enhance a reduction sauce. The
more flavorful the liquid used, the more intense the sauce. Stock
is the most common, but you can also add cream, milk, wine, sherry
or port, fruit or vegetable juice, or even the liquid from soaking
dried mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating other flavors as you cook the sauce also boosts
intensity, and adding bits of cooked meat or vegetables to the
finished sauce can add bulk and texture. (Traditional turkey gravy,
for example, uses giblets simmered to produce stock.)
</P>
<P>
   Here's the recipe for a basic sauce, followed by a variation for
those who want a thicker, more traditional gravy, and a few ideas
for jazzing it up. The basic recipe can be doubled or tripled,
something to consider Thursday, when the crowd arrives. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BASIC REDUCTION SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallot, onion or scallion
</P>
<P>
   3 cups stock or water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons softened butter or olive oil (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Remove the roast and pour off all but 1 or 2 tablespoons of
the cooking fat (if there are nonfatty juices in the skillet or
roasting pan, leave them there). Place the roasting pan over high
heat. (Use two burners if the pan is large.) Add the shallot and
cook, stirring, until it softens, about 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the liquid and cook, stirring and scraping to loosen the
brown bits at the bottom of the pan. Allow the liquid to boil for
about 5 minutes, or until about a third of it evaporates. (This is
a good time to carve the meat; the boiling liquid needs only
occasional stirring.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Turn the heat to medium-low and add the butter or oil, a
little at a time, stirring well after each addition. Taste and
season if necessary with salt and pepper, then serve with the
meat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 2 cups. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make thickened gravy: Combine 1 tablespoon cornstarch with \
cup cold water. (It will dissolve easily.) Stir this into the sauce
after incorporating the butter or oil, and heat, stirring, until
thickened, just about 1 minute. If you want even thicker gravy,
repeat with another tablespoon of cornstarch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
