<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, TIME IS A REAL LUXURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rich, as Scott Fitzgerald (or one of his characters)
observed, really are different from the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   They wear fancier wristwatches.
</P>
<P>
   A recent full-page ad in a national newspaper pictured some of
the models available. They weren't called watches, of course. They
were ``timepieces'' and ``chronographs.''
</P>
<P>
   The page was dominated by one with a dial the diameter of a
grapefruit and a leather band of corresponding size. I don't know
if the picture was enlarged to attract attention, or if it was a
specialty item for eccentrics who prefer to strap their
chronographs to the calves of their legs.
</P>
<P>
   That particular one went for only $4,580 and was the cheapest,
if ``cheap'' is the word for it, on the page.
</P>
<P>
   The others were priced in a range from $5,200 to $14,400,
although the copy in the ad noted that the seller of these
timepieces carried no fewer than 7,000 styles, retailing from
$250,000 to as little as $25.
</P>
<P>
   The $25 model was not shown.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the seven pictured were described as having automatic
movements. Others were said to have quartz accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is you'd hope so! It would be pretty disappointing
to pay 10 or 15 grand for a watch _ excuse me, a chronograph _ and
find out the darned thing wasn't self-winding and lost a couple of
minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   If price is the bad news, the good news is that these fine
instruments come with free lifetime battery replacement by trained
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I had a watch battery replaced it was by the clerk
behind the counter in a country hardware store. I didn't ask if she
was a trained professional, but the watch has worked fine for two
years going on three.
</P>
<P>
   For those folks for whom price is no consideration, buying a
chronograph like the ones in the ad must be an impulse kind of
thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the event your heavy schedule doesn't permit you to travel to
New York or Houston or Palm Beach or any of the other cities where
this purveyor of fine timepieces has establishments, you can pick
up the phone, dial an 800 number, and make the purchase while you
happen to be thinking of it.
</P>
<P>
   And the best part of all, you can wear your fabulous
automatically moving or quartz-accurate chronograph for two years
interest free with no down payment!
</P>
<P>
   After the words ``no down payment'' there was an asterisk about
one-fourth the size of the head of a pin. And, at the bottom of the
page, another asterisk, this one about half the size of the hole
you'd make if you pricked the paper with the point of the pin.
</P>
<P>
   After that second asterisk there was a single line of print that
ran the width of the page, in type so incredibly small that I
couldn't read it with my glasses on. So I got a magnifying glass
from the other room.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the magnifier it still was hard to make out. As nearly
as I could tell, it was saying the monthly minimum payment was $25.
</P>
<P>
   It also was explaining what would befall you in the way of
interest if you bought one of those quarter-million-dollar
timepieces and didn't get it paid off in the 24-month period of
grace.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell you right now that every month, when I wrote my $25
check, the deadline would be in the back of my mind, right there
along with death and taxes. And those two years would be gone like
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Ironic, isn't it, that for anyone who can afford a watch like
that, time doesn't really matter so much. I guess that's another
way we're different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
