<HEADLINE>
`THIS REALLY TAKES A MAJOR BURDEN OFF OF GORE'S BACK' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The road to the White House became a bit smoother
for Al Gore on Tuesday after Attorney General Janet Reno declined
to appoint a special prosecutor to probe alleged fund-raising
abuses by the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an independent counsel rummaging in possibly
illegal and potentially embarrassing fund-raising incidents had
hung like a dark cloud over Gore's presidential ambitions ever
since Reno announced she was considering such a move in August.
</P>
<P>
   While the appointment of a prosecutor would not necessarily have
doomed Gore's chances, it would have forced him to spend precious
time and political capital responding to various charges as he
tried to wage a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the threat now lifted, political observers say Gore is in a
stronger position to discourage potential primary challengers and
concentrate on what will likely be a competitive general election
contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really takes a major burden off of Gore's back,'' said
Mark Rozell, political science professor at the University of
Pennsylvania. ``It could give him an almost unfettered path to the
presidential nomination in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Rozell noted that Republicans still are likely to raise the
embarrassing fund-raising incidents, such as Gore's visit during
the 1996 campaign to a Buddhist temple as ``evidence that Gore is
not squeaky clean.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that ``without an independent counsel it will be
hard to keep it before the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls have continued to show Gore a favorite in hypothetical
Democratic matchups for the 2000 nomination. Nevertheless, a number
of other prominent Democrats have been mentioned as possibles in
the race, including House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno had appointed an independent counsel, potential
challengers may have been emboldened to take on the vice president,
arguing that Gore was too vulnerable to beat a strong Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from dodging an independent counsel, Gore recently
strengthened his position among the party faithful with his
aggressive campaigning for candidates in the midterm election, when
Democrats picked up five seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
   He also does not appear to have been hurt by the scandal
surrounding President Clinton involving former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats suggested that voters are so turned off by
independent counsels, particularly after Kenneth Starr's probe into
Whitewater and the Lewinsky matter, that if Reno had sought one for
Gore it may have backfired on the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this country are disgusted with independent
counsels. They have become witch hunts,'' said Molly Beth Malcolm,
the chairwoman of the Texas Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Woodburn, the chairman of the New Hampshire Democratic
Party, said that voters in the state that holds the first
presidential primary were not paying much attention to Reno's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   He said the vice president has to overcome other obstacles if he
wants the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test for Gore is not the independent counsel. The test for
Gore is how he is going to relate to real people on the ground
here,'' said Woodburn. The chairman said that some voters in the
New England state have low expectations for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think he is stiff, he can't relate to people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Woodburn said in today's volatile political atmosphere, no
one can predict where the candidates will be in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of political environment where one day you
are up, the next day you are down. The key is to be up a week
before the primary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
