<SLUG> BC-COURT-CENSUS-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO REVIEW COUNTING METHOD PROPOSED FOR 2000 CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case that could alter America's political
landscape and redirect billions of dollars in federal money, the
Supreme Court on Monday will examine whether a new method to
conduct the 2000 census is legal.
</P>
<P>
   The method would employ statistical sampling to help determine
the number of people in the United States rather than relying
completely on the traditional system of mailing out questionnaires
and then dispatching thousands of enumerators to hunt down those
who don't respond.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of sampling say it would help correct an expected large
undercount in the next census.
</P>
<P>
   They point to a 1992 study by the National Academy of Sciences
that showed the 1990 census missed 8.4 million people and
double-counted 4.4 million others. The study also said that a
disproportionate number of those missed were minorities and recent
immigrants living in urban or rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that if the 2000 census uses the old method, the
survey results will be worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau _ backed by President Clinton and
congressional Democrats _ has proposed using statistical sampling
to improve that result. Under the plan, the bureau would use
traditional methods to count everyone living in 90 percent of the
households in each of the country's census tracks _ neighborhoods
containing about 1,700 houses each. The bureau then would use the
data gathered to estimate the number of people in the remaining 10
percent of the population who haven't been located.
</P>
<P>
   Following that count, the bureau would conduct another,
independent census _ known as the Integrated Coverage Measurement
(ICM) _ of 750,000 specially selected households that, when put
together, mirror the country as a whole. This second count would
much more intensive, with enumerators tracking down and questioning
every person, not just the head of the household, in each of the
750,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau then would compare the results of the ICM with those
of the original 90-percent census. In areas where the two counts
differ, the bureau would use the ICM figures to adjust the original
census.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the plan, including congressional Republicans, say
it would violate the Constitution, which mandates an ``actual
enumeration'' of the population every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Walker, spokesman for Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who is
chairman of the House subcommittee that overseas Census Bureau
appropriations, said the framers of the Constitution called for an
actual count of population and that sampling could result in large
errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration wants to `guesstimate' 10 percent of the
population using the unproven technique of sampling,'' he said.
``It's just crazy to take chances with something as important as
the census.''
</P>
<P>
   The census is used to determine the makeup of the House of
Representatives and state legislatures and to decide where federal
funds should go.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists from both political parties say sampling would turn
up increases in the number of people living in historically
Democratic areas, giving the party an advantage when new boundaries
for congressional, state and local legislative districts are drawn
after the 2000 census has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   These strategists also say that since sampling would find
increases in the number of poor people counted in urban and rural
areas, cities and agricultural counties would receive extra federal
dollars at the expense of suburban communities.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., argues that sampling is
not about helping Democrats or hurting Republicans, but about
achieving the ``most accurate census possible.'' She adds, ``It's
about basic fairness and getting money and political representation
to the people who need it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of sampling have attempted to block its use by filing
lawsuits in federal district courts, claiming the method is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has fought the suits by saying that
the plaintiffs _ congressional Republicans in one case and a group
of 16 individuals in six states plus officials from Cobb County,
Ga., in another _ have no right to file the motions. The
administration argues that since the census has yet to take place,
the plaintiffs have not been hurt by it and therefore cannot say it
is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In September, a three-judge federal district court in Richmond,
Va., unanimously ruled, in the case of the 16 individuals and Cobb
County, Ga., that federal law bars the use of sampling for the
purpose of apportioning congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   That court said the six states where the 16 people live are
``substantially likely'' to lose seats in the House if the national
head count is determined partly by sampling. As a result, the lower
court found, the 16 can legitimately claim that they would be hurt
by prospective ``vote dilution'' of the sort that the Supreme Court
has recognized in the past as a basis for challenging an
apportionment plan.
</P>
<P>
   The six states are Connecticut, Massachusetts, Minnesota,
Missouri, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in August, a separate three-judge district court panel
here in Washington, D.C., issued a unanimous ruling in the suit by
House Republicans, saying sampling violated federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The D.C. court ruled that the lawmakers did have the right to
file the suit. It said sampling threatens the ``institutional
interests'' of the House because it could alter that body's
composition.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the courts' decisions, Clinton and the congressional
Republicans agreed last month to postpone their fight over whether
to use sampling in the next census until the Supreme Court rules on
the two cases. The high court is expected to decide the case in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that even if the court rules sampling legal,
they will still try to make sure that the 2000 census uses
traditional counting methods.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said an experiment in 1991 by the National Academy of
Sciences to conduct the count using the old method plus sampling
resulted in a number of errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If sampling was used again and the same errors occurred, the
whole 2000 census might be ruled invalid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pat Cantwell, a bureau statistician, said the errors in
the experimental census were quickly discovered and corrected. He
added that even with the errors, the experimental census was more
accurate than the original census.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
