<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT25-COX     11-24 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CITING AOL DEAL, MICROSOFT URGES GOVERNMENT TO DROP LAWSUIT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. attorneys urged the federal
government Tuesday to drop its antitrust case, saying the America
Online-Netscape merger has created a seismic shift in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry can change dramatically overnight. And this shows
that government is five steps behind when it comes to regulating
this technology,'' said William H. Neukom, Microsoft's general
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom said the AOL-Netscape deal creates an Internet powerhouse
that will give consumers new choices in markets ranging from web
hosting to Internet browsing to e-commerce. It undercuts the
government's argument that Microsoft is stifling competition in
these areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's lead attorney, John L. Warden, added that
Microsoft would move to have the case dismissed when the government
completed presenting its evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the government has no intention of withdrawing this
case,'' said lead Justice Department attorney David Boies.
</P>
<P>
   Underlining the government's main intention, that Microsoft has
used its dominance in operating systems to stifle competition in
other markets, Boies said that ``even if the AOL-Netscape deal goes
through, the impediments to competition in the operating-system
market still exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning's announcement of the $4.3-billion merger
between Dulles, Va.-based America Online Inc. and Silicon Valley's
Netscape Communications Corp., which markets the popular Netscape
Internet browser, jolted the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   AOL will swap 0.45 of its shares for each Netscape share,
valuing Netscape at $41.12 a share. AOL will enter into a second
marketing agreement with Sun Microsystems Inc., in which Sun will
pay AOL $350 million for the right to sell Netscape software. AOL,
in turn, will pay Sun $500 million for various services and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies testified against Microsoft in the
government's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies aren't running scared from Microsoft,'' Neukom
said. ``They are running hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Many attorneys and legal scholars predict that the pending
merger will have some effect on the antitrust case. In particular,
if the government wins its case against Microsoft, some believe the
shake-up likely would influence the type of remedy selected to curb
Microsoft's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the 20 states that have filed suit
against Microsoft have not been specific about what remedies or
penalties they would favor if U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson rules in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Options would range from Jackson giving Microsoft a stern
warning to curb its bullying behavior to a move to break up the
company by insisting that it spin off different product
departments.
</P>
<P>
   William Kovacic, a professor at George Washington University
School of Law, says the AOL-Netscape deal means Jackson would be
less likely to impose the most stringent remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the deal, the judge is less likely to think he has
to take specific actions to reduce Microsoft's dominant market
position,'' Kovacic said. ``Now there's evidence that the market is
taking care of it. So it takes a great burden off his shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
