</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Nov. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another powerful storm will affect the Northwest on Thursday,
bringing inclement weather to northwest California and western
sections of Oregon and Washington. Windswept heavy rain will buffet
coastal areas as a steady stream of moisture from the eastern
Pacific is lifted by an approaching cold front. Local flooding will
occur, particularly where the ground is saturated from recent rain.
As the damp air is further lifted and cooled by the interior
mountains, rain will turn to heavy snow above 4,500 feet with over
a foot of fresh snow blanketing sections of the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and seasonably warm conditions will extend from southern
California to southern sections of the interior West. Skies will be
mainly sunny across the region, though filaments of clouds will
obscure the sun at times near the Rockies. Meanwhile, partly sunny
skies and mild air will extend eastward into the Plains where
another day of unseasonable warmth covers western Kansas and
eastern Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   After a clear and cold start, ample sunshine will boost
temperatures to near normal levels from the northern Middle
Atlantic states to New England as high pressure drifts off the
Eastern Seaboard. Farther west, scattered showers will develop near
a cold front pressing through the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
Isolated thunderstorms could occur as a jet stream disturbance
passes overhead. Elsewhere, partly sunny and warm conditions will
cover much of the Southeast and Florida with isolated showers
burgeoning in the increasingly humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Late Season Storm
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storm Nicole swirled to life in the far eastern
Atlantic Ocean on Tuesday, a rare event given that hurricane season
officially ends November 30. The birth of tropical storm Nicole put
the Atlantic ahead of the normally more active eastern Pacific
Ocean for the number of tropical storms and hurricanes in 1998. The
Atlantic has been a busy basin in recent years. Since 1995, 53
named tropical cyclones have roamed the Atlantic, marking the
busiest four consecutive hurricane seasons on record. In contrast,
the period between 1991 and 1994 was one of quietest, spawning only
30 named storms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
