<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SHAKEUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ TO REPLACE 18 AMBASSADORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In the largest diplomatic shakeup since the
Gulf War, Iraq decided Tuesday to replace 18 key ambassadors,
including Baghdad's most visible envoy, UN ambassador Nizar
Hamdoon.
</P>
<P>
   The move, portrayed by Iraqi sources as a routine changing of
the guard, comes just months after Baghdad's ambassador to the UN's
Geneva office ignored his government's request to return to Iraq.
And it has fueled speculation among some observers that Iraq is
seeking to head off an embarrassing wave of potential defections in
its diplomatic corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what's going on in the mind of Saddam
Hussein,'' said White House foreign policy spokesman David Leavy.
``But any time he can tighten his grip on power, he will do it.
This could be one of the reasons for the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and analysts said the move to replace Hamdoon will
deprive Iraq of its most effective advocate for ending more than
seven years of economic sanctions. Leavy said the recall of Iraq's
high profile envoy appeared aimed at permitting Hussein to keep
tighter control over Iraq's message to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdoon will be replaced by his deputy, Saeed Hasan, a shy
Sorbonne-educated diplomat who admits to being allergic to the
media spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamdoon is without a doubt their best spokesperson in
English,'' said Gregory Gause, an Iraq scholar at the University of
Vermont. ``He is the smoothest and the best the Iraqis have. I
can't imagine his successor can do any better.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials said privately that the departure of Hamdoon, a
regular guest on American talk show circuit, would make it easier
for the Clinton administration to prevail in its battle of words
with Iraq. Publicly, the US expressed sarcastic ``sympathy'' for
the new diplomatic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is I feel sorry for those who have to defend
such a lost cause,'' said State Department spokesman James P.
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic shuffle also brought about changes in other key
diplomatic outposts, including Iraqi missions to the Arab League,
the UN headquarters in Geneva, and the Vienna-based International
Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling speculation of defections was the recent refusal
by &UR;  &LR; Saddam Hussein's half-brother, Barzan Tikriti, to return to
Baghdad in June from from his job as Iraq's representative to the
UN office in Geneva. Tikriti initially refused to return home in
order to be with his ailing wife, who was receiving treatment for
an illness at a Swiss hospital. But he refused to come home after
she died last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tikriti is to be replaced by Mohammed Douri, a legal expert in
the Iraqi foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdoon, a trained architect who enjoyed close relations with
the United States during the Iran-Iraq war, is expected to return
to Baghdad around the end of the year to take a senior post in the
Iraqi foreign ministry, according to Iraqi sources.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday that Hasan, who has served as his deputy for
four years, is ``probably the best replacement at this very crucial
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
