A7675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-LORDS-BOS &LR;      11-24 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LORDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN SETS STAGE FOR END TO HEREDITARY PEERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Uttering the political equivalent of ``Off with their
heads,'' Queen Elizabeth II opened a new session of Parliament
Tuesday by announcing the government's intention to get rid of
hereditary peers, those who inherit their seats in the House of
Lords.
</P>
<P>
   The queen's annual speech, in which she reads a
government-scripted list of its legislative agenda, took place at
Westminster in a ceremony replete with the regal pageantry that
many of those who want to throw out the hereditary peers say has no
place in modern British democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the paradox of having a monarch who inherited her crown
formally set the stage for the eradication of one of the most
tangible examples of aristocratic privilege also underscores the
political bind in which Prime Minister Tony Blair finds himself.
While Blair has declared war on the hereditary peers, calling their
position in the upper house of Parliament an embarrassing
anachronism, he would move similarly against the monarchy at his
own political peril.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the queen listed 21 bills the government hopes to pass,
none more controversial and central to Blair's pledge to replace
Britain's constitutional monarchy with a modern democracy than his
plans to strip the hereditary peers of their voting and speaking
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the government's agenda, which includes bills aimed at
modernizing the health, welfare, educational, and criminal justice
systems, could get bogged down if the hereditary peers decide to
obstruct Blair as their last gasp.
</P>
<P>
   While the queen's speech is traditionally received without
partisan response, there were cheers of ``Hear, hear!'' from a
number of Labor partisans when the queen said the government
intended to begin ``a process of reform to make the House of Lords
more democratic and representative.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the red-robed peers, as members of the House of Lords
are known, harrumphed in disgust, although it was unclear whether
they were registering their disapproval of Blair's plan or partisan
triumphalism.
</P>
<P>
   Some 759 of the 1,164 peers are hereditary peers, whose seats
are awarded by birthright. Blair has vowed to get rid of them, but
his vague plans to replace them and the House of Lords with a more
democratic upper house has led critics to charge that Blair merely
wants to neuter one of the few checks on his power.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has said he will give up his right to appoint so-called
life peers, who account for the other 400 or so members of the
Lords. Only 17 of the hereditary peers are Labor supporters, and
fewer than 100 are women, making them a relic of Britain's
aristocratic past.
</P>
<P>
   But many Britons, especially those in the Conservative Party,
which has traditional ties to the hereditary peers, say they are an
important balance of power. Their supporters point out that they
regularly frustrated the Conservative prime minister Margaret
Thatcher, using their powers to veto bills.
</P>
<P>
   Some peers have threatened to use those powers to frustrate
Blair's plan. But, under law, they can only delay government plans
for a year, so the most they can do is put off the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Blair later told the House of Commons it was time to end the
``feudal domination'' of the Lords by one party.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party leader William Hague dismissed the
government's legislative agenda as irrelevant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABE-REVIEW-LADN     11-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABE' SEQUEL GETS TOO DARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the whimsical swine named Babe tramped into
theaters three years ago, the film was initially perceived as a
cute little movie about a talking pig who thought he was a
sheepdog. Then it was nominated _ and deservedly so _ for seven
Oscars, including one for Best Picture, and ``Babe'' suddenly had
the aura of artistic respectability.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst thing that could have happened to the little
porker.
</P>
<P>
   With the inevitable sequel, ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' director
George Miller (who produced and co-wrote the first film) labors
under delusions of grandeur. He's so determined to prove that
``Babe'' is more than a cute little pig movie that he destroys the
franchise's delightful charm in the process. To market this dark,
dreary Fellini-esque shambles as a kid's movie is the ultimate pig
in a poke. The only children who will appreciate this movie are the
ones starved for a little more somber poignancy in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe: Pig in the City'' picks up immediately where the first
movie left off. Babe and his owner, laconic farmer Arthur Hoggett
(James Cromwell), triumphantly return from winning the sheepherding
competition, heroes to the townsfolk who once mocked them. The good
times don't last for long, though (Miller wants us to begin moping
as soon as possible), and an accident involving a well _ and caused
by Babe _ cripples Farmer Hoggett. Mrs. Hoggett (Magda Szubanski)
must then deal with the men in suits with pale faces and soulless
eyes who come to foreclose on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: Cash in on Babe's popularity by accepting an
appearance fee from a fair in the city. Hoggett reluctantly agrees
but makes his wife promise to ensure the pig's safety. That's
easier said than done. Miller's metropolis is a harsh, frightening
place populated by gun-toting, frowning people who will eagerly
knock you down, take everything you have and then kick you for good
measure. In this weirdly stylized world, the women wear string
bikinis, and the men dress in leather and chains that seem to be
taken from Miller's ``Mad Max'' wardrobe leftovers (he directed the
gritty Mel Gibson-starring flicks).
</P>
<P>
   Refuge is found in Flealands Hotel, where Babe meets stray dogs
and cats and a family of chimpanzees who perform with a pitiful
clown (Mickey Rooney). There's also a sad-eyed orangutan named
Thelonius, a melancholy creature Miller seems more interested in
than Babe, given the number of heart-rending ways he films the
animal. (I guess there are only so many mournful ways to shoot a
pig.) Babe teaches all these critters that a kind and steady heart
can endure against the darkness of the city. It's a painful lesson
to endure, both for the pig and the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who also co-wrote and co-produced ``Babe: Pig in the
City,'' made the decision to film the movie as a mixture of wildly
fantastic images, tragicomic lyricism, burlesque, satire and
pathos. It was a significant blunder, largely unsuited to the
material. While there are many beautifully filmed images in this
movie, Miller's work, taken as a whole, comes off as self-indulgent
egotism. It would have been better that the movie dissolve into
mushy treacle than this misguided homage to self-conscious cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the first film had its share of darkness. Babe, after
all, was originally ticketed as the centerpiece of the Hoggetts'
holiday meal. But ``Babe: Pig in the City'' often wallows in the
blackness with its scenes of animal cruelty. (A dog hangs from a
bridge on a chain, drowning in a brook. A goldfish slowly
asphyxiates. And so on and so on ...) You don't have to pander to
kids, but you don't have to smother them in misery, either. Miller
would do well to learn that lesson should he decide in the future
to make another pig movie designed for audiences instead of
film-school students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1835EST &QL; 
