<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS DISCOVER `WIRING' THAT CONTROLS YEAST GENES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exploiting the power of new, miniaturized ``laboratories on a
chip,'' scientists have discovered the key network of biological
controls that turn off or on all of the 6,000 genes in a baker's
yeast cell.
</P>
<P>
   It is a step, said the researchers, toward eventually tracing
the same kinds of gene controls in humans, which could lead to
better and safer drugs and a deeper understanding of health and
disease.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in the current edition of the journal Cell,
researchers led by Richard Young of the Whitehead Institute in
Cambridge, Mass. say they used the tiny silicon chip-based
analyzers, also known as DNA arrays, to identify a master ``wiring
diagram'' that enables yeast cells to regulate their genes,
one-at-a-time or in groups.
</P>
<P>
   They created the biological wiring diagram by knocking out parts
of the control mechanism, one at a time, to see which genes were
affected. In concept, it is like switching different
circuit-breakers off in a house, noting which rooms go dark and
which appliances go off, to figure out the paths controlled by the
circuit breakers.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of different on-off patterns of genes in the yeast
cell gives scientists insights into how the organism grows, mates,
and responds to environmental changes, said Young in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The report is published as other scientists, also using the
lab-on-a-chip tool, are looking for similar patterns of gene
activation and deactivation when they expose yeast organisms to
various pharmaceutical drugs. This is a quick and comprehensive way
to predict what beneficial effects and side effects the drug might
cause. Still others, in the field of what is called
pharmacogenomics, are using the DNA arrays to scan human genetic
material in a search for normal variations that explain why drugs
have different effects in different individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who headed a team from the Whitehead and UMass Medical
Center, credited the relatively new DNA chips with making possible
a great leap in analyzing how genes work. Until now, he said, using
traditional lab techniques ``it's taken us 40 years to learn how a
few dozen genes are regulated. Now, almost overnight, we're
learning how 6,000 genes work.''
</P>
<P>
   The chips are tiny silicon wafers, less than an inch square, to
which tens of thousands of DNA genetic probes are attached.
</P>
<P>
   In searching for the control circuits of the yeast cell, Young
explained, the scientists isolated all the messenger RNA _ copies
of genetic information that are produced when a gene is
``expressed,'' or switched on. When the solution of messenger RNA
was placed on the tiny chip, the tens of thousands of genetic
probes searched for specific RNA sequences. By noting which RNA
sequences were present and which were absent, the chip created a
rec-ord of which genes were on and which were off.
</P>
<P>
   Those on-off patterns were different depending on the state of
the yeast cell when its genetic information was analyzed, said
Young _ mating, responding to shortages of nutrients, or meeting
other environmental challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists knew that every gene's activity is regulated by a
protein _ part of the control mechanism. In yeast, there are about
250 activator proteins that shut genes on and off. In an effort to
determine which genes each protein regulated, the &UR;  &LR; scientists
``knocked out'' or disabled one protein at a time and noted the
gene changes using the DNA arrays.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, noted Young, the scientists thought that perhaps
knocking out even one important regulatory component would disable
the entire cell. ``Instead, what happens is that when one regulator
is knocked out, sets of genes that are involved in very specific
cellular functions shut down,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitehead scientists say they will have a complete
description of the regulatory components of yeast genes by next
summer. They are placing the results on a Web site for other
scientists to access. Otherwise, said Young, publishing all their
findings in paper journals ``would take all the volumes Cell ever
produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Other authors of the paper include Frank Holstege and Eric
Lander at the Whitehead and Michael R. Green of UMass Medical
Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
