<HEADLINE>
OTTAWA SEEKS TO BLOCK TEXAS EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Canada is pulling out the diplomatic stops to save a
native son from the deadly needle of the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stanley Faulder, a 61-year-old Albertan on death row at
the Ellis Unit prison in Huntsville, Texas, is scheduled to be
executed Dec. 10 by lethal injection for the murder of an elderly
widow. Faulder would become the first Canadian put to death in the
United States in nearly half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa is expected to take the unusual step Wednesday of filing
a ``friend of the court'' brief with the US Supreme Court in an
effort to block the execution. It is rare for a foreign government
to lend its weight to the last-ditch legal maneuvers that take
place as the hours tick down toward an execution.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy has appealed for
clemency to Secretary of State Madeline Albright, Texas Governor
George W. Bush, and the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada opposes capital punishment on a humanitarian basis, but
we also feel this individual's rights were violated under the
Vienna Convention,'' said Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Sophie
Legendre, referring to an international treaty requiring that
foreigners accused of crimes be informed that they have the right
to seek diplomatic assistance from their own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Faulder was never informed of his right to speak to the
Canadian government,'' said Legendre. ``Nor was the Canadian
government ever told he was arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of Faulder's supporters in Canada believe he is innocent.
Still, his plight has touched a nerve in a country that banned the
death penalty in 1976, and conducted its last executions in 1962
with a double hanging in Toronto. He is one of three Canadians on
death row in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely wrong, that Americans would still use such a
means of punishment,'' said Joyce Milgaard of Winnipeg, a
prisoners' rights activist whose son, David, served 23 years in
Canadian prison for a murder that later evidence showed he did not
commit. ``We can't stand by and let this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pleas reverberating from the north, there appears
little prospect that either Bush or the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles will opt for clemency. Texas executes more people than any
other state: 161 of the more than 480 convicts put to death since
the United States restored capital punishment in 1976 have been
executed in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder would be the first Canadian executed in the United
States since 1952, when Stan Buckowski of Ontario died in the gas
chamber in San Quentin, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On July 8, 1975, Faulder and a prostitute named Stormy Summers,
bent on robbery, talked their way into the home of Inez Phillips in
Gladewater, Texas, binding the 75-year-old woman with tape and
torturing her before driving a knife into her heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrible, vicious crime that still haunts our
community,'' said Gladewater Mayor Curtis Bight.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was caught in 1977, and convicted on the basis of a
confession given to police. That conviction was overturned, but he
was convicted again in 1981 on the basis of testimony from the
prostitute, who was given immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Faulder has won five stays of execution. But his
appeals appear to have run out.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Canadian Broadcasting Corp., he refused
to discuss his guilt or innocence. But he did offer views on
capital punishment. ``I'd hate for Canada to go back to the death
penalty,'' he said. ``There is no fair way you can adjudicate
capital punishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
