<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-FUNDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND INVESTORS JUMPING BACK INTO STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excited by Wall Street's surge, mutual fund investors are once
again buying stock funds in earnest, casting off months of doubt
and helping to fuel a rise in the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Only four months ago, investors were scared out of equity funds
by the stock market's steep plunge. Now they have apparently
decided that the Dow's upswing is too good to sit out. The renewed
confidence, the result of recent interest rate cuts designed to
boost the economy and quell prospects of a global recession,
represents a major shift after months of skittish sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are expected to pour $13 billion into equity funds
this month, according to Carl Wittnebert of Trimtabs.com Investment
Research, a Santa Rose, Calif. firm that estimates fund flows. That
amount is six times October's level and double September's flows,
and is an about-face from August. That month, amid cries that the
US bull market had run out of steam, investors shocked fund firms
by yanking $11 billion out of stock funds as the Dow plunged.
</P>
<P>
   November's buying also represents a strong rebound from October,
when stock funds gained a meager $2.35 billion in net new
investments, according to data released Tuesday by the Investment
Company Institute, a trade group. The Dow did not begin to pick up
until mid-October, when the Federal Reserve undertook the second of
three interest rate cuts; investors apparently waited until
November to digest the news and wade back in.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after withdrawals are factored in, net investments in
stock funds last month are only a third of year-ago levels. In
October 1997, when the US stock market first shuddered at Asia's
economic crisis, domestic stock funds still drew in a net $18.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   There is strong evidence that a major market rally will lure
fund investors back into buying, regardless of volatility or
warnings about overvalued prices. At Fidelity Investments of
Boston, the nation's largest fund firm, net sales of stock funds in
November are on track to be the strongest monthly sales so far this
year, and possibly the best November sales in five years,
spokeswoman Anne W. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity stock funds had grabbed $3 billion so far this month,
compared to outflows of $1 billion in October, she said. Overall,
Fidelity funds of all stripes would take in around $6 billion this
month, three times October's levels.
</P>
<P>
   Other fund firms also reported a rebound in sales this month.
The Vanguard Group of Valley Forge, Pa., the nation's second
largest fund company, said its stock funds would attract $2.6
billion for November, double October's level. Eighty percent of the
new cash was going into the company's popular index funds, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds attracting new cash these days are chock-a-block
with the large-company issues behind the market's new rally.
Crowley said Fidelity's best sellers included Dividend Growth,
Magellan, and Growth &AMP; Income. The latter two are closed to new
investors, meaning existing shareholders have clamored to put more
money in, she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the August crash, when the Dow sank 6.4 percent and
investors worried that the eight-year bull market was over,
stock-loving Americans switched gears and turned to conservative
investments.
</P>
<P>
   While investors are now buying stock funds again, conservative
products are still selling well this year. Although down 18 percent
last month compared to September's level, bond fund sales have
tripled so far in 1998. And year-to-date sales of money market
funds are up 129 percent. Overall, stock funds have taken in $142.7
billion over the first 10 months of 1998, a decline of 19 percent
on year-ago levels and the first time since 1994 that annual sales
may drop, ICI data showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
