A7703 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-HUD-PA     11-24 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-HUD-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  NAVY YARD NETS $14 MILLION HUD GRANT
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Nov. 24 -- A new batch of $29.9 million in loans and
grants is on the way to Philadelphia as part of a federal effort to
spur urban economic development, with a focus on luring businesses
and industry to the now-defunct Philadelphia Naval Shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development officials doled out the funding Tuesday, giving
Philadelphia a $2 million grant and $27.9 million in loans.
Philadelphia's share was the largest of $213 million in loans and
grants for development and job creation in 23 cities.
</P>
<P>
   City development officials said they will use about half of the
money to offer incentives and low interest loans to businesses to
move to an industrial park in the Navy Yard in the next five years.
The rest of the funding will go to other economic development
efforts, such as refurbishing run-down buildings and other ongoing
programs.
</P>
<P>
   All told, federal officials believe the Philadelphia funding
would lead to almost 1,800 new jobs, particularly if the city can
leverage the federal money into an estimated $260 million in
private funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thrilled to have this leverage in getting businesses
interested in moving to the shipyard,'' said William Hankowsky,
president of the Philadelphia Industrial Development Corporation,
the city's economic development arm that will administer the loan
funds. ``We will be able to attract industrial firms, corporate
offices, warehouses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hankowsky said he hopes the funding will help make Philadelphia
into a national model on how to redevelop closed military bases.
</P>
<P>
   The base closure commission announced its intentions to shutdown
the Navy Yard in 1991, officially closing its doors in September of
1995.
</P>
<P>
   But, with the new federal funds and private shipbuilding
contracts, city officials hope the shipyard is well on the way to
being converted from military to commercial and industrial use.
</P>
<P>
   The federal money will go toward luring businesses to the
industrial park section of the old Navy grounds, around I-95, west
of the shipyard section. That portion of the yard is being taken
over by Kvaerner, a Norwegian shipbuilding company. Kvaerner
Philadelphia Shipyard is being underwritten with $240 million from
the state and the city, and another $185 million in workforce
training funds from federal and local sources.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the Thanksgiving spirit, Gore said creating urban
jobs was a key mission in an otherwise robust economy. ``We must
not judge our success by the size of the national feast, but by the
number of those who fit around the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
