</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURGERY FOR BLEDSOE'S BROKEN FINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Hope surfaced again for the Patriots
following a 26-23 victory over the Miami Dolphins Monday night.
Hope that a season could be saved. Hope that Drew Bledsoe may play
Sunday afternoon against Doug Flutie and the Buffalo Bills. Hope
that the Patriots could make a comeback after losing four of five
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' quarterback fractured his right index finger in
two places with less than two minutes remaining in the game and
debated whether he could stay in. But he pulled out a huge win with
a gutsy fourth-down completion to Shawn Jefferson to the 25,
followed by a touchdown pass to Jefferson with 29 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's heroic effort, with a busted finger that had gone
numb, may have saved the Patriots' season.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Bledsoe visited Dr. James Herndon, a hand specialist at
Massachusetts General Hospital, who ruled out surgery, which means
Bledsoe will not have to have pins or screws inserted.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether Bledsoe will be able to play with a
fitted splint, which may allow him enough freedom to grip the
football and throw it. That appears to be a long shot, but the
doctor decided that Bledsoe was not going to be fitted with a cast.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots said in a statement that Bledsoe's status ``is
undetermined at this time and will be updated during the week.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Bledsoe will test the splint to see if he can
throw effectively with it. The index finger is used mainly to guide
the ball and get a tight spiral; without use of it, Bledsoe found
that his throws tended to sail, as evidenced by a pair of
incompletions before the fourth-down heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Another hand specialist, Dr. Susan Scott, who is a member of the
Association of Professional Team Physicians, said, ``In general, a
fracture of that kind would take four weeks to heal and it would
require immobilization of the area (i.e. a cast).''
</P>
<P>
   Scott did not examine Bledsoe, whose condition may be less
severe than the kind she was addressing, since he does not need
surgery or a cast.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe may find, after practicing with a splint, that he is
unable to go, which leaves the Patriots with either Scott Zolak or
Tom Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak had his helmet on Monday night and was two steps on the
field when Bledsoe came to the sideline during a timeout shaking
his hand, unable to get feeling in the finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know whether I'd be hurting the team by going back
out there,'' said Bledsoe, who injured the finger with 1:55
remaining when he hit the helmet of onrushing defensive tackle
Shane Burton on his follow-through.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates in the huddle were wondering whether Bledsoe should be
out there, because the finger looked bad. Jefferson even told
Bledsoe, ``I'm not sure this is going to work.'' As it turned out,
Bledsoe made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who earned NFL Player of the Week honors after
completing 28 of 43 passes for 423 yards and two touchdowns, said
after the game that he expected to play against the Bills. But the
finger likely has stiffened since then, with soreness setting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably know more by the end of the week,'' said
Carroll. ``If he can play with what he's got, then he'll be out
there. I don't know how hard it is to play with two cracks in your
finger. Hopefully, he'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll wouldn't commit to Zolak as the substitute if Bledsoe
can't go. Tupa, who played well in the exhibition season, has a
good throwing arm, which might suit the spread-out offense that
Ernie Zampese introduced Monday night. But the Patriots may not
want to risk getting their punter injured.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the injury couldn't be worse. He seemed to thrive
in the shotgun formation with five receivers, and he was excelling
in the no-huddle offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the Drew Bledsoe we know,'' said safety Willie Clay.
``The whole defense was rooting for him. He took charge and control
and directed the offense with a broken finger. That's the character
we see in this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots will have to decide is whether a less-than-100
percent Bledsoe is better than Zolak or Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to be in first place again next week,'' said
Carroll. ``We're hoping we can overcome these things and do it. It
seemed the odds were stacked against us late in that game and we
pulled it out. Those are my favorite moments in this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
