<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATORS-JOHNSON-CO     11-24 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATORS-JOHNSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Videotape of midfield brawl shows Gator QB involved
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Further review of the videotape of Saturday's pregame
fight between Florida and Florida State revealed that Gator
quarterback Doug Johnson threw the ball into the pile of players,
nearly hitting Florida State coach Bobby Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Florida does not plan to punish Johnson, but athletics director
Jeremy Foley said he was ``embarrassed'' by the total incident and
guaranteed that ``it will not happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Players from the two teams began exchanging blows at midfield
about 20 minutes before kickoff at Doak Campbell Stadium in
Tallahassee. SEC officials separated the two teams and ejected
starting Florida cornerback Tony George and two Florida State
reserves, linemen Ronald Boldin and Josh Baggs.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Sentinel reported Tuesday that it had reviewed
several videotape clips of the melee and saw Johnson firing a ball
into the middle of the fracas, hitting assistant strength coach
Eric Johnson and narrowly missing Bowden. The SEC officials who
worked the game were aware of the thrown ball when they were
discussing penalties but could not determine who had thrown the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said he had not reviewed the videotape but was aware of
reports that Johnson had thrown the ball at the Florida State
coaches. He said that he had discussed the matter with coach Steve
Spurrier and that Johnson would not be punished.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Johnson nor Spurrier could be reached for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best thing to do at this point is to let the
ejections stand and move on,'' Foley said. ``Doug will have to live
with the criticism he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   But Foley made it clear Tuesday that he is upset about the
incident, which he called ``an embarrassment to everyone associated
with the University of Florida.'' He said that by next season he
will have a plan in place to prevent it from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to surround the field with police to separate
the teams, but we will find a way to make sure nothing like this
ever happens again, I guarantee you that,'' Foley said. ``It was an
embarrassing situation for the university and totally uncalled for.
Maybe if I had been more pro-active, I could have done something,
but we will not tolerate that kind of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The videotape also showed that George's ejection came for
punching FSU graduate assistant coach Steve Gabbard, not assistant
Odell Haggins, as had originally been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said that George, a senior, will play in Florida's bowl
game.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
