<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-VOTERS-NYT &LR;      11-24 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-VOTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA TRIES TO SMOOTH VOTER-REGISTRATION WRINKLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ In 1994, South Africa's first
all-race elections were sloppy, but everybody was too happy to
care. This time they care.
</P>
<P>
   Last time, there was no voter registration. All you had to do
was show up with an identification document. This time, however,
the country is trying to enforce stricter controls.
</P>
<P>
   But for weeks controversy has been brewing over the registration
process, and fears that administrative chaos could keep millions
from voting have been growing. A date for the elections has not
been set, though sometime in May seems likely.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Independent Electoral Commission announced that it
would postpone its registration drive in about half the country,
saying it was not prepared to meet a goal it set for itself that
seemed hopelessly optimistic _ to sign up 23 million of 25 million
eligible voters this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials said they needed more time to train the
72,000 civil servants and 8,000 soldiers who were to man 15,000
registration booths.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had to turn to the civil servants because it does
not have the money to hire and train its own workers.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the latest problem with the registration. More than
5 million people are thought to lack the updated national identity
booklets needed to register. Red tape, confusion and long lines
have hindered many from getting their documents. And most of those
left out in the cold are white, because blacks acted quickly to get
rid of their apartheid-era papers.
</P>
<P>
   The governing African National Congress is nevertheless
insisting that the new bar-coded identification documents are
needed to register, and this has set off an outcry from the mainly
white-supported opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in the registration process hardly appeased them.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the National Party, Marthinus van Schalkwyk, said
the delay in voter registration showed that the country was being
governed ``by a bunch of incompetent people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally broadcast speech, President Nelson Mandela said
difficulties were to be expected given the scope of the first-time
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the work that has been done so far and the good will that
has been shown give me the confidence that we will succeed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the commission's new plan, only the nation's five northern
provinces, including Gauteng, where Johannesburg and Pretoria are
situated, will register voters Friday, Saturday and Sunday. The
provinces account for about half the number of eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
   The other four will go forward Dec. 3-5, said the commission's
chief electoral officer, Mandla Mchunu.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate a decline in the support for the African
National Congress, with a growing number of South Africans saying
they are uncommitted to any party. Some experts believe, however,
that those voters are likely to return to the parties they left. In
any case, even with the lost of support, the ANC is still the
choice of between 50 and 60 percent of the voters, making its
victory a largely foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The issue for the ANC, however, is not whether it will win the
election, but whether it can capture more than two-thirds of the
vote, the share needed for it to change the constitution. A few
months ago, party officials were open about this goal, but lately
say less about it. The other parties rallied quickly to question
what it was that the ANC wanted to change and to warn about giving
any one party that much power.
</P>
<P>
   Which party will become the official opposition is more in
question. There is quite a lot of jockeying among the opposition
parties. The party that brought South Africa apartheid, the
National Party, has plunged in many of the recent polls. It won
about 22 percent of the vote in the 1994 elections, but some
surveys have said it would now win less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The largely white, liberal and very vocal Democratic Party is
gaining ground, as is the newly created United Democratic Party,
which is an attempt at a multiracial party.
</P>
<P>
   The date for the election is to be set by Mandela. But the
constitution prohibits him from doing so before late April. Mchunu
said the commission was urging Mandela to settle on a May election
date, before the winter set in and days shortened in the Southern
Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7744 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-JOHNSON-HN     11-24 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
A courtship that seemed one-sided from its inception ended rather
predictably Tuesday morning. To the surprise of almost no one,
Randy Johnson will wed himself to a team other than the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Meister, one of Johnson's agents, informed Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker that it would take a four-year contract to
sign the Big Unit, and that was one more year than the Astros were
willing to offer. The Astros officially withdrew their three-year,
$33 million offer to Johnson and likely are done with any major
dealings this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit that early on I was less than optimistic,''
Hunsicker said. ``For a guy who spent a couple of months here, I
would like to have heard a more definitive endorsement that we were
among the top teams vying for his services, and we really never
heard that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was 10-1 with a 1.28 ERA after joining the Astros
in a July 31 trade with Seattle, is expected to decide on a new
team by the end of the week. Arizona, Anaheim, Los Angeles and
Texas appear to be on his final list of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy really enjoyed Houston,'' Meister said. ``He had a
wonderful time there. All things being relatively equal, Houston
was clearly a part of our plans. It was a mutual parting of the
ways. We agreed to disagree. This wasn't just about money; it was
mostly about the term of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy would like to play at least four more years, and he's
hoping to sign where he would finish his career. We've spoken to a
number of clubs that feel like four years is the right term for
this contract. There's a pretty good chance that Randy will make a
decision in the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his past experiences with Doug Drabek and Greg
Swindell, Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. didn't feel it was in his
team's best interest to offer a four-year contract to Johnson, who
will celebrate his 36th birthday next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for some reason Randy was not able to pitch at a high level
in the third and fourth year, it just paralyzes the entire team
because you have so much money wrapped up in one player who is not
producing at an extremely high level,'' McLane said. ``We just were
not ready to take that risk. We're disappointed that it didn't
work, but we just had to be truthful and honest with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros also were truthful with themselves, realizing the
longer the Johnson saga played out, the more their chances of
re-signing the coveted free agent eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling was that once we got past the exclusive period
and into the open market, we're always going to be the underdog
when it comes to an open competition financially, and ultimately
that's what happened,'' Hunsicker said. ``We made a very aggressive
offer right out of the box, and it really didn't go from there. As
the stakes got higher, we were not prepared to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Re-signing Johnson would have put the Astros over the $50
million mark in terms of payroll already committed to players in
1999, and that doesn't include the eight arbitration-eligible
players on the roster. Signing Johnson almost certainly would have
meant unloading key members of last season's team, which won a
franchise-record 102 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, the whole payroll wasn't $11 million,''
McLane said. ``I was very optimistic about it in the beginning, but
as time lingered and no decision was made, we felt it slipping
away. We're not sure, if Randy had agreed to the $11 million a
year, just how the team would have shaped up next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would have had to make some provisions to the
team. We weren't sure if Randy was going to accept our offer, so we
really hadn't sorted through those things. But now, we don't have
to make those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears third baseman Ken Caminiti will be the Astros' only
major free-agent acquisition of the offseason. The club does not
expect to use the money designated for Johnson to lure another
big-ticket free agent to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way in a short period of time, and we have
to get back somewhat to reality,'' Hunsicker said. ``We have a very
exciting baseball team, and it's among the best in baseball without
Randy Johnson or another high-profile pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on our way to winning a division championship without
Randy. Certainly, he added the excitement and a significant piece
to our club. But as we all found out in the postseason, one person
does not make the difference between winning and losing. I like our
baseball team. I think it's going to be one of the top teams in all
of baseball and certainly a top contender to win our division next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, speculation in regard to acquiring five-time Cy Young
Award winner Roger Clemens from Toronto will continue to linger
until the Blue Jays decide which direction they're headed in the
immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Blue Jays don't indicate a strong desire to
trade Clemens, but that could change next month when the general
managers get together for baseball's winter meetings in Nashville,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros explored the possibility of trading for Clemens
before they acquired Johnson but were turned off by the Blue Jays'
demands, which are believed to have included at least two
established players and either outfielder Richard Hidalgo or
pitcher Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   ``In getting someone like a Roger Clemens, we can't give up the
really high-quality young players that we have just to get one
player,'' McLane said. ``It's got to be something that works for
us. We'd certainly look at that very aggressively before we made a
decision. Shane Reynolds, Mike Hampton and Jose Lima are not a bad
crew to go with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had hoped Johnson would help them reach the World
Series, but they were eliminated from the playoffs in the first
round despite two well-pitched games by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Although they now have nothing to show for the trade that sent
prospects John Halama, Freddy Garcia and Carlos Guillen to Seattle,
Hunsicker said he had no second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely no regrets about the trade,'' Hunsicker
said. ``It provided a magical time in the city. It took the
excitement and enthusiasm for major-league baseball to a new level.
When we made this trade, we went into it with our eyes wide open
and really didn't even think about 1999. I think we got our money's
worth. We took a gamble that was worth taking, and I'd do it
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
