<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7745 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      11-24 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; KING OF THE WORLD &QL; 
 &UR; David Remnick (Random House, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Remnick, who won a Pulitzer Prize for his book, ``Lenin's
Tomb,'' and is now editor of ``The New Yorker,'' tells the deeply
American tale of the self-creation of Muhammad Ali. The book begins
with Ali's predecessors as heavyweight champion: Floyd Patterson _
the kind-hearted ``Good Negro'' who was burdened with a relentless
awareness of his own failures _ and his antithesis, Sonny Liston,
whose prison background and lack of education made him a target for
a condescending public. Then came Ali. Fast, sleek, confident and
controversial, he flew in the face of everything audiences and
sportswriters expected from fighters. He lived by his own terms,
and for a long time no one would forgive him for it. Remnick does a
spellbinding job of recreating the atmosphere into which Ali
brought his remarkable persona, dooming all of the best
heavyweights from that point on to languish in his shadow. ``I came
to love Ali,'' Patterson told Remnick. ``I came to see that I was a
fighter and he was history.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LAS CHRISTMAS &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Esmeralda Santiago and Joie Davidow (Knopf, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Junot Diaz came to the United States when he was 7, just before
Christmas. He arrived in New York, where, he says, ``the December
winds plowed me open. . . . I remember my first weeks as a series
of astonishments: the cold, my father, English, our apartment, the
indoor plumbing, the TV, the loneliness of apartment life, of being
a recently arrived immigrant.'' Denise Chavez remembers better
holidays, paced by the quirky generosity of her mother. Julia
Alvarez writes about an uncle who on Christmas Eve was delivered
from political oppression in the Dominican Republic. Sandra
Cisneros offers a sermon about understanding and generosity, based
on memories of her father. We get lots of warm, fuzzy, forgettable
books at Christmas time, so when a good one comes along we like to
mention it. Here are poems, songs, recipes and stories by Latino
authors, including Luis J. Rodriguez, Ray Suarez, Gary Soto and
Francisco Goldman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MADNESS ON THE COUCH &QL; 
 &UR; Edward Dolnick (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Dolnick, a contributing editor of ``Health'' magazine and former
science writer for the ``Boston Globe,'' takes on Freudian
psychoanalysis and the arrogance with which it was applied to three
forms of mental illness: schizophrenia, autism and
obsessive-compulsive disorder. Convinced of their righteousness,
Freud's disciples set out to conquer madness, their approach heavy
with egotism and unsupported by science. Here is psychoanalyst
Frieda Fromm-Reichmann in 1948: ``The schizophrenic is painfully
distrustful and resentful of other people due to the severe early
warp and rejection he encountered in important people of his
infancy and childhood, mainly in a schizophrenogenic mother.'' Or
Bruno Bettelheim, who said ``the precipitating factor in infantile
autism is the parent's wish that his child should not exist.''
Parents were blamed for their children's misery, whether they were
too cold or too loving _ either sin would do. As Dolnick points
out, it was an era of guilt-mongering and misinformation from which
we were slow to recover. ``Unlike con men,'' he writes, ``the
psychoanalysts fervently believed their own patter and ended up
bewitched by their own spells.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AIR-CONDITIONING AMERICA &QL; 
 &UR; Gail Cooper (Johns Hopkins, $35)
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Which could you live without _ your computer or
your air-conditioner? Cooper's history of efforts to achieve
artificial climates indoors (she points out that air-conditioning
first gained acceptance not among people looking for comfort but in
factories where owners were concerned about the effects of humidity
on production) is scholarly but entertaining. By 1917, movie
theaters were air-cooled as a competitive tool, but until the
technology was perfected, moviegoers took newspapers to wrap around
their feet as chilled air settled to the floor. And during World
War II, systems were removed from civilian buildings such as
Tiffany's and Lord and Taylor's and placed in military production
factories. These and other anecdotes make for an interesting look
at how new technologies become part of our lives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SESAME STREET UNPAVED &QL; 
 &UR; David Borgenicht (Hyperion, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   This one arrived with a bunch of yellow feathers tucked inside
the cover, and we almost swooned. ``Sesame Street'' (known as
``Sesameet'' to some people we know) is 30 years old this month.
Many of you have children or grandchildren who counted on it, and
Hyperion is now counting on you to be interested in a walk down
Memory Lane. The milestones are here: the death of Mr. Hooper, the
marriage of Maria and Luis, and one of our favorites (although not
a milestone by everyone's definition), Robert MacNeil's interview
with Oscar the Grouch (MacNeil: I see that you're in the ice-cream
business. Oscar: Oh, d'you figure that out all by yourself or did
Lehrer help you?). There's trivia _ Luis was the first human
addition to the original cast, and his marriage to Maria was done
in haste (Sonia Manzano, who plays Maria, was already pregnant in
real life _ her baby played Maria's baby on the show). Also
included are profiles of cast members and a list of famous guests.
Says Barbara Walters: ``I hear more from people who see me on
``Sesame Street'' singing ``Put Down the Duckie'' than from almost
any interview I do.'' &QL; 
Correspondent Anne Stephenson receives e-mail at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
