<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CONFESSION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SCREENWRIT ER'S `DAY' FAL TERS AFTER `TOMORROW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
DAY OF CONFESSION 
Allan Folsom (Little, Brown, $25) 
 
 By MONTY PHAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you didn't know author Allan Folsom was a former
screenwriter, his new novel, ``Day of Confession,'' may give you
some clues.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, there's a bit more going on than in your average pop
fiction thriller. Inside the front cover, there's a map of Italy,
where the story takes place. Inside the back cover, there's a map
of Vatican City, also crucial to the plot. Before the first page,
there's a movielike list of characters and their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the main character is an entertainment lawyer, a type
of person Folsom likely is familiar with, because he got a million
bucks for the film rights to his first novel, 1994's ``The Day
After Tomorrow,'' before it even was released.
</P>
<P>
   That book got its fair share of praise, and rightly so, melding
elements of horror and political intrigue into a tightly woven
plot. But this is a different ``Day.'' The maps and character list
make the book seem more like the print version of a movie than a
means to enhance the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Also, of the 20-some characters mentioned in the list, only
about 10 show up with regularity. Surely the reader is able to keep
track of 10 people in the time it takes to finish the book,
especially if the story is the up-all-night page-turner it claims
to be.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the point: It's not. It focuses on Harry Addison, a
Los Angeles entertainment lawyer who receives a desperate-sounding
message from his estranged brother, Daniel, a Vatican priest, days
after a Vatican cardinal is assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, while traveling to Assisi, Italy, the bus Daniel
is on explodes. After arriving in Rome to claim his brother's body,
Harry is taken into custody by Italian and Vatican police, who
believe Daniel was behind the cardinal's assassination and suspect
Harry may know something about it.
</P>
<P>
   However, Harry then begins to doubt his brother really is dead.
Before he can do anything about it, however, he is framed for a
police officer's murder, kidnapped, tortured by a terrorist also
looking for Father Daniel and then left for dead.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to flee police while searching for his brother, Harry
also stumbles onto a bizarre plot by Cardinal Umberto Palestrina,
the Vatican secretariat of state, to orchestrate a Vatican takeover
of China as the first step in creating a modern-day Holy Roman
Empire.
</P>
<P>
   It's as outrageous as it sounds. It's also incredibly linear.
Palestrina's plan is revealed in the first fifth of the book, then
becomes a subplot to the ``bad guys chase good guys'' portion of
the novel. That's a real disappointment, considering Folsom's first
novel was rife with subplots and twists.
</P>
<P>
   That book, although at least as far-fetched, was original in its
fiendishness, even if it did use German neo-Nazis as its primary
evil-doers. In ``Day of Confession,'' villainy falls in the hands
of the Holy See, which, despite the trendiness of Catholic-bashing,
still is difficult to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that the scheming Cardinal Palestrina is
depicted as cartoonishly flat and devoid of any redeeming
qualities, traits he realistically would have had to have to reach
a position that high. In fact, only one character, Otello Roscani,
an Italian detective trailing the Addison brothers, shows any signs
of internal conflict needed to give him life beyond the words on
the page.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither novel is a benchmark of fine writing, lines
such as ``It was nuts, but it might work'' in ``Day of Confession''
are disappointly typical of pop-fiction schlock. Folsom mostly
avoided that in ``The Day After Tomorrow,'' another illustration of
how his first effort succeeded in areas his second does not. If
Folsom fans are to tolerate another ``Day,'' it had better be more
like ``Tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
