<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SHAKESPEARE-AZR &LR;      11-24 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHAKESPEARE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAYIST DIS PLAYS AWESOME GRASP OF THE BARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
SHAKESPEARE: THE INVENTION OF THE HUMAN 
Harold Bloom (Riverhead Books, $35) 
 
 By LELA STROMENGER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin itals) Not marble, nor the gilded monuments / Of princes,
shall outlive this powerful rhyme. (end itals) &QL; 
_ Sonnet 55 &QR; 
It's been almost 400 years since William Shakespeare made that
prediction, and so far so good. Many a gilded monument crumbled
while the Bard rose to the rank of first among the greatest.
Outright Bardolatry began in the 18th century and continued
unabated into our intellectually Balkanized age.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, the Swan has occasionally swum into rough
waters. Among his detractors, New Historicists base their denial of
his supremacy on a rejection of the whole traditional literary
ordering, or canon. Neo-Marxists attribute his reputation to a vast
right-wing conspiracy they feel has used him for centuries to help
preserve the social status quo. Feminists and multiculturalists can
be found who see him simply as the deadest White European male.
</P>
<P>
   Into the breach made by these critical armies leaps Harold
Bloom, the champion of ``the Western Canon'' (a phrase he made
current in his 1994 book of that title) and the canon's final
arbiter and gatekeeper, at least in his own opinion. And as the
holder of prestigious chairs at Yale and New York University, the
winner of a MacArthur Fellowship and the author of an enormous body
of influential criticism both scholarly and popular, he's entitled
to his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom contends that the canon rules us and that Shakespeare
rules the canon. More than that, he asserts Shakespeare actually
created us as personalities. Before Hamlet and Falstaff, he
believes, people lacked the faculty of ``self-overhearing'' _
individual self-awareness _ that defines us as post-medieval human
beings.
</P>
<P>
   Quibblers are going to feel that Bloom arrogates for Shakespeare
an achievement that belongs to the entire Renaissance, but Bloom
doesn't spend much time pushing his thesis. The idea seems to be
more of a peg on which to hang his favorite form of Shakespearean
criticism: analysis of the characters, in particular the
``prodigies'' _ Hamlet, Falstaff, Rosalind, Shylock, Iago, Lear,
Macbeth and Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news here is that this approach leaves out any explicit
discussion of the poetry, an area in which Shakespeare's influence
on the modern world is surely at least as pervasive as in
characterization. The good news is that Bloom is the equal of his
famous predecessors in this kind of analysis _ Samuel Johnson,
William Hazlitt, A.C. Bradley _ and is, in fact, a walking
summation of the Shakespearean sensibility of the past 400 years.
</P>
<P>
   Canon specialist Bloom can bring in the big guns _ he has read
them all. We hear the roar of Nietzsche, Kierkegaard, Freud,
Melville, Dostoevski, Auden and their ilk as well as the academic
critics. His lighter artillery ranges from Cormac McCarthy, whose
``Blood Meridian'' boasts a character Bloom considers the only peer
of ``pyromaniac Iago'' in the art of evil (except for Milton's
Satan), to Josephine Tey, whose ``The Daughter of Time'' Bloom is
not too proud to include in his discussion of ``Richard III.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to this sweep of readership 50-plus years of knowing and
loving the plays (Bloom is 68), and you have a formidable
Shakespearean commentator. And commentary is probably nearer the
heart of this volume than analysis.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a sharply focused study. It's a big, shambling,
opinionated, alternately warmhearted and cranky, endlessly
interesting collection of essays that read the way a very good
lecturer talks and that probably are lightly reworked lectures,
complete with a sprinkling of critical jargon and a lecture series'
relentless repetitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   It seems ungracious, however, to object to the method when the
results are so illuminating. You may disagree with individual
judgments, but Bloom's overall grasp is awesome. His mental
storehouse is so crammed, his concept of Shakespeare's artistic
course so clear and his heart so large that on practically every
other page the reader finds a fragment of Bloom that can light up a
facet of Shakespeare the way pages of somebody else could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``This echo chamber of a play,'' for instance, simultaneously
illustrates a point about ``Twelfth Night'' and awakens the
reader's own realization of the extent to which duplicated elements
make up the harmony and counterpoint of that musical drama. ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' ``could be anyone's dream or any night in
midsummer, when the world is largest.'' The brilliant, lengthy,
conflicted and almost uncontrollable ``Hamlet,'' written ``partly
out of . . . compulsion,'' is ``Shakespeare's white elephant.'' The
book is an Ali Baba's cave of this kind of treasure.
</P>
<P>
   In the light of this golden trove, you can see that Bloom and
the traditionalists don't have much to worry about. Shakespeare has
survived four centuries of intermittent trashing, misreading, bad
editing and rewriting, and he's a safe bet to survive a few more.
People will probably be reading and watching his plays when most of
the gilded monuments we're busy with at the moment are moldering in
some archive in another solar system. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
