<SLUG> BC-MA-BLUES-FOUNDATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE CROSS PLAN WOULD SUBSIDIZE ELDERS' DRUG COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts said
Tuesday it expects to plow &UR;  &LR; more than $5 million next year into a
foundation to subsidize the purchase of prescription drugs for
approximately 7,500 seniors currently enrolled in Blue Care 65, its
Medicare health maintenance organization.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The foundation would compensate seniors for prescription costs
greater than $300 a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after Blue Cross and other insurers in
Massachusetts proceeded last week with final plans to cap drug
coverage for the elderly beginning Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Cross foundation, proposed several weeks ago without
much detail, is an attempt to temporarily shield current customers
from the new limits. Blue Cross's subsidies, however, would be
available for just one year and would be open only to seniors who
are members of Blue Care 65 as of Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Though limited in scope, the subsidies are expected to cost Blue
Cross $5 million in 1999. Blue Cross reported net income of $12.7
million in 1997 and expects &UR;  &LR;  to make more than $50 million in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Senior advocates Tuesday praised Blue Cross, but noted that
other insurers also need to step up to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend Blue Cross for their responsibility and compassion
in offering this solution,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy. ``I urge
the other HMOs in Massachusetts to live up to their
responsibilities as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased to see that Blue Cross is working quickly to
find a stopgap measure to this crisis,'' said Allison Staton of
Health Care For All, a consumer advocacy group in Boston.
``However, we're disappointed that this isn't more of a group
effort among all of the plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care has said it will create a
``transitional assistance program'' for low-income seniors in its
First Seniority Medicare HMO, but has not released details. Tufts
Health Plan, which runs the state's largest Medicare HMO, has not
indicated whether it will provide financial assistance to its
seniors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
