<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-DOCUMENTS-BOS     11-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-DOCUMENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BATCH OF KENNEDY RECORDINGS RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the largest batch of recordings it has yet released,
the John F. Kennedy Library Tuesday made public 37 hours of tapes
in which President Kennedy conceded that his administration must
bear some responsibility for the assassination of South Vietnam
President Ngo Dinh Diem.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for that conclusion, in Kennedy's view, was a cable
sent to South Vietnam in August 1963 that appeared to give tacit US
approval for a coup against Diem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we must bear a good deal of responsibility for it
beginning,'' Kennedy said on Nov. 4, 1963, two days after Diem's
assassination. ``In my judgment, that wire was badly drafted. It
should have never been sent on a Saturday. I should have never
given my consent to it without round-table discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Fawcett, a former Kennedy Library archivist who
prepared the tapes for declassification, said Kennedy was at
Hyannisport when the cable was sent. The president mistakenly
believed it had been approved by all relevant Cabinet officials,
according to Fawcett.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Robert S. McNamara, for one, had not been in
Washington when the cable was dispatched, and protested to the
president when he returned, Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked by the death of Ngo Dinh Diem,'' Kennedy
continued in the recording, which he dictated less than three weeks
before his own assassination. ``He was an extraordinary character.
While he became increasingly difficult in the last few months, he
has been able to hold his country together for the last 10
months.''
</P>
<P>
   With Diem dead, Kennedy said, ``the question is now whether the
generals can stay together and build a stable government or whether
public opinion will turn on Saigon.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, South Vietnam's continued instability in the face of a
communist insurgency led to a massive infusion of American military
support by Kennedy's successor, Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The memo on Diem was part of four hours of tapes held privately
by Evelyn Lincoln, Kennedy's personal secretary, until her death in
1995. The Kennedy Library received the tapes in March from Robert
White, a private collector of Kennedy memorabilia who had been
given the tapes by Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 37 hours of recordings released Tuesday, 24 hours are of
meetings held in the White House. The remainder are of telephone
conversations, Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
   In the phone recordings, Kennedy is heard briefing former
Presidents Dwight Eisenhower, Harry Truman, and Herbert Hoover
about the conclusion of the Cuban missile crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Although satisfied with the outcome, Kennedy showed he did not
consider the communist problem in the Caribbean to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Cuban story is over yet,'' the president
told Truman. ``It may be only one more chapter in a very long story
as far as Cuba is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   In other tapes, Kennedy and his advisers discuss the Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty and foreign policy concerns in such widely diverse
places as Berlin, Laos, China, Taiwan, and the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   To Fawcett, part of the importance of these recordings is that
they provide the public with a freeze-frame of debate on vital
issues, such as nuclear weapons and relations with China, that
continue to concern the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes, Fawcett said, ``won't dramatically alter the
historical records, but they certainly fill in some gaps in what
was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a person among us who wouldn't want to
be in the Oval Office or Cabinet room when these decisions are
made. And these take you there.''
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's release, 110 hours of tapes from the Kennedy
White House have been made public. All of the recordings about the
Cuban missile crisis have now been made available.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett said 150 hours of tapes remain to be declassified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
