<SLUG> BC-NH-SCHOOL-FUNDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. SEEKS 2-YEAR EXTENSION OF SCHOOL FUNDING DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ In a debate before the state Supreme Court
Tuesday, advocates for a swift end to New Hampshire's school
funding crisis welcomed a ``meltdown'' if they don't see action
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Justices whose patience appeared to have been tried by the
long-running case listened as the state asked for a two-year
extension of the court's April 1 deadline to replace New
Hampshire's unconstitutional school funding system.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for towns that sued the state in 1991 said it deserved
no extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it is costing $196 million per year in
unconstitutional taxes, and children are sitting in bathrooms
learning,'' said Andru Volinsky, lead lawyer for the Claremont
Coalition of property-poor towns. ``That should not continue.
That's why we need to move forward, and there is no guarantee that
the Legislature will move to correct any of these problems unless
they are facing a deadline and a meltdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The system relies more heavily on local property taxes than any
other in the nation, and allows tax rates to vary by as much as 15
times between property-rich and property-poor towns. Last December,
the court found that disparity illegal, ruling that all taxes used
to fund public education must be levied ``reasonably and
proportionately.'' It gave the Legislature until Dec. 2 to devise a
plan and until April 1 to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Attorney General Philip McLaughlin told the court
that progress has been made, if only through the elimination of
some possible responses to the court's order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that if this court grants a reasonable
extension, it will continue to see the funnel narrow,'' McLaughlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has been reluctant to consider any replacement
plan that would result in a broad-based sales, income, or property
tax. Governor Jeanne Shaheen has pledged to veto any such plan.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative action has focused instead on amendments that would
modify or reverse the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year extension would give lawmakers time to bring such an
amendment before voters in November 2000, a scenario that did not
escape the justices or the Claremont Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The problem is not a lack of time. The problem is a lack of
will,'' said John Tobin, a lawyer for the coalition. ``The court
three times has respectfully asked the governor and Legislature to
do their duty and they have accomplished nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The court should prepare to place the state into receivership,
Tobin said. Appointing a receiver empowered to spend the state's
general fund on education could force the state's hand or, failing
that, provide money to keep public schools open after the fiscal
year ends in July, Volinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one judge indicated interest in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be prudent of us at this time to start exploring
the possibility of being put in a constitutional crisis and a
meltdown and to find out what remedies are available to us?'' asked
Justice Sherman Horton. ``I don't want the schools to close ... I
want to see the education system perking along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
