<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-PROFITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD QUARTER PRODUCED STEEP DROP CORPORATE PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The government said Tuesday that the US economy grew
faster last summer than previously estimated. But analysts
cautioned the economic tour-de-force was more a marker of good
times past than a portent of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Of special concern, according to analysts, were new figures
showing that US companies suffered their steepest profit decline of
the decade during the three-month quarter ended in September, and
for the first time in nearly seven years cut the amount it invested
in new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate profits and business investment are key indicators of
economic health. Analysts said their decline raises doubts about
the economy's ability to keep growing and the stock market's
capacity to sustain record highs reached Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With weakening profits, it's going to be hard for businesses
to keep expanding,'' said Mark M. Zandi, chief economist with
Regional Financial Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``As a result,
they will be hiring and investing less aggressively than they have
in the past,'' he said, moves that are likely to cause both the
economy and market to falter.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over corporate profits sent stock prices lower Tuesday,
taking some of the snap out of what was hailed a day earlier as the
fastest comeback from a bear market in US financial history.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average slid 73.12 points, or 0.8
percent, to close at 9301.15, well off its record close on Monday.
The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 5.22 points, or 0.4
percent, at 1182.99. The high technology-laden Nasdaq Composite
index lost 11.54 points, or 0.6 percent, to close at 1965.88.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department, which originally estimated that the
economy grew at an unexpectedly strong 3.3 percent rate during the
third quarter, boosted its estimate Tuesday to an even stronger 3.9
percent, crediting a surge in consumer spending,
less-severe-than-expected deterioration in the trade deficit and an
almost-total absence of inflation for the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said if the economy keeps growing at a 3 percent or
better rate through the end of the year, as many now believe is
likely, that will make the current expansion the longest ever in
peacetime America, topping both the boom of the 1980s and the even
longer boom of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news Tuesday seemed to stop there. Commerce
Department officials said corporate profits dropped 6.2 percent
last quarter as compared with the same quarter in 1997, the
steepest such drop since 1989. And they said that business
equipment investment, which has accounted for about one-third of
the economy's growth during the decade, fell 1.1 percent, its first
decline since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are concerned that the stock market's miraculously fast
recovery is almost entirely the result of recent Federal Reserve
interest rate cuts, rather than fundamental improvements in the
economy, and is therefore unsustainable. Some worry the central
bank has gotten itself trapped in a bind of having to prop up the
market to protect against a growth-damaging tumble even as stock
prices grow increasingly out of line with profits and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is the captive of the financial markets here,'' said
Charles I. Clough Jr., chief investment strategist with Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. ``You had a bubble that threatened to take the economy
down with it so the Fed flooded the finacial markets with
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have to be trying to figure how to produce a soft
landing,'' Clough said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 1942EST &QL; 
