<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's Y2K `point person' breathing easy
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Commissioner Herbert McCall, head of Atlanta's
Department of Administrative Services, acknowledges he's ``the
city's point person on Y2K.'' His message is, breathe easy.
</P>
<P>
   According to McCall, the city doesn't have much in the way of
vulnerable inventory and the problems that remain are being
addressed with straight-forward simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   The city has about 3,000 desktop computers. The glitchy software
on them is being replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these have been ``mostly upgraded with compliant''
software, McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   There are only about 27 computer mainframe programs and just
eight mission critical systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what they are. Most are in the process of being
remediated, `` McCall added.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, mission critical means life, safety, health,
McCall explained.
</P>
<P>
   The work being done is both centralized and de-centralized.
There are about 40 centralized technology specialists and another
60 spread around the city. All of them have at least part-time Y2K
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In addition there are three different consulting teams, with a
total of about 30 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use the state's contract for Y2K program management,''
McCall said, ``and we're using the top-ranked firm, Information
Systems and Network Corp., based in Maryland'' as the overall
manager.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has three project management offices. One focuses
upon legacy systems, the software that's been handed down; a second
team is assigned to the airport's software. The third, for
non-legacy systems, deals with everything else, including embedded
software chips that operate equipment and machinery.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the city has inventoried these chips and his team is
deciding which are critical.
</P>
<P>
   What's all this costing? McCall said that's hard to figure. A
lot of equipment is decentralized and some has been fixed as a
by-product of overall repairs.
</P>
<P>
   So, as a ``shot in the dark,'' McCall estimated the city had
spent $2 million fixing the desktops and ``$4-to-$6 million
overall'' in 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, the city expects to spend another $9 million in
1999, but, again, some of that will be general technology upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be in the ballpark. For instance, Los Angeles, a
larger city than Atlanta, recently reported expenditures of $10
million with another $5 million projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the drop dead date'' for fixing Y2K is Dec. 31,
1999, Mayor Bill Campbell has given us a June 30, 1999 deadline,
McCall said. ``We will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   For an all-day Internet Y2K conference Nov. 27 that will feature
U.S. cities, go to http://www.y2kactionday.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
