<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-ATL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta rated towards the top in real estate trusts
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Buoyed by the recent sale of Lenox Square and Phipps
Plaza, metro Atlanta ranks at the top of the heap of U.S. cities in
the dollar value of properties owned by real estate investment
trusts. The ranking affirms metro Atlanta's attraction for real
estate buyers.
</P>
<P>
   REITs own 936 properties here valued at $14.6 billion, according
to Alliance Capital/CB Richard Ellis , which tracks quarterly
transactions of 142 of the largest U.S. REITs.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.3 billion in purchases completed here in the third
quarter largely reflects deals negotiated before the turmoil in
capital markets made financing more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   While acquisitions of $1.3 billion last quarter pushed Atlanta
ahead in total REIT holdings, two other cities had higher sales
volumes during the three months. Boston had $1.6 billion and
Midtown Manhattan, $1.31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Transactions nationwide totaled a strong $20.5 billion despite
the tightening in credit markets and lanquishing stock prices that
are expected to take a toll on REIT purchases. Almost 40 percent of
the third quarter sales were in three large deals worked out months
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Debartolo Group's $5.8 billion purchase of Corporate
Property Investors _ the deal that included Lenox Square, Phipps
Plaza and other holdings here _ accounted for 28 percent of the
third quarter volume nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, REITs purchased $861 million of retail
property last quarter, much of it in the Simon DeBartolo
acquisition. After that transaction, which was announced last
February, Simon Debartolo ranks second among REITs in the amount of
property owned here.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Debartolo's $1 billion in metro Atlanta holdings is
surpassed only by the $1.3 billion of Atlanta-based apartment
developer and owner Post Properties.
</P>
<P>
   In other third quarter acquisitions, apartments accounted for
$213 million and office buildings $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   While retail properties and hotels have been most favored by
REIT purchasers this year, they are outranked by apartments and
office buildings in total REIT-owned properties in metro Atlanta.
Apartments, valued at $4.5 billion, comprise nearly a third of the
holdings, followed by office buildings, valued at $3.5 billion, a
fourth. Retail assets total $2.8 billion and hotels, $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Value of properties owned by real estate investment trusts at
Sept. 30, 1998
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta $14.6 billion
</P>
<P>
   Chicago $14.4 billion
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C. $13.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles $11.1 billion
</P>
<P>
   Dallas $10.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   Source: Alliance Capital/CB Richard Ellis
</P>
<P>
   Sallye Salter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
