<SLUG> BC-CLASS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forum on whether college class violates civil rights laws
delayed
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Federal officials have delayed until early
next year a public forum to examine whether a community college
noncredit course violated civil rights laws by teaching that most
black people during the Civil War were happy under slavery.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Civil Rights Commission had planned to hold the forum
in Greensboro by the end of the year. But officials said Tuesday
the commission wants to broaden the scope of the forum beyond the
recently canceled Civil War class on the Archdale, N.C., campus of
Randolph Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Knight, a civil rights analyst in the commission's
Atlanta office, said he believes ``it might be a stretch to find a
rights violation'' solely in the continuing education course, which
was sponsored by a High Point, N.C., camp of the Sons of
Confederate Veterans. Taught by people affiliated with the veterans
group, the final class scheduled for last week was canceled amid
criticism by civil rights leaders and skepticism by historians.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said federal officials are still gathering information
about the course.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt Kirk, chairman of the North Carolina advisory committee to
the U.S. Civil Rights Commission, praised the college's
administrators for canceling the course, and he urged the college
to participate in the forum.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said the forum could possibly focus on the commission's
recent investigation of racial tensions in North Carolina. A report
on the investigation's findings is being reviewed by the state
advisory committee before it is released to the public, Kirk said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible topic is the 1994 police shooting of
19-year-old Daryl Eugene Howerton. A jury last month ruled in favor
of two Greensboro policemen, charged in a civil lawsuit of using
excessive force when they shot Howerton. A group representing 92
black churches has asked the city to pay damages to the victim's
mother, who claims her son was mentally unstable when, according to
police, he lunged with a knife at a bystander.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
