A7797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES-COX     11-24 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More bad news from Hayes: manufacturing site closing down
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hayes Corp. started shutting down its once-stellar
manufacturing unit Tuesday, laying off about 100 employees, with 50
more slated for pink slips in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Norcross, Ga.-based company, which filed for bankruptcy
protection Oct. 9, suspended two shifts right away and told workers
the third shift will be idled soon. When that happens,
manufacturing will cease.
</P>
<P>
   Of about 225 employees who were working in manufacturing several
weeks ago, about 25 have left voluntarily and about 50 will be
retained _ at least for awhile _ while the rest of the jobs will
disappear. The company, which once dominated the market for analog
modems, has already shrunk from a workforce high of about 1,200 to
less than 450.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes officials both here and in the company's executive offices
in Maryland could not be reached for comment. Ron Howard, chief
executive officer, was unavailable, as was Steve Mank, the
company's chief operating officer. Mank was the one who came to
Norcross to make the announcements and meet with employees.
</P>
<P>
   But bad as it was, the news wasn't as grim as many had expected
_ at least, not yet. Hayes could face a fire sale of assets, that
would leave virtually nothing of its former glory except perhaps
its brand name slapped on someone else's modems. And the shutdown
of manufacturing had been expected, part of a restructuring that
might leave the company fit for competition in markets for new
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   However, Howard had said he hoped the operations would lure a
buyer who would keep employees on the job.
</P>
<P>
   A quick and painful demise for Hayes was avoided days ago, when
financing for Hayes expired. That deal with NationsCredit expired
Nov. 20, but the bank has agreed to a two-week extension, according
to bank attorney Jesse H. Austin III, who declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   That action, which staved off the grimmest possibility, was
apparently linked to the desperate cost-cutting that comes with
suspension of manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Another key to the company's fate is the committee of creditors
named as part of the Chapter 11. That committee, whose goal is to
receive as much as possible of what its members are owed, is still
open to all options, said Charles Campbell, attorney for the
committee. ``They've got to come up with a proposal acceptable to
the banks. We don't rule anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hayes, the best-possible scenario calls for emergence as a
shadow of its former self, a company that would sell modems made
overseas by someone else. Hayes would need engineers, if it wanted
to sell newer modems, and it would need a sales staff _ but not a
lot more. The company's total workforce could wind up far fewer
than 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, during a previous bout with bankruptcy, had fended off
takeover tries by several rivals, including a $140 million proposal
from Diamond Multimedia. This time, no companies have been bidding
for Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa-based Reptron Electronics, which has an office in
Norcross, had apparently expressed interest in Hayes, but employees
were told Tuesday that an agreement calls for Kaifa Technology of
Taiwan, to take on manufacturing of Hayes modems. As part of the
arrangement, Kaifa, one of the company's largest creditors,
apparently wants Hayes to keep its warranty and repair shop open.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
