</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-N0TICKETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dec. 4 might be lucky day for lawbreakers in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fed up with the prospect of yet another year with
hardly a pay raise and possibly no uniform allowances, Atlanta
officers are threatening a one-day work action that could leave the
city thousands of dollars short.
</P>
<P>
   They call it ``no ticket Friday'' and it's planned for Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if a ticket is written on Dec. 4, except
if there's an accident,'' said Chip Warren, vice president of the
International Brotherhood of Police Officers, the city's 800-member
police union. ``It's been years since I've seen officers this
enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a ticketless Friday was the brainchild of an Atlanta
officer _ who union officials will not identify. The officer said
he's ``had enough of Mayor Bill Campbell's abuse of the police
department,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer distributed fliers encouraging his colleagues to
stash their ticket books. The fliers read: ``Ticket-free Friday.
December 4th. Don't write 'em. Have the Christmas spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   If the plan takes off it could mean a shortfall of as much as
$50,000 in revenue. The money is garnered through speeding,
accident and DUI tickets, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Warren assured the action would not compromise public safety.
</P>
<P>
   Through a written response Campbell said: ``We expect our police
officers to maintain and uphold their sworn oath of office and
enforce the laws of this city every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Beverly Harvard had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week officers learned their annual pay increases may be
frozen and their $600 uniform allowance may be wiped out as
cost-cutting measures next year. For the past three years, officers
have received only a 1 percent raise each year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether officers would be disciplined for not writing
tickets, Warren smiled: ``What are they going to do fire all of
them?''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
