A7801 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KERRY-RUN-BOS &LR;      11-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERRY-RUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY SAYS HE'S LEANING TOWARD FORMING PAC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a new signal that Senator John F. Kerry may seek
the presidential nomination, the Massachusetts Democrat privately
has begun taking steps toward establishing his first political
action committee, which could pay many of his pre-campaign expenses
and raise his national profile.
</P>
<P>
   In addition Kerry, who throughout his career has made much of
his refusal to accept PAC money, has told associates he may lift
his ban on accepting funds from other political action committees
because it is so time-consuming to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, sounding exultant over having erased much of his leftover
Senate campaign debt with a $650,000 fund-raiser Monday in Boston,
said Tuesday that he is ``very inclined'' to form the political
action committee soon. Such PACs are frequently used by
presidential prospects to cover costs such as travel and staff
salaries and to distribute campaign money to a network of political
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said the creation of the PAC doesn't mean he is running
for president, but he didn't discourage people from interpreting it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine if they want to conclude that,'' Kerry said in an
interview. ``Regardless of what happens, I want to play a stronger
role and have an impact. That builds the reason for setting up a
PAC; it can go both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Kerry might end his career-long refusal to
accept PAC money is another signal of his presidential ambitions.
``I'm not sure I can continue to do that,'' Kerry said about his
ban on PAC funds.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry plans to spend the next few weeks consulting with friends
about whether to seek the nomination and expects to make a decision
in January or February.
</P>
<P>
   While Kerry is considered a longshot to win the Democratic
nomination, his chances could be improving. For example, House
minority leader Richard Gephardt is considering staying out of the
race in hopes that Democrats will win control of the House in 2000
and elect him as speaker. Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska,
meanwhile, expressed some reservations about running, telling the
Omaha World-Herald last weekend, ``I don't intend to enter a race
to cause anybody any difficulties.'' Aides to Gephardt and Kerrey
stressed that no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   If both Gephardt and Kerrey decline to run, that would leave
Kerry, former Senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey and Senator Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota as the most prominent Democrats who have
said they are seriously considering challenging the front-runner,
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, remains a formidable candidate, especially with
Tuesday's announcement that Attorney General Janet Reno will not
seek the appointment of an independent counsel to investigate the
vice president's fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's difficulty in paying off his Senate campaign debt led to
speculation earlier this year that he would be too burdened to move
toward running for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry said Tuesday that his campaign debt should not be
considered an issue, because he raised more money than any other
Senate candidate in 1996 and is continuing to raise money that
should result in nearly eliminating the debt within months. While
the extent of Kerry's debt won't be known until he files a year-end
report, Kerry said Monday's fund-raiser went a long way toward
paying off the $1.2 million debt he reported in June. As long as
his debt is below $500,000, Kerry said, it should not be a factor
in his decision whether to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry is behind other presidential prospects in establishing a
PAC. Republicans Lamar Alexander and Dan Quayle have raised
millions of dollars this year for their PACs to help boost their
candidacies. Alexander, for example, uses his PAC not only to
contribute to candidates, but also to pay many expenses that
otherwise would have to come from a formal campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   PAC contribution limits are more generous. A campaign committee
can accept no more than $1,000 per person for the primary and
general election, totaling $2,000, while a PAC can accept $5,000
per person per year. Individuals can give to campaign committees
and PACs at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the presidential race, you are limited to $2,000,'' Kerry
said. ``A lot of people in this country are prepared to do both.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hendrie, of the non-partisan Center for Responsive
Politics, said setting up a PAC often is a crucial step for a
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help people run for president because you can pay a lot
of your general political expenses from the PAC,'' Hendrie said.
``If you want to have a fund-raising event in New Hampshire, you
can pay for air transportation and all costs associated with that.
It is a way of covering a lot of those expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   After a person formally declares his candidacy, a PAC cannot pay
direct campaign expenses such as travel. But the PAC still
continues to be a valuable source for staff support and can absorb
the high cost of important projects such as developing a direct
mail fund-raising list.
</P>
<P>
   Some presidential prospects such as Alexander have gone further,
establishing PACs in states that have no limits on contributions.
Such a step would be politically difficult for Kerry, given his
efforts to pass campaign finance laws that would restrict
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry said he saw no conflict between his support for
overhauling the campaign finance system and his move toward
establishing a PAC. Indeed, Kerry said, he hoped he could use a PAC
to help elect other members of Congress who would support his
campaign finance effort. Asked why he waited so long before taking
such a step, Kerry responded: ``Because I haven't been considering
the kinds of options that I am considering now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
