<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO REJECTS INDEPENDENT COUNSEL TO INVESTIGATE GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno decided Tuesday against
seeking an independent counsel to investigate whether Vice
President Al Gore intentionally lied to federal officials during an
inquiry into his 1996 campaign fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   Calling evidence of wrong-doing ``insubstantial,'' Reno said
there ``are no reasonable grounds'' for further examination into
Gore's statements to FBI agents about his effort to solicit
campaign funds by telephone from his government office.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision not to launch an independent inquiry of Gore's
campaign fund-raising practices _ her second such decision in a
year involving the vice president _ heads off what could have been
an embarrassing probe of Gore as he gears up for a run for the
White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The White House expressed relief and congressional Republicans
expressed outrage over the attorney general's decision, which she
outlined in a 19-page document filed with a three-judge federal
panel that oversees appointment of independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is conducting similar preliminary reviews
of alleged campaign finance irregularities involving President
Clinton and his former White House chief of staff, Harold Ickes.
Decisions by Reno on whether to seek outside investigators in those
cases are due in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton ``believes the
vice president has always acted within the letter and the spirit of
the law and that the news of today indicates this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said, ``The vice president is
pleased that this preliminary review has been concluded without the
need for an independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, an Indiana Republican who chairs a House
committee that examined Democratic fund-raising practices, blasted
Reno's decision. ``This is a sad day for the rule of law,'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not Janet Reno asks for independent counsels based
on three separate, preliminary inquiries really misses the point,''
Burton said. ``There should be one, single, independent counsel
named to investigate the entire set of questionable
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, echoed Burton's call for an independent inquiry and
suggested that Congress might ``need to take these matters out of
the hands of the attorney general, who appears to be acting
politically and not in accordance with the act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The improper placement of phone calls or misstatements to
investigators is not the issue here,'' Hatch said. ``What is at
stake is whether the public's confidence in the rule of law and the
integrity of the Department of Justice will be further eroded by
this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno dismissed critics' claims that her department has not
aggressively investigated charges against Clinton and Gore.
``Today's determination does not mean our work has ended,'' she
said. ``We will continue to vigorously investigate all allegations
of illegal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, for more than two years, the Justice Department's
120-member Campaign Financing Task Force has been investigating
allegations of wrongdoing surrounding the 1996 elections,'' she
said. Investigators have ``traveled across the country and around
the world tracking down leads. Their work is paying off _ already
14 people have been charged.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Reno decided against launching an independent
investigation of telephone calls made by Gore after he said none of
the money he raised was for the Clinton-Gore re-election campaign,
which would make the funds ``hard money'' under federal law.
Instead, he told the FBI, his efforts were to raise ``soft money,''
which would be used for issues advertising by the Democratic Party.
Soliciting so-called ``soft money'' is not regulated by law.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Gore's private attorney delivered to the attorney
general a meeting memorandum bearing hand-written notes by a Gore
aide. The notes suggest that Gore could have known more about the
purposes of the money he agreed to raise. The notes also indicate
that a portion of what Gore was soliciting would be ``hard money,''
which federal law prohibits officials from soliciting while on
government property.
</P>
<P>
   The notes were ``not sufficient alone to warrant a conclusion
that the vice president made a false statement,'' Reno said, adding
that some meeting participates had vague and, in a few instances,
mistaken understandings of the complicated allocation of money Gore
was raising. And some said Gore did not concern himself with the
details of the uses made of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find by clear and convincing evidence that the vice
president did not lie,'' Reno said in her filing with the
three-judge panel. She added: ``I am unable to identify any
additional investigation that might reasonably be expected to
provide sufficient evidence to support a successful prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision not to seek an independent counsel in the
Gore case was the first of three Reno must make by Dec. 7. Under
the independent counsel statute, the attorney general has 90 days
to decide whether to go forward with an inquiry once a formal
review of an allegation is begun. The three-month period for Gore
ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, Reno must decide whether to seek appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate the case of Harold Ickes, a
former White House deputy chief of staff who ran the 1996
re-election campaign for President Clinton and Vice President Gore.
The attorney general's review focuses on whether Ickes lied to a
Senate committee about administration assistance to the Teamsters
during a strike against Diamond Walnut Co.
</P>
<P>
   By Dec. 7, Reno must decide whether to seek an outside counsel
to investigate whether President Clinton and his aides violated
federal law when they set up a multimillion-dollar advertising
campaign financed by the Democratic National Committee. Federal
rules limit such ad campaigns to generic party ads, but Federal
Election Commission auditors have said the ads directly supported
the Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Ickes have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has turned to six independent prosecutors to investigate
allegations against Clinton administration officials. Although the
Justice Department has conducted several preliminary reviews _ the
step prior to naming of an independent counsel _ Reno has never
allowed an outside counsel to review how the Democrats financed the
1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
