<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BISHER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heavy hitters go to bat for Jackson
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S. C. _ Since the time Shoeless Joe Jackson was
banished from organized baseball, campaigns to clear his name have
been mounted, reached feverish peaks, then faded away. This time
it's different. This time it's in a serious state.
</P>
<P>
   It begins centuries, well, decades ago. After Shoeless Joe had
been set down with seven of his Chicago White Sox mates for
allegedly consorting with gamblers in the 1919 World Series, he had
played his way through semipro leagues, operated a dry cleaning
shop in Savannah, managed bush league teams, then had come home to
Brandon Mill village, where he grew up. A few doors down the street
lived this lad who delivered his afternoon paper, raked his lawn
and occasionally swung at his pitches when Joe dropped in on the
game they were playing down the street. The kid's name was John
Burgess.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening, John Burgess and a few of his close, personal
friends gathered in the Poinsett Club to keynote the latest
campaign to right the Shoeless Joe injustice. Now, the Poinsett
Club is about as far from Brandon Mill as Harvard is from Sul Ross.
John Burgess has prospered as a manufacturer, and while he had no
idea of the prominence of the man whose papers he delivered and
whose pitches he swung at on the sandlot as a kid, as an adult he
does.
</P>
<P>
   For this occasion, he spared no expenses. Tommy Lasorda flew in
to preside. Ted Williams appeared by two-way video. The newly
elected governor, Jim Hodges, announced his support. The outgoing
governor, not to be outdone, announced he was making a special
award to Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   For Tommy, this was a homecoming of sorts. It was here, as a
young pitcher, that he met his bride, Jo, and one corner of the
room was filled with her kin. It was a big ballroom, every table
occupied, including a lot of old-time players, Alvin Dark, Lou
Brissie, Billy O'Dell, Bobby Bolen, Don Buddin, John Buzhardt and
Sonny Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   The only time I've seen that many judges was at Olympic figure
skating. Congressmen, state legislators, sheriffs and every kind of
public official, including the mayor, Knox White. The president of
Furman University, Dr. David Shi, was there, and his football
coach, Bobby Johnson, in a state where coaches are living
perilously these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to get together and put Joe Jackson in the
Hall of Fame,'' Lasorda said, delivering the evening's theme.
</P>
<P>
   Highlight, though, was Williams, ``The Splendid Splinter,'' a
member of the Hall of Fame Veterans Committee who has picked up the
cudgel and spoken out for Shoeless Joe. And few can wield a cudgel
and speak out more forcefully than Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He flashed onto the screen to deafening applause, sitting in an
easy chair at his place in Citrus Hills, Fla. Lasorda had just
preceded him with, ``It's the bottom of the ninth. Who's up? Ted
Williams!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I look better on screen than in real life,'' he said, for
openers. He did look better than expected, strong of voice, and he
got through the whole spiel without a profanity, a new turn in his
elocution. ``I just hope these players and all you people will join
in our cause and see that an injustice can be rectified. His debt
has been paid and it's time for the commissioner's office to
reinstate him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a sensitive issue, in view of Pete Rose and his
non-status, but Williams has recruited some strong names, including
his old wing pilot in the Korean War, John Glenn. Fritz Hollings,
the senator, messaged his backing, as has nearly every South
Carolina senator before him.
</P>
<P>
   It's a provincial thing. Shoeless Joe is one of their own. He
made no attempt at reinstatement, never visited commissioner
Landis, wrote his congressman or filed a suit. He took it silently,
went on with his life and had no regrets, as he told me when I
wrote his story of the Black Sox Scandal 50 years ago. Of course,
whatever becomes of this, he'll never know. Shoeless Joe died in
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor for the Atlanta Journal,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
