<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oliver takes himself off Auburn list
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Speculation grew Tuesday that Tommy Tuberville of
Mississippi will be Auburn's next football coach, after interim
coach Bill Oliver withdrew his name from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's withdrawal leaves the list of candidates at three:
Tuberville, Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary and Temple coach
Bobby Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   One report Tuesday from Alabama said Tuberville, 44, will be
offered the job as early as Friday, the day after Mississippi ends
its regular season at Mississippi State. The report said that
Tuberville will be offered a compensation package that exceeds $1
million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberville has refused to comment on the reports, except to say
that speculation surrounding his future was blown ``way out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, 59, who had been the defensive coordinator, took over as
interim Auburn coach on Oct. 23 when Terry Bowden resigned with the
team at 1-5. Oliver coached Auburn to a 2-3 record, including a
season-ending 31-17 loss to Alabama on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver had expressed a strong desire to become the permanent
coach, which was one of his lifelong goals. But over the past 10
days, as Auburn pursued Tuberville, it became apparent that he
would not get the job.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said he made his decision to withdraw some time after the
loss to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my age, I just can't look in the mirror and justify to
myself that I can do for these players what a younger coach can do
for them,'' Oliver said. ``I can't say that after a year the fire
will still be (there).''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's chance to become coach might have been hurt by a media
story that accused him of undermining Bowden and orchestrating his
ouster, which Oliver has denied strongly. Tuberville became coach
at Ole Miss on Dec. 1, 1994. Two months later, the Rebels were
placed on a two-year probation that cost them 26 scholarships. Even
so, the 1997 team went 8-4 and beat Marshall in the Motor City
Bowl. He was named SEC coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberville last year turned down $900,000 to become coach at
Arkansas. In his four seasons at Ole Miss, the Rebels are 25-19
overall, 12-19 in the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
