<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Southern gets ready _ again _ for I-AA playoffs
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been business as usual this week for Georgia
Southern coach Paul Johnson. Just as he did during the regular
season, Johnson clicks on the light in his office at 5:30 a.m. A
few minutes later, he is viewing film.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' second-year head coach is not leaving anything to
chance, as he prepares his top-ranked team for an opening round
game in the I-AA playoffs against 16th-seeded Colgate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down to a one-game season, and we've got to be ready to
play,'' Johnson said, who hopes that his players are as focused as
he is heading into the 1 p.m. game Saturday in Paulson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern (11-0), winner of four Division I-AA national
championships, has a home playoff record of 17-0. The Eagles hope
it will be an advantage against Colgate (8-3), which averaged 35.5
points and 477.5 yards in total offense as a member of the Patriot
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we played hard for all year -- the chance to play
at home,'' said Johnson, who guided the Eagles to their second
Southern Conference title in a row. ``History has shown that
(Paulson Stadium) has been very good to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Colgate is led offensively by junior quarterback Ryan Vena and
senior receiver Corey Hill. The pair is sure to challenge the
Eagles' secondary, one of the weaknessess on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Vena, a 6-0, 195-pound junior, has hit 58.3 percent of his
passes for 2,298 yards and 16 touchdowns and has rushed for 736
yards. Hill, a 5-11, 186-pound senior, has 71 catches for 1,267
yards and 11 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Vena ``can make plays, so we've got to be concerned about him,''
Johnson said. ``And (Hill) is a good receiver. In fact, they're a
solid football team.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Georgia Southern, which gained its 10th playoff appearance
behind a potent one-two offensive punch of its own. Junior
quarterback Greg Hill has rushed for 1,061 yards and 16 touchdown.
He also has completed 58.8 percent of his passes for 108 yards a
game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles' most awesome weapon has been fullback Adrian
Peterson, the first freshman in NCAA Division I history to rush for
more than 1,900 yards. Peterson, a 5-10, 207-pound native of
Alachua, Fla., will face Colgate after gaining 1,932 yards and
scoring a national freshman record of 25 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
