A7841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-HAMILTON-C     11-24 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-HAMILTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star QB has done it all at Tech, except beating archrival
Georgia
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Junior quarterback Joe Hamilton has won a Carquest
Bowl MVP trophy, is on the brink of a first-team All-ACC selection,
and has helped Georgia Tech get its first New Year's Day bowl
invitation since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is Tech's most valuable player and a proven winner. But
something's missing. Like it or not, Hamilton will be judged by
whether he leads Tech to a win over Georgia. ``They'll probably put
an asterisk by my name to say, `He never beat Georgia,' '' Hamilton
conceded. ``Georgia people will say, `He may have done this and
that, but he could never beat us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Hamilton committed to Georgia Tech, he has been
compared with former Yellow Jackets standout Shawn Jones. With two
games left in his junior year, those comparisons have all but
stopped, as Hamilton has carved out his own quarterback niche. But
he'd love to have one important reason to bring up the Jones talk
again: Jones is the last Georgia Tech quarterback to beat Georgia,
his sophomore season in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's certainly capable of winning a game like that,'' said
offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen, who coached both at Tech.
``Shawn won the big games. Joe has won some big games, but that's
still there for him, too. What's left for Joe is to beat Florida
State and Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's first big win came against Virginia this season,
putting Tech in position to accomplish two of its three team goals
this season: win the ACC _ the Yellow Jackets were co-champions
with FSU, despite losing to the Seminoles _ and make a New Year's
Day bowl. Now he's going after the third _ beating Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to the Virginia game, Friedgen got in Hamilton's ear,
challenging him by saying he couldn't win the big ones. Friedgen
said he didn't plan to do that this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell Joe to play his game,'' Friedgen said. ``If
he does that, things will happen for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton doesn't want this game perceived as his own personal
issue; he just wants a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean a lot,'' Hamilton said. ``Even if the first play
of the game I'd have to go out with an injury, I'd celebrate just
as well. If we get a win 2-0 or 1-0, all you want is a win. It'll
be so exciting, you want to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the low country of South Carolina in the tiny town
of Alvin, Hamilton wasn't even much of a Clemson or South Carolina
fan. He knew hardly anything about the Georgia Tech-Georgia
rivalry. But once he arrived on campus as a redshirt freshman in
1995, he was a quick study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was talking about (how) the big game is Georgia, we
have to beat Georgia,'' Hamilton said. ``Then I saw how bad it
hurts to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He felt it as he watched from the sideline of Bobby Dodd Stadium
his redshirt year when Georgia beat Tech with Kanon Parkman's
wobbly, last-minute field goal, 18-17.
</P>
<P>
   He was feeling two kinds of pain the next year, 1996, when a
sprained ankle cosh him his first opportunity to start against
Georgia. Hamilton's initial appearance in the rivalry came that
day, in the desperate final minutes of Tech's 19-10 loss in Sanford
Stadium after backup Brandon Shaw left with an injury of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in Hamilton's first start of the series, he brought
Tech its closest to beating Georgia since 1990. He had 276 yards
passing, 55 yards rushing and one fumble on the Georgia goal line.
He figures he's got to do more on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play mistake-free football, play to the best of
your abilities, pray for some luck and refuse to lose,'' Hamilton
said. ``Right now, they've got a lot of confidence (and think) that
it's hard for us to beat them. It's our job to try to turn that
around.''
</P>
<P>
   By coming so close last year, before losing on the final drive,
Hamilton might be that much more hungry. He watched the drive in
anguish while standing on the bench on Tech's sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that moment of time when we scored to when they scored,
that's the loudest I've ever heard it,'' Hamilton said. ``(It gives
you) the feeling that you want to get a win for the community,
everybody around the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
