<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GATECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Similarities reign in upcoming UGA-Ga. Tech match
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Both defenses have been criticized for
surrendering too many yards, but Georgia and Georgia Tech enter
Saturday's game among the best in their conferences in points
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Their ability to stop the other's high-powered offense will be
the key when they meet in Georgia's Sanford Stadium. Last year,
Georgia Tech was allowing an ACC-worst average of more than 418
yards before the Georgia game. This year, despite making some
strides under first-year defensive coordinator Randy Edsall, the
Yellow Jackets have cut that number by only 20 yards and still rank
eighth in the conference. ``It's just like our defense,'' Georgia
coach Jim Donnan said. ``Factually, they've given up a lot of yards
and a lot of points. But they haven't had to worry about that
because their offense is scoring so many points.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, led by quarterback Quincy Carter and receiver Champ
Bailey, has struggled to score in recent weeks. In their last three
games, the Bulldogs have scored just one second-half touchdown. The
Dogs have battled injuries on the offensive line _ All-America left
tackle Matt Stinchcomb missed last week's game against Mississippi,
and starting center Miles Luckie probably will be out against Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia also has committed a lot of turnovers, losing three of
nine fumbles and throwing five interceptions in the last three
games. In last year's 27-24 win at Georgia Tech, the Bulldogs'
offense was its own worst enemy. Quarterback Mike Bobo threw
interceptions on two of the first five drives, and the Yellow
Jackets stopped the Bulldogs twice on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, (Georgia Tech) had some similar problems on
defense, but we couldn't put them away,'' Donnan said. ``We had
every opportunity to put them away, but we couldn't do it. Their
defense rose up on a couple of short-yardage situations and they
stopped us inside the 20-yard line once with an interception. They
did a good job of stopping us last year, but we stopped ourselves,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets' improvement on defense this season has been
against the pass. Last year, opponents threw for more than 350
yards in four games against Tech's secondary, including 489 by both
Florida State and Duke and 415 by Georgia. This season, the Jackets
had not surrendered more than 330 yards passing until Wake Forest
threw for 494 in last week's 63-35 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The difference has been in the pass rush provided by senior
defensive ends Jesse Tarplin and Nate Stimson. Tarplin, a 6-foot-3,
250-pounder from Cross Keys High, has nine sacks, nearly double his
total from last season. Sophomore Felipe Claybrooks, who had two
sacks in some 40 plays against the Demon Deacons, is Tech's best
pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns are still in the secondary, despite the presence of
free safety Travares Tillman, whom Donnan calls ``one of the better
players we will play against.'' Both cornerbacks, Louisville
transfer Jamara Clark (5-8) and senior Jason Bostic (5-9), must
contend with height disadvantages against Georgia receivers Bailey
(6-1), Tony Small (6-2) and Michael Greer (5-10).
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
