<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIABETES-SCREENING-CO     11-24 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-SCREENING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Early detection of diabetes urged
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Screening and treating adults earlier for Type 2 diabetes would
reduce its most severe complications and result in a better quality
of life, but not a longer life, a study by the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention found.
</P>
<P>
   A computer analysis published today in the Journal of the
American Medical Association found that detecting diabetes earlier
in its onset would reduce the likelihood of kidney failure during a
patient's lifetime by 26 percent, blindness by 35 percent and foot
or leg amputation by 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Using what is known as ``opportunistic'' screening _ adding a
diabetes blood test onto an already scheduled doctor's visit _ on
average found diabetes 5.5 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   However, such a strategy also ends up costing more in health
care dollars, not less, said Dr. Michael Engelgau, CDC medical
epidemiologist. Screening and treating those age 25 and older now
for diabetes instead of waiting until age 45 _ the current
guideline _ would cost about $4,500 more over a person's lifetime,
Engelgau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some cost reductions from the decrease or delaying
complications, but in the end, it's not a net savings,'' Engelgau
said. ``You actually spend a little bit more on the screening, and
the treatment begins earlier. But you're getting a better value for
your money. It's an improved quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Type 2 diabetes, or adult-onset diabetes, has increased in the
past decade to record numbers among Americans, particularly among
minority groups. About 16 million Americans are estimated to have
the disease. However, up to 5.3 million may not be aware of it
because its symptoms often go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   The disease, caused by an inability to properly process glucose,
is usually treated with exercise, a change in diet, and,
oftentimes, medications. Not catching and treating the disease
early can lead to kidney failure, dialysis, blindness, nerve damage
and possible amputation.
</P>
<P>
   While it's been widely assumed that detecting and treating Type
2 diabetes earlier would prove beneficial for individuals and for
the health care system at large, that theory had never been tested.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the CDC researchers used 10,000 hypothetical
patients, breaking them into groups by age to measure health care
costs over a lifetime. It compared costs and disease complications
between those who were screened beginning at age 25 and those
detected through current practice.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly any difference was noted in the longevity of the two
groups; those screened earlier lived only one week longer than
those screened later. African-Americans benefited the most from the
early screening.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
