<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEETHING-DANGERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer group brands 20 items as risky for kids
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some teething rings could be dangerous to a baby's
health, and other toys on the market pose choking hazards for young
children, according to the U.S. Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual survey of dangerous toys, released Tuesday, the
nonprofit consumer group cited 20 examples of items it thinks
should be discontinued or carry more prominent warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Consumer Product Safety Commission has banned small
toys and parts for children under 3, PIRG says manufacturers
circumvent the law by labeling the items for older kids, even
though they might have play value for a younger child.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some products are poorly labeled and retailers sell
toys with outdated warnings, according to PIRG.
</P>
<P>
   The teething rings appear on the group's trouble list because
they contain ``pthalates,'' substances that PIRG says can cause
liver and kidney problems and reproductive abnormalities. Specific
teethers named include the Baby Looney Tunes Cooling Ring by
Gerber, the Cool Ring Teether by First Years, the Funny Face
Teether Rattle and Disney Babies Mickey Collection by Playskool and
the Sof'Sport Teether and the Sports Fan Water Teether, both by
Safety First.
</P>
<P>
   Kirpal Singh, PIRG's campaign director, said the group wants the
use of pthalates banned, particularly in products aimed at children
under 3, because they are toxic. The group based its recommendation
on tests commissioned by Greenpeace, an environmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Toy Manufacturers of America, which represents more than 300
toy producers and importers, disputed the claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at the research and the allegations. The toys are
safe. Period,'' said Terri Bartlett, TMA's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, PIRG sends surveyors to stores to check out toys.
Their findings form the basis of its report. PIRG hopes the report
will help educate parents about toy hazards, encourage the industry
to make safer products and, ultimately, lead to stronger laws and
regulations about toy safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the toy industry is not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very interesting that the media gets a list
before the industry gets a list. I really question their
motivation,'' Bartlett said, calling PIRG's pre-holiday news
conference an ``annual ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   TMA also accused PIRG and other ``self-appointed watchdog
individuals and groups'' of alarming consumers when no real danger
exists.
</P>
<P>
   The PIRG report on the Web: http://www.uspirg.org/consumer
</P>
<P>
   /products/toy/98/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
