<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-GORE-BOS &LR;      11-24 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SEES NO CAUSE TO INVESTIGATE GORE FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno Tuesday said there were
no ``reasonable grounds'' to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Vice President Al Gore's fund-raising activities,
removing a potential hurdle in his bid for the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the evidence was ``clear and convincing'' that Gore
did not lie to FBI agents investigating the legality of
fund-raising telephone calls he made from his West Wing office at
the White House during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the evidence fails to provide any reasonable support
for a conclusion that the vice president may have lied,'' Reno
wrote in a 19-page filing to a three-judge appeals court panel. ``I
also find a lack of evidence to reasonably support a conclusion
that he may have had a motive'' to lie.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time Reno has rejected an independent counsel
to investigate Gore, and she previously has resisted pressure to
ask for a special prosecutor to examine Democratic fund-raising
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's determination does not mean that our work has ended,''
Reno said in a statement. Referring to the work of the Justice
Department 120-member Campaign Financing Task Force, she said: ``We
will continue to vigorously investigate all allegations of illegal
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two weeks, Reno must decide whether an independent
counsel is warranted to investigate campaign fund-raising issues
involving President Clinton and former White House deputy chief of
staff Harold Ickes. She is expected to reject a special counsel for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But her review of Gore had broad political implications, with
analysts predicting that the decision could narrow the field of
Democratic candidates considering challenging him for the party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was attending a staff meeting in the West Wing when he
got the news of Reno's decision, had a ``muted, modulated''
reaction, said one of his aides. ``There were no cartwheels,'' the
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane: ``The vice president is
pleased that his preliminary review has been concluded without the
need for an independent counsel. Vice President Gore will continue
focusing on what he has been doing _ working with the president to
prepare America for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision brought swift and angry reaction from Capitol
Hill, mostly among Republicans who have been calling for an
independent counsel to investigate the Clinton adminstration's
fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad, day for the rule of law,'' said Representative
Dan Burton of Indiana, chairman of the House committee
investigating campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, a Republican from Arizona and possible
presidential candidate, said Reno ``blatantly disregarded'' the
recommendations of FBI Director Louis Freeh and US Attorney Charles
LaBella to request the appointment of a special prosecutor to
investigate Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very hard to refute suspicions in this town that
this was a political decision, not one based on the merits,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether Gore lied to FBI agents investigating the
legality of fund-raising calls he made from his office to help pay
for a media campaign run by the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he believed he was soliciting ``soft money,'' or
unregulated contributions to the party, and that the media campaign
was being paid for only with soft money, which turned out to be
false.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, after a 90-day preliminary review, Reno decided
not to seek an independent counsel to examine Gore's telephone
solictations, concluding that the 45 calls he made from the White
House in 1995 and 1996 were not in violation of the federal law
that bans political fund-raising on federal property. She said the
law applied only to federally regulated contributions known as
``hard money'' while Gore thought he was soliciting unregulated
contributions or ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reno reopened the question in August when the Justice
Department obtained a memo that seemed to suggest Gore knew he was
solicting hard money. The memo, from a Democratic National
Committee budget meeting on Nov. 21, 1995,t hat Gore attended,
included handwritten notes by David Strauss, who was then a Gore
aide. The notes said the fund-raising would be ``65 percent soft,
35 percent hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In her decision Tuesday, Reno said the handwritten notes alone
were not sufficient to conclude that the vice president made a
false statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the vice president was present at the meeting, there is
no evidence that he heard the statements or understood their
implications, so as to suggest the falsity of his statement two
years later that he believed the media fund was entirely soft
money,'' Reno wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She said she reached her conclusion based on interviews that
investigators conducted with the 15 people who attended the DNC
meeting, plus documents and depositions from previous congressional
and Justice Department task force inquiries on campaign
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said none of the people who attended the meeting recalled
any particular questions or comments by Gore about the financing of
the media campaign. One attendee said Gore did not often get into
``that level of detail.'' Reno also said Strauss was unable to say
whether the references in his notes to soft and hard money were
about the media fund, the DNC's operating budget or something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor does anyone recall the vice president asking any question
or making any comments at the meeting about the media fund, much
less questions or comments indicating an understanding of the issue
of the blend of hard and soft money needed for DNC media
expenditures,'' Reno wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is thus only weak circumstantial evidence of the vice
president's knowledge _ his presence at a meeting where the subject
was briefly discussed _ which I do not believe provides reasonable
grounds to belive that further investigation of this matter is
warranted,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said the decision will make Gore, who is
already considered the front-runner for his party's presidential
nomination, even tougher to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it might just give him unfettered control over the
nomination for the Democrats,'' said Mark Rozell, a political
scientist with the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nomination now becomes his to lose,'' said James A.
Thurber, director of the Center for Congressional and Presidential
Studies at American University. ``One way to lose it would have
been to have an ongoing investigation about how he solicited funds
and have to go through that Chinese water torture test.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Reno's decision will make it harder for other
Democratic candidates to compete against Gore, saying, ``it's bad
news'' for Senators John F. Kerry of Massachusetts and Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska, who are weighing presidential bids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
