<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH-COX     11-24 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI's Freeh visits N.C. to rally team searching for Rudolph
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ FBI Director Louis Freeh vowed in a visit here
Tuesday that federal agents would search the rugged western North
Carolina mountains ``as long as necessary'' for bombing suspect
Eric Robert Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent effort to rally the small army of agents who have
hunted the area for Rudolph for almost 10 months, Freeh met for
about three hours with federal, state and local law officers
serving on the Southeast Bomb Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will maintain the investigation and search for as long as
necessary,'' Freeh said during a short media conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case will not be closed,'' he added. ``We will not stand
down. We will do whatever is reasonable and appropriate given the
information we have at the time to find the suspect and bring him
back safely to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's stopover comes at a time when authorities have again
reinforced the manhunt to more than 150 agents with hopes of
apprehending the former soldier and self-employed carpenter they
still believe is hiding in the surrounding mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It was at least the second time Freeh has flown in a government
jet to the local airport to spend a few hours being briefed on the
course of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the extent of the operation and the importance of
the case to myself , the attorney general, the (Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms), the country, I wanted to make sure the men
and women on the front line have all the equipment and resources
that they need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the agents will be working Thanksgiving, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh declined to speak about specifics of the manhunt, saying
merely, ``I was very impressed with the briefings, as I was in
May.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI director also praised the morale of the agents and the
cooperation they have received from the local community, despite
the fact that a gunman two weeks ago fired as many as eight rounds
at the Task Force command center. No suspect has apprehended in the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to extend my appreciation to the local community,''
Freeh said. ``We've not been received with anything except warmness
and support.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, 32, who grew up in the nearby mountains, is wanted in
connection with a string of nail bomb attacks in Atlanta and
Birmingham. He is accused of setting the bomb that killed one
person and wounded more than100 people during the Atlanta Olympics
in 1996, as well as the 1997 bombings at a Sandy Springs abortion
clinic and an Atlanta gay nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were led to this area the day after a Jan. 29 blast
rocked a Birmingham abortion clininc. A witness spotted a gray
Nissan pickup truck registered to Rudolph near the clinic. The
attack killed an off-duty police officer working as a security
guard and seriously wounded a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   With the leaves off the thick forest of hardwoods that cover the
ridges, authorities searching for Rudolph are optimistic. They hope
the suspect, who is considered a seasoned woodsman, will be easier
to spot. In addition, investigators also think Rudolph's food
supply is nearly exhausted and that he may make another move to
obtain more food.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph resurfaced briefly in July and took supplies from an
acquaintance who runs a health food store in Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to really exploit any opportunity, any break,''
Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   John Harmon writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
