<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-COMPANY-COX     11-24 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-COMPANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern unit plans far-reaching expansion
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Energy Inc., a unit of Southern Co., plans to
spend $1.2 billion to buy electric generating plants in California
and New York, a move that will double its U.S. capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now, for a number of months, seen a lot of opportunity
in the North American market,'' said Southern Energy President Tom
Boren.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Co. is racing to diversify its holdings in advance of
deregulation of the nation's $200 billion-a-year electric utility
industry. A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg, the company's chairman, president
and chief executive, projects 30 percent of Southern's profits will
come from new U.S. businesses and foreign operations by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy will be responsible for generating much of that
growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Boren said Southern Energy has identified
four markets for development: the Northeast, the upper Midwest,
Texas and Louisiana, and California and the Southwest desert.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy already has announced acquisitions and
developments in all of those regions except California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have generating assets in all of our target regions,''
Boren said. ``We are linking those assets with our trading and
marketing business that is run out of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren said the challenge now is to develop those assets and look
for new opportunities to enhance the company's national presence.
</P>
<P>
   In the first deal, Southern said it would buy 1,776 megawatts of
capacity in New York from Orange and Rockland Utilities Inc. and
Consolidated Edison Inc. for $480 million. The deal includes oil,
coal, natural-gas and hydroelectric plants.
</P>
<P>
   The largest asset in the New York deal is the two-unit,
natural-gas-and oil-fired Bowline power plant in West Haverstraw,
which has a total capacity of 1,215 megawatts. The other plants are
in Grahamsville, Ramapo, Tomkins Cove, Sullivan County, Middletown
and Mongaup River.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy also said it is considering spending $390
million to upgrade the New York plants and increase its new
natural-gas-fired generation in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In the other deal, the company will purchase plants with a total
capacity of 3,065 megawatts from San Francisco-based Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric for $801 million.
</P>
<P>
   The largest purchase in this deal includes seven Pittsburg
natural-gas-fired plants in the San Francisco Bay Delta with a
combined capacity of 2,022 megawatts. The other plants are Contra
Costa and Potrero plants in southeast San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitions, which are subject to regulatory approval,
``are quite significant,'' said David Burks, an analyst with
Hilliard Lyons in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The deals are indicative ``of a trend within the industry where
one utility will purchase the generating capacity from another
utility, and certainly a major company like Southern would want to
be able to have the strong capacity to meet future energy
demands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Southern purchased a network of electricity
power plants in New England for $537 million. Those plants were
sold off by Massachusetts-based Commonwealth Energy System. The
company also has completed major deals in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy's power plants serve utilities and industrial
companies. It supplies energy in 10 countries on four continents.
It's parent is the largest electricity producer in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Southern Co. closed
at $29, down 12 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
