<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURB ON TRAVEL AGENCY FEES FOR OVERSEAS FLIGHTS MAY COST PUBLIC
MILLIONS  
 THANKSGIVING TRAVEL MANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If travel industry predictions prove accurate, the public will
pay millions of dollars more in air fares as the result of the $100
limit that the major airlines recently imposed on travel agency
commissions for booking international flights.
</P>
<P>
   American Express has warned that those increased costs could
amount to $500 million, and the industry consensus is that business
travelers will pay the lion's share.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines was the first to impose the limit, on Nov. 12,
but was quickly joined by most other big carriers. Instead of the
existing 8 percent commission _ which, for example, would earn
travel agents a commission of $240 on an international round-trip
fare costing $3,000 _ the maximum commission is now $100 for a
round-trip international flight and $50 for a one-way flight.
</P>
<P>
   United chief executive Gerald Greenwald said the cap would save
the airline about $100 million annually, enabling United to operate
more effectively against worldwide competition, while Delta Air
Lines projects a savings of $40 million to $45 million annually.
Those savings are on top of the almost $1 billion that American
Express estimates the airlines have saved from the two earlier
commission reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the airlines lowered the commission to 8 percent
from 10 percent for both international and domestic fares, but with
no limit on international commissions. In February 1995, while the
airlines did not touch the existing 10 percent commission rate,
they put a $50 commission ceiling on domestic round-trip fares and
a $25 ceiling on domestic one-way fares.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that the new caps will raise costs for leisure
travelers by putting some travel agencies out of business and
requiring surviving agencies to impose fees for service even higher
than the $10 to $15 average already charged by 64 percent of
members of the American Society of Travel Agents. Both the society
and the Association of Retail Travel Agents are loudly protesting
the latest commission caps to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers are likely to be the hardest hit, according
to Ed Gilligan, president of American Express Corporate Services,
because the large majority of big corporations already pay their
travel agencies a management fee, in return for receiving the
commission on air fares. But he added that leisure travelers would
also be affected by the cap, which he described as ``an indirect
fare increase.''
</P>
<P>
   That Time of Year
</P>
<P>
   The indigestion that often accompanies Thanksgiving may have
less to do with turkey and all the trimmings than with the huge
crowds on roads and at airports. A record 33.6 million people,
roughly one in eight Americans, will travel at least 100 miles from
home over this Thanksgiving holiday, 2 percent more than last year,
according to a survey by the AAA auto club.
</P>
<P>
   That breaks down to 27.7 million people going by car _ at a time
when the average gallon of gasoline is about $1.07, or 18 cents
cheaper than last Thanksgiving, according to the Lundberg Survey _
and 5.8 million by airplane, bus or train. Average air fares appear
to be about the same or slightly higher than last year, but many
airlines have some sort of Thanksgiving sale, even if only for
quickie trips of three to four days.
</P>
<P>
   Most travelers (63 percent) plan to stay overnight with family
or friends, according to the AAA survey, and the 23 percent who
intend to stay in a hotel can expect to pay an average $80.34 a
night, or $3.55 more this year than last, according to the Lodging
Research Network of PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, however, where the occupancy rate through the
remainder of this year is expected to be very tight, the daily room
rate will average $245, 15 percent higher than last year. The rate
for a standard room at deluxe New York hotels will range between
$350 and $700 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday travel advice does not change much from year to year,
but it bears repeating that Wednesday and Sunday are among the peak
days of the year for air travel, while Thursday and Friday are the
least hectic.
</P>
<P>
   And along with advice to arrive at the airport at least an hour
ahead of time, remember that airports are cruising grounds for
pickpockets and thieves, so don't let your luggage or your laptop
out of your sight.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, drivers should bear in mind that on New England
roadways alone, an estimated 80 people are likely to be killed from
Thanksgiving through New Year's Day and 20,000 are likely to be
injured, according to the Connecticut Department of Transportation.
As the AAA advises: ``Take your time. The current land speed record
is 733 miles per hour. Don't try to break it on the way to
Grandma's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
