<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S TENNIS SEASON RUNS ON AS THE TOUR LIMPS ON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At least on the surface, women's tennis shut down for
the season at Madison Square Garden on Sunday, and did so with a
flourish:
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis received a check for $500,000 for winning the
Chase Championships, Lindsay Davenport received $250,000 as
runner-up and became the first American-born player since Chris
Evert to take the No. 1 ranking home for the holidays, and Mother
Tennis, Billie Jean King, was on hand to acknowledge the renaming
of this world championship trophy in her honor. In perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   But perpetuity, when it comes to the women's game, is a relative
term.
</P>
<P>
   Just how long the year-end championships will remain sponsored
by Chase, and just how long the event will retain the prestigious
Garden as its address, and just how long the Women's Tennis
Association will hold out before acquiescing to the novelty of an
annual championship that is combined with the men's ATP Tour
championships and staged vagabond-style in a different spot on the
globe each year _ well, all of those unanswered questions are the
reason women's tennis really didn't shut down on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did its top players, for whom a lion's share of the
circuit's $40 million yearly prize money, plus whatever endorsement
deals they have, apparently is not quite enough to make ends meet.
After complaining interminably about the interminable length of the
tennis season, which this year stretched from January through late
November, and after parading an assortment of nagging,
fatigue-related injuries from start to finish of championships
week, it would have seemed sensible for the players to beat a hasty
retreat to their spa of choice for some major unwinding.
</P>
<P>
   For example, how did Steffi Graf plan to spend her ``time off''?
Immediately after losing to Davenport in the semifinals, Graf
hopped a flight to Florida not to hit the beach, but to hit her
mark at a commercial shoot for a sponsor. Tuesday, it was back to
the airport for a quick visit to Baltimore, where Graf had herself
penciled in for an exhibition with Jana Novotna. And because Graf's
opening-round defeat of Novotna at the championships made Novotna
the event's first defending champion ever to be dethroned in the
first round, the rematch in Baltimore promised not to be a
hit-and-giggle affair.
</P>
<P>
   Then Graf planned to fly home to Germany for business meetings
and another exhibition, this time in Cologne against 17-year-old
Anna Kournikova, who evidently doesn't spend her off-season
catching up on her homework.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the WTA's intentions of shortening the tennis season
by three weeks by the year 2001, a sleight of scheduling that Bart
McGuire, the chief executive officer, claimed he would accomplish
without actually trimming away any tournaments or prize money, were
met with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't three fewer weeks of official events just open up the
players' calendars for more exhibition appearances? Kournikova
admitted she finds them more rewarding than real tournaments
because they inflict less stress and give her a chance to put on a
livelier show for her fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would try to discourage the over-playing of
exhibitions during the off season; we certainly ought to build in
dis-incentives,'' McGuire said. ``One of the ways we can keep them
from over-playing exhibitions is to make the Tour itself lucrative
enough that making another hundred thousand dollars is of less
significance to them.''
</P>
<P>
   That'll be the day. That type of approach to the problem would
require something the Tour doesn't happen to have right now: a
title sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance hit a record of 3.6 million in 1998, and domestic and
international television coverage will virtually double in 1999,
but the $4 million-a-year deal with its title sponsor, Corel, the
Canadian software firm, expires at the end of this year. Because
Corel chose not to embellish the deal beyond the bare bones
stipulated in its four-year contract, the company exits with the
WTA's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But unless one of the four global firms currently mulling the
prospect of a multiyear pact in the $7 million-$9 million range
(plus promotion, corporate entertainment and other perks that
essentially double the sponsor's investment) comes to terms with
McGuire by year's end, the tour will be running on the fumes of its
contingency fund in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the future fate of the championships, which has a
lease at the Garden through 2000?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think if we can get the championships of both the men and
women together, it would be a dynamite way to end the season,''
McGuire said. ``I simply don't know what will happen to the
Championships in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for perpetuity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
