<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-GORE25-COX     11-24 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TO GOP OUTCRY, RENO DECLINES GORE FUND-RAISING PROBE
 &HT;    580&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Tuesday there was
insufficient evidence to request that an independent counsel
examine whether Vice President Al Gore misled officials about
campaign fund-raising phone calls from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's conclusion, after a 90-day preliminary investigation,
removed a major obstacle for Gore's 2000 presidential campaign,
which otherwise would have begun under the shadow of an ethics
probe.
</P>
<P>
   However, the decision brought renewed protests from Republicans
that the attorney general is shielding the Clinton administration
from a serious examination of the campaign fund-raising scandals of
1996. ``Janet Reno has gone through extraordinary contortions not
to appoint an independent counsel for the entire campaign finance
investigation,'' said Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee. He called the
attorney general ``hopelessly conflicted when investigating her own
boss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general has a responsibility to see that the laws
are faithfully executed,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga. ``By twisting
the independent counsel statute beyond recognition, the attorney
general is actively subverting the law in order to protect the
president who appointed her.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two years, Reno has resisted calls for an outside
investigator to delve into the funding controversies of the last
presidential campaign. Both FBI Director Louis Freeh and a Justice
Department fund-raising investigator, Charles LaBella, have urged
her to appoint an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision on Gore _ the first of three similar
decisions on campaign funding probes that Reno faces within two
weeks _ was the second time that she has reviewed the vice
president's fund-raising activities and concluded that no outside
probe was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I base my decisions solely on the facts and the law, not
politics, pressure or polls,'' Reno said in a statement that
anticipated the outcry over her latest move.
</P>
<P>
   In a 19-page explanation filed in federal appeals court here,
Reno said, ``I find the evidence fails to provide any reasonable
support for a conclusion that the vice president may have lied''
when he told investigators last year that he believed his phone
calls were to raise unregulated, or ``soft'' money for Democratic
TV issue ads.
</P>
<P>
   It was later learned that some of the money Gore raised went
into ``hard'' money Democratic campaign accounts, which have more
stringent regulations and which can be used to directly support
individual candidates. A staff memo unearthed earlier this year
indicated that the vice president may have learned at a November
1995 meeting about plans to use the ``hard'' money for the TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Reno told the court that interviews with the 15 attendees at the
meeting found only two who recalled the subject of ``hard'' money
coming up. Gore was among those who said he did not remember such a
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who also attended the session, provided a
statement that ``he had no independent recollection of the
meeting,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Gore brought a low-key response from members
of the vice president's team, who have insisted that they expected
him to be cleared. His spokesman, Chris Lehane, released a terse
statement saying Gore was ``pleased'' at the outcome and that he
would ``continue focusing on what he has been doing _ working with
the president to prepare America for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it good news? Absolutely,'' said former Gore press
secretary Marla Romash. ``All of us believed that this would be
where we would be in the end. So to get there sooner rather than
later is certainly good news, but I think this is where we believed
we would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Romash cast doubts on whether having an independent counsel
examining Gore would have been an inducement to other Democratic
hopefuls to join the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to make a decision about whether to run for
president as to whether the vice president is the subject of an
independent counsel, that's nuts,'' she said. ``I think the vice
president, if he decides to run, is going to be a very formidable
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore averted an outside probe on his phone calls, the
Clinton administration could still face scrutiny on the 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno faces two more decisions on whether to seek outside
investigators. By Monday, she must announce whether to seek an
probe into whether former White House aide Harold Ickes misled a
Senate committee on his dealings with the Teamsters Union.
</P>
<P>
   And by Dec. 7, the attorney general must decide whether to seek
an independent counsel to examine Clinton's role in directing the
$44 million in Democratic TV issue ads, which critics say violated
federal campaign spending limits by tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   That allegation could lead to the broadest examination yet of
campaign finances in both parties, if Reno chooses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some reformers see that investigation as far more
significant than the Gore case. ``This was very narrow question
involving a technical issue,'' said Don Simon, counsel for Common
Cause, a non-partisan reform group.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton and the TV issue ads, Simon said, ``the question
Reno now has to face is on the broader issue that really goes to
the heart of the massive illegalities that occurred in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
said at a news conference Tuesday that ``what is at stake'' is
``whether there will be a full accounting for the reckless
fund-raising practices of President Clinton and other
administration officials.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that if Reno turns down an independent counsel in the
next two cases, then Congress may pass legislation to overrule her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it is becoming very apparent to me, and I think many
others as well, that we need to take these matters out of the hands
of the attorney general,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
