<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHORTSALES-NYT &LR;      11-24 0223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORTSALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ'S OPEN POSITIONS OF SHORT SALES DOWN 2 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions of short sales on the Nasdaq stock
market fell 2 percent in the most recent monthly period, the
National Association of Securities Dealers, which oversees the
market, reported Tuesday. It was the first time in the last 12
months that short-interest positions have declined for two
consecutive periods.
</P>
<P>
   In the month ended Nov. 13, uncovered short positions totaled
2.01 billion shares, down from 2.05 billion shares in the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
   A short position is created when an investor sells shares that
have been borrowed. If the share price falls, the investor can
profit by buying shares at a lower price to replace the borrowed
ones. Conversely, if the shares rise in price, the short-seller
faces a loss. Uncovered short sales, or those with open positions,
are those shares that have been borrowed and sold but not yet
covered by repurchase.
</P>
<P>
   For the second month, the largest short position on Nasdaq was
Dell Computer. But the stock, whose price rose sharply in the
period, also recorded the biggest decrease in open short positions.
Short positions in Dell totaled 35.8 million shares, a drop of 18.9
million shares, or 34 percent, from the previous month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
