A7872 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIPLE-MURDER-COX     11-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE-MURDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspect indicted in hotel slayings
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During a string of killings at hotels last month,
suspect Timothy Carl Dawson made repeated visits to a jailed man
whose name he had assumed, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost a counseling, a soul kind of healing process for
his wrongdoings or something,'' Fulton County District Attorney
Paul Howard said Tuesday after a Fulton grand jury indicted Dawson
on 32 charges related to the slayings of four men.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson is accused of killing LaDarris Hawkins, 19, at a College
Park, Ga. hotel Oct. 15 and Phillip Dover, 31, of Gainesville, Ga.
and Gerrold Shropshire, 50, and Ronald Gutkowski, 51, of Florida on
Oct. 18 at the downtown Hilton. All were shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson will plead not guilty, said his attorney, Thomas West.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson's motive was robbery and he killed his victims so they
could not identify him, said Howard, who is considering whether to
seek the death penalty. Howard said he wants to meet with the
victims' families in the next two weeks before announcing whether
he will try to send Dawson to death row.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson, 37, was arrested early Oct. 31 in Shelby County, Tenn.,
and initially told police his name was Harry Lee Johnson. Johnson,
in fact, was an inmate in the DeKalb County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson visited Johnson in jail after the slayings, Howard said,
although he did not know how many times or exactly when.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really aren't sure about what the dimensions of these
discussions were,'' Howard said. ``It's interesting at this point,
but we are not sure that it's of tremendous significance to us.
It's strange. It's very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's apparently some kind of symbiotic relationship they
had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said Johnson is not considered a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson probably met Dawson in jail and is cooperating with
investigators, DeKalb County Sheriff Sidney Dorsey said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Dawson visited Johnson here at the DeKalb jail several
times,'' Dorsey said recently. ``They were friends. In fact Johnson
was aware that Dawson had used his identity.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury indicted Dawson on four counts of murder; 12
counts of felony murder, which applies when someone is killed
during the commission of a felony; eight counts of aggravated
assault; four counts of armed robbery; and four weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual to load up as many charges as they can think
of,'' West said. ``We've got a long way to go to sort out what the
state has and what they don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawson also has been charged with the Oct. 5 slaying of DeKalb
County (Ga.) real estate agent Raycell Mason, 44, who was shot
several times in the head at his home. DeKalb County District
Attorney J. Tom Morgan said he will not seek an indictment against
Dawson until the Fulton cases are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said Dawson apparently had some prior knowledge of
Hawkins. But Dawson did not know the Hilton victims, although he
might have met Dover in the hotel bar, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, it was a crime of opportunity and, for some
reason, he saw this as an opportunity to rob one of the victims,''
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Gutkowski reportedly had about $600 with him, but the money was
not found on his body, Howard said. Police did not find it when
they stopped Dawson. They are still trying to learn if he used
victims' credit cards, which were found in his car, along with the
same type of gun used in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Croft writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
