<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-BUSH-APPOINTEES-C     11-24 2038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BUSH-APPOINTEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guessing game on over Bush appointees
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore and Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Decisions that Jeb Bush will begin
announcing the week after Thanksgiving will affect the lives of
Floridians more than all promises he made on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   The governor-elect's appointments to 18 state agencies and
nearly 100 boards will play a critical role in determining such
matters as:
</P>
<P>
   Whether the state's Department of Children and Families will
fire state workers in order to contract with private agencies. Bush
made it clear Friday the needs of foster children take precedence:
``Our foster care must be more compassionate and efficient. Though
I want to be considerate of state workers, it will not deter me
from doing what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Who controls Florida's water in the next century. If he wishes,
Bush will be able to remake all fivecq of the state's water
management boards within three years. Because of quirky vacancies,
the change could happen even faster at the Everglades-managing
South Florida Water Management District.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion. An anti-abortion legislator/physician with views
shared by Bush, Rep. Bob Brooks, R-Winter Haven, is a leading
candidate for Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the next developments in South Florida cities are in the
suburbs or downtown. Bush, a developer, must decide how hard he
wants his Department of Community Affairs to enforce
growth-management laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire face of environmental protection in Florida is at
issue here,'' said Charles Lee, senior vice president of the
Florida Audubon Society. ``The appointments will guide whether this
administration lives up to its promises. This is where the rubber
meets the road.''
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach City Commissioner Mary Hooks, who Bush selected
as a policy adviser to his transition team, met Friday in
Tallahassee with a nine-member group that will deal with
environmental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   She revealed little, saying the team's job is to recommend
candidates whose ``policies reflect Jeb Bush's vision . . . we've
got to look at each department in its entirety in 50 days.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Bush will appoint more than 3,000 people in his first
two years., running mate Frank Brogan estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Already, hundreds of resumes have flooded the offices of the
Bush transition team in a fourth-floor office in Tallahassee. One
long shot: a Tampa woman who listed her experience as co-sales
manager at Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County names mentioned include County Commissioner
Mary McCarty and Sheriff Bob Neumann, but both say they plan to
serve out their elected terms.
</P>
<P>
   The incoming governor has sole power to nominate secretaries or
executive directors of 18 agencies, from Corrections to the
Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The picks must be approved by a Senate committee chaired by Sen.
William G. ``Doc'' Myers, R-Hobe Sound. Bush will share power with
the Cabinet for appointments at several more agencies and has
indicated he may want to keep some department heads in place, such
as Tim Moore at the Florida Department of Law Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   With the Department of Transportation, there's talk Bush may
wait until after the legislative session to take action because of
a messy bullet-train debate and other pending business. Democratic
Sen. Jim Hargrett of Tampa, the former Senate transportation
chairman who endorsed Bush, was an early name mentioned for the job
but he may not want it.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush may leave some agencies alone, make no mistake: He
will have tremendous power to make changes right away if he wants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to posts where terms are expiring, there is a huge
backlog of nominations left over from last session. Despite
Democrats' protests, the Republican-controlled Senate never
confirmed 285 nominees of Gov. Lawton Chiles last year.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly stranded nominees included 145 trustees of community
colleges, all but 10 of which are Democrats, including four at Palm
Beach Community College and six at Indian River Community College.
Also in limbo are 37 nominees to the state's five water and
environmental boards, of which 25 were Democrats. In virtually all
cases, Bush is free to put forward his own picks.
</P>
<P>
   Appointments to the Department of Environmental Protection and
the South Florida Water Management District will put a new stamp on
what, for this entire decade, has carried Gov. Lawton Chiles'
imprimatur.
</P>
<P>
   Adding even more intrigue is a 1997 law that directs that the
new governor ``shall'' appoint three members to the South Florida
water board in his first term, and two members in each of the next
three years. The intent: to prevent a new governor from remaking
the water boards in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, however, neglected the case of the water district,
SFWMD, where the terms of five board members began in March 1995
and end on March 1, 1999. In addition, there is a vacancy left
because of board member Eugene Pettis, whom the Senate refused to
confirm this spring.
</P>
<P>
   So does that mean Bush can appoint three members his first year,
or four? Leaving the board with only six or seven members for a
year?
</P>
<P>
   Water district lawyers aren't sure. Neither are lawyers for the
House committees that wrote the bill. Rep. Lee Constantine,
R-Altamonte Springs and chair of the House Resource and Land
Management Council, said it was never the legislature's intention
to leave some geographic areas unrepresented for a year on a water
board, as would happen if one or more vacancies remained opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly if we're going to have openings on the board that
can't be filled, we'll just have to change it,'' he said, promising
a quick new law to fix any problems caused by the last one.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Bush appoints six members in one or two years makes
little difference in the long run: By the end of his first term, he
will have shaped the entire board in the image he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   While some environmentalists viewsee with this trepidation,
others do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to find out that Bush is a pretty savvy
guy,'' said Peter Antonacci, who until last year was Attorney
General Bob Butterworth's chief deputy and who now lobbies for The
Everglades Trust.
</P>
<P>
   He predicts, for example, that farmer and cattle rancher Frank
``Sonny'' Williamson Jr., the SFWMD's chairman, will be reappointed
for a third four-year term: a prospect he believes
environmentalists should welcome. ``Just because you're a farmer or
rancher doesn't mean your interests are adverse to ours,''
Antonacci said.
</P>
<P>
   Should change come, some of the most mentioned names as board
members or possible replacements for Executive Director Sam Poole _
a favorite of environmentalists _ include former Deputy Executive
Director Tom MacVicar, who narrowly lost to Poole for the top spot
in 1994, and former district spokeswoman Cathy Vogel. Both work as
consultants to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the rumor mill: retired Army Corps of Engineers
commander Terry Rice, who is a consultant to the Miccosukee Indian
tribe, and Ken Adams, a former board member and ex-Palm Beach
County commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said he has no plans to leave, but even he has heard the
rumors. For example, he said he's heard that former district
Chairman Jim Garner _ a Fort Myers agribusiness and development
lawyer _ has been recruiting people to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   But Garner said that's news to him. ``I'm not aware of a
throw-Sam-out movement,'' he said before the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam and I have been friends for years,'' Garner added,
although he acknowledged that ``If I had a complaint about Sam,
it's that I believe he lacks the management skills and management
training to deal with a 1,600-person agency. . . . I guess time
will tell whether he's been effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Eva Armstrong, a lobbyist for the Audubon Society, said Bush
promised to extend the Preservation 2000 land-buying program and to
continue Everglades restoration during the campaign, and that he
will be obligated now to reflect those commitments in his
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct tells me that the appointments he makes the first
year will be the most balanced we'll see,'' she said, scoffing at
some worries that Bush will fill the board with road pavers and
sugar growers. ``I'm not sure it'll be all pavers, at least
initially. Or at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dunbar, a prominent Republican lobbyist and a decade ago
the general counsel to Gov. Bob Martinez, said Bush has far more
pressing worries in the next two months than filling vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be astounded if they've even thought about these,'' Dunbar
said. ``They have hundreds, HUNDREDS, of appointments that have got
to be made first.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar denied any interest in running the Department of
Environmental Protection, as some rumors in Tallahassee would have
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumors are running wild in this town.'' he said, adding
that he had heard Curt Kiser was a possibility for the job but
would be surprised if he took it. Kiser said he wasn't interested.
</P>
<P>
   Antonacci said he had heard that Martinez' running mate in 1990,
former Monroe County sheriff Allison DeFoor, was interested in the
DEP position. ``Rest assured: I'm sure Sally (Bradshaw) is handling
it,'' Antonacci said.
</P>
<P>
   A state legislator who opposes abortion, Rep. Bob Brooks,
R-Winter Park, is a name frequently heard for Secretary of Health.
Bush shares Brooks' views though he said during the campaign he was
not in favor of any drastic action without a wide consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The man Brooks would replace, James T. Howell of Palm Beach
County, took a cautious approach to Brooks-sponsored legislation
that required the state to give women seeking abortions a pamphlet
about risks and alternatives. The size and content of the
three-fold pamphlet came under fire from abortion foes., who said
it was not nearly as bold or straightforward as publications in
other states. Distribution was halted by a court injunction that is
still in place while a constitutional challenge to the law is
decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Brooks) would be a good selection,'' said Mike
McCarran, executive director of the Florida Catholic Conference.
``I think he has the credentials and experience to be a good
director of that agency.''
</P>
<P>
   People who say they support abortion rights expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem I have with Brooks is he is anti-choice,''
said Charlene Carres, a women's rights attorney in Tallahassee. ``I
know he's a very caring physician.'' who treats AIDS and HIV
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   As an agency head, Brooks would have to carry out laws passed by
the legislature, though his own judgment would come into play in
sometimes subtle ways, Carres said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the state gathers statistics on abortion, but there
have been debates about whether the state should obtain more
specific personal information, such as age, ethnicity and other
characteristics. Doing so might help identify them in smaller
communities, Carres argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I hear is Brooks, Brooks, Brooks,'' said one
Department of Health employee. ``I think Howell thought for a while
he would not be replaced, but that doesn't seem to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he talked last week with Broward County Circuit Judge
Kathleen Kearney though he did not get into specifics about the
Children and Families job. A call to her chambers was not
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Manatee County Sheriff Charlie Wells, who has led pilot efforts
to have child-investigative and foster services assumed by private
or law-enforcement agencies, is on Bush's transition team. He could
wind up part of the Bush administration as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would try to be creative with state employees who
might be displaced by privatization efforts, perhaps shifting them
to other jobs, but their welfare should not be the overwhelming
priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to focus on the children we are serving,'' Bush said.
``Not on who's providing the service.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore and Shirish Date write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. Staff writers Bob King, Noah Bierman and
Brian E. Crowley contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
