<SLUG> BC-FLA-SMOKESUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoke not cleared yet over lawsuit
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ The fight over legal fees in the state's
tobacco lawsuit isn't quite over, and a last-ditch appeal by three
of the state's trial lawyers has at least temporarily delayed
approval of a $1.7 billion bonus Florida won from the industry two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday lawyers for the state asked a judge to formally
approve a deal with cigarette makers giving the state $1.7 billion
over the next five years _ elevating the total settlement to $12.7
billion _ and expanding restrictions on advertising of tobacco
products.
</P>
<P>
   A judge must approve the deal so its provisions can be enforced
by the court.
</P>
<P>
   But retired state Supreme Court Justice James Alderman, the
seventh judge to oversee the suit since 1995, said he could not
approve the deal because some of the lawyers are seeking a new
hearing before the Florida Supreme Court on their fees. Until the
high court decides on the hearing or grants him jurisdiction, he
can't rule, Alderman said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Licko, a lawyer for the state, said the deal must be
ratified soon if the state is to collect its first payment under
the agreement, $123 million, on Jan. 4 as scheduled. The state
won't get the money until 30 days after the agreement is approved,
when the time for appeals has expired.
</P>
<P>
   Additional restrictions, such as the ban on sales of T-shirts
and other merchandise bearing the logos of cigarette brands, are
set to be in place on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Three trial lawyers hired by the state _ Bob Montgomery of West
Palm Beach, Sheldon Schlesinger of Fort Lauderdale and Bob Kerrigan
of Pensacola _ have sought to be paid under a contract they and
other lawyers signed with the state; that would give the trial team
25 percent of the settlement. The rest of the trial team has agreed
to have fees determined by arbitrators, a plan proposed in the
state's 1997 settlement with the industry.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 13, the Florida Supreme Court ruled the lawyers had a
valid fee contract, but could not file liens against the money
being paid to the state. To collect their fee, the lawyers would
have to file a breach-of-contract lawsuit against the state,
something they are loath to do because they would still need
legislators'approval to get paid.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, for one, said he was ready to give up his case _ and
another suit he filed against other trial team members _ after the
high court's ruling. But now he's reluctant to go to arbitration
because doing so requires the ``consent'' of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very difficult time believing what anyone says,''
Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hiaasen writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
