<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARK-ATTACK-COX     11-24 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARK-ATTACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rare shark fatality remains mystery
 &HT;    By staff reporters
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When 9-year-old James Willie Tellasmon
vanished from the surf under a sunny sky about 40 yards off the
Vero Beach shoreline Saturday, chance as much as nature conspired
against him.
</P>
<P>
   James became one of the very rare victims of a fatal shark
attack, an event that hasn't occurred at a Florida beach in 22
years.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities and shark experts say they might never know exactly
what happened to the boy as he swam in 8 to 9 feet of water with
his mother's boyfriend. The attack happened fast, and left little
evidence. Moments later, the only trace was a toy gun floating in
the water, one rescuer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any fin, any thrashing, any lifting the person
out of the water,'' said William ``Billy'' Heffelfinger, 30, who
helped pull the boyfriend, Jimmy Wilson, to shore before returning
to search for James.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the kid had vanished and . . . a shark crossed my
mind because I said, you know, as much fight as (James) was putting
up, he's got to at least splash or show some bubbles or something.
It was like he fought his last battle.''
</P>
<P>
   James had a far better chance being struck by lightning, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida leads the world in the number of shark attacks _
25 occurred off its beaches last year _ they are seldom deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to the family on this. It doesn't make them
feel any better this was the result of a statistically rare
event,'' said George Burgess, a University of Florida biologist and
curator of the International Shark Attack File at the school's
Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess theorizes that a large shark _ any shark over 6 feet is
a threat to humans _ was in the area hunting for bait fish on a
small reef in the area, in front of a sharp drop in the ocean
floor. Sharks had been sighted earlier. On Nov. 11, about 2 miles
away on a stretch of unguarded beach 300 yards south of South Beach
park, a 13-year-old boy was bitten by a small shark as he walked
through the surf, said Vero Beach Police Chief Jim Gabbard, who
fielded calls Tuesday from reporters across the country and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shark could have grabbed him and pulled him over the edge
of the bar,'' said Burgess.
</P>
<P>
   In October and November, mullet and other fish begin migrating
from rivers and lagoons into deeper, warmer water. Sharks follow.
Some species head south for warm water while others remain offshore
foraging, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically when sharks mistake swimmer for bait, they immediately
release their hold and rarely cause serious injury. Scientists call
this a hit-and-run attack. Bigger sharks will bump their prey
before biting. Sometimes, but more seldom, a shark will launch a
sneak attack, usually in deep water. In both cases the shark
continues the attack with repeated bites.
</P>
<P>
   James' small size could have played a part in the shark not
releasing him, Burgess said. He also could not say whether other
sharks scavenged the body after that.
</P>
<P>
   Along the east coast, migrating sharks are often closer to
bathers because the continental shelf narrows, unlike the Gulf
Coast where attacks are far more infrequent, said Dr. Carl Luer of
the Mote Marine Laboratory in Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, James came to the beach for a family outing, said
Vero Beach Detective Dan Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 2 p.m., he and Wilson were swimming when
Heffelfinger, who was playing football with a half dozen friends,
noticed them struggling in water 100 yards north of the guarded
shore on Jaycee Beach and raced down the beach, Heffelfinger said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached Wilson, James had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I looked at (Wilson), another five to 10 yards, that's
where I last saw the boy. When I didn't see him come up any more, I
took the father and got to beach. I said, `Where's the boy, where's
the boy?' It was apparent he was already in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Heffelfinger said he handed Wilson off to his friend, Chad
Taylor, and swam back to look for the boy. He said he dove under
again and again until three lifeguards arrived minutes later.
Within 15 minutes, police and fire department divers arrived,
Gabbard said.
</P>
<P>
   The search continued until dark without any trace of the boy or
a shark, and resumed about 5:45 a.m. Sunday. About 7:22 a.m.,
divers found James' torso and legs. His head and arms are still
missing, Gabbard said.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess plans to review autopsy findings in hopes of getting a
better idea of what happened to James.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, we'll certainly be able to tell the size (of
the shark). The species may never be known. If a tooth fragment was
left behind, we can usually tell. But more than likely, we'll never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Coast Medical examiner Frederick Hobin's office said no
teeth were recovered.
</P>
<P>
   While yellow and blue flags warning of currents, bait fish,
jellyfish and Portuguese man-of-war flew along Vero's beaches
Tuesday, there was no sign of sharks, said lifeguard Capt. Tom
Adams. Guards typically keep an eye on bait fish for splashing or
jumping that would indicate predator fish, he said. There are no
plans to change the way the area's seven beaches are guarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control what's out there in the ocean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sheriff's Office might sweep the beach with its
helicopter during routine patrols, Gabbard said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Burgess suggests swimmers use common sense: get out
of the water if there's a shark and get out of the water if there
are a lot of bait fish. Sharks are attracted to irregular
splashing. In 1988, a swimmer diving from a boat with a small dog
off Bay County was killed by a shark. The dog probably lured the
shark, Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic this is all happening now because over the last 15
years the story on sharks has not been shark attacks man, but man
attacks shark. The reality is in Florida, as well as other areas,
shark populations are in very sharp decline as result of over
fishing by sport and commercial fishermen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the whole situation, one bathers tend to forget, is
when you enter the ocean, you're entering a wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post researcher Philip Pettijohn contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
