</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 26
 &HT;    Settle in for good acting, action from negotiators Jackson,
Spacey
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   In this crisply acted thriller, Samuel L. Jackson plays a
hostage negotiator who's framed for skimming millions from the
police department's disability fund. Refusing to be jailed on false
charges, he takes four Internal Affairs officers hostage, then
insists on a jackpot negotiator (Kevin Spacey) to act as mediator
between himself and his former colleagues, who are outside the
building hoping to smoke Jackson out. Or kill him. The movie's main
kick is the duel of bluffs and counterbluffs between Spacey and
Jackson, but director F. Gary Gray remembers the meat and potatoes
of this genre: lots of action scenes. Match that with some terrific
acting, and the movie takes no hostages. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Also directed by F. Gary Gray: ``Friday'' and ``Set It Off.''
</P>
