<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-VIAGRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NTSB to look at Viagra connection in crash
 &HT;    By Mary Lou Pickel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH _ Federal investigators are wondering whether
Viagra played a role in the deadly crash of a Delray Beach, Fla.
man's airplane in a Maryland creek Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   William G. Knight, 56, a former stockbroker, safari hunter and
sometime actor, carried a prescription bottle of Viagra in his
luggage, National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Matthew
Furman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-impotence drug can affect a pilot's ability to
distinguish between different colors, including blue and green,
Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman Arlene Salac said.
Those colors are used in runway lighting and in cockpit
instruments, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB knows of no crashes related to Viagra, Furman said.
</P>
<P>
   But an FAA pamphlet issued in October to doctors who perform
physicals on pilots recommends ``six hours from Viagra to
throttle.'' That's enough time for the drug to pass through the
body.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB sent Knight's blood and tissue samples to an FAA lab in
Oklahoma Tuesday to test for alcohol and drugs, Furman said. The
results are expected within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Furman stressed that the NTSB simply is gathering information to
do a thorough investigation and has cast its net wide to include
possible Viagra use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be remiss if we didn't find out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Greer of Lake Park, who routinely gives pilots
required physicals, said he doubts Viagra had a direct effect on
Knight's crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would a guy take it if he's going to get in his plane
alone?'' Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland medical examiner determined that Knight died from
head injuries and drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Knight's plane sputtered before crashing about
5:43 p.m., and Larry Walker, chief pilot for Anne Arundel County
Police, surmised that Knight overshot the runway, then crashed in
the creek as he turned to make another pass.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB will investigate whether Knight refueled at two
scheduled stops along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, a former naval intelligence officer, had flown 30 hours
in his RV-6 two-seater, which professionals had built from a kit.
Knight had landed at the Lee Airport outside of Annapolis, Md.,
before, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members recalled Knight as an adventurer who played small
roles in Oliver Stone movies, including Born on the Fourth of July
and Wall Street. The thrice-divorced father of two loved living on
the edge, wrote articles for magazines, restored World War II
planes and flew in air shows, his brother, Morton F. Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Pickel writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
