A7926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-COX     11-24 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Education Commission wants to toughen TAAS By Sharon Jayson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Education Commissioner Mike Moses said
Tuesday he wants to toughen up the TAAS by raising passing
standards on the state's achievement test and adding new elements
to the statewide accountability system used to grade schools.
</P>
<P>
   Moses will announce his ideas at a news conference Dec. 4, but
said they would include continuing to raise the TAAS passing rate
for a campus to be considered acceptable and adding the Algebra I
end-of-course exam into the accountability equation. ``We're
looking at additional changes to the assessment system and some
tweaking of the accountability system,'' Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Assessment of Academic Skills lies at the heart of the
accountability system that rates campuses according to how well
their students perform on the test. Ratings are based on standards
for all students at a school and for each student group _
African-American, Hispanic, white and economically-disadvantaged.
The standard for an acceptable rating has been increasing by 5
percent every year, with 40 percent as this year's acceptable
standard. The increases were due to end in 2000, but Moses said he
favors a 70 percent acceptable standard by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools have been by-and-large showing the growth to be able
to meet that standard,'' he said. ``When I became commissioner, 25
percent was considered acceptable. This next year it will be 45
percent. In 2000 it will be 50 percent. I'd like to see us continue
to talk about raising the bar at five percent increments.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Moses' ideas would require action by the Legislature,
but he has the authority to implement others on his own. A
commissioner's advisory committee on accountability also will offer
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Moses said adding the end-of-course Algebra 1 exam into
calculations for a school's accountability rating might draw
attention to the test in which only 39 percent of students received
a passing grade of 70 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems when you put things in the accountability system
schools pay more attention to it,'' Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years the Algebra 1 exam has been given, the
passing rate was 28 percent in 1996, 35 percent in 1997 and 39
percent this year. In comparison, the passing rate for the
comparable Biology 1 end-of-course exam was 80 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hopkins, who oversees math curriculum for the Texas
Education Agency, said Algebra 1 exam scores have been especially
poor because it's up to schools to decide if they want to include
those scores in a student's grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been improvement in the scores, but they are still
extremely low. Part of the thinking has been that there's no real
motivation for students to pass the exam,'' he said. ``The
commissioner is thinking if they raised it to accountability status
there would be more emphasis on encouraging students to pass the
exam.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cole, president of the Texas Federation of Teachers, said
``there's no doubt there's a need to be making the standards
higher, but the algebra problem is a tough one'' due to factors
like a shortage of math teachers and promotion of students who are
flunking. He's sure that factoring the math test into ratings
calculations would cause school ratings to drop, but he said it
would get districts to pay attention to the end-of-course test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that a fairly high percentage of teachers assigned
to supervise algebra classes are not qualified to be there. Parents
and students are not told. Nobody knows that they're not qualified
except the teacher and principal,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Algebra 1 is one of three math classes required for graduation
from Texas schools. Some students take the class in middle school,
while others take it in high school. Schools must give the
end-of-course exam during a two-week period at the end of the term.
``Many kids in Algebra 1 classes never passed a math class in their
life and have been promoted from grade to grade. They ended up in
Algebra 1 because they have to take it,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Austin school district, Bowie High School's math
department chair Lloy Lizcano said the algebra exam counts 25
percent toward the final exam. She said difficulties in
administering the test could account for lower passage rates. ``We
don't have enough calculators nor the time or place to put 650 kids
to take it all at the same time so we run it in shifts. It's a
massive scheduling problem and some students are cut short,
especially at end of the day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lizcano said she would like some kind of accountability system
for math before students get to high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have students who start 9th grade here who haven't passed a
math class since third grade. You can fail a math class and be
promoted and fail TAAS and be promoted,'' said Lizcano.
</P>
<P>
   With a nationwide shortage of teachers in certain subjects like
math, science, bilingual and special education, a spokeswoman for
the 82,000-member Texas State Teachers Association said teacher pay
also figures into the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Cootes, the organization's spokeswoman, said there were
10,000 teaching vacancies in Texas last year that were never
filled.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Jayson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
