<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7933 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-SECONDA     11-24 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-SECONDARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS FIDDLE WITH SECONDARY,  LASSITER REPLACES TILLMAN AS
STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeing the Washington Redskins score touchdowns on six
consecutive drives last Sunday has prompted Cardinals Coach Vince
Tobin to make two moves in his secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-year pro Kwamie Lassiter was promoted to starting free
safety ahead of rookie Pat Tillman, and second-round draft pick
Corey Chavous was moved from strong safety to right cornerback,
where he could start Sunday at Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter moved to the first team after his game-saving
interception in the final 70 seconds of the 45-42 victory over the
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Playing mostly in nickel back situations, Lassiter has four
interceptions, second most on the team. He also has forced three
fumbles and recovered another on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter began training camp as the starting free safety but
lost his job to Tillman the week of the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kwamie didn't sulk,'' Tobin said. ``He played extremely well.
He has been in the right spot. He has made the right calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter said he didn't think he should have been demoted in the
preseason but that he got over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised,'' he said of Tuesday's move. ``I thought it
would be a lot harder to get the starting job back. But I feel I've
been playing my best football. I feel a lot more comfortable out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he hasn't lost faith in Tillman, the seventh-round
pick from Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not blaming Pat for our woes in the second half of the
Washington game,'' Tobin said. ``I haven't given up on Pat Tillman
by any stretch of the imagination. We think he's getting better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch of Chavous to cornerback came after the Redskins
picked on veteran J.B. Brown throughout the second half. Brown
played the entire half because of Tom Knight, who began the season
as the starter, aggravated a hamstring injury that caused him to
miss four consecutive games earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said Chavous will be evaluated at cornerback in practice
the next three days before a decision is made on a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous started at left cornerback for four seasons at
Vanderbilt and had 12 career interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams, such as the Minnesota Vikings, considered him one of
the best cornerbacks in the 1998 draft. Most teams, including the
Cardinals, felt he was more suited for strong safety, where he has
backed up Tommy Bennett most of the season but played in nickel
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of a corner, you think of a (fleet-footed),
turn-on-a-dime kind of guy,'' Tobin said. ``Cory doesn't have that
kind of quickness, but he has plenty of attributes that let him
play that position _ he's strong and has the size.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavous (6 feet, 204 pounds) said he is excited about the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible challenge and a position that's very
demanding, but it's the one I feel comfortable playing,'' Chavous
said. ``I have to meet the challenge because this team is in a
position to do a lot of good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can play either position in this league. There were
some questions about me playing (corner) in some schemes because I
was a bump-and-run corner in college. Bump-and-run corners who
don't run 4.3 (in the 40-yard dash) . . . teams have some
reservations. But I competed against some great college receivers _
Ike Hilliard, Reidel Anthony, Marcus Nash _ and I felt I held my
own.''
</P>
<P>
   J.J. McCleskey will move from cornerback to strong safety to
back up Bennett. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
