<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Rights Investigations Merged
</P>
<P>
   A panel of 11 senior judges upheld the merger of two separate
investigations into human rights abuses in Chile and Argentina
under former military rule, putting both under the control of
Baltasar Garzon, the Spanish magistrate who issued the arrest
warrant for the former Chilean dictator, Gen. Augusto Pinochet, on
charges of genocide. Britain's highest court rules Wednesday on
whether Pinochet, who is in British custody, deserves immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   France: Terrorist Ends Hunger Strike
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ The international terrorist known as Carlos ended a
20-day hunger strike in a French prison where he is serving a life
sentence for murder, according to one of his lawyers. Carlos, whose
real name is Ilich Ramirez Sanchez, was protesting solitary
confinement and alleged harassment by his guards, but began eating
again after pleas from his family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Hindu Nationalists Tested
</P>
<P>
   NEW DEHLI _ Voters in the capital of Delhi and the states of
Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh and Mizoram will chose Wednesday among
the ruling Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, the Congress
Party and other smaller parties. The local elections offer the
first test of the Bharatiya Janata Party's popularity since it took
power at the head of an 18-party coalition eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Higher Wages Sought
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's two most important labor federations said
they would join forces to press for a 22 percent wage increase. The
government offered a 13 percent wage hike in its 1999 budget
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Air Force Apologizes
</P>
<P>
   Two Air Force colonels, both chiefs of intelligence units, were
dismissed for spying on 10 Argentine journalists who were reporting
about airport security and privatization of airport facilities. The
Air Force apologized and said it was investigating other officers.
</P>
