<HEADLINE>
BONNER LIKELY TO SIGN DEAL WITH FALCONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rattlers quarterback Sherdrick Bonner left for Atlanta on
Tuesday and is expected to sign with the Falcons today, Rattlers
Coach Danny White said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner, who led the Rattlers to the ArenaBowl two years ago and
holds all of the franchise's passing records, was given a tryout
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons Coach Dan Reeves was impressed enough to inform Bonner
that he would be signed once a slot opened.
</P>
<P>
   It did this week, White said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons on Tuesday tracked down Bonner on a Phoenix golf
course, where he was playing in a charity tournament with White.
White informed Bonner of the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was obviously pleased,'' White said. ``He couldn't wait to
get home and pack. I'm sure his head is spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was an assistant coach with the Dallas Cowboys when White
played quarterback. They've remained close friends.
</P>
<P>
   White said last week he went to Atlanta to talk to Reeves more
about Bonner, who was the ArenaBowl Most Valuable Player in 1994
when the 6-foot-4, 225-pound left-hander led the Rattlers to their
first title.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reeves is) aware not only what kind of thrower he is, because
he's seen him, but he's also aware that Sherdrick has thrown 11
touchdown passes to every interception he's thrown and he's only
been sacked once in three years,'' White said. ``Those are things
he can't show in a tryout.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner will remain Rattlers' property and go on their exempt
list, White said.
</P>
<P>
   White said Bonner will start out on the Falcons' practice squad.
Chris Chandler suffered an injury Sunday and is questionable this
week. His backups are Steve DeBerg and Tony Graziani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great opportunity,'' White said. ``He's with a
good team, a good program, a great head coach. He's got a
legitimate shot not only to make the team but to play. I think
within a couple of weeks, he could have the system down well enough
to play if they needed him to. I'm sure they hope they don't have a
need for him to play. But the way injuries are, two of those guys
could get hurt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
