</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SODOMY-LAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STRIKING DOWN THE SODOMY LAWS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Nov. 25:
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Hardwick looked up from the privacy of his
apartment in Atlanta one day 16 years ago, he was stunned to see a
policeman standing in the door. ``What are you doing in my
bedroom?'' he asked. It is a question that took on a special
bitterness for gay men and lesbians after the U.S. Supreme Court in
1986 upheld the Georgia law against sodomy under which Hardwick was
arrested that day. The law was 170 years old. It prohibited oral
and anal sex by anyone, homosexual or heterosexual, and like all
such laws in the United States it was modeled on old English law,
which was shaped by religious teachings.
</P>
<P>
   In his argument to the Supreme Court, Georgia Attorney General
Michael Bowers attacked homosexual sodomy as ``anathema to the
basic units of our society _ marriage and the family.'' Five
justices bought the argument, upholding the law in a decision that
removed any claim homosexuals had to privacy or to protection from
government intrusion in their bedrooms. To decide otherwise, Chief
Justice Warren Burger said, would ``cast aside millennia of moral
teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   But the critical constitutional question, Hardwick's lawyer
later wrote, ``was not what Michael Hardwick was doing in his
bedroom, but rather what the state of Georgia was doing there.'' On
Monday, ruling in another case, the Georgia Supreme Court agreed,
and struck down the law. This case arose from heterosexual acts
between a man and woman, but the court made clear that Georgia's
Constitution guarantees rights of privacy that make no distinction
between homosexuals and heterosexuals. ``We cannot think of any
other activity that reasonable persons would rank as more private
and more deserving of protection from governmental interference
than consensual, private, adult sexual activity,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia decision follows one by a city circuit judge in
Baltimore last month who held that Maryland law could not
discriminate by making sodomy illegal for homosexuals and not for
heterosexuals. In Rhode Island, the legislature voted to repeal its
anti-sodomy law earlier this year. One way or the other, in almost
two-thirds of the states, outdated legal restrictions on private
sex have fallen away. The remaining holdouts should drop the last
traces of this assault on privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEZER-DEATH-COX     11-24 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEZER-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Body of missing woman identified
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett and Alexandra Navarro Clifton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For five days, police officers who were
friends and relations of Christopher Benedetto and Janette Piro
used the couple's Singer Island home as the command post to solve
their disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives with decades of homicide experience in New York City
searched the house for clues and could find none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did notice when I first went into the house I was struck by
the smell of cleanliness,'' said Arthur Esposito, Benedetto's
cousin and a Titusville police detective. ``I smelled Clorox, Lysol
maybe. But I didn't think much of it because Chris always kept his
house immaculate.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to lock up the home Monday morning and return
to their jobs, Esposito said they decided to check the box freezer
in the corner of the garage to make sure it contained nothing that
would spoil.
</P>
<P>
   What they would find inside was more than even hardened New York
cops could handle.
</P>
<P>
   It was Janette Piro's hunched and frozen body. It had been there
in the house full of detectives all along.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Benedetto, Christopher's brother and a Nassau County
officer, raised the freezer lid and screamed in horror at seeing
his dead sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul stumbled back and ran inside the house and into the
living room,'' Esposito said. ``He was screaming and he was going
into shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Benedetto, another brother who is retired from the New York
force, then saw the grisly contents and broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike was extremely upset,'' said Esposito. ``I could see the
body from where I was standing and I went right for the phone. I
called 911 and told them we needed the police to come right over
because we had a homicide. Then I called for an ambulance because I
could see Paul needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Benedetto used the freezer to store fishing bait,
Esposito said, and none of the officers staying in the house
thought to look in it until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tucked underneath a counter, like a work bench,''
Esposito said. ``You had to walk around the BMW parked on the far
side of the garage to get to it. You couldn't open the lid without
pulling it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Riviera Beach police identified the body Tuesday as Piro, who
along with her husband, Christopher, had been missing since the
evening of Nov. 11 when they failed to show up for a dinner date
with friends. Neighbors, worried over the Benedettos'
disappearance, called the family in New York on Sunday, Nov. 15,
and the brothers and Esposito arrived Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is a suspect, including Mr. Benedetto,'' Riviera
Beach police Detective Pat Galligan said. ``Family, friends,
associates; we're exploring every avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they identified the body through photographs of
Piro. The Palm Beach County Medical Examiner's Office will use
super-glue to lift any fingerprints from the body and an autopsy is
scheduled early next week, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County sheriff's crime scene technicians tested the
couple's home, two cars and boat Tuesday night with a chemical
called Luminol. The liquid, which must be applied in total
darkness, will glow to reveal any traces of blood.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, at least eight people, including neighbors
who had spare keys and family members, had walked through the
house, Riviera Beach police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we walked through the house Friday, there was no evidence
of a crime,'' police Major David Harris said. ``If we had any
inkling, we would have kicked everyone out.''
</P>
<P>
   Esposito said several fellow New York City officers flew down to
help search for the couple and also had inspected the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had briefly thought about the house,'' Esposito said, ``but
you have to understand that by the time we got in there, the
neighbors had been all through it. It had been like Grand Central
Station in there. The crime scene was already contaminated by the
time we walked through the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Esposito said he and the Benedetto brothers ``examined
the house in small sections,'' looking for blood or signs of a
struggle. They checked the carpet for discoloration but could find
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   They moved their focus outside the home, handing out flyers
throughout the neighborhood and searching hotels on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to stay in the background and not interfere with the
Riviera Beach police investigation,'' Esposito said. ``We didn't
want to give the wrong impression and make the detectives here
think we were taking over the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Medical Examiner Dr. Jacqueline Martin said the fact that
Piro's body was frozen could make it easier to determine the cause
of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial characteristics are intact for evaluation,''
Martin said. ``The freezing period will stabilize the body in its
same state.''
</P>
<P>
   But this will also make it difficult for examiners to calculate
when Piro died.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell the time of death when (the body) is frozen,''
Martin said. ``Once the body starts to thaw, the decomposition will
start to take place . . . I don't think we will be able to
establish an exact time of death.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there are several other factors which will help them
establish a reasonable time of death, Martin said. The condition of
the body and whether it was partially decomposed before freezing
are factors they will consider.
</P>
<P>
   Esposito, 50, spent 25 years with the NYPD before taking a job
with the Titusville department three years ago. He said he has
worked hundreds of homicide cases, but none has come so close to
him.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-figure settlement Benedetto received three years ago for
back injuries from a construction accident may be at the root of
his cousin's disappearance, Esposito believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut tells me this probably had something to do with
money,'' he said. ``You can make a whole lot of guesses, but I
think someone went after Chris and Janette for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett and Alexandra Navarro Clifton writes for the Palm
Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla. Lillian Weis contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
