<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED-ZONE SCORING RATE TOPS NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No NFL team has been more successful in the red zone this season
than the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   They lead the league in scoring touchdowns inside the opponents'
20-yard line with 25 in 38 possessions, a success rate of 65.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get down there more often to exploit our ability to
get in the end zone,'' Coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin attributes the success to excellent play-calling by the
offensive coaches and the continued improvement of second-year
quarterback Jake Plummer, who led the team to six touchdowns in
Sunday's 45-42 victory over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   All six of the scores came after the team was in the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake has the ability to make (big) plays, and we haven't
forced the ball in there much, which is extremely critical,'' Tobin
said. &QL;  &QL; 
Road warriors
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' three road victories this season put them one
away from their most in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   They have two chances to get a fourth road win, beginning Sunday
at Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who also play at Philadelphia on Dec. 13, are 3-3
on the road for only the second time since moving to Arizona in
1988, the last time coming in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three seasons, the Cardinals have gone 1-7, 2-6 and
1-7 on the road, a combined 4-20. But they've beaten St. Louis,
Detroit and Washington on the road this season.
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL;  &QL; 
The Cardinals have signed former Georgia guard Antonio Fleming, a
seventh-round draft pick of Dallas, to their practice squad.
Fleming had been on Carolina's practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals continue to lead the NFL in takeaways with 29, one
more than Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Frank Sanders is tied with Cris Carter of
Minnesota for the NFL lead in third-down receptions with 23.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Simeon Rice's two sacks against the Redskins gave
him a team-high nine, tying him for 11th in the league. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
