<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARIZONAS-TATE-LANG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING AN INVISIBLE OPPONENT  
 ARTHRITIS HOBBLES SUN DEVILS' LANG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes when Rechelle Lang calls to New Zealand, it's easier
to talk about something else.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of topics: her parents' move from TeKuiti
to Auckland and the sale of the business they owned for 16 years;
her brother Brent, married two years ago when she last visited
home, already with a 7-month-old child and another baby on the way;
the Arizona State women's basketball upcoming tour of Australia in
May, after which Lang will go one direction and the Sun Devils
another.
</P>
<P>
   Any of those subjects is preferable to another lecture about
inflammatory arthritis and the unfairness of it striking a
24-year-old and ruining her brief Division I basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get upset knowing the things I'm going through,'' said
Lang, referring to her parents, John and Lynne. ``I want to share
the good times and what's happening back home. I don't know if they
know the extent of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``extent'' of it includes:
</P>
<P>
   A mysterious eruption of her left knee that caused it to grow to
3-4 times its normal size during a three-hour plane flight to
Eugene, Ore., in January, which transformed their daughter from
starting point guard to DNP (did not play) for 12 consecutive
games, including ASU's opener Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A long, confusing ordeal to correctly diagnose the problem, let
alone treat it.
</P>
<P>
   An occasional easing of the pain, only to always return when she
optimistically practices just a little harder.
</P>
<P>
   And a growing admiration from her coaches and teammates for how
Georgie, as Lang is known, is coping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to watch her be miserable, but she doesn't show
it to the team very much at all,'' said ASU Coach Charli Turner
Thorne. ``Knowing how good she is and what she could be doing, but
having to watch every day in practice. And knowing how much she
could help us, but not being able to play a game she loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can imagine how difficult it's been for her. But she's not
standing around pouting.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead Lang quietly goes about her business during practice.
Riding a stationary bike, shooting and participating in some
half-court drills. Dreaming of when the three or four medications
she ingests and lubricating injections in her knee will allow her
to train full court and eventually play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of it is learning about my body and what I can and
can't do, when I have to cut back,'' Lang said. ``If I play for
even five minutes, I'd call that a start.''
</P>
<P>
   A transfer from Casper (Wyo.) College, Lang started the first 14
games last season and was averaging 22.4 minutes. She had eight
assists in ASU's upset of then-seventh-ranked Washington on Jan. 8
and six assists and nine points two days later in a 20-point win
over Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   But during practice the week before the Oregon trip, Lang took a
hard hit on the shin that developed into a large bruise, then the
swollen knee.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne now wonders about the 32 minutes Lang played that
weekend. ``She was almost like a pylon,'' due to her immobility
against Oregon. ``We just didn't know what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   And they wouldn't for months.
</P>
<P>
   The knee was drained and tested for infection. There was a
magnetic resonance imaging test and arthroscopic examination for
structural damage. Not until April was Lang able to describe the
pain in other joints that provided the answer. She was referred to
a specialist, Dr. Paul Howard, who immediately recognized the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start, it was pretty overwhelming,'' Lang said.
``Having such limitations, and no one knew what it was and what I
should do. Now it's a different frustration of dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard told Lang that he is pleased with how she is responding
to aggressive treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that the clock is ticking on her athletic career
because she already has gone to the NCAA once to successfully
petition for eligibility this season because of a question over
trade school classes taken in New Zealand before she started at
Casper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the way she's kept at it,'' said Natalie Tucker,
Lang's roommate who unintentionally is benefiting from her absence
as the new starting point guard. ``A lot of people would have said
they're not going to be able to come back and given up their senior
year. But she keeps in shape, just in case. She puts in more
shooting practice than anyone else on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone would be so happy for her,'' if she plays again.
``But we don't want her to do anything to make her hurt herself
more.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Lang has company in street clothes. Ebony Edwards and
Theresa Jantzen have knee injuries, and Kisha White is academically
ineligible until the second semester. But by the first of the year,
when the Pac-10 schedule starts, she could be the lone inactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is doing everything she possibly can to help herself and
help the team,'' Turner Thorne said.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, betrayed by Lang's sad eyes, is that might not be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to handle it in an affirmative way, sometimes to the
point of ignoring it,'' Lang said. ``It feels just like an injury
rather than arthritis. Instead of debating why, I just treat it.
You show your character by how you deal with it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
