<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA PONDERS EXPANSION OF PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how well both teams play, the Mercury and two-time
champion Houston Comets probably won't meet in a rematch for the
1999 WNBA title.
</P>
<P>
   That's because an expanded playoff format proposed at league
meetings last week keeps teams playing within their conference
until the championship series.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs would grow from four to six teams as the WNBA adds
expansion teams in Orlando and Minnesota and increases to 12 teams
and 32 regular season games for its third season.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a tight playoff time frame, the new round would
consist of a single game between the second- and third-place
finisher in each conference. Those winners would advance to
best-of-three semifinals against the conference champions, who get
a first-round bye. The West and East champions then would play in a
best-of-three final round.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of three plans to be discussed by the WNBA
competition committee, which will make a recommendation to the
operating committee. The other options are to continue the current
format or to expand to four playoff teams per conference.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and '98, the conference champions earned the right to
host a playoff semifinal, with two other teams qualifying based on
best record, regardless of conference. Semifinals and finals were
one game in '97 but were increased to best-of-three in '98.
</P>
<P>
   If the six-team proposal is adopted for 1999, the Mercury would
have to get past the two-time defending champion Comets before
reaching the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy if they decide to go East-West because they know
which conference is the stronger,'' Mercury Coach/General Manager
Cheryl Miller said. ``Wait until the balance is a little even.
You've potentially got four or five teams killing each other in the
West to get out of it to get to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with it, but it's not like I have a choice. I'm
not looking forward to that format. I guess we just have to make
sure we have the best record (in the West).''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury was closer to missing the playoffs last season than
to surpassing the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Houston ran away with the West at 27-3, eight games ahead of
Phoenix (19-11), which for the second straight year had to win its
regular season finale to clinch a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   If the six-team playoff format had been in effect last season,
the Mercury would have faced the Los Angeles Sparks (12-18) in a
one-game playoff for the right to meet the Comets in the West
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the New York Liberty (18-12) would have played the
Charlotte Sting (18-12), with the winner meeting the Cleveland
Rockers (20-10).
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota goes into the West for 1999 along with Houston,
Phoenix, Los Angeles, Sacramento (8-22) and Utah (8-22). Orlando
joins the East along with Cleveland, Charlotte, New York, Detroit
(17-13) and Washington (3-27). Of the four expansion teams added
since 1997, three are in the East, with Houston having been shifted
to the West. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
