<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-24 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CUCUMBER CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Bill Clinton has been an exhausting president. He
requires too much work and stirs up too much sturm und drang. After
Clinton leaves, everyone will surely be in the mood for a little
peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   In the election, Americans sent vengeful Republicans and
evangelical scolds the message that they do not want intrusive,
hectoring politicians who are always demanding that they get
outraged over something. Baby boomers don't want to spend a lot of
time on moral umbrage. They want to spend a lot of time checking
their stocks and reserving tee times at golf retirement resorts.
</P>
<P>
   So, perhaps, after this tumultuous period of overstimulation,
the time is right to go bland. Maybe the White House needs a
politician with a restful personality. Or better still, no
personality at all. A low-maintenance leader. The sort of guy you
could just elect and then forget about. The sort of guy who would
just fade into the West Wing woodwork. The sort of guy who has, in
fact, been compared to a wood chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, are you running for president?'' I ask George Elmer
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do my best to make this a better state,'' replies
the governor, sitting in his office, occasionally rolling a
basketball around with his foot. ``We had a meeting just before you
came here with our budget director ...''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has a unique quality for a successful politician: You can
actually forget, for long periods, that he's in the room with you.
Even his wife, Libby, has described him as ``the softer shades of
gray.''
</P>
<P>
   He is swishing around a Diet Coke bottle, trying to make the
bubbles go away. ``I like soda flat,'' he sighs. ``I know. It is
the perfect metaphor.''
</P>
<P>
   He apologizes for his socks. ``I hate short socks but I figured
today nobody was going to be around,'' he said. ``I want to cross
my legs but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup. He's perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Michael Dukakis said his idea of a great evening
was laying black mulch on the tomatoes in his back yard? Well, the
New York governor has written a biography that offers a loving
homage to his family farm in Peekskill, with its ``spectacular
cucumbers.'' The Pataki family motto, printed at the beginning of
the book, is: ``Pray for a good harvest, but keep hoeing.''
</P>
<P>
   So, I ask him, what about a Bush-Pataki ticket? ``I know Bush,''
the governor replies. ``He was a year behind me in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he know anything about that alleged wild side of George W.?
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head. ``At Yale, they have 12 colleges. His and
mine were next to each other and we were rivals, Pierson and
Davenport. He was at Davenport. I was at Pierson. I actually met
him a few times. ... He was a very competitive guy. He wasn't
involved at all in college politics. He was more involved in either
sports or playing poker. He's a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Could this genial, sleepy-eyed governor, who has been called
lazy by his political rivals, handle the grinding hours of a
national campaign?
</P>
<P>
   He says he wouldn't mind long hours if they were ``productive''
hours. ``I'll just give you an example: Saturday we had a bus with
my old friends, going up to the Harvard-Yale football game. We
spent the entire morning talking about America in the 21st century.
It was tremendous fun and it was stimulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup. He's the one.
</P>
<P>
   He could very well ride that blandness into the White House. His
rival in New York City, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has been making
trips to Iowa and getting flummoxed by questions about hog policy,
may not suit the public mood. The revulsion with Kenneth Starr may
cause voters to turn away from any more self-righteous, puritanical
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's softer focus could be a tonic after the nasty intensity
of the impeachment crusade. The governor faults Newt Gingrich and
other GOP leaders for the disastrous election results. ``The idiot
Republican Party was running commercials nationalizing what is an
inside Washington problem,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is proposing that what Washington needs is a nicer
atmosphere and less partisan sniping. ``I'm not naive,'' he says.
``But to the extent you can minimize that through the personal
relationships and through the pursuit of an agenda that advances
not a political interest but a common interest, then everyone is
better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup. He's ideal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
