<HEADLINE>
TO HAVE OR HAVE NOT HEMINGWAY NOVEL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although editor &UR; David Remnick  &LR; had high praise in Berkeley on
Monday night for  &UR; Joan Didion &LR; 's recent New Yorker essay
criticizing the publication of an unfinished  &UR; Ernest Hemingway &LR; 
novel, it turns out that he is disregarding Didion's main point.
New York magazine reports that the New Yorker has bought rights to
publish a portion of the novel, despite Didion's view that
Hemingway, who committed suicide, was less than satisfied by the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner's decision to publish ``True at First Light''
represents a ``systematic creation of a marketable product,'' she
wrote, ``... tending to obscure the body of work published by
Hemingway in his lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick told New York that Didion's essay ``made a brilliant
case for not publishing incomplete work of any kind. ... And yet,
there's a case to be made that without publishing such work, we
would never have had Kafka's `The Trial' and `The Castle' or
Virgil's `Aeneid.' We'll publish an excerpt of the Hemingway
manuscript in the spring,'' said Remnick, ``and let the reader
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOLIDAY GIFT ITEM THAT GOT AWAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the auction was at Sotheby's in Sussex, England, on
September 22.  &UR; Angela Weber &LR;  is wistful that she missed the chance
to bid on two pair of carved stone putti (cupid-like babies) ``in
the style of  &UR; Jan Pierre van Bauerscheit &LR; ,'' an early 18th century
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog includes a picture of one of the works, ``two putti,
one astride a pig, the other administering an enema to the
reluctant swine!'' It could have been yours for a figure in the low
$20,000s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ABC offered  &UR; Alec Baldwin &LR; , working actor and wannabe
politician, a spot as co-host of ``Good Morning America,'' says the
New York Daily News, but the actor turned it down. And  &UR; Linda &LR; 
 &UR; Tripp &LR;  is going to be on &UR; Larry King &LR; 's show soon after
Thanksgiving, because it is said that she trusts him.
</P>
<P>
   _ First the Latina singer  &UR; Shakira  &LR; was pictured on the cover of
her latest album with dirty hands and her hair braided with strips
of fabric. Then  &UR; Alanis Morissette  &LR; was pictured on the cover of
Rolling Stone with dirty feet and the same hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   Shakira's handlers are calling Morissette a copycat, says the
New York Post. ``Shakira did the hair first,'' one of Shakira's
representatives said, ``she did the dirty body part first.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Who says feminism is dead? The monologue that's been drawing
cheers and applause at showings of the new movie ``Elizabeth'': ``I
am no man's Elizabeth! If you think to rule, you are mistaken. I
will have one mistress here _ and no master!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Retired Wyoming Senator &UR; Alan Simpson &LR; , who was a prominent
Republican, told Roll Call that he wasn't unhappy that the
Republicans fared poorly in the recent elections. ``I liked it. I
didn't look on it as a horror story in any way. I look upon it as a
very good thing that people voted for thoughtful people. They
didn't want to vote for people who frightened them or people who
looked like zealots.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Novelist  &UR; Sugar Rautbord &LR; 's response an Elle Decor question,
``What's the most fabulous decorative gift you've received?'' was
simple: a Picasso. ``It's so decorative.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Web site www.treasuresfromrussia.com is selling All the
President's Dolls, a set of five nesting matrushka cq  &LR; dolls
decorated with friends of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; : The president is on the
outside;  &UR; Monica Lewinsky  &LR; next; &UR; Paula Jones &LR;  next;  &UR; Gennifer &LR; 
 &UR; Flowers  &LR; next; and  &UR; Kathleen Willey &LR; , the tiniest. Maxim magazine
says that demand is so high for the dolls, which come in two sizes
and cost $26 and $35, that pensioners and laid-off factory workers
have been recruited to fulfill one factory's orders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Susan McDougal  &LR; was acquitted of embezzling $50,000 from
 &UR; Zubin  &LR; and  &UR; Nancy Mehta &LR; , but the Los Angeles trial revealed some
startling details of the Mehtas' lifestyle. According to a report
in the Times of London, Nancy Mehta flew her plumber, his wife and
an assistant first class from Los Angeles to Florence to fix a
broken garden sprinkler in their rented villa.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal revealed that Mrs. Mehta had McDougal sign credit-card
slips for her during shopping sprees, because she was too vain to
put on her glasses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; ``When your arms are bigger than your head, something is
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Reeves, former movie Hercules, on the beach scene in
Venice, Calif. Reeves was quoted in the November issue of
Smithsonian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
