<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS EYES IRISH GAME WITH USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's in UCLA's best interest for USC to beat Notre
Dame in football on Saturday, but one Bruin will be rooting for the
Fighting Irish. Baron Davis is a Notre Dame fan.
</P>
<P>
   No, check that. He's a Notre Dame nut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching Notre Dame football since I was 5,'' said
Davis, an L.A. native. ``And even without (injured quarterback)
Jarius Jackson, they're going to smack SC.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has Notre Dame media guides and reads the school's
football newsletter. During his Pop Warner days, Davis wore No. 9 _
after ex-Notre Dame quarterback Tony Rice _ and dreamed of playing
safety for the Irish. Then he enrolled at Crossroads School in
Santa Monica, which doesn't have football, and turned his attention
to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   His Irish allegiance is so strong, he even liked Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Holtz,'' he said. ``I loved every single person to
play for Notre Dame, except one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Powlus.
</P>
<P>
   __ In doubt: Davis will travel with UCLA this week to the Puerto
Rico Shootout, which begins Thursday against San Francisco, but he
is not expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was cleared for full-contact practice last week, but he
has not received permission to play competitively on his surgically
repaired left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no official word,'' coach Steve Lavin said.
``We're still working on the assumption that he won't play in
Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he does not have full strength or range of motion,
Davis is moving well in practice and slowly regaining his timing
and conditioning. Patience is another problem. He wants to play,
and he wants to play now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I've got to do,'' he said. ``It's extremely
hard (to stay patient) when you know you're ready, and when you've
proved it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ One Bailey to another: Sophomore guard Ryan Bailey, Toby's
brother, scored nine points in 17 minutes against Santa Clara and
is the backup point guard _ at least until Davis returns.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey was the starting point guard for Penn State as a freshman
in 1996-97, then transferred to UCLA as a nonscholarship player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played better in games than practice,'' Lavin said,
smiling. ``The Baileys are all gamers. It's a gene.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Game change? The Bruins might change the 7:30 p.m. tipoff
time of their Jan. 4 game against Arizona State if the football
team is in the Fiesta Bowl that evening. The Fiesta Bowl starts at
5:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA wanted to move the game to Jan. 5, a Tuesday, but ASU
declined.
</P>
<P>
   __ The schedule: UCLA arrived in San Juan on Tuesday night and
will practice this afternoon. Tipoff against San Francisco is 3:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If the No. 10 Bruins win, they'll play either No. 5 Maryland or
the host school, American University-Puerto Rico, on Friday at
10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky looms in the other bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin has not chosen a starting lineup and probably won't until
tonight or Thursday morning. But expect him to rotate 12 players _
in part to evaluate personnel, in part to keep the Bruins fresh for
three games in three days.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to whittle the rotation to eight or nine by late
December, just in time for conference play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 14 guys and I feel comfortable putting any of them
in the game,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
