<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS MEET WITH WILLIAMS; ORIOLES SHOW SUDDEN INTEREST IN BELLE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernie Williams met with Yankees officials in Tampa, Fla.,
Tuesday night, wielding a substantial seven-year offer from the
Boston Red Sox and apparently giving the Yankees one last chance to
match the Boston bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had the opportunity to increase their five-year, $60
million pitch to Williams, a member of their organization since
1985. But Boston's offer apparently dwarfs that of the Yankees.
Some within the Red Sox organization are saying the team has
offered a seven-year deal worth perhaps $13 million a season, and
the Red Sox are also believed to be working on a way to add an
eighth-year option to the contract. The largest contact in basebal
history currently belongs to Mike Piazza, who signed a seven-year
$91 million deal with the Mets in October.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Yankees owner George Steinbrenner met with Williams
Tuesday, his team was actively negotiating with Albert Belle,
although the Yankees must now contend with the Baltimore Orioles'
sudden interest in the controversial slugger. In addition, the
Orioles are aggressively pursuing free-agent pitcher Kevin Brown,
who pitched for Baltimore in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' agent, Scott Boras, had told Yankees officials all
along that they would get one last chance to sign the center
fielder, and with Williams deep into negotiations with the Red Sox
and the Yankees ready to strike a deal with Belle if Baltimore
doesn't interfere, Tuesday's meeting in Tampa, Fla. represented
that final opportunity. Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general
manager, who also participated in the meeting, would not confirm
the gathering occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner and Williams had years of shared history to discuss
_ the eight seasons Williams played in Yankee Stadium, his two Gold
Gloves, the batting title he won this summer, and the two World
Series championships the Yankees won with Williams in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a complete reversal by Steinbrenner, however, it
appeared the gap in negotiations is untenable. While the Yankees
have held fast to their offer, Boston's proposed deal with Williams
would far surpass any other offer disclosed publicly. Boras had
maintained to executives with other teams that he already had
multiple offers for Williams for as many as seven and eight years,
and the Red Sox apparently are heeding his assertions with an offer
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who met with Boston officials Sunday and Monday and
was said to have an instant liking for the Red Sox Manager Jimy
Williams, would change the dynamics of an organization that has
relied on slow-footed power hitters for much of its frustrating
history. If Bernie Williams signs with Boston and, in effect,
replaces the slothful slugger Mo Vaughn, the strength of the team
would shift toward speed and defense, and its offense would be at
least partially built on singles and doubles, rather than the
long-time devotion to home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Williams would also assume extraordinary pressure as the more
expensive substitute for the immensely popular Vaughn, to whom the
Red Sox offered a five-year, $63 million contract, which Vaughn
rejected. Vaughn is now expected to sign for more money with the
Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees officials, long convinced that Williams will sign
elsewhere, are believed to have made a four-year offer to Belle for
between $48 million and $50 million, and Cashman, negotiated with
Belle's agent for much of Tuesday. Belle's asking price could climb
as high as $60 million. A deal could be completed as soon as
Wednesday, although the emergence of the Orioles in the chase for
Belle could delay resolution until after the holiday weekend. Arn
Tellem, Belle's agent, would not say whether Baltimore had entered
the bidding. He did say this: ``There have been some interesting
developments, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, coming off a hugely disappointing 1998 season, have
lost the second baseman Roberto Alomar (who agreed to a four-year,
$32 million contract with Cleveland) and negotiations with the
first baseman Rafael Palmeiro _ offered four years and $32 million
_ seem to have bogged down. B.J. Surhoff, another free agent, is
being courted by the Mets and Pittsburgh, and Eric Davis has signed
with St. Louis. The Orioles bid $40 million for Brian Jordan, but
lost out to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Given those repeated failures and perhaps fearful of what
appears to be a poor offensive team in 1999, Baltimore is exploring
the option of signing Belle; according to a major-league executive,
an offer likely was forthcoming, perhaps as soon as Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles have not been as tenuous in their approach to Brown:
They have informed the pitcher's agent they are willing to give him
a five-year deal, knowing full well that Brown wants at least $12
million annually and a six-year contract. Signing Brown would give
Baltimore perhaps the strongest pitching rotation in the American
League, with Mike Mussina, Scott Erickson, Juan Guzman and the
youngster Sidney Ponson also included. Their catcher could be Todd
Hundley, because the Mets have proposed a trade in which they would
get Orioles reliever Armando Benitez in return. But the Orioles are
wary of the possibility that Hundley's surgically repaired right
elbow will prevent him from being an everyday player behind the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams signs with the Red Sox or the Arizona Diamondbacks
(the other team with a stated interest in the center fielder) and
Belle somehow lands with the Orioles, the Yankees suddenly would be
without a slugger for the middle of their lineup. Cashman said
Tuesday that his priority for the off-season is ``to get something
done with the final piece to our puzzle _ a position player.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing a free agent, he said, would be the ``more realistic''
way to get that done. Without Belle or Williams, the Yankees could
pursue Vaughn, a first baseman who would not fit naturally into
their lineup. Or the Yankees could attempt to trade prospects for
Montreal's Rondell White or Anaheim's Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are not among those teams in the running for the
pitcher Randy Johnson. The Houston Astros, who traded for Johnson
late in the 1998 season and were rewarded when he drove them to the
playoffs, pulled out of the bidding for the left-handed pitcher
Tuesday. The Anaheim Angels, Texas Rangers and Diamondbacks appear
to the front-runners for Johnson, the four-year bids of both teams
approaching $13 million annually. The San Diego Padres seem to have
dropped out of the running for Brown, while St. Louis and Colorado
remain among the clubs still hoping to land the hard-throwing
right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
