<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 25
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Nov. 23,
about Boris N. Yeltsin's health problems attributed a statement to
Mr. Yeltsin wrongly in some copies. While his meeting at a hospital
with President Jiang Zemin of China was a signal that he did not
intend to allow his frailty to further loosen his grip on the
Russian Presidency, Mr. Yeltsin did not explicitly say that.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Nov. 16,
about a dispute over a new book by Dr. Bob Arnot, ``The Breast
Cancer Prevention Diet,'' omitted a description of the finances of
the American Council on Science and Health, an organization
critical of the book. The council, a nonprofit group, receives 40
percent of its financing from corporations, including food
manufacturers. The rest of its support comes from private
foundations, individual contributions and sales.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PAINEWEBBER-AD-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Thursday, Nov. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Nov. 19,
about a revival of the ``Thank you, Paine Webber'' campaign, by the
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi agency, referred imprecisely to the campaign's
origins. The original version, in 1975, was created by Marshall
Karp and Andrew Langer, not by Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AFRICA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Thursday, Nov. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Nov. 19,
about ``The Shadow of Kilimanjaro'' by Rick Ridgeway misstated an
estimate of how long it would take to walk from the top of Mount
Kilimanjaro in Tanzania to the Indian Ocean. Mr. Ridgeway wrote
that he was told it would take ``a little over three weeks' time,''
not three days.
</P>
</TEXT>
