<P>
   These inventors did not start off trying to discover entirely
new products or technologies. Rather, they and most other investors
came up with their creations after they encountered a situation or
assignment that prodded them to think of doing something
differently. By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW  &LR; _ Question: I am at the preliminary stage of starting a
business. 1) Do I need to get a fictitious business name? 2) Do I
need to trademark or register the name through the federal
government? Columnist Peter Sinton has the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 What's in A Name? Plenty  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I am at the preliminary stage of starting a business. 1)
Do I need to get a fictitious business name? 2) Do I need to
trademark or register the name through the federal government?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  If you plan to do business under your own name, you do
not need to apply for a fictitious business name. But if it is
under an assumed name, you should file a DBA (doing business as)
statement in the county where you plan to incorporate. Contact your
county clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what you call your business, if you plan to form a
corporation, you will need to register with the secretary of
state's office in the state in which you plan to incorporate.
</P>
<P>
   But neither applying for a fictitious name nor filing for
incorporation is the same as clearing the name for use as a
trademark. To do that, San Francisco trademark attorney Michelle
Kahn suggests getting a trademark attorney to conduct a legal
availability search.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring what does and does not constitute trademark
infringement often requires expert analysis. Even if no one is
using the name you want to use, that doesn't mean you have rights
to it. For example, say you want to use the name McBagel for a
fast-food bagel outfit. If you do, be prepared to get creamed by
McDonald's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing your business name can get costly. Paul Frohlich, a
mutual fund portfolio manager turned chef turned entrepreneur, came
up with the name Yum for his gourmet-food retailing concept. He
paid $35 to file for the fictitious name at the San Francisco
clerk's office, after first paying a $75 business tax registration
fee. He also paid $20 for a name search with the secretary of
state's office, a $100 filing fee to incorporate under the name Yum
and another $600 for the annual franchise fee.
</P>
<P>
   Costs did not end there. Frohlich, 39, wanted to make sure
someone else hadn't already made use of Yum as a trade name or
trademark on the same or similar goods.
</P>
<P>
   An informal screen search on the Internet turned up nothing, but
he consulted an attorney who cleared the name and is in the process
of &UR;  &LR; obtaining registration with the U.S. Patent and Trademark
Office. It costs $250 to file for each industry classification, and
in Frohlich's case, he could have filed for as many 13. Then there
are lawyer fees, which easily can top $5,000. But that's cheaper
than most legal battles if someone challenges your name and
business later.
</P>
<P>
   Books and online guides to starting a business offer much more
information on protecting your intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Partner Problems
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Question: What are the top management problems faced by
principals in a partnership?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &LR; Answer: Resolving disputes without ending up dissolving the
business is the main problem partnerships have, according to
Richard Harroch, an attorney at Orrick, Herrington &AMP; Sutcliffe and
author of the new book ``Small Business Kit for Dummies'' (IDG
Books, $24.99).
</P>
<P>
   In a corporation, key decisions typically are decided by
majority vote of the directors. Partnerships need to spell out what
decisions require unanimous approval of all partners, or two-thirds
or majority approval, and what decisions can be made by the
president or individual partners.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues include:
</P>
<P>
   _How much will each partner invest? This includes initial
investment, additional contributions if needed and investment caps.
</P>
<P>
   _What services and time commitment are expected of each partner?
</P>
<P>
   _How will profits be divided?
</P>
<P>
   _Can partners work on their own outside the partnership, either
in competition with the company or in unrelated fields?
</P>
<P>
   _What happens if a partner wants to leave the partnership, dies
or is disabled? Is there a buy-out formula so that the business can
continue?
</P>
<P>
   Betting on Brunch
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Question: I am interested in finding out how to go about
opening my own breakfast/lunch cafe. I currently am a chef but
don't know where to go to get the information I need about costs,
budgeting, finding locations, etc.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Answer: You might start your quest at your local chamber of
commerce. Also contact the Service Corps of Retired Executives for
more personal attention. Its office in San Francisco is 455 Market
Street, sixth floor. Volunteer Barry Livingston says SCORE has
plans, including detailed cost analysis, for about 150 types of
businesses from antiques and carpet cleaning to sandwich shops and
taverns. Would-be entrepreneurs can study these businesses on
computers at SCORE and also talk with volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants are one of the riskiest businesses. The failure rate
is daunting, and there is plenty of competition, especially in the
Bay Area. But consumers' appetite for new culinary experiences also
remains high. Experts suggest doing a lot of homework and market
research to help ensure that your concept is not half-baked.
</P>
<P>
   It can be very expensive setting up a restaurant. Livingston,
whose family once ran a local department store of the same name,
suggests that a good real estate broker can help find the right
location at the right price. In addition to base rent, it is
important to negotiate who pays for what share of taxes, insurance
and improvements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
