<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGN-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Reinventing the Wheel  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Berkeley architect Charles Debbas came up with the idea for his
finger-fitting Ergo pen after his hand cramped up sketching for
hours on end.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Stanford grad Chris Flink designed a better shopping
basket as part of a class assignment, and it could soon make him a
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Chico optician Bruce Holden created his own wraparound,
bullet-proof sunglasses after fighting wind and glare during a ski
outing and is now trying to get military and police units to buy
them.
</P>
<P>
   These inventors did not start off trying to discover entirely
new products or technologies. Rather, they and most other investors
came up with their creations after they encountered a situation or
assignment that prodded them to think of doing something
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California is a world capital of innovation as
demonstrated by the number of information technology and health
science companies based here and the fact that one-third of all
U.S. venture capital investments flow to local startups.
</P>
<P>
   But non-high-tech innovations also are getting to market. And
they don't necessarily require a Ph.D. or terribly deep pockets.
They just needed imagination, patience and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   The Swatch of Pens?
</P>
<P>
   After drafting for six hours a day with a conventional pencil,
architect Charles Debbas decided to design a more ergonomic writing
instrument three years ago. He molded Play-Doh into different
shapes before baking it in the oven. In less than two months,
Debbas arrived at a design, a bit like a chile pepper, which felt
right in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Ergo ballpoint pen comes in right-hand and left-hand
versions, in leather-clad aluminum for $85 retail or bright plastic
for $16 to $20. The pen can be found at various outlets, including
Nordstrom, the Nature Co. and San Francisco Museum. The biggest
customer, Disney, sells a version with a cap shaped like Mickey
Mouse's head.
</P>
<P>
   Debbas avoided the mistakes of many entrepreneurs by testing the
market for his product before rushing it into production.
</P>
<P>
   He had prototypes of his pen produced by Plynetics in San
Leandro and did the drawings and engineering work himself, as he
did for his patent applications. By the time he took a booth at the
New York Stationery show in May 1997 to gauge public reaction,
Debbas figures he had invested about $30,000 of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the response was ``phenomenal,'' he said. ``People
lined up for four-and-a-half days.''
</P>
<P>
   He raised another $130,000 from family and friends to produce
molds and get into production.
</P>
<P>
   But launching Ergo has not been without problems. The first
manufacturer in Grass Valley (Nevada County) could only produce
about 300 plastic pens a week, and there were glitches like blotchy
color and rubber thumb grips that peeled off. Debbas changed
contract manufacturers, but not before production was halted for
four months early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he plans to produce as many as 15,000 pens this
year in Colorado and California. Orders are flowing in from as far
as Italy and Japan, and Debbas plans to add new tropical colors and
versions for people with larger hands next year. Eventually he
hopes to become ``the Swatch of pens.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, about $600,000 has been invested in the business,
including some reinvested revenues. Debbas figures he needs to
raise about double that amount with the hope of breaking even in
about 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to other innovators: ``Follow your gut feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Basket
</P>
<P>
   Chris Flink, 26, came up with his ergonomic shopping basket four
years ago as a senior at Stanford. His assignment for mechanical
Engineering 116c was to find a need and then develop a product to
fill it.
</P>
<P>
   After searching for a few weeks, he settled on the handheld
shopping basket _ a product used by millions of people that hadn't
evolved very much. ``It was basically a crate with wire handles
that fold out of the way,'' Flink observed.
</P>
<P>
   After studying shops and shoppers, interviewing friends and
strangers, and researching patents and basket manufacturers, Flink
figured he could come up with a better design. What he designed for
class was a prototype that replaced the two thin metal handles that
can pinch fingers and dig into the hand with a plastic handle
rising from the center of the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the handle was like one you would find on a
briefcase. The shape of the basket was slightly curved and could be
held more easily against the body. In addition, it could still be
stacked like conventional baskets.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Flink worked in New York for a design
consultant for a year but then returned to his basket concept. To
reduce the ``financial peril'' of launching a product, he did the
drawings and filed for a provisional patent himself. Then Flink met
with purchasing agents for such potential customers as Safeway,
Thrifty Payless and Orchard Supply.
</P>
<P>
   With ``letters of interest'' from some of the main buyers of
shopping baskets, Flink went to Russell &AMP; Miller, a major Southern
California supplier to the retail trade and licensed the company to
produce his design.
</P>
<P>
   The market for handheld shopping baskets in the United States is
about 7 million units a year, and Flink hopes to capture a big
chunk of it. His baskets, priced about the same as conventional
baskets at $5 each, are starting to show up at A&AMP;P, Ralph's,
Orchard Supply and Co-Op markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bulletproof Idea
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Holden, one of five brothers who all ended up opticians,
created Zurich International after a Tahoe ski outing in 1985. His
wraparound glasses keep out wind and dust as well as ultraviolet
and some infrared rays. Because they are made from the same
$50-per-pound Lexan polycarbonite used in jet windshields, the
glasses reportedly can stop a speeding bullet or flying shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   Holden, 57, makes a living selling about 20,000 pairs of the $50
to $60 glasses a year, primarily to ski and other outdoor
enthusiasts at fairs and by direct marketing. But sales of the
specs have not been spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people buy sunglasses because they are good-looking,''
said Bill Seidel, a Sebastopol marketing expert who is advising
Zurich on how to develop a broader market. Holden acknowledges that
the glasses ``are designed for protection and performance rather
than style and fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's glasses are going through required ballistics
testing to qualify for sales to military and police units. Zurich
also hopes to raise $1.2 million in a public offering and use some
of the proceeds to develop an infomercial. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Seidel, who also teaches entrepreneurship, innovation and direct
marketing at UC Berkeley Extension, notes that it can take a long
time to launch a new product. The average span from idea to product
introduction is about seven years.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of best-selling products take longer than that.
Television, which was invented in 1884, took 46 years of research
and development before reaching the market in 1930, and then
another 15 years to become popular.
</P>
<P>
   The original 1948 Pluto Platter took only two years to develop.
But it wasn't until 1964 when it was rechristened as the Frisbee
and aimed at an older, teenage market that the product took off.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Focus on Needs
</P>
<P>
   One of the main problems innovators have, according to Seidel,
``is not knowing what the market is looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Rosa consultant Lawrence MacDonald, who helps
entrepreneurs develop electronic commerce and other products,
agrees. ``People get fixated on products rather than satisfying
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasizes the importance of developing a market for your
product, especially since only one out of 100 or 1,000 ideas ever
becomes a moneymaker. MacDonald subscribes to management guru Peter
Drucker's maxim that a new idea has to offer 10 times as much value
or cost one-tenth as much as an existing product to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Some product ideas, which might save lives or prevent injuries,
are harder to measure.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Orinda anesthesiologist Nicholas Hyde came up with
a concept for a safer football helmet after he saw Denver Bronco
star Terrell Davis injure his neck after he was grabbed by the face
mask during last year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who practices medicine 60 percent of the time, is talking
with one of the major helmet manufacturers about testing his idea
for reducing cervical spine injuries and developing a prototype
helmet. To save development costs, he got an engineer to design the
accessory device in exchange for a 20 percent stake in the company
if the idea pays off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
