<SLUG> BC-NETCOM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Service Provider Netcom Is for Sale Again  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barely a year after it was sold to ICG Communications Inc., Netcom
is going on the block again.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Internet service provider, which sold for $225
million in a stock-swap in October of 1997, is for sale, according
to ICG officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``ICG bit off more than they could chew,'' said Laura Crowley, a
spokeswoman for Netcom.
</P>
<P>
   ICG of Englewood, Colo., said it wants to sell Netcom so it can
concentrate on its core business of providing local telephone
service and data communications to business customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to keep Netcom's Internet backbone _ one of
the main reasons ICG bought Netcom _ to route traffic, but does not
want to be involved in the dial-up Internet access business. ICG
officials said they plan to sell Netcom's operating assets within
the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will not affect existing Netcom customers, who will
continue to get dial-up Internet access, said Heatherecq &LR; 
Evans-Keenan, a spokeswoman for ICG.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really focusing on what our customer base is asking for
_ the core telecom voice and data products,'' Evans-Keenan said.
``We got what we wanted when we purchased them. It doesn't make
sense for us to offer some of Netcom's products as part of our
customer portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   When ICG bought Netcom, officials said the purchase would help
it compete against regional phone companies, such as Pacific Bell,
which offer both voice and data products.
</P>
<P>
   Evans-Keenan said retaining Netcom's backbone will allow ICG to
continue that goal. She added that the company spend the next 12
months deciding which parts of Netcom to sell and retain.
</P>
<P>
   For Netcom, the outcome of being sold is not as clear. Analysts
said they don't expect ICG to have a problem selling Netcom, but
said ICG may not get as good a price as it would like.
</P>
<P>
   With so many Internet access providers on the market, Netcom's
value may not be as high as it was last year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect they'll be bought by somebody, but I don't know what
the price will be,'' said Frank Governali, who follows ICG for
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He said the decision to sell Netcom is wise because it does not
fit in with ICG's main business line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's smart for (ICG) to get rid of it. They have so much to do
and so many things to concentrate on,'' Governali said. ``Were they
overly aggressive or optimistic with that purchase? Well, probably.
But a lot of other companies have done the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Netcom's Crowley said the company's 750 employees are not
concerned about the sale and don't expect any layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things here are business as usual,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
