<SLUG> BC-FRANKFURT-BALLET-2TAKES-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSCENDENTAL MEDITATIONS ON THE POSSIBILITIES OF FORM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 29) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Roslyn Sulcas has been writing about William Forsythe's work since
1990.  
 By ROSLYN SULCAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In Europe, the choreographer William
Forsythe is widely considered the most important dance maker on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   In his own country, the United States, his name is probably
known only to dancers and a limited number of balletgoers who have
seen his works in the repertories of the New York City Ballet, the
San Francisco Ballet or the Joffrey Ballet, or perhaps performed by
a touring company from across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The visit of Forsythe and the company he directs, the Frankfurt
Ballet, to the Brooklyn Academy of Music for six performances
starting Wednesday marks a decade since the troupe's last
appearances in the United States _ a surprising absence for a
company that has put its hometown on the dance map, held a 10-year
residence contract at the Chatelet Theater in Paris and is coveted
by programmers all over the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a surprising absence also for Forsythe. Born in 1949, he
grew up in New York City, made his first dances to rock-and-roll
and for school musicals, and took his first professional steps with
the Joffrey Ballet junior company.
</P>
<P>
   He left home in 1973, however, to join the Stuttgart Ballet
(becoming the last dancer hired by the renowned choreographer John
Cranko before Cranko's untimely death that year), and like many
others, John Neumeier and Jiri Kylian among them, made his first
serious works in the creative context of that company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, after a short period as a freelance choreographer
(during which time Rudolf Nureyev commissioned ``France/Dance'' for
the Paris Opera Ballet from him), Forsythe was invited to take over
the directorship of the Frankfurt Ballet, a competent provincial
troupe with a conventional ballet repertory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, Forsythe has transformed this company
into a unique instrument for his choreographic meditations on the
possibilities of the dancing body _ and in the process has formed
many dozens of exceptional artists. Forsythe has developed an
idiosyncratic, personal style of movement into a complex physical
language that encompasses, utilizes and often transcends classical
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a Forsythe work is to enter a thrilling theatrical
universe with its own laws and logic, in which movement, sound,
lighting and space draw the spectator into unexpected and
compelling realms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 34 ballets that Forsythe has made for his own
company are evening-length works that incorporate speech,
theatrical events, dazzling lighting effects, sets and costumes.
Others are pared-down events in which dancers in practice clothes
seem to be engaged in their own explorations of movement, or are
caught up in dreamlike states in bare, open spaces subtly colored
by blue shadows or blanched by white light. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite a long absence from the American stage, the slow
filtration of Forsythe ballets into the repertories of most major
ballet companies worldwide means that American dancers and
choreographers _ and thus audiences _ have probably been
unobtrusively influenced by his distinctive eye and style.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Frankfurt Ballet in the full-length ``Eidos:
Telos'' at BAM is nonetheless likely to astonish those for whom
Forsythe is synonymous with the extreme off-balance extensions of
his 1987 work ``In the Middle, Somewhat Elevated,'' or the
deceptively easy-on-the-eye allegro footwork and witty partnering
of ``Herman Schmerman,'' of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into three parts, the 1995 ``Eidos: Telos'' (loosely
translated as ``The Form: The End,'' or ``Genre: The End'') is one
of Forsythe's large-scale works that brings out his big creative
guns. Framing a dramatic narrative act with two pure-dance
sections, Forsythe fully demonstrates his gift for creating
theatrical effect, as well as the complex, contrapuntal movement
style that is a result of more than a decade of choreographic
exploration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He began to introduce improvisational techniques into the
creative process with the making of the ballet ``The Interrogation
of Robert Scott'' in 1987. ``Ballet is a body of knowledge, not an
ideology,'' says Forsythe, whose analytical approach and fondness
for citing philosophers and thinkers in program notes have won him
a reputation as an intellectual.
</P>
<P>
   His choreography, however, is animated by very concrete ideas.
``With `Robert Scott,' '' he says, ``we developed the idea of
`kinetic isometries,' which are ways of imagining the geometric
relationships between different parts of the body as they move.
Ballet is in our bodies, but we began to see that we could also
create our own language.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forsythian language now contains so many terms for
compositional techniques, or ``operations,'' that in 1994 Forsythe
created a CD-ROM as a learning tool for new dancers in the company,
a process that led to the creation of ``Self Meant to Govern,'' the
first part of ``Eidos: Telos.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an extraordinary compilation of slippery, intricately
connected, densely coordinated sequences for six dancers on a bare
white-lighted stage populated by ticking clocks, a metronome and a
violinist. (The music, with sources in Stravinsky's ``Apollo,'' is
by Thom Willems, a Dutch composer who has worked with Forsythe
since 1984.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using the ``135 little sequences,'' cued to them by letters on
the clocks, the dancers can apply various operations _
``iterations, reversing a movement, repeating it using another part
of the body, and so on,'' Forsythe explains _ within specific time
frames, and the resulting movement is like nothing one can imagine:
knees buckle, bottoms push up into the air, elbows skew into
elaborate angles, shoulders trace complex trajectories in space in
fluid counterpoint.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
