A7976 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PG&AMP;E-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PG&AMP;E to Sell Power Plants For $1 Billion  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pacific Gas and Electric Co. said yesterday it will sell three big
gas-fired power plants and a network of 14 geothermal plants for
$1.01 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The plants sold for nearly double their book value. Altogether,
the sale brings the utility's total take from asset sales to $1.5
billion, all of which were stimulated by deregulation of the
state's $23 billion electricity marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Purchasers include Southern Energy Co. of Atlanta, which is on a
nationwide buying spree. In addition to buying $801 million worth
of PG&AMP;E plants, the Georgia firm said yesterday it will buy $480
million worth of New York power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Net proceeds from the PG&AMP;E divestiture will bypass shareholders
and flow directly to PG&AMP;E's rate-paying customers. That's because
every dollar utilities reap from power plant sales, by order of the
state's deregulation law, must be used to offset billions of
dollars in utility debts that ratepayers otherwise are on the hook
to pay.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest round of sales, the second of three, buyers were
solicited for power plants constructed between 1954 and 1985 that
collectively produce 4,289 megawatts of power or enough electricity
to light four-and-a-half million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy will pay $801 million for the gas-fired Potrero,
Pittsburg and Contra Costa power plants that provide power and
electric stability to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   FPL Energy Inc. of Florida will pay $213 million for The Geysers
power plants in Lake and Sonoma counties, the largest system of
geothermal generating plants in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The price paid for gas-fired plants, at $396 per kilowatt,
slightly surpassed the average price of $370 per kilowatt for other
oil and gas plants sold previously, primarily in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, approximately 40,000 megawatts of capacity has been
sold by former monopoly utilities in the past 18 months for $17.5
billion, according to Resource Data International, a Colorado
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The plant sales reflect a concerted push by federal and state
energy regulators to make the generation and sale of electricity
competitive enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are being divested at the behest of regulators who
don't want companies with a stranglehold on supply to be in a
position to set prices in emerging electricity markets.
</P>
<P>
   But in many cases, operators have decided to go beyond plant
sales mandated by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E, for example, was ordered to sell half its gas-fired plants
but decided, instead, to sell everything except its 2,200-megawatt
Diablo Canyon nuclear plant. It sold three plants to Duke Energy
Power Services late last year for $501 million, or about 1.3 times
book value. Its hydroelectric resources, consisting of 68 power
houses on 16 river systems, will be part of a future transfer that
is expected to occur next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANKFURT-BALLET-2NDT     11-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKFURT-BALLET-2NDTAKE-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FRANKFURT, Germany: fluid counterpoint.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While straightforward balletic works like ``In the Middle,
Somewhat Elevated'' play overtly with the dancers' technical
abilities, there is no exhibition of prowess in ``Eidos: Telos.''
</P>
<P>
   Every movement is full of understated, elaborated detail as
different body parts appear to initiate their own small dance
simultaneously; no step ever serves as a transition to another,
more important visual effect.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the way Forsythe joins movements together is a
particular pleasure of all his work. Exquisitely beautiful shapes
coalesce and vanish, like objects moved by water.
</P>
<P>
   And though the shapes of these movements and the dispositions of
weight have little to do with ballet's formal positions and clean
lines, the dancers' classically trained bodies hold balletic
clarity and articulation as a perpetual, elusive point of
reference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forsythe is chary of the word ``improvisation''; rather, he
likes to think of the dancers' responsibilities in this section as
similar to those of virtuoso musicians who make choices about order
and timing when performing sequences in a cadenza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of memorizing intellectually,'' he says.
``It's about the body being a form of memory; the physical patterns
in your body are listening to the music and recalling
themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the third section, the sequences are expanded into complex
formal groupings that align and dissolve like a shaken
kaleidoscope. Performing when you are partly responsible for the
material, Forsythe stresses, takes both courage and years of
training. ``What I wanted to show in ``Eidos,' '' he says, ``is the
extent of the dancers' accomplishment.'' (They also perform in more
conventional fashion; Forsythe most recently made two balletic,
on-point works for his company.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That accomplishment extends to other arenas, too. Dana
Caspersen, an American who has been a member of Frankfurt Ballet
for 10 years and is one of its most striking performers, dominates
the middle section of ``Eidos: Telos'' with a tour de force
speaking role that she wrote herself, drawing inspiration from
Robert Calasso's ``Marriage of Cadmus and Harmony,'' a book about
the myths that underpin Western culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caspersen's lengthy, mesmerizing monologue is dominated by
the myth of Persephone and evoked in fragmented poetic segments as,
bare-breasted in a long flame-colored skirt, she strides and crawls
around the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Forsythe's theatrical skills _ his ability to give structure and
rhythm to a dreamlike domain, to explode and contract the space,
and to conjure up moments of hallucinatory beauty _ are fully
evident in this section, as the corps de ballet in long
jewel-colored silks swirl across Ms. Caspersen's mythological
universe.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Eidos: Telos'' was made in the wake of the death of Forsythe's
wife, the American dancer Tracey-Kai Maier, and Ms. Caspersen says
she wrote the text ``thinking about the appearance of radical
change in people's lives, and how these sudden experiences of
insolidity alter your vision of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing one's vision of the world might well describe
Forsythe's modus operandi, too, insofar as he seems always to want
to break up or interrupt any comfortable response to his work; to
strive for beauty, yet resist its seduction. While his works never
display a linear narrative, they often contain multiple narrative
elements that create strong emotional overtones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's about shifting frames and perspectives,
reimagining contexts,'' Forsythe says. ``In `Eidos' there are
sublime moments and grotesque moments; it forces you to keep moving
away from and back towards what is happening on stage. But you can
always come up with explanations afterward. What I always want to
say is that you don't have to understand this, you just have to
watch it, and then maybe something will happen to you without
thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
