A7981 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONTECH-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AOL Deal May Doom Netscape  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Netscape Communications would end up as a subsidiary of America
Online if yesterday's $4.2 billion buyout goes through. But whether
Netscape has any future at all is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; As part of a sidecar deal, AOL and Sun Microsystems said they
will develop future versions of Netscape's software, including its
popular Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Netscape personnel would be involved in the
products, Sun's chief strategy officer Bill Raduchel said simply,
``There is no Netscape anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If the merger spells trouble for Netscape, it promises to be a
boon to Sun of Mountain View, which would be in position to mount a
major challenge to Microsoft in the fast-growing area of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, a leading maker of business computers, already is one of
the star players on the Internet. Its computers run the majority of
the world's Internet service providers, and the Java programming
language it developed has become a staple in creating interactive
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Under a three-year agreement with AOL, Sun now also will have
Netscape's corporate software _ the stuff that lets corporations do
business online.
</P>
<P>
   In return for marketing rights to the Netscape software, Sun has
agreed to pay AOL more than $350 million up front, plus what the
companies termed ``significant minimum revenue commitments'' over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Sun will recoup some of that investment because the deal also
calls for AOL to purchase $500 million worth of Sun's computer
systems and services at list price.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts called the deal a good one for Sun. ``It's a very
finite investment with a very good potential for return,'' said
Daniel Kunstler of J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Raduchel insisted that Sun was not to blame for holding up the
AOL-Netscape deal, denying speculation that his company held out
for better terms than AOL wanted to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us bargained hard, and both sides had to protect our
shareholders,'' he said. ``We finally had an agreement at 2:05
(Tuesday) morning.''
</P>
<P>
   By combining Sun's computers and Netscape's e-commerce software,
Internet service providers and online businesses would be able to
get all of their technology from one company.
</P>
<P>
   This will make Sun a more formidable competitor to Microsoft,
which went head to head with Netscape in e-commerce software but
does not sell hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Sun the tools to be the competitor to Microsoft
they've always wanted to be,'' said analyst Rob Enderle of Giga
Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Sun also said they will develop new Internet devices
that will help users access the Web or AOL from anyplace. According
to Raduchel, those devices could be pagers, smart phones, set-top
boxes and portable Internet-only appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The new devices promise to be fertile ground for Java, and
perhaps a Java-based operating system that could rival Windows CE,
Microsoft's OS for handheld computers and other portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge over the next 20 years will not be speed or cost
or performance,'' said Raduchel. ``It will be a question of
complexity, and we're going to try to eliminate an awful lot of
that complexity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
