<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CRITIC SEEKS CENSURE RATHER THAN IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's fiercest Democratic critic in
the House on Tuesday called upon Speaker Newt Gingrich to abandon
the impeachment process in favor of a strong censure against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The critic, Rep. Paul McHale of Pennsylvania, who in August
became the first House Democrat to demand that Clinton resign, said
he now supported censure. It is unlikely, McHale said, that a
two-thirds majority in the Senate would vote to remove Clinton, and
national security crises, like the confrontation with Iraq, demand
the commander in chief's undivided attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's now clear that impeachment is a blind alley, it's time
to resolve the matter as quickly and as responsibly as possible,''
he said Tuesday night in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gingrich, McHale urged censure, at a time when
House Republicans and Democrats are counting heads to see if there
are enough votes to impeach the president. His suggestion
underscores how Republicans, already faced with mounting
defections, cannot rely on a handful of Democrats thought to be
leaning in favor of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   McHale's proposed resolution would ``censure and condemn William
Jefferson Clinton for having engaged in a pattern of deceitful and
dishonest conduct that was grossly inconsistent with his
constitutional obligation and sacred duty to faithfully execute the
laws of the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders Tuesday sought to dismiss McHale's gesture as
a premature move to short-circuit the House Judiciary Committee's
impeachment proceedings, led by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``First things first,'' said Christina Martin, Gingrich's
spokeswoman. ``Chairman Hyde and his committee have to send a
report to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., whom Republicans have chosen as
Gingrich's successor, also sought to distance himself from McHale's
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not change his personal view that the Constitution
does not provide for censure in the House,'' said Mark Corallo,
Livingston's spokesman. ``That's like a plea bargain,'' a penalty
that Livingston himself has said would be more appropriate for the
Senate to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston appeared to indicate Sunday that censure was not his
first preference, but he did not close the door either, saying that
censuring or rebuking the president would ``certainly be a
possibility'' for the Judiciary and House Rules committees to
study.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats reacted with glee to McHale's proposal,
embracing the retiring three-term former Marine who had been
ostracized by many in his party after his stinging criticism of
Clinton. McHale said on the House floor in October that Clinton's
conduct was ``predatory, reckless and breathtakingly arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Epstein, the Judiciary Committee's Democratic staff
director, observed, ``It's another nail in the impeachment coffin,
and it's a really big one.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, James Kennedy, said, ``While we don't
agree with Congressman McHale's view of the allegations, as we said
before, it's up to members of Congress to decide how to bring this
whole matter to a prompt and just conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Gregory Craig, a special White House counsel, signaled
that the White House was open to any ``serious and reasonable''
compromise that allowed Clinton to put the yearlong scandal behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   With the Judiciary Committee scheduled to begin considering
articles of impeachment the week of Dec. 7, amid the growing
likelihood that the panel will approve at least one article, the
House is set to receive the recommendations the week of Dec. 14.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McHale, who said he had not consulted with any other lawmaker,
proposed that the House consider his resolution after the committee
vote as ``an alternative to and in lieu of further impeachment
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   His four-paragraph resolution also states that Clinton, ``in
violation of his constitutional oath to faithfully execute the
office of president of the United States and in violation of his
constitutional duty to take care that the laws be faithfully
executed, has prevented, obstructed and impeded the administration
of justice by providing false and misleading testimony under
oath.''
</P>
<P>
   It also says that Clinton ``engaged personally and through his
subordinates and agents in a course of conduct or plan designed to
delay, impede and obstruct the investigation into and the
disclosure of information about the president's improper and
reprehensible relationship with'' Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   By engaging in an affair with Ms. Lewinsky, Clinton ``has acted
in a manner contrary to his trust as president, impairing the due
and proper administration of justice in the conduct of lawful
inquiries, to the great prejudice of the cause of law and justice
and to the manifest injury of the people of the United States,''
the resolution says.
</P>
<P>
   Even before McHale sent his letter to Gingrich, the Judiciary
Committee rejected the idea of circumventing its proceedings with a
reprimand.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Republican members on the committee have publicly
rejected the idea of censure either because it's not
constitutionally prescribed or because it would set a bad
precedent, given the seriousness of the allegations,'' said Paul
McNulty, a Republican committee spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Delahunt, D-Mass., a member of the panel, drew
McNulty's response after announcing he would offer a resolution to
censure Clinton rather than impeach him. Another committee
Democrat, Rep. Thomas Barrett of Wisconsin, immediately seconded
Delahunt's proposal.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
