<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETTING ON WIRED FUTURE, INTERNET PIONEERS COMBINE
</P>
<P>
   Banking on forecasts of rapid, lucrative growth in electronic
commerce and a long-term vision of a thoroughly networked world,
America Online laid out the details of its agreement to buy
Netscape Communications for $4.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AOL hopes that by moving quickly toward what both companies have
recently come to see as the inevitable convergence of technology
and media, it will secure a solid lead in a battle for market share
that will pit the merged company against giants like Microsoft and
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   An economist testifying for the government in the Microsoft
antitrust suit sat through another day of cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY SHOWS SURPRISING STAMINA
</P>
<P>
   The latest snapshot of the U.S. economy showed the
long-predicted slowdown is still more forecast than fact. The
economy performed better during the summer than first reported and
consumer confidence bounced back this fall. But corporate profits
weakened in the July-September quarter.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYPENS POSE DANGER TO CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   The government announced that nearly 10 million playpens must be
repaired or destroyed because children could strangle themselves in
them. Companies are offering refunds or repair kits to consumers
who own the playpens, which carry brand names like Kolcraft,
Playskool, Strolee, Bilt-Rite, Evenflo, Gerry, Graco and
Pride-Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   TELMEX PHONE VENTURE CHALLENGED
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission said it had received
significant evidence that a joint venture created by the Sprint and
Telefonos de Mexico had committed anti-competitive practices in the
long-distance market. FCC Chairman William Kennard said the high
rates charged by the venture affected ``the most vulnerable
consumers,'' recent Hispanic immigrants who used the service to
call home.
</P>
<P>
   BANK LANDSCAPE SHIFTING IN EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's $9.7 billion bid for Bankers Trust is merely the
most visible sign of a much broader upheaval in European finance.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO FACES NAFTA COMPLAINT
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials have acknowledged that their labor laws do not
adequately protect the rights of Mexican workers, according to
documents obtained by Canadian union officials who have filed a
complaint under the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL ON CONCERN OVER PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell on concern that the euphoria that sent the Dow Jones
industrial average up 21 percent in six weeks was unjustified by
the outlook for corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Money is flowing into stock mutual funds again now that stocks
have rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   COURTSHIP MOVES TOWARD MARRIAGE
</P>
<P>
   After engaging in one of the slowest-moving courtships ever
between two companies, the French drug maker Rhone-Poulenc and
Hoechst of Germany are expected to announce their merger as early
as next week. The companies' investors have seldom enjoyed such a
robust ride. Hoechst's American depository receipts have jumped 26
percent since Oct. 13, and Rhone-Poulenc's ADR's have risen 38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   NOVELL PROFIT EXCEEDS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Novell reported fourth-quarter earnings that exceeded estimates
and attributed the performance to strong sales of the new version
of its network operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit reported a fiscal first-quarter loss, reflecting the
costs of developing tax preparation products to sell in coming
months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
