<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN GROWS OVER DIMAGGIO'S HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Mass.)   (jw) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Fla. _ Joe DiMaggio, hospitalized here since Oct. 12,
turns 84 on Wednesday amid mounting concern over his condition.
</P>
<P>
   WPIX in New York, which had long televised Yankee games,
reported Tuesday night that DiMaggio had lung cancer and had a
tumor removed from his left lung last month. The station also said
the Hall of Famer had a heart attack last week, basing its report
on three people who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Tony Segreto, a longtime news anchor at WTVJ, a
Miami television station, said he confirmed the WPIX report from a
person at Memorial Regional Hospital, where DiMaggio is a patient.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami station said DiMaggio was on a ventilator, but ESPN
reported Tuesday that DiMaggio's condition had improved enough so
that he was off life support.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg, a lawyer and a friend of DiMaggio's who has
been serving as his spokesman since he entered the hospital, denied
that DiMaggio had had a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``DiMaggio never had a heart attack _ this is totally false _
and he is not in grave condition,'' Engelberg said in a statement
from his Fort Lauderdale, Fla., office. `` DiMaggio and his family
heard this information on the television and were very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Engelberg, in referring to the reported heart
attack, said, ``We were all shocked by this false rumor.''
Engelberg did not comment on the report that DiMaggio has lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio remains in intensive care at the hospital, where he was
admitted for what was described as pneumonia and a lung infection.
</P>
<P>
   His birthday will be limited mostly to family. Among those
expected to visit are his granddaughter Paula and her husband,
their two daughters, Joe's brother Dom and Engelberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take a ride down there,'' Dom DiMaggio said
Tuesday night from his Boynton Beach, Fla., home. ``I'm hoping
maybe we'll have a celebration of some kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio, the former Boston Red Sox center fielder, declined
to discuss his brother's condition, saying Engelberg is the
spokesman. Engelberg said in his statement that DiMaggio has
advised him to no longer discuss his health with anyone other than
DiMaggio's doctors and immediate family.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Joe Nachio, an old friend of DiMaggio's, said the
former Yankee felt better after talking to Engelberg on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morris just told me now that he's wide awake, he's gained 20
pounds, he's starting to smile and he recognizes a conversation and
the people around him,'' Nachio said from his office in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Memorial Regional Hospital have refused to comment
on DiMaggio's condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Merger Means Uncertain Changes for Netscape   By Jon Swartz and Jamie Beckett  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Finalizing a deal that will create a formidable rival to Microsoft,
America Online agreed yesterday to purchase Netscape Communications
for $4.21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process, Internet pioneer Netscape may end up as just
a shell of its former self.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to build a 21st century media company that
reaches the biggest possible audience,'' AOL Chief Executive
Officer Steve Case said in a telephone interview yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal elevates AOL to kingpin of the Net and marks an
unceremonious ending for Netscape's fairy tale rise from scrappy
startup to Internet icon.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain View firm will cease to exist as an independent
company and will become the West Coast subsidiary of AOL, run by
AOL Chief Operating Officer Bob Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale will join AOL's board of directors
after the deal closes this spring but will not have any day-to-day
responsibilities. Netscape co-founder and Internet prodigy Marc
Andreessen is negotiating to work at AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the combination with AOL is a killer deal,'' an
apparently buoyant Barksdale said during a five-minute press
conference at Netscape's headquarters yesterday. But despite
executives' optimism, employees seemed worried. At lunchtime
yesterday, several stood together in tight knots on Netscape's
campus, sullenly telling reporters, ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Case said AOL and Netscape are in the process of poring over
company ranks to determine possible cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, which acquires Netscape's Navigator Web browser and popular
Netcenter site for online news content and shopping, intends to
continue running Netcenter as a separate Internet gateway site
catering to a different audience than AOL, said Mike Homer,
Netscape's manager for Netcenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same as having MTV and VH1. Each is targeted to a
different audience,'' he said. While AOL.com caters to the Internet
novice who uses the service at home, Netcenter is intended for more
experienced Net surfers who access the Internet primarily at work
during the day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related three-year deal between AOL and Sun, the Mountain
View workstation-maker will develop and market e-commerce software
that makes it easy to set up shop in cyberspace. Sun will
co-develop future versions of Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   One Sun official said Netscape would no longer be involved in
the products that made it an Internet pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   While the pacts align three of Microsoft's staunchest rivals,
surprisingly, AOL will not drop Microsoft's Internet Explorer as
the browser on its online service in favor of Netscape's Navigator
browser. AOL will continue to offer both browsers, with Internet
Explorer the primary choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to maintain our presence on Windows-based computers
(through a reciprocal agreement with Microsoft),'' Case said. ``We
need to continue working with Microsoft where we can and compete
with them when necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Both AOL and Microsoft have benefited greatly from that
relationship. AOL gained prominent placement on computer screens
running Microsoft's Windows operating system, while Microsoft's Web
browser emerged as the standard on the largest online service.
</P>
<P>
   Case balked at suggestions that the Department of Justice's
antitrust case against Microsoft forced the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The deal was not dictated by the DOJ (Department of Justice)
case. It's about e-commerce,'' Case said. ``This is about building
a company for the next century. The government has a strong case,
which is based on Microsoft leveraging its operating system to gain
a monopoly. Our acquisition of Netscape had nothing to do with the
antitrust case.''
</P>
<P>
   He said AOL's motivation is to capture a sizable chunk of the
booming e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR;  &LR; Both AOL and Netscape have megasites, called portals, that
are doorways to the rest of the Internet. The portals were designed
to be the first place Web surfers go online, and the home base for
all their Internet activities.
</P>
<P>
   The potential payoff is astronomical: Net advertising is
expected to hit $7.7 billion by 2002, and e-commerce sales could
balloon to $37.5 billion this year, according to market researcher
Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   By combining Netscape's services with its own, AOL will reach a
staggering 70 percent of all people who access the Internet,
industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always thought there would be three major portal players
_ ourselves, AOL and Microsoft,'' Yahoo Chief Operating Officer
Jeff Mallett said.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett and others predict the AOL-Netscape arrangement will
affect midrange portal players, forcing Excite, Infoseek and Lycos
to either seek a buyer or merge with one another to remain
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for Excite, Yahoo and other portal sites will be
to figure out how to compete with this new creature lumbering
through the underbrush _ is it going to start stomping everybody or
chasing its tail?'' said Jeff Tarter, publisher of Softletter in
Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, Netscape shareholders will receive 0.45 shares
of AOL stock for each share of Netscape stock.
</P>
<P>
   The blockbuster deal's big winners are Case _ the 40-year-old
online mogul _ and Pittman, AOL's marketing whiz who is nicknamed
``Pitchman.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittman _ a diligent cost-cutter who began the practice of
selling space on the AOL service to retailers and advertisers, such
as Amazon.com, Preview Travel and 1-800-Flowers _ will be
responsible for overseeing Netcenter and Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   In fourth-quarter results announced yesterday, Netscape said
revenues for Netcenter rose 24 percent from the previous quarter,
to $48 million. Netscape's Enterprise software and services
business posted a 2 percent increase in sales, to $114 million.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape reported a better-than-expected profit of $2.7 million
(3 cents per share) on record sales of $162 million, compared with
a profit of $10.2 million (10 cents) on sales of $152 million in
the same quarter a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
