<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-NETSCAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE TO BUY NETSCAPE FOR $4.2B IN STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kicking off an expected round of consolidation among Internet
companies, America Online Inc. said Tuesday it would purchase
Internet software maker Netscape Communications Corp. for about
$4.2 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was widely anticipated, as was a side accord in which
AOL said it will license Netscape software to Sun Microsystems Inc.
for $350 million and will buy $500 million of electronic commerce
services and equipment from Sun. Together these assets will add
significantly to AOL's reach on the World Wide Web and boost the
pressure on smaller Internet firms in the race for revenue &UR;  &LR; and
users.
</P>
<P>
   The race centers primarily on a dozen or so ``portal'' sites on
the Web, which offer users everything from stock quotes to pet-care
tips. Such sites have been among the fastest-growing on-line
businesses to date, but in the long run many doubt whether the
Web's 62.5 million domestic users will support more than a handful.
</P>
<P>
   Already popular before its Netscape purchase, AOL now poses more
of a threat to smaller on-line companies like AltaVista and
InfoSeek, which also are trying to become gateways to the Internet,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   A ``portal shakeout'' is how Forrester Research analyst Chris
Charron describes the situation, which he said will force smaller
players to become more specialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing more of the opportunities going to the larger
players,'' Charron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is natural Darwinism, and it happens in every other
industry as well,'' said Tim Koogle, chief executive of the portal
company &UR;  &LR; Yahoo Inc. in Santa Clara, Calif. ``There's no  &UR;  &LR; reason to
believe the Internet shouldn't follow a similar trend.''
</P>
<P>
   The terms of AOL's deals with Netscape and Sun were in line with
AOL's previous disclosures. Under the terms of the agreement, AOL
will exchange 0.45 share of its stock for each of Netscape's
roughly 100 million common shares, valuing Netscape stock at $41.12
apiece, based on Tuesday's closing price for AOL.
</P>
<P>
   AOL executives said the agreements will enable the Dulles, Va.,
company to eventually introduce a new browser _ software used to
surf the Web _ based on Netscape's popular Navigator technology.
For now, AOL will continue to buy Web-browsing software from
Microsoft. In addition, AOL will take control of Netscape's popular
NetCenter Web site, giving it a business audience in addition to
AOL's traditional consumer base.
</P>
<P>
   AOL also said it plans to roll out new electronic commerce
services, such as on-line banking built around Sun's versatile Java
programming language.
</P>
<P>
   Together, said AOL president Bob Pittman, the new assets will
give AOL ``an unparalleled array of interactive services.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape chief executive Jim Barksdale will step down from daily
operations but will join AOL's board. Netscape will remain at its
Mountain View, Calif., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said it expects to complete the buyout in the spring of
1999, pending antitrust reviews and approvals from Netscape
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Investors drove up shares of AOL and Sun following the
announcement. AOL stock rose 2 1/8 to 91 3/8 Tuesday. Sun stock
rose 1 5/8 to 72 15/16, while Netscape fell 2 1/16 to 39 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's shares rose rose 2 1/2 to 121 11/16 on expectations
that the deal would weaken the government's ongoing antitrust
prosecution of the Redmond, Wash., software giant.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Consumer Project on Technology, affiliated
with Ralph Nader, said it will urge officials to reject the planned
purchase of Netscape. The group's leader, James Love, said the
proposal would lead to undue concentration of the market for
software used to display images on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape pioneered that market four years ago with the
introduction of its Navigator browser.
</P>
<P>
   But since then a bevy of on-line service companies has sprung
up, putting pressure on &UR;  &LR; Netscape. As of October, Netscape's
various sites could claim visits from 33 percent of the Web's
users, according to Media Metrix Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That market share trailed significantly behind AOL, Microsoft,
Yahoo, and Lycos Inc., each of which had a market share in the
mid-40s.
</P>
<P>
   Like AOL, other leading portal companies have scrambled to buy
up content they believe will attract new users to their sites.
Microsoft's offerings include a partnership with NBC television and
the on-line magazine Slate.com; Lycos in October agreed to buy
closely held Wired Digital Inc. for stock worth $83 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is becoming a lot like television,'' said Lycos chief
executive Bob Davis. ``There will be four to six general-interest
portals, just like there are about four big networks in the
television environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, many smaller Web services are becoming more
like ad producers, piping material over others' networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
