<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 How Internet Stocks Are Like Beanie Babies and Cabbage
Patch  Dolls  By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Perhaps we should think of recent Internet initial offerings in the
same vein as Beanie Babies and Cabbage Patch dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, this is the grounded thinking of financial analyst
Lise Buyer of CS First Boston in Palo Alto, who tries to make sense
out of a lot of this Net nonsense. Besides, while we contemplate
the global implications of the America Online-Netscape marriage, we
can reduce the rationalization of betting junior's college fund on
Internet stocks to child's play.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Buyer suggests that Beanie Babies are today's Cabbage
Patch dolls as far as toy hysteria goes. And at a recent
presentation before venture capitalists, she produced two Beanie
Baby dolls that already were out of production and named them
Theglobe.com and EarthWeb. Both are newly minted Internet IPOs
that, at their peak, saw their share prices multiply like stuffed
bunnies. (After peaking in the 60s, both companies' shares are
slumping in the 40s _ still three and four times their offering
prices of two weeks ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike these Internet IPOs, you can't buy these particular
Beanie Babies from the manufacturer. You now must purchase these
``retired'' models from holders in the open market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You no longer can get them, ergo their prices have gone up,''
Buyer explains.
</P>
<P>
   After trying to buy one of the out-of-circulation Beanie Babies
on eBay, the online auction site trading at 11 times its initial
offering price, Buyer found the toy going for about $25 _ or at
least four times the doll's initial offering price (the suggested
retail price charged by stores).
</P>
<P>
   Thus, even dolls with thin floats and intense demand are able to
fetch premium prices beyond their original value. And in the midst
of a Beanie Babie craze, there are more buyers than sellers bidding
up demand. Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   In order to predict what might happen to Beanie Baby valuations
after the frenzy falters, Buyer studied the demise of Cabbage Patch
dolls _ the Beanie Babies of their day, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, a Cabbage Patch doll would go for about $49.95
off the shelf if you were fortunate enough to procure one. As you
may recall, the average Cabbage Patch doll's value soared well
above its fifty-buck ``issue price'' to as high as $500 a doll on
the open market. That's 10 times the IPO value of your average
Cabbage Patch doll.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, eager-to-please parents bidding for a finite number of
stuffed-toys drove the price of these dolls into another
stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   But like many things that are too good to be true, the Cabbage
Patch craze died and was replaced by, among other things, Beanie
Babies. Guess what happened?
</P>
<P>
   The Cabbage Patch market tanked. The cuddly little things are
now underwater, with new issues going for about $32.50. That's
about $17.50 off their mid-'80s initial offering price, Buyer says.
</P>
<P>
   Will Theglobe.com and EarthWeb _ Internet juggernauts that they
are _ suffer demises similar to the erstwhile Cabbage Patch dolls?
You can bet your Beanie Baby they will, Buyer contends.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all Internet stocks are created equal. And
certainly, Theglobe.com should not be confused with the likes of
electronic commerce superstars Amazon.com and Yahoo, she adds. But
beware the majority of Internet companies that have gone, or have
yet to, go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere along the line, one of these companies is going to
turn out to be a fraud,'' Buyer warns.
</P>
<P>
   IN PLAY: With the dramatic return of the buyout boom, at least
one merger expert admonishes individual investors not to bet on
acquisition targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to pick companies that would get taken out takes a lot
of (home)work,'' says Judy Cohen, editor of Mergers &AMP; Acquisitions
Report in New York.
</P>
<P>
   If investors are lucky enough to own shares in a company that
gets taken over, they should sell their stock immediately after the
deal is announced, she suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the takeover premium _ or the rise in stock price
triggered by a sale _ already is built into the shares by the time
a deal is struck.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you insist in investing in companies you think will
get bought, be careful, she warns. If anything, look for companies
that are good investments based on their fundamentals regardless of
the potential for takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``But make sure it's not already trading with a takeover premium
built into the price,'' Cohen says.
</P>
<P>
   Because if a buyout candidate gets abandoned at the alter,
investors are left holding the bag, she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
