<SLUG> BC-TELMEX-FCC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TELMEX EYES US, FCC HAS PRICING QUERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Ever since President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico
unplugged the country's telephone monopoly in January 1997 and
opened up its $3.5 billion long-distance market to private
competition, the bruising battle for customers has read like the
storyline from a classic Mexican soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   In a plot filled with drama, schemes, backbiting, unlikely
alliances, and angry accusations of abuse and betrayal, Telefonos
de Mexico, the giant that still dominates the local market here,
has fought aggressively against a half-dozen foes, including US
giants AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Things just got uglier.
</P>
<P>
   Just three months after it received approval to be the first
foreign long-distance carrier to operate in the United States,
Telmex is now being questioned by American authorities about
whether it unfairly blocks competition back home. Late Tuesday, the
US Federal Communications Commission issued an order calling for
Telmex officials to explain their pricing and accounting practices
to prove they are not overcharging competitors in an effort to
squeeze them out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC action is in response to increasing pressure brought on
this year by AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom, who say Telmex charges them
seven cents a minute _ seven times higher then the actual cost to
Telmex _ for interconnection rates to the local network.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has oversight over Telmex's partnership with another
American company, Sprint Communications, to market long-distance
service in US cities with large Mexican-American populations.
Telmex has 30 days to respond to the FCC's order.
</P>
<P>
   Although Telmex no longer holds a monopoly inside Mexico, it is
still one of the nation's largest and most influential corporations
and it still controls the switches that provide access to local
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies have managed to lure more than a quarter of
Mexico's long-distance customers in less than two years. Both AT&AMP;T
and MCI, however, say Telmex's monopolistic practices are costing
them hundreds of millions of dollars in revenues and violate a
world trade agreement signed in February to open up
telecommunications services to foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   Avantel, S.A., which is half-owned by MCI, has halted $900
million of investment planned for Mexico because of the dispute.
The Mexican company Alpha, one of three partners in Alestra, the
AT&AMP;T-developed Mexico enterprise, disclosed last month that it had
lost nearly $50 million so far this year from the long-distance
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of behavior is impacting the viability for us and
others who want to compete'' in Mexico's market, Dianne Bernez, an
AT&AMP;T spokeswoman, said last week. ``You won't see competitive
pricing in Mexico if we don't have access to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   When it approved the Telmex-Sprint partnership, which AT&AMP;T and
MCI vehemently opposed, the agency attached several conditions,
most of them aimed at Telmex's willingness to open Mexico's market.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, FCC officials said this week that they have grown
frustrated with the company's seemingly unfair business practices
and the lack of regulatory and legal muscle that exists in Mexico
to force Telmex to change its behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pricing structure is so far askew in favor of Telmex that
it has become an economic liability issue'' for American
competitors, one FCC official said this week on background. ``There
is the feeling that'' Mexico's Federal Telecommunications
Commission ``has not done enough. They need to step up to the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Telmex's foreign competitors also want the company to reduce its
settlement rates _ the fees carriers pay each other to terminate an
international call _ which have ranged about 39 cents a minute,
making them the highest in the world. Settlement rates to Canada
are about 10 cents and even less for calls to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate decision Tuesday, the FCC rejected a settlement
rate agreement of 37 cents between Telmex and its American partner,
Sprint Communications, because the rate was still too high.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials said the license granted to Telmex is not in
immediate jeopardy of being rescinded _ because of the company's
right to respond. But Telmex must now answer to American
authorities, who are believed to be stricter than their Mexican
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Telmex officials did not immediately return a phone call Tuesday
seeking comment. But Mexican regulators and company officials have
said that the settlement rates were clearly spelled out in a 1997
agreement, and that the fees will be reduced to 19 cents by 2000, a
benchmark that US officials agreed to previously.
</P>
<P>
   When Mexico's long-distance market was opened, government
officials on both sides of the border pointed to it as proof of the
merits of the North American Free Trade Agreement. But with
government bodies in both countries now involved in the
cross-border long-distance dispute, the battle for telephone
service in Mexico is likely to escalate further.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few months ago, Telmex had been controlled by Carlos
Slim Helu, a 58-year-old stockbroker who bought the company when
the government privatized it in 1991. He is now considered to be
the richest man in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   As competition has been introduced into Mexico, every company,
including Telmex, has become even more aggressive. Long distance
rates have declined by nearly half since February 1997 _ as Telmex
lowered prices to undercut new companies _ while local rates have
gone up 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican customers now also get something many Americans are all
too familiar with: the dinnertime phone call from a long-distance
company representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been called about three times in the last two
weeks by the same company,'' said Emilio Barraza, a 40-year-old
Mexico City banker. ``I don't know what to say. It's always been
Telmex. I'm not saying I'm happy, but that's what I'm used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2203EST &QL; 
