<HEADER>
A8021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      11-24 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS IN SYNC WITH HOLYFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The champagne has been chilling for so long it has
frostbite. After six weeks of haggling over such things as the
shape of the bargaining table, the deal for the heavyweight
unification bout between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis is
finally done.
</P>
<P>
   All sides have agreed to terms and a news conference is
scheduled next Monday at Madison Square Garden, which will be the
site of the bout March 13. Don King will be the promoter and the
bout will be televised on pay-per-view by TVKO.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, the World Boxing Association and International Boxing
Federation champion, will receive $20 million and Lewis, the World
Boxing Council champion, will receive between $8 million and $10
million. The winner can look forward to two years of mandatory
defenses against guys like Henry Akinwande.
</P>
<P>
   King Has the Edge
</P>
<P>
   Don King has won Round 1 of his legal fight with Felix Trinidad,
the idle IBF welterweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Monday a federal judge in Manhattan refused to grant Trinidad a
preliminary injunction to set aside his contract with King,
derailing the fighter's attempt to sign another promotional deal
with Main Events and scuttling a Jan. 9 bout against Pernell
Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad had sought the injunction based on his belief that his
contract with King had expired. But King believes that the contract
is in force because it is tied to Trinidad being a champion.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Medina, Trinidad's Puerto Rico based lawyer, said his
fighter was weighing his option on what to do next. Medina said
Trinidad could appeal the judge's ruling on the preliminary
injunction or proceed with a juror trial on the other issues of his
lawsuit. Both options are time consuming and will hurt Trinidad, a
brilliant boxer whose career is in neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad was supposed to fight Ike Quartey two weeks ago under
an agreement he signed with Main Events. But that fight was
canceled. Now that his fight against Whitaker has been snatched
away, there is no telling when Trinidad will get back into the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   HBO Sports, which has a separate contract with Trinidad, is
still holding the Jan. 9 date, apparently looking to put Roy Jones
Jr. in the ring for that date. If so, it would be the third time in
10 months that Jones filled in for a broken fight for the cable
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had more saves this year than Trevor Hoffman,'' Mike
Boorman of Main Events, said citing the San Diego Padre relief
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor Mill Is Spinning
</P>
<P>
   Jay Larkin, the Showtime senior vice president of sports and
events programming, said he was waiting for someone to call him
with a rumor that Mike Tyson had been kidnapped by aliens and would
not be around for his heavyweight bout against Frans Botha on Jan.
16.
</P>
<P>
   ``These rumors that the fight is in jeopardy are getting
ridiculous,'' Larkin said. ``But has there ever been a Mike Tyson
fight where there haven't been rumors running rampant?''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said there was no truth to a rumor that the MGM Grand was
not satisfied with its deal for the fight and might be backing out.
</P>
<P>
   A news conference scheduled in Manhattan last week to announce
the fight was canceled because Tyson did not want to break the
rhythm of his training in Phoenix and fly to the East Coast.
Instead there will be a news conference at the Century Plaza Hotel
in Los Angeles next Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
