<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEROIC-US-CONSUMERS-R     11-24 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIC-US-CONSUMERS-RESEND-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW LONG CAN U.S. CONSUMERS PROP UP WORLD ECONOMY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending for those needing; moved 11-20)   (This excellent 1,000-word ``separate buy'' financial story is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from New York Times sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By JIM JUBAK  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund is out of dough. Politicians
from Tokyo to Moscow lack the mandate or the will to fix their
economies. Intervention has failed the central banks and
speculators.
</P>
<P>
   All that now seems to stand between the world and a slide into
global recession are U.S. consumers, armed with wallets full of
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh at this unlikely superhero _ these notoriously
casual savers who already strain under a mountain of debt are
stronger than they look. But don't overestimate what they'll be
able to pull off, either.
</P>
<P>
   At best, U.S. consumers can buy the global economy some time and
prevent a worldwide panic. But they won't be able to stop the Asian
flu from infecting Latin America, and they can't, by themselves,
turn the situation around.
</P>
<P>
   How did the global economy get to this pass? More than a year
after the collapse of the Thai baht triggered an avalanche that
buried all of Asia, the International Monetary Fund's program of
huge loans, higher rates, and big cuts to government spending
hasn't stabilized the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   That medicine did indeed stop the feverish descent of Asia's
currencies (particularly the South Korean won, which is worth more
today than it was in January), but overall, the economies of the
region have become sicker, not healthier.
</P>
<P>
   High interest rates, for example, have helped choke off growth.
Indonesia's gross domestic product will fall an estimated 15
percent this year. (For context, Mexico's GDP sank 7 percent in
1995 after the peso crisis.)
</P>
<P>
   And Japan is, even its traditionally optimistic bureaucrats
admit, officially in recession.
</P>
<P>
   Now the IMF is almost out of money. The bankers are so close to
the bottom of the vault that in mid-August they elected not to
throw more cash into Russia. A bailout, the IMF felt, would have
depleted reserves without offering the slightest chance that
Russia's problems would be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled Latin American countries such as Venezuela and Brazil
aren't likely to get a warmer welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The standard remedy for recession is to generate spending,
either by running budget deficits to pay for public works or by
cutting taxes to stimulate private demand.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, that extra money soaks up the supply of unsold goods
and services, stimulates new capital investment, and creates jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But even when governments in Asia have been able to muster the
political will to take these steps, the program hasn't worked.
</P>
<P>
   Asia isn't in the grip of your standard-issue, plain-vanilla
recession. Nope, this is the deluxe model that combines falling
economic activity, constantly shrinking asset values, and a
seemingly endless credit crunch. Efforts to stimulate growth
disappear into these devastated economies without a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, for example, has poured trillions of yen into
infrastructure projects and cut taxes _ albeit timidly _ without
noticeable effect. Consumers are too afraid to spend _ the Japanese
and Koreans are clearly saving more in response to the crisis _ and
who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   The official unemployment rate in Japan, the land of lifetime
employment, is now at 4.3 percent, and the real rate is probably
closer to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. consumers are spending every dollar they have
and then some. Personal income rose 0.2 percent in June, according
to the Department of Commerce, after an increase of 0.4 percent in
May. Personal expenditures rose 0.6 percent in June, after a 0.9
percent climb in May.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. consumers are doing exactly what their counterparts in Asia
aren't willing to do. In June, the U.S. trade deficit with the ten
major Asian nations totaled $15 billion _ that's up more than 40
percent from the deficit in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty clear where at least some of the dollars headed to
Asia are coming from. U.S. consumers are saving less and running up
more debt. In the first quarter of 1998, according to the
Department of Commerce, U.S. consumers saved just 0.6 percent. At
the same time, consumer debt grew at an annual rate of better than
6 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are now paying a record 15 percent of after-tax income
in interest and principal, according to Economic Analysis
Associates of Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   If you judge from those trends, the U.S. consumer sounds pretty
tapped out and poorly cast as the hero who will save the world
economy. But these numbers ignore the ``wealth effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve estimates that since 1994 the stock market
has added $12.5 trillion to the assets of U.S. households. Using
traditional estimates of the way this wealth effect flows from the
financial markets into consumer spending, that asset explosion will
add about $600 billion annually to consumer purchasing power in the
U.s.
</P>
<P>
   That number is both reassuring and scary. Reassuring because it
suggests the United States will be able to continue its role as
consumer of last resort into 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Scary because it suggests that U.S. consumers will play this
role only as long as a buoyant stock market makes them feel
wealthy. No one has any real idea, unfortunately, of how far the
market would have to fall before consumers would stop feeling
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of buying by U.S. consumers can fix the structural
problems in the Korean, Japanese, or Brazilian economies. But it
can buy time for those economies to right themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It can pump liquidity into cash-starved companies in these
countries. And it can give countries _ China most importantly _ an
incentive for working to help fix the global economy rather than
pursuing a ruinous policy of beggar thy neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it offers the hope that hard-pressed countries have
a way out of this fix. That's pretty important in a world that, for
the moment, seems to be out of alternative ideas. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Jim Jubak is the senior markets editor at
Microsoft Investor (www.investor.com), and a regular contributor of
WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,000-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from New York Times sales representative NIRDI RELIS
in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
