</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAGGING OF A SNUB FOR `DR. DEATH' 
TRADING TENORS 
PEEKABOO SUITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the anything-for-a-ratings-point world of
television, on-camera personalities often want to spread the word
when they pass up a blockbuster. Consider Oprah Winfrey, who said
that she had turned down a pay-for-chat proposal involving Monica
S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Walters landed the Lewinsky interview with no money
down. But Ms. Walters said no to Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who went on to
make a videotape of the death of a Michigan man that was shown on
the CBS News program ``60 Minutes'' on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Murphy, a spokeswoman for ABC News, said that a lawyer
for Kevorkian had contacted Ms. Walters last year. But Ms. Murphy
said that Ms. Walters and her bosses decided not to do a Kevorkian
segment on ``20/20,'' which had shown parts of a Dutch documentary
on assisted suicide in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the decision at that time that we would not include
the moment of death,'' she said, ``out of respect for the audience
or the privacy of the person who died.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversations with the lawyer for Kevorkian, Geoffrey
Fieger, ``never went that far along,'' Ms. Murphy said. ``What they
wanted Barbara to do was witness a death and presumably film it.
Her immediate reaction was that was not something she was
interested in doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading Tenors
</P>
<P>
   Call it a three-for-three swap. Luciano Pavarotti bowed out of
three performances of ``Tosca'' at the Metropolitan Opera earlier
this month when recuperation from a midsummer hip-replacement
operation took longer than he had expected. Richard Leech was
tapped to fill in for him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Sunday, Pavarotti returned to the Met for a gala
performance that celebrated the 30th anniversary of his Met debut.
It went well, and Tuesday the Met said that Pavarotti, 63, would
sing three performances of ``Tosca'' that Leech had been scheduled
to do in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it means to the audience to have the experience of
hearing his Cavaradossi in person,'' Leech said, explaining why he
had agreed to step aside in March. ``To be honest, I can't wait to
hear it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Leech's days in ``Tosca'' are not over yet, though. In January
2000, he will sing Cavaradossi in a broadcast performance of
``Tosca.''
</P>
<P>
   Peekaboo Suite
</P>
<P>
   There were few short skirts at the party for Nest magazine at
the Beekman Place town house that belonged to Paul Rudolph until
his death last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, an architect who embraced modernism in all its
eccentric formulations, was well known in interior-design circles
for see-through Plexiglas floors.
</P>
<P>
   So if a thoughtful partygoer happened to be on one of the lower
floors of the Rudolph house and happened to look up, he or she
might have caught a glimpse of something more than just a plain
white ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   But the partygoers on Monday night _ who all behaved and didn't
look up _ had other plans. The group _ which included the hotelier
Andre Balazs, the designer Robert Isabell, the designer Mary
McFadden and a vice president of the Metropolitan Museum of Art,
Ashton Hawkins _ had gathered to celebrate the third winter issue
of Nest. (Remember Nest? It is an interior design magazine.) But by
Tuesday, it was clear that some of the guests had had something
else in mind: buying the house, which Sotheby's International
Realty has had on the market for $6.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nadine Johnson, who planned the party with Joe Holtzman, Nest's
editor, said she had had two phone calls from interested buyers:
Balazs and Isabell. But Ms. Johnson is a publicity agent, not a
real-estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   One word of caution to the adventurous buyer: You will get the
see-through floors, but the skylighted Jacuzzi with the clear
bottom has been boarded over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
