<HEADER>
A8029 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     11-24 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS LOOKS CAN BE DECEIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Officials are often infuriated by his antics.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably to be expected. UCLA senior linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo looks you square in the eye and says, ``I want to play
on the edge of insanity. I don't want to go overboard. I want to be
right on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   So he negotiates that fine margin, yelling, stomping about,
riotously celebrating his big plays (which have been many this
year), grinding an opponent into the turf until the very instant of
the first whistle _ well, maybe a little bit after.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday against USC, a game for which Ayanbadejo's
contributions earned him Pacific-10 defensive player of the week
honors, this exuberance threatened to bubble over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played with so much fire,'' said fellow linebacker Tony
White, ``that the refs were, like, `Calm down, No. 50.' `Blue
captain! Come take your guy, calm him down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Get a look at Ayanbadejo off the field and this image is only
enhanced. He has a tattoo on each arm and another _ the Egyptian
eye of Horus _ on the back of his skull. He has a pierced nose, a
pierced eyebrow, a pierced nipple. His head is shaven and his chin
bears a 1{-inch tuft of wavy black beard.
</P>
<P>
   When he's angry or there's a USC tailback in front of him _ or
both _ he can deliver a scowl that would buckle your knees.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe more people should see the smile. That big generous
one that he seems to break into the instant he steps off the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm going to be some lunatic or something,''
Ayanbadejo said this week. ``They think, `Oh, you must be some type
of party animal like Dennis Rodman.' . . . They say, `Oh, your face
is so scary sometimes.' They get to know me and they find out quite
the opposite about me.''
</P>
<P>
   At Warner Avenue Elementary School in Westwood, they've seen
this other side. Ayanbadejo volunteers there three times a week,
working with fifth-graders in theater arts. He and other UCLA
students, through a program called Equal Opportunities Production,
help the kids put together all aspects of a live play. Now in the
works: ``Huckleberry Finn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him on television,'' said principal Jeff Felz, ``at
first we were almost saying, `Is that our guy?' But in person here
at the school, he is so relaxed and such a sweet guy, if I can use
that term.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayanbadejo, a history major who aspires to teach, was so
unassuming in his approach to this project that he didn't inform
anyone of his athletic fame when he arrived last April to help with
``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids really didn't know him as a football player,'' said
Lynda Edmundson, the teacher of the class. ``They didn't know who
he was. But we had a number of kids who would hang onto him and
think he was really great.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, they know who he is. They watch him on TV. The kids
seem to really like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for Ayanbadejo's jersey number over the weekend
got a tutorial in big-play football. And when he walked in on
Monday, the kids chanted, ``50's in the house!''
</P>
<P>
   In a 34-17 victory over USC, Ayanbadejo sacked quarterback
Carson Palmer four times, had a team-leading nine tackles and also
forced a Chad Morton fumble that set up a UCLA field goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was output the unbeaten Bruins have gotten accustomed to this
season. Ayanbadejo leads the team in sacks (nine) and tackles for
loss (13), making him personally responsible for the opposition
going 156 yards in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys,'' said coach Bob Toledo, ``where he
thinks he's the only guy on the football field on defense, that if
he doesn't make the play, it will be a touchdown or a big play. He
has got to make every play and that's the sign of a great defensive
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the excitability is a direct byproduct of that.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ayanbadejo produced a sack against Arizona, but he
was so intent on rising to celebrate that he didn't realize a
fumble had occurred on the play. The ball was knocking about his
high-stepping knees as his teammates scrambled beneath him to get
it.
</P>
<P>
   A former high school wrestler, he has been known to don a
Spandex outfit and tear around the locker room, looking for players
_ usually freshmen, ``just to humble them a little'' _ to wrestle.
</P>
<P>
   And Toledo raved about the inspiring remarks Ayanbadejo made to
the assembled Bruins the night before the USC game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted to convey to them was to take advantage of your
time at UCLA,'' the linebacker said, ``and every time go out there
like it's your last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I was just going to go out there and play wild and go
out with a bang.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are off this week before concluding their regular
season at Miami on Dec. 5. If they win _ subject to the vagaries of
the Bowl Championship Series rankings _ they could be headed to the
Fiesta Bowl for a shot at the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins reach that game, they might have to chain this guy
up the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Whoops. There are those perceptions again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a normal person and everything, but on the field,
that's the only place I can be on the edge of insanity,''
Ayanbadejo said. ``On the street, I can't go out and start acting
like a nut.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he has never had alcohol. Or cigarettes. Or illegal
drugs. Let the kids at Warner Avenue Elementary get that message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love being around them,'' Ayanbadejo said. ``It brings
me down to earth. I'm in L.A., with the glitz and the glimmer, but
the kids are so innocent and natural. I think it's part of my
spirituality. It brings me back to a sense of who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   And buries the impression of what he might appear to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
