r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-CAN-WAIT-ECONOM     11-24 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CAN-WAIT-ECONOMY-RESEND-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET JAPAN; LET'S FOCUS ON A RECESSION CLOSER TO HOME  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending for those needing; moved 11-20)   (This insightful 1,000-word ``separate buy'' financial story is
from the November issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this
article, it must be purchased from New York Times sales
representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By JIM JUBAK  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Federal Reserve is the most powerful central bank in
the world. It can send stock markets around the world soaring or
crashing with merely a word, and wipe out or create billions of
dollars with a hint. But it cannot fix what ails Japan with any
number of interest-rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   That spells continued global economic trouble, since Japan is
the key to ending the economic slump in Asia. But the Fed believes
the current global financial and economic crisis is so serious that
even the recovery of the world's second-largest economy isn't the
most pressing problem of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the dilemma. Fed chairman Alan Greenspan and his
colleagues know that Japan is the key to global economic recovery.
But they also know that there's almost nothing they can do in the
short run to pull that country out of its paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   So the Fed has decided to put its muscle to work simply holding
the line in places like Brazil and the U.S. The hope is to prevent
a global recession _ even if that makes problems in Japan more
intractable.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is caught in what's called a liquidity trap, a kind of
economic black hole that shrugs off interest-rate reductions, huge
public-works programs, and even direct infusions of trillions of
yen.
</P>
<P>
   To fix the run-of-the-mill economic slowdown, a country's
government and central bank throw money at the problem. The
government adds to the country's money supply by running a budget
deficit _ funded by printing more dollars or yen or reals _ and
then puts that cash into the hands of businesses, which use it to
build roads or aircraft carriers or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   That creates demand for products from tar to tarmacs and, later,
for tires and shoes when the money trickles down to consumers in
the form of wages.
</P>
<P>
   An interest-rate cut by the central bank has much the same
effect. Lower rates makes it more attractive for banks to borrow
funds from the central bank _ which increases the money supply.
Lower rates encourage companies to borrow and expand and consumers
to put a few more dollars on their credit cards. That increases
demand and keeps the economy humming.
</P>
<P>
   Despite enough foot-dragging and posturing to get any sumo
wrestler booed out of Tokyo, the Japanese government has generally
followed that prescription recently. The government has thrown
trillions of yen into building roads.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent interest-rate cut by the Bank of Japan took the
official number down to a minuscule 0.25 percent: Banks can borrow
for what is effectively nothing. And last year the Bank of Japan
increased the country's money supply by more than 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But throwing money at the Japanese economy hasn't worked.
Business investment in the quarter that ran from April to June fell
by 9 percent from the same period a year earlier. The economy,
measured by gross domestic product, shrank by 0.8 percent in the
quarter and shows no signs of bottoming.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening to all the money that's being pumped into the
Japanese economy? It's getting stuffed into mattresses. Consumers,
for example, have increased their savings rate during this
downturn. This is characteristic of a liquidity trap.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are so scared about the future that they save every
cent they can. Businesses use every cent they can find to pay back
debt, since they worry that lenders will demand their money back
tomorrow. This behavior, of course, creates the very situation
businesses and consumers fear.
</P>
<P>
   The liquidity crunch has virtually paralyzed Japan's banking
system. What does a bank do right now when, thanks to the growth in
the money supply, it gets a credit to its account from the Bank of
Japan? It could make loans or even pay off some debt. Instead, most
Japanese banks are just keeping the money in reserve to meet the
demand for cash by Japanese households.
</P>
<P>
   A cut in U.S. interest rates won't fix Japan's liquidity problem
_ in fact, a cut could actually make it worse.
</P>
<P>
   Lower U.S. interest rates weaken the dollar and increase the
value of the yen, giving Japanese hoarders of yen one more reason
to hold on to their cash. And the Federal Reserve knows a U.S. rate
reduction makes it easier for the Japanese to avoid the painful
fundamental reforms needed to get the Japanese economy started on
the road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But those are minor issues for a Federal Reserve that is staring
at a global financial and economic crisis. Rate cuts may not help
Japan, but they should prevent the U.S. economy from slowing
further.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed cannot take the slightest risk of having the U.S. slide
into recession. The U.S. is one of only two growth engines left in
the world _ and is also the crucial market for the struggling
economies of Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   An interest-rate cut is the Fed's line in the sand _ the
recession stops here.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. interest-rate cut will also increase the pressure on
reluctant European central banks to follow suit. Greenspan would
prefer to make coordinated cuts with the Europeans. The Europeans,
however, have been resisting.
</P>
<P>
   Lower U.S. rates mean a cheaper U.S. dollar against the deutsche
mark, for example, and a more expensive currency spells trouble for
a country such as Germany, which is so heavily dependent on
exporting.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, preoccupied with their monetary union, may still
hold out, but they know the Federal Reserve is willing to act
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   There's no guarantee that even rate cuts by the Federal Reserve,
the Bundesbank, and the Bank of England can stop the spread of
crisis. Interest-rate cuts in the U.S. could re-ignite inflation
here and re-inflate the stock market bubble.
</P>
<P>
   If the Federal Reserve moves and the crisis deepens, the bank
will lose crucial psychological capital. But when you run the most
influential central bank in the world, you really don't have the
option of sitting out a crisis like this. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Jim Jubak is senior markets editor at Microsoft
Investor (www.investor.com), and a regular contributor of WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
