<HEADER>
A8034 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILIAN-BOOT-CAMP-NY     11-24 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILIAN-BOOT-CAMP-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE ALL THAT YOU CAN BE: GET INTO SHAPE AT `HELL LITE'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: D.C., Philadelphia, NYC, Los Angeles - 19th graf)   (This quirky 750-word ``separate buy'' story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from New
York Times sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.)  
  
 By RESHMA MEMON YAQUB  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 9 a.m., Jon Grossman, 43, is sitting behind a rosewood desk,
making weighty decisions about intellectual property, being called
``sir'' by the minions _ fitting for a partner in a major D.C. law
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours earlier, Jon Grossman was facedown in the dirt,
doing pushups as a drill instructor called him ``muffin ass.''
</P>
<P>
   The only weighty decision on Grossman's mind was whether he
could lift his sweaty carcass off the ground one more time so Sarge
would move on to torturing Hairy Legs, Ritalin, Honeybaby, or one
of the two dozen other boot campers _ including me _ sprawled
beside him who paid good money to enlist in the Sergeant's Program.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Hell Lite, also known as fitness boot camp for
civilians _ a regimen of outdoor, co-ed stretching, running, and
calisthenics led by former military personnel at an obscenely early
hour of day.
</P>
<P>
   Drill instructors spend three weeks bullying your body into
shape through hand-holding, butt-kicking, name-calling, and
encouragement. Your mission: to be all you used to be. And to pass
a modified military fitness test _ a ten-minute mile, 100 crunches,
50 push-ups, 35 bench dips, and four pull-ups.
</P>
<P>
   If you're among those who graduate (about half do), you move on
to an even more intensive program. If not, you reboot until you
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military drill instructor is the foremost known imposing
presence,'' says the Sarge, owner, instructor, and former naval
petty-officer Patrick Avon. ``And fear is an incredible
motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's motto sums up its philosophy: No music. No
dancing. No mirrors. No machines. No juice bars. No spandex. No
crybabies. No refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Sergeant's Program, which Avon has operated for nine
years in parks around Washington, D.C., is totally unlike joining a
gym or exercise class, where nobody knows if you show up, nobody
watches you work out, and nobody monitors your progress.
</P>
<P>
   The Sergeant's Program, which has about 650 enlistees and 25
instructors, takes its accountability for your body seriously.
Instructors call if you skip class. In fact, whole troops have been
known to show up at homes and offices to drag in MIAs.
</P>
<P>
   Drill instructors tell you how to eat. They show you the right
way to stretch, the right way to breathe when you run, the right
way to do push-ups. They watch you, correct you immediately when
you make mistakes, and they get you to do more than you'd ever do
on your own.
</P>
<P>
   That works for Jack Dolan, 35, a systems engineer from
Gaithersburg, Md. ``If I'm alone, I'll do 100 crunches,'' he says.
``If the instructor's there, he'll push and push and push until I
do 250. He yells at you and says, `Come on, man, you're better than
that!' And he does make you better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the pressure is on and the sweat is pouring, the
Sergeant's Program is also about having fun. Instructors keep
recruits smiling with hijinks, jokes, and plenty of verbal rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The sweaty masses of sleep-deprived survivors bond together,
too, in almost cult-like fashion. They coach one another in class.
Some become golf buddies outside class.
</P>
<P>
   And they learn how to be kids again. ``When children see a mud
puddle, they jump into it,'' says the 36-year-old Avon. ``When
40-year-olds see a mud puddle, they bitch about it. I get the
people who bitch about it and make them want to jump into it.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be in great shape to enlist. (But you will get
a health evaluation. And if you're over 40, you'll need a doctor's
note verifying that all parts are in working order.)
</P>
<P>
   Grossman couldn't do one unassisted pull-up when he started; a
couple of weeks later, he can do three. He used to falter after 40
crunches. Now 200 is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Basic training costs $345 for three weeks, five days a week, 45
minutes to an hour a day. (Plus running homework if your instructor
is particularly sadistic.) Maintenance and rebooting costs $80 to
$120 a month, depending on the duration of punishment you sign up
for.
</P>
<P>
   The Sergeant's Program has 18 sites around Washington, D.C. and
two in Philadelphia. Expect sites in New York and Los Angeles early
next year and other big cities later.
</P>
<P>
   For a preview of abuse: Drop, do 20, then log on to
www.sarge.com. To enlist, call 888-BOOT-CAMP. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Reshma Memon Yaqub is a staff writer at
WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this curious 750-word ``WORTH'' magazine article,
it must be purchased from New York Times sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
