<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIRTY-FRENCH-INDEPEND     11-24 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRTY-FRENCH-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: THE FRENCH DO NOT WASH  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 450-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By JOHN LICHFIELD  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It is official. The French do not wash.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one in two French people take a bath or shower every
day; the French buy less than half as much toilet soap as the
Germans and the British.
</P>
<P>
   This statistical manna to Francophobes everywhere is provided by
a series of studies carried out by the French government and
perfume and health industries.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures should, perhaps, be taken with a pinch of bath
salts. Personal experience on crowded Metro and Tube trains in
recent years suggests that the British smell more often, and worse,
than the French.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, that discrepancy can be explained by another
statistic. Although the French do not wash very much, they are
Europe's biggest consumers of perfume and deodorants.
</P>
<P>
   According to a synthesis of opinion polls and surveys published
Friday in Le Figaro, only 47 percent of French people take a shower
or bath every day, compared to 70 percent of Britons and 80 percent
of the fanatically clean Dutch, Germans and Scandinavians.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Italians wash more than the French, it seems. (The
cleanliness of the Spanish, Portuguese and Greeks is best
discreetly passed over.)
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are reinforced by a sad comment by a
near-anonymous French doctor (Dr. J.-F. H. of Saint Cloud). ``For
many of us (French doctors),'' he said, ``the deodorant spray is a
tool of the trade at least as important as the stethoscope.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. H., practicing in one of the wealthiest Paris suburbs,
complained that he dealt with unwashed bodies and dirty
underclothes every day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Edouard Zarifian, an eminent French medical psychologist,
explained the phenomenon this way. For the French, he said,
``eating and drinking are natural functions. Washing is not.''
</P>
<P>
   In the northern European countries and the United States, he
said, washing had long been associated with hygiene in the mind of
the public. In France and other Latin countries, it never had. Even
French doctors, he said, were very lax about washing their hands
after examining patients.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics gathered by Le Figaro suggest that the French buy
very little soap: 600 grams a year each, compared to 1,300 grams
for each German and a sparkling 1,400 grams for each Briton.
</P>
<P>
   However, these figures are for toilet soap only. They fail to
take account of the thrifty French habit of buying blocks of cheap,
kitchen soap to place in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of such evil-smelling soap are ten time higher in France.
Small wonder the French do not wash. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
