A8061 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINISTER-PHONES-US-IN     11-24 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINISTER-PHONES-US-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAL `M' FOR MADNESS: AMERICA'S INFURIATING TELEPHONY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 800-word ``separate buy'' article _ perfect for
commentary pages _ is from The Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phone rings, but nobody is there. Or rather, nobody human.
``A call is coming through for you,'' says a computer voice.
``Please don't hang up.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice sounds at once authoritative and almost comical:
evidently, the call has come through at such lightning velocity
that even the person who dialed the number is a few seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pause. A long pause. ``Please stay on the line,'' the
computer voice resumes. ``An agent will be with you shortly.'' An
agent? All of a sudden this doesn't sound so promising.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a seemingly innocent incoming business call
is threatening to turn into a clammy encounter with some
salesperson trying to flog household insurance or dental floss.
</P>
<P>
   There is a further pause. Finally, the computer voice announces:
``We are sorry, but all of our agents are unavailable.'' And the
line goes dead.
</P>
<P>
   No explanations. No chance to find out who inflicted this
infuriating tease on an unsuspecting telephone subscriber. Not even
an opportunity, as the law theoretically demands, to tell the
organization in question never to make such a call again, ever.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the hazards of telecommunication in modern-day America,
a place where computers are gradually taking over from human beings
and the poor human being, increasingly, is being given no right of
reply.
</P>
<P>
   For several years now _ and not just in America _ the phone user
has been confronted with a dizzying range of mechanized responses,
from home answering machines to voice mail to answering services.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who calls the switchboard of a medium-to-large
organization can expect to be talked through an often bewildering
range of options without ever encountering a live human voice.
(``For a full schedule of post-cosmetic surgery therapy classes,
press 5; to find out more about our rhinoplasty techniques teaching
seminar, press 8; to hear a review of these and other options,
press...'').
</P>
<P>
   In a country quaintly attached to the use of letters as well as
numbers on the telephone dialpad, the services of a receptionist
are rapidly being discarded in favor of recorded messages such as:
``If you know the name of the person you are calling, please dial
the first three letters of their name now.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are calling the company for the first time and don't have
any particular name at hand, all you can do is howl with
frustration or wait in the ever vainer hope that the computer will
eventually shut up to be replaced, as the jargon has it, by a
representative who will assist you shortly.
</P>
<P>
   These experiences are alienating enough, but the new trend in
U.S. telephony goes even further. Computers not only receive phone
calls; they make them, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wish to try our great range of household cleaning
products, please stay on the line while...'' Slam. ``Good morning!
Have you ever...'' Click.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it doesn't take more than a millisecond to pick up on
the mechanized sales patter and hang up, but every now and again
there is an opportunity to marvel at the sheer mechanical nuttiness
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parr-pp!'' blares a now-familiar sound on my answer machine,
apparently unprompted by any human agency. ``If you wish to make a
call, please hang up and try again. Parr-pp! If you wish to make a
call...''
</P>
<P>
   Even more insidious than the computers doing their pathetic best
to sound like human beings, though, are the human beings on the
line who sound disconcertingly like computers. These are the
telemarketers, the women (for they are almost always women) paid
some miserable piece rate to recite a carefully prepared list of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning sir I'd like to ask you a few questions about the
car you recently acquired was it a lease or a purchase what was the
make of the vehicle was it new or used how did you finance the
vehicle...''
</P>
<P>
   You could probably tell them you bought a space shuttle with a
stolen credit card and they wouldn't flinch. Any register of
emotion only slows them down and cuts into their pay rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you describe the experience of buying a car with
us?'' the marketer asked me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most horrendous experiences of my life,'' I
answered, truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   She barely skipped a syllable. ``And what color was the
vehicle?`` There was no getting around it. She had to get to the
bottom of her list, like a computer reading out all the options
before allowing you to return to the main menu.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone communication in America may be getting faster and
slicker, but old honest to goodness human contact seems to be going
seriously out of fashion. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this lively 800-word article, it must be purchased from
New York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New
York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINISTER-PHONES-US-IN     11-24 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINISTER-PHONES-US-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
