<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. LAWMAKERS WILLING TO TALK TO PATRIOTS OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH   AND TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Signaling an apparent new flexibility on behalf of
House members, Majority Leader William P. Nagle Jr. said Tuesday
that Democratic legislators stand ready to negotiate with New
England Patriots owner Robert Kraft if his plan to move the team to
Connecticut falls through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sense of the Democratic members is that there
would be some willingness to at least talk,'' Nagle said. ``I think
the fact that there would be discussions would be different, and I
think he should hear that the membership is interested in doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagle, the second most powerful man in the House after Speaker
Thomas M. Finneran, wouldn't say whether he was offering an olive
branch on behalf of his boss. Pressed repeatedly on whether
Finneran had authorized him to float the possibility of further
negotiations, Nagle said: ``I think the fact that I am saying it is
significant in itself. I am the number two guy in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran's philosophical opposition to using tax dollars to
support professional sports teams, as well as his power to
single-handedly block legislation, has been the team's biggest
obstacle to winning approval for a new stadium in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, who spoke with Nagle earlier Tuesday, insisted he has
been flexible all along on the stadium. However, he admitted that
Nagle's outreach _ particularly his insistence that ``almost
anything can be compromised'' _ struck a different tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is somewhat different than what you heard from me,''
Finneran conceded. ``There's no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Nagle emphasized that ``my position is the
speaker's position. We are on the same page, singing the same song
in the same church.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with some State House sources saying Finneran was
surprised Kraft signed a deal with Connecticut, and some House
members worrying about the long-term image of the House as a
chamber where representatives don't dare cross the speaker, Nagle
clearly wanted to signal a new stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think almost anything can be compromised,'' said Nagle, a
Northampton Democrat. ``I think there is a general interest in
trying to do something so that everybody's needs are met in
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Finneran has struck an antagonistic stance toward
Kraft, essentially saying the team owner would have to take a deal
on the speaker's terms. Asked Monday whether he would reconsider
his position on the stadium _ which at last offer was $57 million
in publicly-financed infrastructure along Route 1 in Foxborough _
Finneran first shrugged off questions. But later, turning to
several House members, he suggested that the House had little
interest in revisiting its stance.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the message from Nagle Tuesday, who said several
times that Democratic representatives want to find a way to keep
the team in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House would be interested in entering into some sort of
discussion,'' Nagle said. ``It would probably redefine the
parameters of what we have been discussing with Bob Kraft. There is
an opportunity for movement that I think is significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagle stressed that he didn't think the House would move on the
fundamental issue where Finneran has balked: Buying land that Kraft
owns around the current stadium and having Kraft lease it back from
the state.
</P>
<P>
   However, Nagle said he thought there were other ways to solve
Kraft's needs. ``There are a whole host of things that could be
looked at,'' he said. ``We could look at who owns the land and who
would acquire it.'' Nagle offered no further elaboration on that
point, saying he didn't want to negotiate in the pages of the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Patriots declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the memorandum of understanding that Kraft and
Governor John Rowland signed last Thursday, the team owner has
placed $2 million in an escrow account to show good faith that he
will not negotiate with another state until Dec. 31 or after the
Connecticut Legislature votes on the issue, whichever comes first.
Kraft would forfeit the money if he breaks the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani said Tuesday that legislators
could be called back to vote on the stadium proposal as early as
Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Finneran is taking a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ball is in the court of the Connecticut
Legislature,'' he said. ``But we never said never. That's not an
appropriate style of negotiations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
