<HEADLINE>
FOR NBA TALKS, NOT SO WONDERFUL A LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First, the National Basketball Association told NBC
to run ``It's a Wonderful Life'' instead of a Christmas Day
doubleheader, featuring the Bulls vs. the Knicks. Thus, the season
will not start until 1999. Bad news got worse for the league
Tuesday when the players withdrew their agreement of an escrow plan
_ a major issue in the five-month-old lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy commissioner Russ Granik sent a letter to Billy Hunter,
the union executive director, suggesting that Saturday's full
bargaining session in Manhattan be canceled. Earlier in the day,
Jeffrey Kessler, the union's chief outside counsel, told Granik
that there was a misunderstanding among the players of the escrow
tax proposal agreed upon during a 10-hour bargaining session
Friday. That apparent agreement was considered the most significant
progress in the 146-day lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are nowhere,'' Granik said Tuesday night. ``Whatever
progress we made on Friday is all but gone. If this is their
position, then I don't expect there to be a meeting on Saturday. I
accept it was a misunderstanding rather than any bad-faith
bargaining. But that doesn't help a lot. Based upon their not
accepting the tax, we're back to square one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter disputed Granik's contention that it would be futile to
hold a meeting Saturday. ``If the NBA is serious about making a
deal,'' Hunter said, ``they should stop posturing and come to the
bargaining table this Saturday with the goal of ending the lockout
and saving the season.''
</P>
<P>
   In NBC's first televised date of the season, the Knicks were
scheduled to play at Chicago and the Phoenix Suns were scheduled to
meet the Los Angeles Lakers in the second game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, NBC spokesman Ed Markey said, the network's
entertainment division has planned to show ``It's a Wonderful
Life.'' The network's next NBA telecast is regional coverage on
Saturday, Jan. 16. In the New York area, the Nets at Knicks would
be the featured game.
</P>
<P>
   Granik admitted that any thought of playing in December has been
lost. ``In light of these developments, there's no chance we start
before 1999,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The league has resisted issuing a deadline for canceling the
season, despite the suggestion made by the union on Friday. But no
agreement in principle by mid-December would severely jeopardize
the chance for playing an even 50-game season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them on Friday, `Let's set a date to cancel the season
on Wednesday,''' Kessler said. ``And we'll negotiate around the
clock for six days and see where were are. Our feeling is, whatever
deal we can make a month from now, we can make now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler added, referring to David Stern, ``But the commissioner
didn't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   What is now putting the season in jeopardy is an economic plan
discussed and tinkered with for the better part of a month, a plan
that may be days away from termination. Soon after reports of
progress emerged from Friday's meeting, the players said they would
not accept a proposal from the owners that dealt with the unlimited
signing of free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rule would force teams who sign another team's free
agent to give up the right to re-sign their own players under the
Larry Bird exception, which allows teams to pay the players
whatever they want. The proposed change to the ``timing rules'' was
shot down by many of the more than 100 players who took part in a
union conference call over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of several disagreements between the two sides, along
with the escrow tax. The players had agreed to put aside 10 percent
of their salaries at the beginning of the season in the fourth,
fifth and sixth years of a proposed-seven year deal. The escrow
fund would go toward paying back the owners if an agreed-upon
salary percentage had been exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can continue to be hopeful,'' Kessler added. ``We
believe the players have put more than enough on the table already.
The owners have to be irrational to cancel the season. But we can't
stop them from committing irrational acts.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked when the league would make the announcement, Granik
replied, ``We're going to do everything we can to resist that. But
someday in the not-too-distant future, we're going to turn around
and realize the season is lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said in a prepared statement: ``We strongly disagree with
Russ' statement that the parties made no progress at last Friday's
negotiating meeting. At that meeting, the players proposed an
additional method _ on top of what we already proposed _ to address
the owners' desire to obtain cost certainty. That new proposal and
the entire escrow framework remain on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
