<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS DISPUTE VACCO'S CLAIMS ABOUT DECEASED VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Democratic officials Tuesday bitterly assailed an
accusation that as many as 1,000 ballots might have been cast in
the race for state attorney general in the names of voters who had
died before the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation, from the campaign of Attorney General Dennis
Vacco, was also rejected by officials at the city Board of
Elections. They said Vacco's claims could not possibly be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Thomas Spargo, a lawyer for Vacco, told a state
Supreme Court justice that a series of computer searches conducted
by the Vacco campaign showed that ballots might have been cast in
Manhattan by 1,000 people listed as dead by the Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of their charges so far have been unfounded, I believe
this will be the same,'' said Jon Del Giorno, administrative
manager of the New York City office of the Board of Elections.
``All of their previous attempts to show that there have been
mistakes have not played out, I don't think this one will either.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state Board of Elections said Tuesday that Eliot
Spitzer, the Democratic challenger, was maintaining a lead of more
than 21,000 votes over Vacco, with less than 500 ballots left
uncounted, all from Erie County, and almost 22,000 paper ballots
set aside because of objections.
</P>
<P>
   Spargo said Tuesday that the Vacco campaign had compared the
Social Security Administration's list with ``a computerized active
list of voters'' in New York City. But the Board of Elections said
that its computerized records of voters who went to the polls Nov.
3 had not been compiled and would not be completed until next week.
</P>
<P>
   The only other method to determine whether fraudulent ballots
were cast using the names of dead people would be to compare names
from the Social Security Administration list with the signatures
written on the Board of Election books that voters must sign at
polling stations.
</P>
<P>
   Spargo said that the Vacco campaign had not begun to examine
those books until late Tuesday afternoon, a day after he made his
assertions before Justice Thomas Keegan. The judge, while
expressing dismay about the delays in determining the election's
outcome, allowed the Vacco campaign a few more days to look through
voting records to clarify the claims of voting irregularities.
Vacco's lawyers were instructed to return to court Monday to
present their findings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Spargo said he was uncertain of precisely what computer list the
Vacco campaign had secured from the Board of Elections or of the
period in which that information was compiled. ``My understanding
is that it is an overall list of voters in New York City, an active
voter list,'' he said. He said the Social Security Administration
data were supplied by a vendor hired by the Vacco campaign and
included a list of names and birth dates of people for whom death
benefits had been paid.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Herman Farrell, the Democratic Party chairman in
Manhattan, said that it would not be unusual for the names of more
than 1,000 dead people to appear on voter rolls. ``But that doesn't
mean that anyone voted in the names of those people,'' Farrell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Spitzer campaign reacted strongly to Vacco's charges
Tuesday. ``This is becoming like a horror movie starring Dennis
Vacco,'' said Steven Goldstein, a spokesman for Spitzer's campaign.
``The title would be: `The Attorney General Who Lost and Would Not
Leave.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
