<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-LEASE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEASE DOESN'T BLOCK NETS' MOVE TO NEWARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets, whose owners would like to move to a
proposed arena in downtown Newark, now have a better lease at their
current home through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The lease, made public Tuesday, significantly alters the Nets'
revenue stream, but imposes stiff penalties on the team if it moves
from New Jersey. The lease lets the team move anywhere it wants
after the 1999-2000 season, with six months' notice. If it moves to
Newark, there is no financial penalty, because the state is
expected to play some financial role at that facility.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Nets leave the state, it would pay the New Jersey
Sports and Exposition Authority $15 million after next season, $10
million after the 2000-1 season, $7.5 million after the 2001-2
season and $5 million after the 2002-3 season. For the final four
years of the lease, no fines would be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   The lease was written so that the sports authority has time to
study whether to overhaul Continental Arena, or build another arena
in its place at the Meadowlands Sports Complex in East Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a satisfying lease,'' said Michael Rowe, the Nets'
president, ``because it recognizes our desire to relocate to
Newark, but gives the sports authority time to show us whether the
Meadowlands is the best place for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lease that binds us, but gives us time to reach a
long-term solution on an arena,'' said John Samerjan, the sports
authority's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The lease will require the Nets to pay the sports authority rent
based on 2 percent to 5 percent of gross ticket receipts, depending
on attendance, down from a range of 10.5 percent to 25 percent in
the previous lease.
</P>
<P>
   The team will also receive 40 percent of gross luxury box
revenues (up from 25 percent), 100 percent of net parking receipts
(up from 50 percent) and 100 percent of the sports authority's
share of concessions (up from 50 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The team will also keep 60 to 70 percent of the revenues from
advertisements posted in new locations in the arena, and be
reimbursed $2.5 million by the sports authority for nearly all the
costs of a new practice facility.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe would not estimate how much greater the Nets' revenues will
be. ``The authority's acting as a partner, not a landlord,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By not blocking a Newark move, Rowe said, ``The authority is
acting as a New Jersey sports authority, not an East Rutherford
sports authority.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2233EST &QL; 
