<HEADLINE>
CIA DENIES WITHHOLDING REPORTS ON RUSSIAN CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The CIA said Tuesday that it had provided many
reports on the corruption of senior Russian officials to the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The agency strongly denied that its analysts had censored
themselves after concluding that senior administration officials
did not want evidence of corruption to obstruct doing business with
the Russian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have published numerous pieces on corruption in the Russian
government over the past several years and up to the present,'' a
spokesman for the agency, Bill Harlow, said. ``We do not withhold
reports because they are inconvenient.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was a response to an article on Monday in The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Some CIA officials, the article reported, said important
administration officials had been dismissive of intelligence
reports about the corruption of Russian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, the analysts said, included former Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Anatoly Chubais, who was until recently
considered by administration officials to be an important leader in
the field of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA said Tuesday that its analysts had continued to provide
reports on high-level Russian corruption, no matter how they were
received by administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Officials acknowledged frequent tensions between the agency and
policy makers over the reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to remain independent in the face of political
pressure is a sensitive issue for agency officials. Political
pressure on the intelligence community is a recurring theme in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The debate may have reached a high point in the battle in 1991
over the nomination of Robert Gates to be director of central
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, who had been deputy director of the CIA in the Reagan
administration, came under fire during Senate hearings because of
allegations that he had sought to tailor intelligence reports on
the Soviet Union to fit the Reagan administration's conservative
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Gates was confirmed as director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
