<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE COMMISSIONER WANTS OUT, SOURCES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt,
who has presided over declining auto and workers' compensation
rates and a series of hot-button controversies in her 5 1/2 years
in the job, wants to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Two people close to Governor Paul Cellucci said Ruthardt
informed the governor's office in the last few days of her desire
to leave. Both sources, who did not indicate when the commissioner
planned to depart, said she had not been asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
   A Ruthardt spokesman denied she was leaving. ``There is no truth
to the rumor, and I cannot substantiate your sources of
information,'' said Christopher Goetcheus, a spokesman for the
Division of Insurance. Ruthardt declined to comment. A Cellucci
spokesman said the governor's office would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt is hardly the only change in the offing as the Cellucci
administration starts to focus in earnest on its new term. The top
jobs at the departments of environmental affairs and public safety
are open. Administration insiders say there could be an unusual
amount of shifting of key personnel in the term.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci sources said there was no obvious choice to replace
Ruthardt, whose salary is $86,580 a year. One name mentioned was
Julie Bowler, Ruthardt's first deputy. But Bowler, seen as close to
new Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift, lacks heavy insurance
experience, having arrived at the division only this summer from
the department of Medicaid assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt has been a good-news, bad-news insurance commissioner
for the Weld and Cellucci administrations.
</P>
<P>
   During her tenure, the state has seen unprecedented drops in
auto and workers' compensation insurance rates. Auto rates have
fallen four years in a row, with the average Massachusetts driver
today paying $798 for insurance, or $120 less a year than in 1994,
Ruthardt's first full year in office. Workers' comp rates have been
nearly cut in half in five years.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruthardt has also been involved in an unusual number of
high-profile dustups and been the subject of barrage of complaints,
mainly that she conducted too much business behind closed doors and
tried to thwart access to public documents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the state attorney general, citing ``ethical issues''
raised by the division's conduct, took the rare step of refusing to
defend her in a dispute with a consumer group over the
demutualization of a Worcester insurer. In another case, she
quickly approved a Massachusetts insurer's move to Bermuda, only to
have the company file for liquidation a few months later; that move
touched off an embarrassing series of reversals that dragged on in
the courts for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently Ruthardt has been criticized by the attorney
general and consumer groups for a private meeting she held with an
insurance industry executive just before the current round of auto
rate hearings was to begin. Her longtime head of the State Rating
Bureau, the division unit that helps sets rates, criticized
Ruthardt as being too cozy with the industry and too ready to serve
the political interests of Weld and Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance job is always tough because it deals with
pocketbook issues that effect consumers. And administrations are
loathe to second guess insurance commissioners because the issues
are arcane and technical. But her style has dogged her in a way
that hasn't other commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Said one Cellucci insider Tuesday: ``She was regarded as
well-intentioned and honest, but she lacks certain personal and
public relations skills. And that hurt her.''
</P>
<P>
   The next commissioner will have no bigger job than overseeing
the complex demutualization of John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance
Co. The process of cashing out current policyholders and selling
shares of the company to the public could take up to two years, and
is sure provoke questions over whether the insurer's surplus is
being divided equitably.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
