<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS OFFER MAY REACH 8 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox, demonstrating anew Mo Vaughn's maxim that
when they really want a player, they pull out all the stops to sign
him, were hopeful Tuesday night that their seven-year offer to
Bernie Williams would be enough to land the free agent center
fielder.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette, after two days of meetings in
Atlanta with Williams and his agent, Scott Boras, returned home
Tuesday to Boston, where he was expected to update CEO John
Harrington. On Monday, Duquette made a seven-year offer in the
neighborhood of $80 million for the American League's reigning
batting champion, and there were indications that the Sox would
consider adding an eighth year as an option, which could make
Williams's deal the biggest to date in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It also could seal the deal quickly, maybe even by Thursday,
though Boras said Tuesday there are still five teams interested in
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question Dan Duquette came down here with the right
arsenal to demonstrate that Boston is sincere about Bernie
Williams,'' said Boras, who refused to discuss specifics of the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams joined Duquette in Atlanta and met
with the outfielder for four hours, and Duquette apparently made a
compelling argument to Bernie Williams to leave his incumbent team,
the New York Yankees, and join the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, of course, was more persuasive than Duquette's
willingness to offer a deal that obliterated the five-year, $63
million offer the Sox made to Vaughn, who turned that down and
subsequently was told that the Sox would negotiate no further.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Yankees have not budged from their refusal to offer
a seven-year contract to Williams, who in Tuesday's editions of the
Bergen (N.J.) Record questioned how much the Yankees want to retain
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't perceive them having a lot of interest,'' he said.
``They keep saying I'm their top priority, but when it really comes
down to it, they don't show it. I guess that's just part of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees apparently have decided to pursue free agent left
fielder Albert Belle instead, and likely will make a trade for a
center fielder, having already talked to the Montreal Expos about
Rondell White. The Anaheim Angels, once they sign Vaughn, also
appear willing to deal Jim Edmonds for a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were indications Tuesday night that the Yankees were
attempting another meeting with Williams and Boras. Last week, the
agent had two days of talks with Yankees owner George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks, whose manager, Buck Showalter, is
close with Williams from their days together with the pre-Joe Torre
Yankees, also are a major player. How far the Diamondbacks are
willing to go on Williams, however, may hinge on whether they can
sign free agent pitcher Randy Johnson. If they sign Johnson, it's
unlikely they would push for Williams, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles expressed interest in Williams, too, but they are
expected to retain free agent first baseman Rafael Palmeiro and
have indicated that Williams's price tag is beyond what they're
willing to spend. If there is indeed a fifth bidder, that team has
yet to surface publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, speaking from his Easton home Tuesday, reiterated that
he expected to sign ``very soon'' with the Angels, who made a
six-year proposal for $72 million that could be worth closer to $80
million if incentives and performance bonuses were met.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something will happen,'' Vaughn said. ``I can't say
today, but very soon, though. I think something is going to go down
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he knows of no other team that has made an offer for
him, and that given the way the Angels have treated him, he could
not envision signing with a last-second bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, it would be kind of unfair if something was put
forth by somebody else, to take that, unless this thing falls off
the face of the earth,'' Vaughn said. ``They've been very
straightforward with me, showed faith in me, and straight up the
whole time. That's definitely something I'm not used to, and it's
definitely been real nice. I feel myself pretty much excited, with
a chance to do a lot of good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never interested in pitting one team against the other.
I think Anaheim can be a great situation. For anybody to come in
the back door doesn't mean much right now. Anaheim, from 9 o'clock
in the morning on the first day of free agency, showed themselves,
and that's important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has had conversations with Johnson, urging him
to sign with the Angels, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' Vaughn said. ``We've been talking. We have a lot
of respect for each other, and we've been talking. We've both
expressed interest in being together. Will it happen? I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that the Sox have offered at least seven years to Williams,
Vaughn said, ``It's like I've always said. The Red Sox sign the
players they want to sign. But I hold no grudges. I had some great
years here, but it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams would play center field and bat third in front of Nomar
Garciaparra in a revised Red Sox lineup that also would feature a
new leadoff hitter, Jose Offerman, with John Val-entin expected to
bat second. The Red Sox already have a center fielder, Darren
Lewis, who signed a three-year, $7 million deal earlier this month
expecting to return to center. Lewis played some right field last
season, too, but Williams's signing would seem to make him
expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette had said last week that the Sox would be adding a
couple of pitchers by now. Instead of offering a contract to free
agent Armando Reynoso, Duquette requested more medical information
on the righthander, who passed a physical with the Diamondbacks and
was offered a two-year deal for $5.5 million, with an option for a
third year.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also have talked to Boras about another client,
righthander Tim Belcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
