<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-PERMITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS SAY CITY PLAYING POLITICS WITH PARADE PERMITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration is wielding its power to
grant or deny permits for parades, marches and protests as a
political weapon, contend several groups that say they have
struggled to get permits.
</P>
<P>
   The administration vehemently denies the charge, asserting that
hundreds of permits are awarded each year by police and parks
officials without regard to the applicants' identities or messages.
</P>
<P>
   But the groups say that to secure permits for demonstrations
that are at odds with the administration's political views, they
have had to agree to curtail their criticism, stage the events at
remote locations or sue the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's selective and it's politically selective,'' said Sara
Flounders, a coordinator with the International Action Center,
which has fought to get permits to protest against American
military interventions. ``Everything is done to discourage us.''
Her organization, she said, had to threaten to go to federal court
before it was granted a city permit to demonstrate in Times Square
against American bombing in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Three groups _ cabdrivers, organizers of the Million Youth March
and an organization that fights police brutality _ successfully
sued in federal court earlier this year to remove city
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   And in the latest ruling, a federal judge ordered the city on
Tuesday to allow Housing Works, an AIDS service group, to march
down Broadway and to hold an event at City Hall to commemorate
World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
   The city, voicing concerns over security and the cost of the
police, denied permits for the demonstrations. But the judge ruled
that the city had undercut its own arguments by staging much larger
events recently, with far greater security risks and police costs _
like the ticker tape parades and City Hall ceremonies for the
Yankees and for Sen. John Glenn. Housing Work said its parade would
draw 1,000 people; police estimated 3.5 million people attended the
Yankee parade.
</P>
<P>
   In the three earlier cases heard in federal court, judges
criticized the way the city handled parade and rally permits. One
judge suggested that the city's efforts this fall to prevent the
October 22d Coalition from marching down Broadway to protest police
brutality had more to do with the group's message than with the
police department's stated traffic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to say conclusively whether political interference
plays a role in the permit process. The administration says that
all it has tried to suppress is public disorder by insuring that
demonstrations are safe and do not clog city arteries.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Bronx borough president's office said the city
raised bogus concerns about police manpower and traffic in 1996 to
discontinue a tradition of converting a section of the Grand
Concourse into a pedestrian mall on Sundays. Borough President
Fernando Ferrer said the permit denial was based on his own
political antagonism with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, members of the Million Marijuana March, a group
that seeks the legalization of that drug, have accused parks
officials of conspiring to block their rally from Washington Square
Park this year.
</P>
<P>
   The group has staged a rally, calling it a smoke-in, for more
than two decades, usually in Washington Square. But officials,
supported by many community residents, contend that the event,
which is usually accompanied by widespread marijuana smoking and
dozens of arrests, has grown too large and rowdy for that site and
should be moved to Battery Park.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Parks Commissioner Henry Stern wrote the group a
letter saying applications for 1998 park permits would not be
accepted before January. But when the group showed up in January
with its application, officials said their traditional date, May 2,
had been claimed weeks earlier by a neighborhood family
association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
