<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX     11-24 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO START THINKING FANTASY BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox Sports Online is launching a Winter Fantasy Baseball league
using statistics from the past Major League Baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   The tough part: Fox Sports Online will use complete statistics
from ``random'' games that were played the past season. That means
fantasy managers won't be able to load their rosters with Mark
McGwire, Sammy Sosa or Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   And that means more chance than strategy in this 54-game league.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our winter league, you don't have to be as hard-core _
you're not following 162 games,'' said Laura Sigman of Fox Sports
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Online is banking on NBA and NHL fans, as well as
baseball fans, to pluck down $19.95 and play Winter Fantasy
Baseball (www.baseballmanager.com).
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Online is teaming with GameLine, operators of the
Baseball Manager, for the game, which concludes its open enrollment
Monday. Baseball Manager was selected Best Fantasy Site on the Web
by ``Yahoo! Internet Life'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   With Winter Fantasy Baseball, fantasy managers will be allowed
to draft players, set lineups and pitching rotations and
participate in trading and free-agent signings.
</P>
<P>
   Membership fees will also give managers access to exclusive
content including daily personalized winter-theme news headlines,
as well as box scores, league standings, league leaders and
statistics, and membership a bulletin board forum where fantasy
baseball managers can meet and discuss the season with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Even if chance is more a part of the game, Sigman said the
league performed well in beta-testing by GameLine.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the (NBA) lockout and the kind of year that baseball had,
it's a great time to launch it,'' Sigman said. &QL; 
Bytes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   News in hand: Do you own a handheld computer? Well, here's a
good reason to own one: The Sporting News Online
(www.sportingnews.com) has announced an agreement with San Mateo,
Calif.-based AvantGo Inc. to deliver sports news free to handheld
computer users. The Sporting News Online will provide content
updated hourly; AvantGo makes the software that accesses the data
from a handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   Polls of the week: The NBA lockout will last longer than the
marriage between Chicago Bulls forward Dennis Rodman and
``Baywatch'' star Carmen Electra, according to 60 percent of 22,001
respondents in an ESPN.com poll. The two were married Nov. 14.
According to a CNN/SI.com poll, 31 percent (7,773 of 24,820)
predict the marriage will last only one month. Twelve percent said
the marriage will last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Night update: Ten years after H.G. ``Buzz'' Bissinger's
book, ``Friday Night Lights,'' cast a critical eye on football
fanaticism at Odessa Permian High School, ESPN revisited Odessa
earlier this month to see how the book affected the community.
ESPN.com writer Greg Garber wrote a four-part companion piece that
can be accessed on ESPN.com
(espn.sportszone.com/gen/columns/fridaynight).
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
