<HEADLINE>
TCU, OKLAHOMA WON'T PLAY IN '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU athletic director Eric Hyman said
yesterday that TCU has released Oklahoma from a football contract
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said he received the written request via fax yesterday,
although, discussions have been going on since July.
</P>
<P>
   The game is likely to be rescheduled for either the 2004 or 2005
season, said Horned Frogs director of football operations Charley
North.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's departure leaves TCU with nine games under contract
for next season. TCU has seven Western Athletic Conference games
and two nonconference games against Arizona on Sept. 4 and
Northwestern on Sept. 11. The Arizona game is being tentatively
discussed as the Thursday night ESPN game.
</P>
<P>
   Because they travel to Hawaii, NCAA rules allow TCU to play a
12th game.
</P>
<P>
   TCU has three open dates, two of which look to be occupied by
Arkansas State and North Texas. A contract has been received on the
Arkansas State game (Sept. 25).
</P>
<P>
   North Texas is likely to occupy the open date on either Nov. 13
or Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a pretty good mix of games. Arizona is going
to be a Top 10 team and maybe go to the Rose Bowl,'' Horned Frogs
coach Dennis Franchione said. ``I'm pretty excited so far.''
Nothing from OU
</P>
<P>
   Franchione said he hasn't been contacted about interviewing for
the Oklahoma job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered to be mentioned,'' Franchione said, ``but I
haven't been contacted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Oklahoman has reported that Franchione was a
candidate. It quoted Hyman in Monday's editions as saying he could
``neither confirm nor deny'' whether he had been contacted for
permission to interview Franchione.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said yesterday not to read too much into that statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my policy to defer those questions to the coach or the
school,'' Hyman said.
Two Frogs make all-WAC
</P>
<P>
   TCU linebacker Joseph Phipps and place-kicker Chris Kaylakie
were selected to the Mountain Division first team as the Western
Athletic Conference released its all-conference selections.
</P>
<P>
   Phipps finished the season with 153 tackles, including a
school-record 95 solo tackles. Kaylakie connected on 15 of 20
field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The second team included six Horned Frogs: offensive linemen
Michael Keathley and Russ Sanders, running backs Basil Mitchell and
LaDainian Tomlinson, defensive end Aaron Schobel and defensive back
Reggie Hunt (DB).
</P>
<P>
   TCU's honorable-mention picks were J.W. Wilson and Curtis
Fuller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
