<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST YEAR'S HERO HOPES TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a glass case in Mark Cusano's house that
contains the football he intercepted in the final minutes of USC's
victory over Notre Dame last season. Right next to it is a framed
letter he received from Notre Dame, when he was a high school
senior.
</P>
<P>
   These are the possessions he cherishes, and why no other player
at USC would enjoy the moniker ``Mr. Notre Dame killer'' quite as
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the hex. He's our Notre Dame hero,'' linebacker Chris
Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the senior linebacker ended USC's winless streak
against Notre Dame at 13 years when he batted down Ron Powlus'
fourth-down pass to preserve the Trojans' 27-20 victory in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cusano intercepted a Powlus pass with 2:34 left and
returned the ball 27 yards to set up the game-winning field goal in
USC's 20-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest moment of my life,'' Cusano said. ``As a
player, as anything, I don't think there's anything that's felt
better.''
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for beating the Irish is so revered, that some
USC fans have taken snapshots with Cusano pointing to the spot on
his arm where he deflected Powlus' pass in '96.
</P>
<P>
   No other USC player seems to relish playing Notre Dame like
Cusano, who always dreamed of playing for the Irish but never
received more than that single recruiting letter.
</P>
<P>
   It's sort of a payback each season for Cusano, who has grown to
dislike nearly every aspect of the Trojans' rival. Those feelings
began to peak when Cusano made his first visit to South Bend with
the Trojans when he was a freshman in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a dream of mine to finally be standing there. It took
my breath away,'' Cusano said. ``Then the little leprechaun started
yelling at us. I heard the fans and I instantly hated them. Tempers
flared on the field. I wanted to beat them more than anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about how I wanted to come to Notre Dame and now I want
to prove to them that I'm a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished. But as Cusano enters his final encounter
with Notre Dame, there's doubts about whether he'll even be on the
field enough to make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Cusano has been plagued by injuries since the Trojans opened
camp at UC Irvine. First, there was a hamstring injury. That was
followed by a sprained ankle and a pulled thigh muscle. He's played
in just eight games and started only one. He has 13 tackles this
season, the worst output of his four-year career. Before this
season, his lowest total was 50 tackles as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the most difficult year of my life, dealing with
football,'' Cusano said. ``I've never had injuries before and it's
been a learning experience. It's definitely frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   To add insult to the injuries, Cusano has been healthy the past
four weeks but has played sparingly since he lost his starting job
to sophomore Zeke Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a huge disappointment to him and to me,''
USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``If your body will not allow you to
go, you can't let yourself fall apart. Mark has dealt with these
issues. It's the toughest part of the profession to see a young
person taken out of what they love to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It got even tougher against UCLA last week. After starting
outside linebacker David Gibson injured his thigh and left the
game, Cusano merely shared time with freshman Darryl Knight. He'll
be in a similar spot this week if Gibson is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been performing at the level of the three guys that
are ahead of me. I can't really ask for anything,'' Cusano said.
``I feel I'm doing my assignments, but I haven't done the extra
thing. Great players make great plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his role has been reduced, his teammates expect
something might happen, given his history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be hyped,'' Claiborne said. ``He's fought through a lot
of things this year. It would great if he had a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusano can describe his Notre Dame moments as if they just
happened. He remembers immediately after the '96 game, looking up
at the big video screen at the Coliseum. He could see former Notre
Dame coach Lou Holtz, his one-time idol, dejected after his final
college game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see him squatted down on the sideline, and he put
his headphones down. You could see defeat in his posture,'' Cusano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cusano said he's not thinking much about his success against
Notre Dame because he just wants to get decent playing time after
spending most of the previous four games on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've done in the past is the past. You're only
remembered for what you've done lately,'' Cusano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
