<SLUG> BC-$100MILLION-GIFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA LAW SCHOOL GIFT NOW AT $100 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon enough, officials at the University of Arizona are going to
just get it over with and rename the school Rogers University.
</P>
<P>
   Alumnus James E. Rogers on Tuesday became one of the largest
benefac tors in the history of higher education, donating $100
million to the UA law school. The gift will likely grow to $130
million, with $15 million of that total going to the general use of
the university.
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable gift not only for its size, one of the five
largest ever in American academia, but also for the lack of strings
attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some very sophisticated written documents from Mr.
Rogers that basically say the dean has the `total discretion' to
spend the gift however he sees fit,'' UA law school dean Joel
Seligman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Board of Regents voted last week to rename the UA
law school after Rogers. Some students grumbled that the honor
should have been reserved for a more noted graduate rather than a
wealthy benefactor, but even outspoken faculty members have been
impressed by the sincere generosity of Rogers' gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``His money will clearly have an influence, but he personally
has not sought to have any,'' said Professor Andy Silverman. ``I,
too, would be leery of someone who gave that much money wanting to,
in a sense, buy a law school, and dictate what goes on there. If he
is pulling strings in the background, I don't sense it, and I don't
know anyone on the faculty who does.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said his aims are simple: He wants to give 80 percent of
his fortune to higher education, and he particularly wants to
support the law school that launched him to such a lucrative
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunes come to people for a lot of strange reasons,'' Rogers
said. ``Just a lot of fortuitous occurences have to come together
for you to say, `wow, look at all the zeroes after that one on my
balance sheet.' I know I have it, but I don't feel particularly
like I earned it. Now I want to put it to good use.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is the former law partner of Louis Weiner, who was lawyer
to Las Vegas casino pioneer Bugsy Siegel. He is also president of
Sunbelt Communications Co., which owns eight television stations
across the West, including one in Yuma. He received a bachelor's
degree in accounting from UA in 1960 and graduated from the law
school in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers made history in April when he announced that he was
giving $20 million to the UA law school. It was the largest gift
ever made to a law school, beating the previous record of $15
million. Then, in September, Rogers announced that he was
increasing the gift to $50 million. On Tuesday, he increased it
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' Rogers said. ``This has always been
contemplated, that we would maybe do two things. That we would
provide a gift during my lifetime, then pay money into an endowment
where it would keep earning income in perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier $50 million in gifts will be paid out over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement calls for the creation of an endowment
after Rogers, 60, has died, and his Las Vegas television station,
KVBC, is sold. In addition, he pledged $15 million to match each
dollar that might be raised from alumni, students or friends of the
law school. Rogers also pledged $15 million from his endowment to
be used by any programs at the university other than the law
school.
</P>
<P>
   Seligman said he and a faculty committee are still trying to
figure out how to spend the money, but the first priority will be
to keep tuition from rising. Law school tuition has almost tripled
at the UA law school in the last five years, to about $5,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   He said the law school will use Rogers' gift to create separate
endowments to underwrite individual professorships, a key factor in
attracting and retaining top faculty, upgrade the holdings of the
law library, offer more financial aid to incoming students, and
improve the legal research and writing program.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he hopes that with his financial support, lawyers
just getting started will not be saddled with debt from student
loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give students the ability to serve people any way
they want to,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin Van Der Werf can be reached at 444-4421 or at
martin.vanderwerf(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
