<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS, AUTHOR BACK TEACHER ON BOOK THAT PARENTS CALL RACIALLY
INSENSITIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ School officials Tuesday backed a white third-grade
teacher's use of what black parents asserted was a racially
insensitive book, but the teacher said she feared returning to her
classroom because of threats from parents.
</P>
<P>
   School officials reassigned the teacher, Ruth Sherman, 27, after
a raucous public meeting Monday at Public School 75 in the Bushwick
section of Brooklyn in which parents denounced her for assigning a
critically acclaimed book titled ``Nappy Hair'' by Carolivia
Herron, a black writer and scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and community organizers said they had received
photocopies of pages from ``Nappy Hair,'' about an African-American
girl coming to terms with her hair, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Told in a gospel-like, call-and-response style, the book is
about a little girl with the ``nappiest, fuzziest, the most screwed
up, squeezed up, knotted up'' hair. It received positive reviews,
including one from The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Davis, a spokesman for the United Federation of Teachers,
said he believed parents who were angry had not read the entire
book. ``Some parents saw only a few pages, taken out of context,''
or heard the title.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Community School Board 32, Dennis Herring, said
the photocopies gave a false impression of what the book's
illustrations were trying to convey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pages were copied from the book and there was no
background information explaining how it was meant, it looks like
pictures to degrade African-Americans. The way it looks in black
and white is different from the way it looks in the book,'' Herring
said.
</P>
<P>
   District Superintendent Felix Vazquez determined Tuesday that
the book, recommended by instructors at Teachers College at
Columbia University, was not inappropriate, but that Ms. Sherman
should have cleared its use with Principal Felicita Santiago, said
J.D. LaRock, a spokesman for the city's Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, the uproar had diminished, because more parents had
reviewed the book in full, said Herring, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herron, an assistant professor of English at California
State University at Chico, said on Tuesday that she was shocked to
learn that Ms. Sherman had been assigned to a desk job because
parents had protested her assigning ``Nappy Hair'' as
extracurricular reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me deeply in the heart,'' said Ms. Herron.
</P>
<P>
   As a scholar at Harvard in the mid-1980s, Ms. Herron specialized
in the epic poetry of Homer, Dante and Milton. Fascinated by its
parallels with her family's oral tradition, she taped her Uncle
Richard's story about her own hair, told to her as a child in the
back yard at family feasts, and turned it into the book ``Nappy
Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Sherman called her Monday night, Ms. Herron said, ``She
wanted to know what was going on _ did she make a mistake?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here she was a teacher doing what many don't have the nerve to
do, to bring to her students books of their own culture,'' Ms.
Herron said. ``I admire what she desired to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Isoke T. Nia, director of research and development at the
Teachers College Reading and Writing Project at Columbia
University, said she was dismayed by the parents' reaction to the
book.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nia, who is black, said she has recommended the book to
hundreds of teachers for two years at summer training institutes
and will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to talk to the parents and ask them, `What is it
about your hair that you are offended by?''' she said. ``There are
things that blacks say in their homes about their hair and this is
bringing it to the public. I'm surprised, astonished and appalled.
A line from the book says a lock of the child's hair is the only
perfect circle. What's so bad about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sherman said that she was uncertain whether she would return
to the classroom on Monday, after the Thanksgiving break, because
parents and leaders of community groups had threatened her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not angry,'' Ms. Sherman said in an interview Tuesday. ``I
just wish that the children were more of concern. My children lost
two days of instruction at a very important time of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
