<SLUG> BC-NY-PAROLE-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PAROLE OFFICIAL CHARGED IN INFLUENCE INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors have charged that a former
official of the State Parole Board tried to hamper their
investigation into whether the campaign of Gov. George Pataki
promised favors to inmates in return for political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In a criminal complaint unsealed in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn late Tuesday, the official, Ronald Hotaling, was accused
of lying to a grand jury and an investigator about a case before
the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves a teen-age gang member, John Kim, who was
freed by the board at the earliest possible date after serving time
for violent felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's father is a Korean-American minister in Queens who secured
the help of a Pataki aide to win his release and contributed $1,000
to the Pataki campaign. Others connected to the minister donated
several thousand dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   Senior aides to the governor, who controls the parole board,
have repeatedly said the board did not give special treatment to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling, 51, served as special assistant to the parole board
until late 1996, when he was dismissed along with several other
staff members, a move that was unrelated to the current
investigation, officials said. In his job, he scheduled cases for
board members, who work in three-person teams traveling to prisons
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling, who began working for the parole board in 1970, is the
second official to be charged in the federal inquiry. Last month,
prosecutors announced an eight-count indictment against a member of
the parole board, Sean McSherry, who was also accused of lying to a
grand jury about the Kim case.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling pleaded innocent Tuesday to one count of obstruction of
justice, which has a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison. He was
released on a $10,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal complaint says Hotaling at first repeatedly told an
investigator that he had never spoken to McSherry and another
commissioner about the Kim case. It says he ``denied receiving
communications about special interests in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   But in September, he confessed that he had lied, ``among other
reasons, to protect the integrity of the parole board,'' the
complaint says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
