<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PONZI-SCHEME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BROTHER GUILTY IN BENNETT FUNDING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks before the chief financial officer of the
Bennett Funding Group is to stand trial on charges that he bilked
investors out of hundreds of millions of dollars, his brother
admitted in court Tuesday that they conspired to thwart a federal
investigation into their company.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bennett, 41, pleaded guilty to perjury, obstruction of
justice and conspiracy before U.S. District Judge Thomas Griesa.
Bennett faces up to 15 years in prison and $750,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has not agreed to testify against his brother, Patrick
Bennett, and was not motivated by a hope that prosecutors would
seek a lenient sentence, said his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bennett has been charged with 100 counts of fraud, money
laundering, perjury, conspiracy and obstruction of justice in what
prosecutors have called the biggest Ponzi scheme in American
history. He has pleaded innocent and is scheduled to go on trial
Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 investors, most of them retirees looking for a safe
place to put their money, lost more than $600 million by investing
in Bennett Funding Group, according to prosecutors. Ponzi schemes
work by funneling the investments of later investors to earlier
participants to fool the early investors into believing their
investments have been successful, while other money may be diverted
to those running the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers were officers of Bennett Funding, a company based
in Syracuse that claimed to be in the business of financing leases
of office equipment like copiers.
</P>
<P>
   Both were important figures in Syracuse's business,
philanthropic and political circles. Patrick Bennett bought the
local racetrack; Michael Bennett, the deputy chief executive, was
praised for his work in partly restoring the landmark Hotel
Syracuse. He was a major fund-raiser for Gov. George Pataki's 1994
campaign. He has recently been living in Virginia, ``trying to work
_ not in the leasing or financing business,'' his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, Michael Bennett was cheerful and talkative,
chatting with lawyers and reporters about the television show
``Ally McBeal,'' some of which takes place in a courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   His voice broke when he told the judge that, in 1996, at his
brother's behest, he had lied to the federal Securities and
Exchange Commission. Investigators there were looking into what
they contend was a fake deal designed to trick Bennett Funding's
accountants _ and some investors _ into thinking the company was in
good health.
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators sued Bennett Funding in March 1996,
prompting the company to file for bankruptcy protection. Former SEC
Chairman Richard Breeden, who is now the court-appointed trustee
trying to recover money for the investors, mailed $50 million in
checks to defrauded investors in August.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are to get more than $100 million as part of a
settlement with an insurance company involved in the case. That
money can be distributed only after the bankruptcy court in Utica,
N.Y., approves a plan of reorganization, Breeden said, adding that
he hoped to file the plan the same week that Patrick Bennett's
trial is to begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
