<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEBACKERS BATTLE WITH WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Normally reluctant to criticize an opponent, USC
linebacker Chris Claiborne changed character Tuesday and responded
angrily to UCLA linebacker Brandon Ayanbadejo's remarks that
quarterback Carson Palmer was ``terrible'' and not even as good as
the Bruins' redshirt freshmen quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of upset me. I'm about sick of him running his
mouth. For him to talk about Carson is ridiculous . . . (it) is not
classy,'' Claiborne said. ``You don't count your season on one
game. You've got to be consistent. If he got four sacks every game,
OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could thrash him. I don't see him up for any awards. But to
talk about him is not classy. I don't think he has a right to talk
about Carson. I don't think he's good enough to talk about Carson
like that. For him to talk about Carson, I take it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer also expressed surprised for a second day in a row about
Ayanbadejo's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he wasn't a senior, I wish I had a chance to play
against him next year,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Cancel the team meeting: Thanks to an unexpectedly sharp
practice Tuesday, USC's players held off on holding a team meeting
to make sure the Trojans are thinking about Notre Dame and not
still smarting over the loss to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If practice had went bad, either me or another senior was
going to step up (and call a meeting),'' wide receiver Billy Miller
said. ``I just want to make sure we keep our focus and realize
we've got to beat that team coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our last hurrah. It's in front of our parents and on
national TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Even USC coach Paul Hackett was surprised with the way the
Trojans bounced back Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we might not come out with as much zip,'' Hackett
said. ``I liked the way the guys responded.''
</P>
<P>
   __ One vote for Florida State: Palmer was asked who was better,
No. 3 UCLA or No. 4 Florida State?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Florida State was better,'' Palmer said. ``We got
killed by Florida State and we couldn't move the ball or do
anything. I think we had a chance to win against UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bowl update: USC is trying to make a pitch for the Holiday
Bowl in San Diego, provided the Trojans can defeat Notre Dame. The
Holiday Bowl could be a possibility if UCLA goes to the Fiesta Bowl
or if Arizona gets an at-large BCS spot, which is considered a long
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' competition is Oregon, which is also strongly
pushing for the Holiday Bowl. Otherwise, the Trojans can probably
expect to receive an invitation to the Sun Bowl in El Paso. There
is a slight chance USC could go to the Aloha Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   __ Day of rest: Claiborne did not practice Tuesday to rest his
sore knee. Defensive tackle Aaron Williams also missed practice to
rest his sore Achilles' tendon. Linebacker David Gibson (bruised
thigh) is expected to return to practice today, although it is
uncertain if he will play. The same applies to defensive tackle
Ennis Davis (sprained foot).
</P>
<P>
   __ Free advice: What two suggestions has Hackett heard most from
alumni and fans since the UCLA loss? Use a shotgun offense and
throw more to the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a lot of pressure for the shotgun,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
