<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8268 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      11-24 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Since 1975, no senior football class at Texas A&AMP;M
has finished below .500 against archrival Texas. However, the Class
of 1998's fourth-year seniors enter Friday morning's battle in
Austin with only a 1-2 record against the Longhorns.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in a season of outstanding accomplishments that has three
matters of business still on the table, beating Texas to arrive at
.500 would add to a variety of good memories Dat Nguyen and his
fellow seniors will eventually carry away from Aggieland.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, you do sit around and think about it. It's hitting
me every day,'' Nguyen said when asked about the impending end to
his college career. ``Every day it's getting closer and closer,
knowing that I'm down to 10 days of practice left. Really, 10 days
of football left until we go to a bowl game. It's like we've got
this week and next week; that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   In actuality, there's a little more time remaining. For after
the Aggies face Kansas State in the Big 12 Championship Game on
Dec. 5 in St. Louis, they will advance to a bowl to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   That's a signal, said Nguyen, that the seniors will have left
the program at an elite level, which is exactly what he envisioned
the first year he set foot on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came in, A&AMP;M was up on a pedestal. They were one of
the elite teams,'' the All-America linebacker said. ``They were in
the top 10 every year; the Wrecking Crew was well known. And for a
couple of years, we went through like a slump. There were a few
mistakes here and there, and it hurt us. The record shows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat around and talked about it last year. We won the Big 12
South and had a chance to play Nebraska in the conference
championship. We didn't play as well as we would have liked. Over
the spring and over the summer, we talked about how we wanted to
leave this place the same way it was when we came in.''
</P>
<P>
   They very well might. After losing to Florida State 23-14 in the
Kickoff Classic to open the season, the sixth-ranked Aggies have
reeled off 10 straight victories and even have an outside shot at
participating in the Fiesta Bowl for the national championship
should they beat Kansas State in the Big 12 title game. (Losses by
Tennessee in the Southeastern Conference title game and by UCLA to
Miami, which would also be necessary, could set up a Fiesta rematch
with Florida State.)
</P>
<P>
   Heady stuff indeed. Especially for the Aggies' 18 seniors, who
could lead A&AMP;M to its first top-five finish since 1956.
</P>
<P>
   But while there are important games to look toward, it never
hurts to take a brief stroll down memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, they were winning the Southwest Conference,''
said linebacker Warrick Holdman of Alief, who has logged 79 tackles
this season and leads the Aggies with seven sacks. ``When we came
here, we saw what the upperclassmen were doing. We were thinking we
wanted to be that type of class. We wanted to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we're doing a lot of great things _ up there in the
top five in defense, (winning) the South Zone championship again.
That's the way it should be. And then the younger guys under me can
look and say, `Yeah, when I'm a senior, that's the way I want to
finish.' It really works.''
</P>
<P>
   For quarterback Branndon Stewart, the celebrated transfer from
Tennessee, the trip down memory lane isn't thoroughly strewn with
rose petals and the smell of jasmine. Though he was the man under
center most of the year when A&AMP;M claimed the South crown in 1997,
Stewart has hardly lived up to the lofty expectations that followed
him from Knoxville to College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Five games into the current season, subpar performances earned
Stewart a seat on the bench. From there, he has watched junior
Randy McCown work his magic, but that hasn't discolored the
memories Stewart will take with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the biggest thing, the memory for me, is of those
football games walking out on Kyle Field,'' Stewart said. ``It was
victory, for the most part, every time we walked out on the field.
We didn't lose too many games, haven't lost one in about two years,
I think. That's special to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy with which Stewart had to deal for the better
part of three years is indelible, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, maybe it made it difficult to enjoy football as much
as you should in college,'' he said. ``But I think it helps me
understand and put into perspective how to deal with people, how to
take the good and the bad. I'm glad I got to experience the things
I did, because going into the next step, past college, it will
help.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot for the seniors to be proud of, said reserve
cornerback Shun Horn of Jasper, particularly because of what has
happened in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well enough all year to get us to the Big 12
Championship Game,'' he said. ``We've played well enough to allow
us to get to a bowl game. But each week, we take one game at a
time. And right now, we're focusing on the University of Texas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
