<DOCNO> NYT19981124.0502 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      11-24 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ Who knows what promises then-head coach John Mackovic made
to get them to sign a letter of intent? There is no way he, or
anyone for that matter, could have foreseen what the 18 players who
this week will play their last home game at Darrell K Royal-Texas
Memorial Stadium would go through in their Texas football careers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But to a man, the Longhorns' seniors say they would not hesitate
to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Their four or five seasons at Texas (depending on a redshirt
year) encompass a set of highs and lows that probably spans as wide
a spectrum as any UT graduating class has encountered.
</P>
<P>
   No, there was no national championship to revel in, as was the
case for players who wore the burnt orange in 1963, '69 and '70.
But it seems this group has seen just about everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, hard, fun ride,'' said linebacker Dusty
Renfro, a three-year starter from Alvarado. ``I've enjoyed every
second of it. I don't think there is anywhere else in the world
that I would rather have spent the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been to the top, and we've seen the bottom also. I've
learned that you've got to get up every time you get knocked down
and keep going. You never can tell what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at some of the happenings over the past five years for
Texas' 1998 seniors:
</P>
<P>
   They were a part of three consecutive conference championships
(Southwest Conference in 1994 and '95; Big 12 in '96) and were one
loss away from a last-place finish (1997).
</P>
<P>
   They played at the Superdome and Trans World Dome, before
Touchdown Jesus at Notre Dame, and in front of a half-naked crowd
at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   They were on a team that saw the end of a 28-game series winning
streak against Rice but posted a couple of the largest victory
margins in school history against rivals Texas A&AMP;M (51-15 in 1996)
and Oklahoma (34-3 this season).
</P>
<P>
   They shocked the nation with an upset of two-time defending
national champion Nebraska in the 1996 Big 12 Championship Game but
were humiliated by the school's worst-ever home loss the following
season against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   They were part of a 4-7 campaign in 1997, the worst at the
school in 10 years, but were also part of one of only two 10-win
seasons at Texas in the past 15 years (10-2-1 in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   They saw the rise of a coach hailed as a genius (Mackovic) and
the fall of a coach who could not get the job done (ditto).
</P>
<P>
   But all things considered, the Longhorns' seniors say they leave
as they thought they would _ as winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great time, and I wouldn't trade it for anything,''
said offensive tackle Jay Humphrey of Richardson. ``There's nothing
that I would even change. I'm gonna leave with (five) rings (two
conference championships and three bowls), and anybody who could
complain about that, something's wrong with 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey, like many of his classmates, has trouble singling out
a particular moment that stands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to pick just one incident that was the high point of
my career,'' the three-year starter said. ``Blocking for (running
back) Ricky (Williams) for the past three years has been special.
There are several games _ Texas A&AMP;M in '96 and Nebraska both times
(1996 and '98) there are not gonna be many people who, 20, 30 years
down the road, can say that they were 2-0 against Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   The seniors agree that following the disaster of 1997, all the
good times could almost have been erased had the team not responded
with a solid year this season under new head coach Mack Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who could further distinguish this group by joining
Earl Campbell as the second Longhorn to win the Heisman Trophy,
breaks down the highlights of his career by year.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman (1995): ``Going to Hawaii, and beating A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore: ``Beating Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   As a junior: ``There weren't any last year.''
</P>
<P>
   As a senior: ``The way the team has come together and played so
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-year senior Tony Holmes thinks this season has provided an
almost perfect close to his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a new challenge, especially for the seniors,'' the
cornerback from Irving said. ``For us to keep the team together
when we didn't have a coach helped bring us together, and we
rallied around each other. When the new coaches came in, it was a
turning point and another leaf in our career. We took it in stride,
and it turned out good.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being part of a much-maligned defense that had the
school's second- (1997) and fourth-worst (1996) seasons in terms of
yards allowed, Holmes believes his tenure at Texas was a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord brought me here for a purpose, and it's been
wonderful,'' he said. ``The friendships, the winning seasons, the
three straight championships it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior vote for the most unforgettable play is easily the
now-famous fourth-down pass play against Nebraska that helped the
Longhorns claim the Big 12 title in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lewis, the recipient of that pass, said that with just two
more games to go _ one against A&AMP;M and a second in a bowl to be
determined _ focus is even more important for the seniors, since
they can create some final pleasant memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the positive things and sit back after you're through
and say wow,'' said the New Orleans native. ``But being a player,
if you strive to be really good, you can't take those things to
heart as they happen, because you're only as good as your last game
in this business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
