<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' HAMILTON CHARGED WITH MARIJUANA POSSESSION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Giants defensive tackle Keith Hamilton was
stopped by Port Authority police for speeding on the George
Washington Bridge early Monday morning and later charged with
possession of marijuana, driving under the influence of a
controlled dangerous substance and possession of drug
paraphernalia, according to Port Authority police.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was stopped at 1:30 a.m. for driving 71 mph in 45 mph
zone. Hamilton was not carrying a driver's license or an insurance
card and the police said they found a bag that appeared to contain
less than an ounce of marijuana and a pipe on Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it was discovered that Hamilton's car insurance had
expired. He also was charged with driving an uninsured car, said
Bill Cahill, a police spokesman for the Port Authority of New York
and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Giants Coach Jim Fassel helped in the release early
Monday of Hamilton, who posted $750 bail.
</P>
<P>
   All charges against Hamilton are either traffic violations or
misdemeanors. Hamilton is scheduled to appear in court on Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Giants officials said Tuesday that they did not expect Hamilton,
a fourth-round draft pick of the team who emerged last year as one
of the Giants better players, to be suspended by the National
Football League because it was Hamilton's first offense of this
kind. Hamilton could be fined and the league could order a
mandatory evaluation along with treatment or drug testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
