<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNAKEBIT-THEATER-REVI     11-24 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKEBIT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE YUPPIES, ALL DOWNWARDLY MOBILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Why are these people not smiling? Michael, Jonathan
and Jenifer, the anxious trio at the heart of ``Snakebit,'' David
Marshall Grant's solid and savvy new yuppie melodrama at the Grove
Street Playhouse, should have found a measure of contentment by
now. Bright, good looking, capable, they present themselves as a
group that is as likely as any in the culture to attain full and
rewarding lives.
</P>
<P>
   But look again. Psychologically speaking, they're nothing if not
downwardly mobile. Michael (Geoffrey Nauffts), a gay social worker,
is a good person who has been abandoned by a lover who objected to
his plan to adopt a foster child. Jonathan (David Alan Basche), his
boyhood friend, is an actor with a rampaging ego, a deteriorating
marriage and a psychiatric seminar's worth of unresolved feelings
for Michael. And Jenifer (Jodie Markell), Jonathan's wife and soul
mate (and erstwhile bedmate) of Michael, is a fetching bundle of
nerves, regretful of the choices she has made but powerless to
unmake them.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, nominated for a Tony for his portrayal of the Mormon
husband in ``Angels in America,'' turns playwright for this
presentation by the Naked Angels theater company, and the
transition could not have been much smoother. Tinkering with what
might have been a formula for an episode of ``thirtysomething'' _ a
show on which he also had a small recurring role _ Grant comes up
instead with a rather smart and absorbing evening of water-cooler
theater, the intimate sort of off-Broadway experience that has you
picking apart the recognizable characters long after the curtain
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The play has been handled with expert attention by an adroit
director, Jace Alexander, and a first-class ensemble; all the
actors dig in and emerge with finely textured portraits of
terminally unhappy people who can't quite put their fingers on the
sources of their misery. Perhaps, for these once promising souls,
not having all the answers is misery enough.
</P>
<P>
   As with Kenneth Lonergan's ``This Is Our Youth,'' the hit comedy
at Second Stage, Grant's play triangulates the attractions,
disaffections and jealousies in a pair of men and the woman who
drives a wedge between them. Grant's characters are a good 10 to 15
years older than Lonergan's drug-dealing, scam-generating Manhattan
ne'er-do-wells, and so ``Snakebit'' deals with a more established
class of privileged citizens, whose personal histories are both
richer and less extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Michael's Los Angeles apartment, authentically rendered
by the set designer Dean Taucher with a sharp eye for the sunbaked
Southwest, ``Snakebit'' takes place during a visit from New York by
Jenifer and Jonathan, who stay with Michael while Jonathan awaits
word on a major role in a big-budget thriller.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the break the fuming, hyperactive Jonathan has
always dreamed of, but the significance of the occasion is lost on
Michael and Jenifer, who have hit emotional dead ends that
Jonathan, who prides himself on, among many other things, his
sensitivity, can barely acknowledge. Their depression seems a kind
of repressed anxiety, focused at the moment on Jenifer's worries
about her young daughter back in New York, who throws up
continually and, more ominously, is losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   Her thoughts revert to the affair she carried on 11 years
earlier with Michael _ the last woman he slept with _ just prior to
her marriage to Jonathan, and the suspicion that Michael may be the
carrier of a dread disease that he transmitted to her and is only
now making its impact felt. Michael, strangely detached from the
doom that might await him if the blood tests he and Jenifer have
taken come back positive, is fixated instead on his abandonment by
Gary, a radio shock jock who carries on a public charade of
heterosexuality. It's in the contemplation of his loss, and
Jenifer's potential disaster, that Michael makes a fateful choice.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to lay out the basics of ``Snakebit'' because
there's a lot going on here: These are carefully plotted
relationships, for which the actors and the playwright find all
sorts of pleasing insights. For instance, near the conclusion, Ms.
Markell, an off-Broadway actress who is always a joy to watch, has
a wonderful moment that sums up marriage in a minute and meaningful
way. In the midst of one her husband's endless, disruptive tirades,
she interrupts with a really important tip on how he might more
practically repack a suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who provides the actors with all manner of clever things
to say, at times overpacks a bit himself, concocting two or three
telling moments or ripostes where one would suffice. Nevertheless,
he's interesting even when he overdoes it.
</P>
<P>
   Nauffts, in a gently understated performance, is grand as the
conflicted conscience of the piece. Basche is equally strong,
putting his leading-man looks to maximum advantage as a clueless
cock of the walk, and Michael Weston, as the play's fourth wheel,
finds the right mix of calculation and guilelessness in the
mysterious visitor who arrives one morning at Michael's house.
</P>
<P>
   What a generous actor Grant must be, to give all the good parts
away.
</P>
<P>
   SNAKEBIT: By David Marshall Grant; directed by Jace Alexander;
sets by Dean Taucher; lighting by Renee Molina; costumes by
Elizabeth Roles; prop master, Patricia Merino; production stage
manager, Kimberley Ann Berdy; assistant stage manager, Lind
Michelle Bartunek. Presented by Naked Angels. At the Grove Street
Playhouse, 39 Grove St., Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: David Alan Basche (Jonathan), Jodie Markell (Jenifer),
Geoffrey Nauffts (Michael) and Michael Weston (Young Man).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2336EST &QL; 
