<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-RUTGERS-STRINGER-     11-24 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-STRINGER-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRINGER COPES WITH A FAMILY CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It could not be happening again. Not to C. Vivian Stringer. Not
during this week of Thanksgiving. But it was her choked voice on
the phone from an airplane heading to Raleigh, N.C., on Sunday
night. And it was her longtime confidant on the other end of the
call, Temple Coach John Chaney, trying to gently comfort her while
letting her know that, once again, she would have to be strong for
her family. Once again, during Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Stringer was devastated when her husband, Bill, died of a heart
attack on Thanksgiving Day in 1992. Two decades earlier, her
father, Charles, had died during the Thanksgiving holiday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, Stringer was in Austin, Texas, preparing
her 11th-ranked Rutgers women's basketball team for its game
against the University of Texas. That game went on without Stringer
on Monday night; assistant coach Larry Lawler filled in. Rutgers
won, 66-59.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday evening, Stringer has been by the side of her son,
David, who faces felony charges after being with two other North
Carolina State football players, two wrestlers and another student
who were arrested early Sunday morning after a bizarre altercation
left a fellow student dead from a gunshot wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vivian was crying, and I was just trying to tell her to hang
on, that we were all counting on her to fight through this, and
that I was with her,'' Chaney said Tuesday. ``It is just
unbelievable from the standpoint that families, at this time of the
year, come together. And yet, too often in Vivian's life, there has
been someone missing or someone in pain at this time of the year.
It's hard to imagine this happening to her now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine that David Stringer, portrayed as heady and
responsible, was involved in a confluence of events resulting in a
shooting death that has shaken the college town of Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to all of the families of the young people
involved,'' Stringer said in a statement issued by Rutgers. ``This
is one of the things parents dread in the deep of the night. I have
visited with my son and am doing all that a mother can do. It is
inappropriate for me to answer any questions at this time. I will
be returning to my team as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raleigh police said that early Sunday, Neil Davis, 21, stood
on the front doorstep of his residence and fired several shots from
his 9-millimeter semiautomatic pistol, with one shot whistling
through a party in a house across the street. The shot ricocheted
and grazed a wrestler at the party. According to the police,
Stringer was among six students who went across the street to
confront Davis.
</P>
<P>
   `` Davis went back into his house and secured himself in his
bedroom, and these gentlemen chose to unlawfully enter his house,''
Capt. Mike Longmire said. ``At some point, they forced their way
into his room and there was a confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   During a struggle with Clyde Blunt, a wrestler, the weapon was
taken from Davis' hand and fired around 2:30 a.m., police reported.
Davis, who was shot in the stomach, died six hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Doug Faucette said that after the fatal shooting, the
group left the scene and one of the football players took the gun
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt was charged with involuntary manslaughter, a felony.
Stringer, 19, a reserve receiver, and two teammates Harold Jackson,
20, and Willie Wright, 19, were charged with misdemeanor assault.
In addition, Wright was charged with larceny of a firearm, a
felony. Jackson and Stringer were also charged with being
accessories to the felony of larceny. All three football players
were released on bond and suspended from the team. Stringer's next
court date is Dec. 14.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when I heard,'' said Chaney, who has known
Stringer since she began her coaching career in 1971 at Cheyney
State, a small, predominantly black college near Philadelphia.
``This kind of thing takes a toll on a mother.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems so much toll has already been paid. After her husband
died, Stringer was left as the single mother of three, including a
daughter, Janine, now 17, who has needed constant care since she
was left handicapped by spinal meningitis at age 2.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has ever been simple. But the wear on her life was
supposed to ease when Stringer left a highly successful career at
the University of Iowa for Rutgers three summers ago. Some
wondered, why Rutgers? More important than the allure of a $150,000
salary _ the richest for a women's coach at the time _ Rutgers was
closer to her Pennsylvania roots, closer to friends and family,
closer to potential happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers was far removed from Iowa, where her father and husband
had died. Although she found Iowa warm and friendly, she sought a
change for herself and her children.
</P>
<P>
   She found out a fresh start was not so easy. When she arrived at
Rutgers, there was jealously from those focused on her salary and
criticism from those who wondered why she could not sprinkle pixie
dust on her team and create a winner out of Rutgers overnight.
</P>
<P>
   David Stringer was also faced with a rude welcome. In December
1996, his mother left 12 minutes into a game against Princeton when
she was told that David, then a student at North Brunswick High
School, had been slashed with a box cutter by another student.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, problems have come to David,'' said Chaney, who
has coached David in his summer basketball camps since he was a
young boy. ``Someone accosted him over a girl one time when he was
getting out of his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was lucky. He had on a big winter coat when this
happened. So he did not get cut too badly. Other than that
incident, which wasn't his fault, he has been someone who has been
free of any kind of acrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringer is best friends with her son. As the oldest, David has
been someone his mother could depend on since his father died,
someone who was able to prop up his mother when she was not sure if
she could coach again.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally spent after the death of her husband, who seemed to
get more out of her coaching victories than she did, Stringer has
said she nearly walked away from the sport in 1992. With a firm
voice and pensive posture on the sideline, she was on her way to
becoming the third-winningest coach in women's basketball history
while at Iowa. But she didn't care. She didn't want a life in
basketball without her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``David and Justin came to me and said, `When are you going to
coach again?''' Stringer said of her sons in an interview a year
ago. ``They said: `This is your life. Dad would not have wanted you
to give up, and neither do we.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Stringer pushed on. And now, she is asked to push through yet
another painful Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot of strength inside of her,'' Chaney said. ``And
sometimes you wonder how much is there and how it keeps her going
all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
