<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-HNS &LR;      11-24 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MINNEAPOLIS _ The Minnesota Vikings' success this season is no
secret: They have more talent than any team in the NFL.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask any scout why the Vikings are 10-1 and the first NFC team to
clinch a playoff spot, and he will tell you coach Dennis Green's
cup runneth over with productive, multitalented players.
</P>
<P>
   Denver, the defending Super Bowl champion, might be a better
team, but individually no team rates across the board with the
Vikings, according to the NFL's pro personnel people.
</P>
<P>
   Green, in his seventh season with the Vikings, believes the
team's three-game lead in the NFC Central is the result of talent,
hard work, proven systems and sound organization from the top to
the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective hasn't changed one bit since the season began,''
Green says. ``We're trying to get as much as we can with the people
we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy to have 10 wins, but the only thing we think
about is how we're going to get No. 11. We don't think about the
division race or getting home-field advantage. The only thing we're
thinking about is the Dallas Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is no stranger to the playoffs, but he has won only one
playoff game. Red McCombs, who bought the team in the offseason,
showed a lot of confidence in Green when he signed his coach to a
three-year contract extension at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs made decisions that brought stability to the team, and
he has been rewarded with the Vikings' best season since 1975 and
record-breaking crowds in the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the season, I don't think anyone could have foreseen
this type of season, especially when you consider the instability
of our ownership situation and the players (Vikings free agents) we
had to sign,'' says Jeff Diamond, the vice president of
administration and team operations. ``We knew we had the makings of
a good team, and once Red took over and brought so much enthusiasm
to the organization, everything fell into place.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Vikings tangle with the Cowboys in the traditional
Thanksgiving game, they will be trying to win their first NFC
Central title since 1994. A Minnesota win and a Green Bay loss
would clinch the division for the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just blessed to have a great group of players and
coaches,'' says quarterback Randall Cunningham, who is compiling
Most Valuable Player numbers after beginning the season as the
backup. ``Dennis likes for us to be a little edgy. If we don't win,
he doesn't want us to exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have been forced to hold their breath only once this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have as many great players on offense like we do, it
makes such a difference,'' Cunningham says. ``We're all role
players. We've got veteran players who stay consistent. We believe
in each other and what we can accomplish. Let me tell you, when you
have guys like this on your team, you come to work every day with a
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Minnesota's offense is so explosive, it gets more
attention than the defense, which allows 16.7 points and 307.8
yards per game. Tackle John Randle, who has seven sacks, is the
best player and spiritual leader of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's offense, second in the NFL with an average of 31.6
points per game, has no weakness, even without receiver Jake Reed,
who is out for the season with a lumbar-disk injury.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who had 34 catches for 474 yards and four touchdowns, had
been overshadowed by Randy Moss, the magnificent rookie who has
eight touchdowns. Moss starts against the Cowboys opposite Cris
Carter, the Vikings' leading receiver with 50 catches for 686
yards. Like Moss, Carter has eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   With Carter, Reed and Moss, the Vikings had the best threesome
in the league. With Carter and Moss, they have one of the best
duos.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Walsh, Robert Tate and Matthews Hatchette will try to
replace Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it (Reed's injury) changes the profile (of the
offense) a little bit,'' offensive coordinator Brian Billick says.
``This is a situation where everybody has to step up and take up
the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to alter our game plan dramatically. Obviously,
you have to pare some things down. You really have to count on your
veterans' experience and their ability to be able to carry it from
the classroom to game situations.''
</P>
<P>
   With the short work week to prepare for the Cowboys, the Vikings
plan to remain pretty basic. There is nothing fancy about their
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Carter works the middle of the field and the sideline like a
magician. The 6-4 Moss goes deep and outjumps shorter cornerbacks.
Moss showed in Sunday's 28-14 win over Green Bay that he's more
than a deep threat. Of his eight catches, five were near the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Moss gets most of the recognition because he makes so many big
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy tells me he'll catch anything I throw as long as I don't
overthrow it,'' Cunningham says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Robert Smith, who has 967 yards rushing and six
touchdowns, has exceptional speed. He excels on artificial turf
with quick cuts and outstanding acceleration. Smith is better in a
one-back formation that allows him to line up deep and read his
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who replaced the injured Brad Johnson, has completed
150 of 239 passes for 2,206 yards and 19 touchdowns. He has thrown
six interceptions. His passer rating is a league-leading 108.9.
</P>
<P>
   On third down, Cunningham has been the most productive
quarterback in the NFL. His passer rating on third down is a
league-high 125.3, with seven touchdown passes and one
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great passer for our system,'' Green says. ``Randall
brings confidence and calmness to this team. He's just so poised.
He never gets overexcited.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who posted an 8-4 record against the Cowboys when he
played in Philadelphia, is fortunate to have one of the best
offensive lines in the league. Guard Randall McDaniel is a
perennial Pro Bowl selection. Tackles Kory Stringer and Todd
Steussie are former No. 1 picks who are having their best seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a lot of time in the pocket,'' Cunningham says. ``I
don't take off and run like I used to. If I feel comfortable in the
pocket, I'll hold the ball a little longer looking for my receiver.
If I feel the pressure, I'll get rid of the ball to avoid the
sack.''
</P>
<P>
   Green can't say enough good things about what Cunningham has
meant to the team. Cunningham can become a free agent after the
season, but he says he wants to stay in Minnesota, even if he has
to accept a lot less money than other teams would offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall was a gift to us,'' Green says. ``He had vowed to
never play again. He came to the right team because we know how to
utilize him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham left Philadelphia after the 1996 season and retired
to his offseason home in Las Vegas. He made a decision to return in
1997 and signed with the Vikings as a backup to Johnson rather than
go to New Orleans as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham helps the Vikings average 378.2 yards per game. He
makes smart decisions and does not force the ball or throw into
coverage. He's much more patient in the pocket than he was with the
Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an awesome feeling these days,'' Cunningham says.
``When I'm in the huddle and I look in guys' eyes and see a feeling
of confidence, I know we can get through any situation. If I throw
an interception, it doesn't get us down. If we lose a fumble, we
get over it. There's a feeling here that we can accomplish just
about anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
