<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8285 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARITY-TIME-AMERICA-     11-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITY-TIME-AMERICA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS SEASON OF GIVING, CHARITY SHIFTS INTO HIGH GEAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The model is doing her best. The lighting in the
Cotillion Ballroom of Manhattan's Pierre Hotel is not helping and
the 200 guests attending the gala fund-raising night for the
American-Italian Cancer Foundation seem somewhat underwhelmed by
the flowing brown shawl she is showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty, but not that pretty,'' grumbles a woman sitting
behind me. ``Yes, but a Fendi is a Fendi,'' protests her husband.
</P>
<P>
   When the auctioneer, Simon Teakle, a senior vice-president at
Christies, closes the bidding, the shawl _ a handmade tulle affair
with tufts of weasel fur _ goes to a gentleman on the left of the
aisle for $12,000. He has a bargain. The donor value, according to
the catalogue, is $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   All told, however, the evening turns out very well for the
Foundation. The Mercedes convertible that was parked outside as we
came in _ value $51,000 _ is snapped up for $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   And someone pays $2,800 to take five friends out to dinner at
the Four Seasons in the company of Norman Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   Before retiring for dinner with the rest of us, Teakle manages
to squeeze $160,000 out of us for just 15 lots.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not just the live auction that brings in the dollars.
It is preceded by an hour of cocktails and delectable hors d'oeuvre
in the adjoining reception rooms where guests are encouraged to
participate in a silent auction for no fewer than 260 items that
have been donated for nothing by a myriad of companies and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The sign-up list is empty for a free checkup at the Westside
Family Dental Group, included in the Hobbies and Entertainment
section. For a free day of game shooting on the Millbrook Preserve
in upstate New York, there are entries from $200 and up. Buying a
table at the dinner runs in the thousands. As a guest of Benetton,
however, I tactfully refrain from asking just how many thousand.
</P>
<P>
   The evening, a glittering, black-tie event that attracts the
rich and powerful of American-Italian society on the East Coast,
provides a glimpse into the world of philanthropic giving that is
peculiar to the United States, and especially to the Upper East
Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when the charity circuit goes into high
gear. If he had the energy, Teakle could be wielding his gavel free
of charge at similar events all across town every night of the week
between now and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at what is coming up in the New York charity calendar.
Last night, for example, you could have paid $25,000 for a table at
the New York City Ballet opening night benefit with performances of
works by George Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the glitziest of all evenings, however, one where
guests have the best chance of getting their picture in the gossip
pages of the city tabloids comes on Dec. 7. That is the night of
the Metropolitan Museum of Art's always-fabulous Costume Institute
Benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Events such as these represent just the celebrity tip of a
fund-raising iceberg in this country. Any institution that needs
money it cannot get from government is forced to invade the pockets
of private citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   Libraries, hospitals and radio stations all find ways to raise
cash, and auctions are a favorite strategy. Even these events are
not always humble. At a recent auction for a girls' school in
Greenwich, Conn., home to this reporter, the star lot was a
labrador puppy. It fetched $38,000.
</P>
<P>
   What possesses Americans to attend these events and shell out so
much? There are, of course, a variety of answers.
</P>
<P>
   The most cynical is that giving like this is many people's
passport to enhanced social status. The more you give, the higher
you are on the rungs of America's faux aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Others go, apparently, because they are lonely. On this evening,
one woman admits her mission is to find a husband. She enters the
bidding twice in the live auction in the hope of impressing the
handsome man next to her.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of tax. Later at my dinner table, a
broker from Morgan Stanley explains I should not be too impressed
by the $75,000 paid for the car. Once you factor in the
tax-deduction the buyer will earn for having given to charity,
really he is paying only $45,000 _ below sticker price.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I refuse to be cynical. This, finally, is about giving
and about generosity. It is about an understanding that many
Americans share, whether at a gala evening at the Pierre or when
they reach into their wallets for the Salvation Army at Christmas _
that this is far from a welfare state and that where the government
does not provide the private citizen has to.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCallion, a voice-training consultant for Christies who
is also at this dinner, said: ``Americans have their social dues to
pay and they pay those dues.'' Judging by the money that is flowing
tonight, he is not wrong. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 850-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-98 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
