<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-24 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETRO-WHITE-AMERICA-I     11-24 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETRO-WHITE-AMERICA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE, MIDDLE-CLASS AMERICANS LOOK INWARDS AND BACK  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Timely for THANKSGIVING!)   (This 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They may be richer than they have ever been, living
in bigger houses, enjoying cleaner air and better health, but some
of that sunny optimism has gone out of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   As they trim and stuff their turkeys for the Thanksgiving
holiday 1998, white, middle-class Americans are looking inwards,
and back.
</P>
<P>
   A recent crop of films examines what might be called the
American condition on the threshold of the millennium, and it is
shot through with angst for a way of life that may not be all it
seems and may never have been.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Truman Show,'' a morality play for the television age
that was released in the U.S. this summer, through
``Pleasantville,'' a critical look back at the America of the
Fifties, to ``Happiness,'' a search behind the respectable facade
of a ``perfect'' American family to find some very dirty linen, the
ideal of wholesome, family-orientated, small-town America held so
dear by generations is cracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show,'' if you have not seen it, is unusual for an
American film in embodying an idea: the exchange of appearance and
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Truman _ the name is no accident _ is the real-life and
unwitting star of a television soap opera that has revolved around
him since his birth.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in the television dimension. Everything else _ wife,
house, neighbors, job, town _ is fabricated according to the
television ideal; every man is manly in a televisual way, every
woman is beautiful in that unsubtle American way and, every child,
as Garrison Keillor said in his gently satirized tales of Lake
Woebegone, ``is above average.''
</P>
<P>
   For the viewer, the earliest clues of the deception are a
prophetic falling ``star'' that shatters like the light bulb it is,
and the digressions by Truman's ``wife'' to advertise commercial
products, directly to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   They culminate in the first storm in living memory to hit the
manufactured white clapboard town that splits the artificial
``sky'' and gives Truman an inkling of a world outside. The
``moral'' is the obvious one: ``True man's'' overriding need for
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The physical and metaphorical limits of small-town America are a
theme also of ``Pleasantville,'' a recent box-office success for
``all the family'' that hammers home just one message.
</P>
<P>
   Those glorious, secure, innocent Fifties you may be tempted to
feel nostalgia for were not so wonderful: they were circumscribed,
cold and bigoted.
</P>
<P>
   The tale is of two Nineties teenagers transported by clumsy
artifice back to the world of a Fifties soap-opera, with
two-parent, two-child families, forced by social and civic
pressures to conform, whatever the personal cost.
</P>
<P>
   In a crude device which transforms the characters from their
black and white originals to glorious technicolor, each is
``awakened'' to personal enjoyment and fulfillment through the
Nineties knowledge and experience of the newly arrived teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Even the issue of race is introduced as the ``coloreds'' are
subjected to discrimination by the as yet unenlightened monotone
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, ``Happiness'' _ a niche film rejected by the big
distributors worried that one of the characters emerges a pedophile
_ lifts the veil on an outwardly ``model'' American family.
</P>
<P>
   Three generations are shown in progressive disintegration, with
the most perfect of them all _ the comfortable, complacent suburban
housewife who ``has it all'' _ big house, money, children and loyal
husband _ having her contentment stripped away as her psychoanalyst
husband's vice is exposed and her own Nineties tolerance breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious combined message from all three films that
the idealized world of family-values America _ whether in the
Fifties or the Nineties, the small town or the sanitized suburbs _
does not exist, something else emerges.
</P>
<P>
   There is at the heart of each an ambivalence; it is as though
none of the directors could bring himself either to embrace or
dismiss the fabricated ideal completely.
</P>
<P>
   Was Truman better off when he believed in his world, or when the
sky fell in? How many Americans now tailor their lives to what they
see on television?
</P>
<P>
   Of the teenagers transported into the Fifties, the boy
(David/Bud) returns to the Nineties still enamored of the stable
family and fixed values that made him such a fan of the aged soap
opera in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The girl (Jennifer/Mary Sue), while railing against the limits
on a girl's freedom pre-Pill, pre-feminism, nonetheless abandons
the permissiveness she has brought to the Fifties world, retreating
chastely to her frilled bedroom and her books.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Happiness'' _ whose title, like that of ``Pleasantville,''
is ironic _ shocked some American critics with its refusal to
condemn the ``perfect'' husband for his pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative effect is of a troubled caste _ an entirely white
caste, it should be stressed _ that is unsure whether the comforts
and principles it lived for ever had any substance.
</P>
<P>
   After all, those pretty clapboard towns are now reproduced as
flimsy housing developments across America; the props of that showy
television world can be bought at every shopping mall, and those
families that will gather around the laden dinner table on
Thanksgiving are, more often than not, fractured.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder these people are reluctant to shame Bill Clinton. The
brash New World is at last starting to feel the self-doubt of the
Old. &QL; 
