<HEADER>
A8293 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-CARD-COMFORT-L     11-24 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-CARD-COMFORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED'S CUTS, COMPETITION DRIVING DOWN CREDIT CARD INTEREST RATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shoppers should get some relief from credit card
payments this year, as interest rates are starting to go down again
after rising since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to recent rate cuts by the Federal Reserve Board of
Governors and intense competition in the credit card industry,
consumers are seeing rates going down. They are expected to
decrease even more in January, as the Fed's last cut this month
finally kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   The weighted average annual percentage rate is 18.08 percent
this year for standard, gold and platinum cards, compared with
18.11 percent in 1997, according to CardWeb Inc., a
Pennsylvania-based payment card research firm. Rates can be as low
as 7.99 percent, which is the case at Pulaski Bank &AMP; Trust.
</P>
<P>
   CardWeb President Robert McKinley said he has noticed record-low
introductory APR rates as well, including some at 2.9 percent or
3.9 percent and others with no interest charges during the
introductory period.
</P>
<P>
   But before shoppers cheer, McKinley and consumer advocates say
that credit card issuers are making up the lost profits -- down to
1 percent today from 4 percent in the early 1990s -- by increasing
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks are adding other fees,'' McKinley said.
</P>
<P>
   Some banks are charging fees to close an account or for not
using an account. More banks are charging penalty interest rates of
up to 25 percent for such violations as making one late payment or
exceeding the credit limit once, according to the 1998 Credit Card
Survey by Consumer Action and Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   They're also adding late-payment fees at an average of $21.82,
up 75 percent from three years ago, the survey said. Grace periods
have been shortened from 25 days to 20 days at many banks. To top
it off, the minimum payment required has been lowered to 2 percent
of the balance from 4 percent, meaning it would take consumers more
time to pay off the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Banking institutions are the most common issuers of credit
cards. Visa and MasterCard are nonprofit associations owned by
their member banks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have ancillary fees because intense competition makes it
hard for them to charge an annual fee while introductory or
``teaser'' rates are the lowest they've ever been, said John
Stafford, a spokesman for the California Bankers Association in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But only 3 percent of customers incur these fees, since most
people pay their accounts on time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers who manage their accounts responsibly don't pay any
fees. Most people do avoid these fees,'' Stafford said.
</P>
<P>
   And now they're avoiding higher rates. Since most cards carry an
adjustable rate, consumers should see their interest rates go down
as the last Fed cut takes effect next year. As the Fed changes the
federal funds rate, or the discount rate, banks tend to follow suit
by adjusting their prime rate accordingly. The prime rate is the
rate banks charge their most valuable customers.
</P>
<P>
   Many credit cards are pegged to the prime rate. Since early this
year, the prime rate has dropped from 8.5 percent to 7.75 percent
today, according to the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
